{ Black is trying to gain central control and to put our Bc4 out of the game after d5. However, it is questionable if Black has time for such activities while White is developing and overtaking the action! Don't forget that  7...h6  8.Qh4  d5  9.O-O-O  c6  10.Rhe1  transposes to the same position which we will consider later.   While  7...Nc6  8.Qh4  transposes to the main line. }
8. O-O-O
{ White completes his development with the most favorite idea - A long castle! This move announces opposite side castled game, where White will launch the attack on the Kingside while Black could try to do the same on the Queenside. Although in the practice, we either mate them or they manage to defend thanks to the active game through the center, I hardly remember a game where Black arranged the attack on the Queenside and that is one more reason why I enjoy Urusov Gambit type of positions! }
8... d5
{ Black concluded the idea of d5, but didn't stop our development since the Bc4 is not really hanging due to Qd8. It is clear that White gained compensation for a pawn with all the pieces in the game aiming to play Rhe1. }
9. Rhe1
{ Take a look carefully at this position - the last piece of White came into a game on the most active possible square! This is an ideal development for White and the last move has just concluded one of the crucial principles in chess - Centralisation! We are ready for the Butchering! One should not forget that  9...dxc4??  is not possible due to  10.Qxd8  Checkmate! Also, the last move gives White apart from the centralization another great tactical shot  Re7!  afterward, which usually happens after Qd4-Qh4 and Bd3 where the move h6? would be bad due to Bxh6! and g6? would be disastrous in a view of Re7! followed by Bf6! }
9... Be6
{ Black chooses the most resilient move aiming to block our Rook nicely placed on the open e-file and makes final preparations for the castle. }
10. Qh4
{ White is swinging the Queen over to the kingside and keeps the Black's Queen pinned by the Rd1. Despite that, d4 square is now available to a Knight which will put Be6 into trouble, while Bc4 remains untouchable! }
10... h6
{ White should realize that Black's idea of this move is not to move the Bishop from g5 away, since hg5 is not a threat due to a pinned Rook, but Black aims to play Nfd7!? followed by exchanges. }
11. Bd3
{ White prepares the pieces for when Black's King journeys on to the Kingside, which would be the most logical 'human move', aiming to create an attack on the Kingside. This move is mainly there to prevent castles, due to the now already obvious threat of the Bxh6 break! }
11... Nfd7
{ Even though it does not look natural, this is the most dangerous move for White in this position. Black threatens to go for  12.--  12...Bxg5  13.Nxg5  Qxg5  . }
12. Bxe7
{ White is forced to remove the dark-squared Bishops and hopes to make use of the semi-opened e-file and possible pins by the Rook on e1. }
12... Qxe7 13. Qg3
{ I would like to mention that the engines suggest  13.Qxe7  for White as the best computer move, and after  13...Kxe7  14.Nd4  gives initiative to White. However, I think that the best way to gain an active position for White is to continue with an attack with Queens on the board and therefore the natural 13.Qg3 move which puts pressure on the g7-weakened square. }
13... O-O
{ Black castles immediately where the King is seemingly safe due to the lack of the dark-squared Bishop in White's position. Anyway, there is still the active Rook on e1 and the uncomfortably positioned Bishop on e6 which is exposed to several pins. }
14. Ne2
{ White aims to relocate the pieces on the Kingside with the idea of Nf4 or Nd4. It is clear that Black has no time to escape the pin, so he must search for another way of activation. }
14... Nc5
{ At the same time, Black supports the Bishop on e6 and threatens to remove our Bishop from d3. However, this exchange would lead to a possible activation of White's Rooks, so White does not need to defend here. }
15. Nf4
{ Not only that White finally puts pressure on Be6, but also has a hidden threat of Nh5, compromising Black's Kingside.   You can find the full and detailed analysis of this line here! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter "]
[Black "Urusov Gambit Accepted: 3...exd4 4.Nf3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever - The Bishop's opening, which is deeply analyzed within this course.   However, entering the Bishop's opening also gives you the opportunity to enter aggressive and wild lines, such as the Urusov gambit. As an introduction to the wild play within this opening, 2.Bc4 controls the important d5 square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, attacks the most vulnerable spot in Black's position on f7, and prepares White to complete development with O-O afterward. }
2... Nf6
{ This move is the most consequential continuation by Black, and believe it or not, it happens in more than 80% of the games after 2.Bc4 according to the statistics! It is also very important to mention that the Urusov gambit would not be possible without it! Line 2...Nc6 leads to a Vienna Hybrid variation and it is covered in the Bishop's opening part. }
3. d4
{ Already on the third move, White has an opportunity to pick the aggressive approach with the Urusov gambit 3.d4!? or to choose a more peaceful 'bulletproof' approach with 3.d3, which enters the Bishop's opening, which will be analyzed in another chapter.  I would like to emphasize that the Urusov gambit, in the beginning, was a tricky 'joke' opening, but through time it has developed to a very high level.   The Urusov Gambit is an exciting option for the players whose main weapon and asset is their tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for Blitz and Rapid games, especially when lower-rated players are seated on the other side hopelessly trying to find a proper plan to defend as Black! On the other side of the pond, many top-level professional players used the Urusov Gambit as a surprise weapon during significant tournaments. They showed their opponents that they are ready to go into the wilderness to snatch the win!   So, fasten your seat belts and get ready to embark on an adventurous journey! }
3... exd4
{ Black takes the pawn and defers the decision whether to enter the Urusov gambit accepted for a couple of moves! We are ready for a road full of attacking opportunities and tactical possibilities! Practically this is the only good move here by Black and other moves such as  3...d6?  and  3...Nxe4?!  lead to dubious play for Black, while  3...Nc6  leads to the Scotch gambit type of positions! }
4. Nf3
{ The main idea of the Urusov gambit is to let Black take the pawns, while we develop pieces. One may think that White permits this material advantage to Black, but don't forget that sometimes one needs to give in order to gain! Whilst Black collects the pawns, they create the space for our developed and centralized pieces, and at the same time, White builds up an attack on Black's King, which still stands exposed in the center. }
4... Nxe4
{ Black takes the challenge and dives into Urusov gambit accepted! The Urusov Gambit accepted is a fun line that can give many opponents lots of trouble, so It might be wise for Black to decline this gambit, as there’s certainly nothing wrong with going back into the Scotch gambit. One thing is sure, when Black accepts the Urusov Gambit and takes on e4, White can easily launch a big attack on the Kingside, so get ready for slamming! The show must go on! }
5. Qxd4
{ This move gives White one of the most important pieces into the action in the Urusov gambit - The Queen! It will later move onto the Kingside Qd4-Qh4, from where it will attack the h7-square @@StartBracket@@usually with Bd3@@EndBracket@@, in addition with Bg5 and White will be able to complete his development with O-O-O with further possibilities for the attack on the Kingside! From this move onwards @@StartBracket@@for the next 6 moves@@EndBracket@@, I decided to put an exclamation mark on each move that presents a crucial part of the attacking plan Qd4-Nc3-Qh4-Bg5-O-O-O-Rhe1! }
5... Nf6
{ Practically the only move! Black decides to stay solid by moving the piece back into safety. Our main aim is to take advantage of the opportunity to play active and force Black to pay out the price while he was collecting pawns. It is quite interesting that engines already favor Black a lot here, but we won't bite that! }
6. Nc3
{ White develops the third minor piece, cunningly prepares for Bg5, followed by the long castle. To one, it might look logical to hurry up with putting the King into a safe zone @@StartBracket@@Kingside castle@@EndBracket@@, but the whole idea of the Urusov Gambit is to make the best out of the position by going into long castles! It is very important to follow the most accurate moves that did not allow Black to consolidate promptly. In that fashion, it is important to point out that  6.Bg5?!  would be suspicious due to  6...Nc6!  7.Qh4  and Black stabilizes and looks even better after  7...d5!  while after  6.Bg5?!  Nc6  if White goes for  7.Qe3  Black is better after  7...Qe7!  with a clear pawn up! }
6... Nc6
{ From my Online experience you are going to get this move in most of your games. There is a logical reason for that, it is developing move, it chases Queen on d4 away with the tempo and looks like Black gains an important move to consolidate himself. In the reality, things do not seem to work that easy for Black, as you are about to see... }
7. Qh4
{ After Black has developed a Knight with a tempo, White swings the Queen to the Kingside where the action will be taken.  7.Qh4  will be followed by Bg5 and O-O-O, altogether with Rhe1, which will conclude White's development.   The alternative  7.Qd3!?  deserves attention too. With the idea of  7...--  8.a3  stopping Black's 8...Nb4, and followed by  8...--  9.Bf4  and  9...--  10.O-O-O   White has an interesting position, as it can be seen in the game played between Tomek, D - Sydlik, J email 2012. }
7... Be7
{ Black chooses the most resilient move aiming to castle, but then they would be facing the same threats coming after Bg5 and O-O-O. }
8. Bg5
{ From this position, where White obviously has way better development, it is of great importance to once more remind Black of our plan - an attack on the Kingside and putting Rooks on the open d and e files after O-O-O! }
8... d6
{ Once again Black picks up the most stable option, most likely followed by Be6 to contrary our main attacker - Bc4. }
9. O-O-O
{ White has just completed his development with the Queenside castle and only one piece left to be developed - Rhe1 is coming soon into the game as well! }
9... Be6
{ This is the most solid answer by Black who tries to remove White's most active piece. }
10. Rhe1
{ Maybe you will be able to see also Bd3 as White's answer against Be6, but I have no doubt that 10.Rhe1! is the best move here.   With 10.Rhe1! White achieved what they always wanted - full development and great activity of all of the pieces. Of course, Black is now forced to react since the threat is to take a pawn by Bxe6. }
10... Bxc4
{ This is the only move that gives hope to Black. If Black decided to go for  10...Qd7?!  instead,  11.Bb5!  would put Black in an uncomfortable pin due to the Ne5 threat and White would be clearly better. }
11. Qxc4 O-O 12. Bxf6
{ This is a key moment in the variation! A lot of players @@StartBracket@@with both colors@@EndBracket@@ wouldn't even think about this move as a good option, but they are clearly mistaken! In order to treat the line properly, it is important to understand White's idea which comes after every different exchange. With Bxf6 White attempts to create space for the Knights, which will be reaching an outpost at d5 with direct Nd5, and another one at e4, after a maneuver like Kb1-Nd2-Ne4. }
12... Bxf6 13. Nd5
{ White goes for the previously mentioned plan, keeps the King safe on b1 square, and prepares for Nd2 with Ne4, at the same time avoiding the pin which would possibly be achieved by Black after Bg5. }
13... g6
{ This is a very good prophylactic move by Black who is now basically stoping the idea of Kb1, Nd2 and Ne4. However, with g6 Black gave another target to be attacked. }
14. h4
{ White is set to storm with a pawn! With the idea of h5, White threatens to open the space around Black's weakened King.   As an alternative,  14.c3  was played in a game between Burkett, M - Helmbrecht, J LSS email 2010, where White had an idea to play against dark-squared Black's Bishop.  14...Bg7  15.h4!  threatening h5, Black answered with  15...Qd7  with an idea of Rae8, and the game continued with  16.h5  Rac8  17.hxg6  hxg6  18.Qh4  with great initiative and attack for White, and the idea of Ng5 and Rh1. }
14... h6
{ Black tries to block White's attack and wants to play g5 if White continues with the idea of h5.   However, that would make new outposts on the light squares for the White's pieces. If Black decides to block White's attack with  14...h5?  he faces  15.g4!  which puts Black's King into an uncomfortable situation. }
15. h5
{ White goes further with the idea to open the space around Black's King. As an alternative, White can also go for  15.g4!  and after  15...Bg7  16.g5  h5  17.Kb1  White puts the King into safety and has decent initiative. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter "]
[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2...Nc6 3.Nc3 Bc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Bc5
{ This is a very common move by Black, who tends to develop the Kingside as soon as possible. Threatening the f2 pawn, Black might also choose to continue afterward with the tricky Qf6. Anyway, 3...Bc5?! is suspicious since g7 becomes vulnerable! I would like to point out that lots of weaker players go for it since it resembles the Italian Guicco Piano, and a majority of the players that like to do it hope that it is the same or at least very similar to it. Still, luckily for us, it is not! }
4. Qg4
{ This is the crucial move of this variation! We have to react aggressively and be on top of the task, so 4.Qg4 is mandatory for a serious opening advantage! Some of the players that go that far, claim how after the last move, White is close to being winning, I would not say so, but it is a huge opening advantage! White chooses the most aggressive approach with a direct threat to the g7 pawn and this continuation might look similar to a good version of the Patzers opening! }
4... Qf6
{ Although this is a suspicious move, it is the most frequent in my Blitz practice and games of my students online and, by stats, it was played in more than 300 games! White scored positively in 80% of the games, but to benefit from this suspicious attempt by Black, White has to understand that the pawn on f2 is not a priority! }
5. Nd5
{ White does not care about f2 hanging because Black has bigger issues with the c7 and f7 spots. Black is forced to continue with the original idea of Qxf2 and that would put Black's Queen into an uncomfortable position as it will be shown soon! }
5... Qxf2+ 6. Kd1
{ Whilst White's King is perfectly safe on d1 Black faces a lot of trouble trying to create or find available spots for the Queen. White's plan is simple, after Nh3 and Rf1 it is questionable if Black will be able to defend f7 and one should not forget that Nc7 is still there as a possible threat! On top of all that, if the Queen goes to d4, White should reply with d3 @@StartBracket@@to defend Bc4@@EndBracket@@ and afterward trap Queen with c3! }
6... Kf8
{ Almost all games from this line continued with 6...Kf8 by Black who aims to move the King away from a possible Nc7 check and to defend the g7 pawn from Qxg7 threat. Although, it does not stop us from executing our main attacking tricks... }
7. Nh3
{ We are ready to start the hunt on the Black's Queen that compromises Black's weak King as well which is miserably positioned on f8. Not only that White aims to continue with Rf1, but Black needs to figure out how to keep the Queen safe now! }
7... h5
{ In an already difficult position, this is the only move that does not immediately lead Black into a losing position.   Believe it or not, in more than 100 games, Black continued with  7...Qd4  and White were directly winning after  8.d3!  because Black's Queen was trapped in the center of the board! Black will be forced to move dark-squared Bishop from  c5  to make space for the Queen, and White will put undefendable pressure on  f7  after Rf1 and Qf3 or Qh5! }
8. Qg5
{ White certainly does not want to accept to exchange Queens in a position where Black's King is placed on f8 exposed to a pin after Rf1. Black is forced to go for the only moves to defend the position, but White, anyways, gains a huge advantage! }
8... Qd4 9. d3
{ Once again, White has a direct threat to win the game with c3 immediately. Queen is captured on d4 and Black is forced to move a Bishop away! }
9... Be7 10. Qg3
{ As it could be seen in the game between Mamedyarov, S-Harikrishnan, A 2020 chess.com, after a clever step back with 10.Qg3 White is ready for domination in a clearly better position with a plan of Rf1, Ng5, and c3. Whilst White's King is safe in the center on the d1 spot, Black's King is more than vulnerable and exposed to harsh attacks, altogether with the f7 pawn! }
*

