[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter "]
[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2...Nc6 3.Nc3 Bc5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Bc5
{ This is a very common move by Black, who tends to develop the Kingside as soon as possible. Threatening the f2 pawn, Black might also choose to continue afterward with the tricky Qf6. Anyway, 3...Bc5?! is suspicious since g7 becomes vulnerable! I would like to point out that lots of weaker players go for it since it resembles the Italian Guicco Piano, and a majority of the players that like to do it hope that it is the same or at least very similar to it. Still, luckily for us, it is not! }
4. Qg4
{ This is the crucial move of this variation! We have to react aggressively and be on top of the task, so 4.Qg4 is mandatory for a serious opening advantage! Some of the players that go that far, claim how after the last move, White is close to being winning, I would not say so, but it is a huge opening advantage! White chooses the most aggressive approach with a direct threat to the g7 pawn and this continuation might look similar to a good version of the Patzers opening! }
4... g6
{ This is the most resilient move by Black who is desperate to secure the King's safety after Kf8 and Kg7. One should not forget that Black also has a threat of d5, which needs to be prevented. }
5. Qf3
{ Black is once again forced to find good defensive moves whilst White prepares for development after Nge2, g3, and Bg5, and of course - Scholars mate on f7! }
5... Nf6
{ Instead of 5...Nf6 Black might think it is useful to exchange Queens in an early opening, thinking that that would help gain some space for pieces.   However, every exchange in this position fits well for White, since after  5...Qf6  6.Nd5  Qxf3  7.Nxf3  Bb6  8.c3  White has a clear long-term advantage of the Bishop pair which will be gained after Nxb6, and Black will struggle with a worse pawn structure as well. }
6. Nge2
{ With a simple developing move, White prevents Black's threat of Nd4 and aims to keep pressure after d3 and Bg5. Unlike Patzer's opening, where Black's Bishop stands on g7 and defends the Knight on f6; here, Black looks way more vulnerable since Nf6 lacks proper defense, or they have to lose tempo to defend it! Also, while Bg7 improves the defense of the dark squares, not only around the Knight but most importantly around the King and the extremely vulnerable dark-squares on the kingside! }
6... O-O
{ It is questionable if Black's King can feel safe on the Kingside. All the White's pieces are eyeing the King, and White is ready for an attack as it will be shown. }
7. d3
{ It is clear that White controls all the dark squares around Black's King and that Black has issues with a Knight on f6. White keeps developing, gaining tempos, and Black is forced to defend before continuing development. Threats are Bg5 and Bh6. }
7... Kg7 8. Bg5
{ Once again, White forces Black to step back and defend the Knight on f6 due to a threat of Nd5! }
8... Be7 9. h3
{ This is a significant prophylactic move by White who kills all Black's hopes for active play. With 9.h3, White stops possible d6 and Bg4 and gets ready for O-O-O, followed by Qe3 and f4! }
9... d6 10. Qe3
{ Faced with a threat of Bh6, Black is certainly not happy with this position after only ten moves of play. White's plan is easy after O-O-O, f4, and Rdf1 and a massive attack on the Kingside. Despite that, Black does not have hopes for any counter-play but only searches for a way to keep the King safe. }
