{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... Bc5
{ This is one of the main and most critical lines of the Bishop's opening. According to my playing experience, I faced this move frequently, and it seems that Black mostly chose 4...Bc5 with the idea to compromise White's King after Ng4. However, the positions reached afterward are maybe not so desirable according to the engines'. Still, I would say that they are a bit dangerous, and offer practical and interesting play with many tactical possibilities and attacking ideas. }
5. f4
{ White slides into a very aggressive Vienna Hybrid variation aiming to open the position and to develop an attack on the Kingside. If you have wondered where the White King is going to escape since it is obvious that O-O is not possible due to Bc5 which controls g1 square, of course, the answer is O-O-O! }
5... d6
{ It might look that this is just a solid move by Black, but actually White reaches a very interesting position to play afterward. Black aims to conquer the g4 spot very soon, going with the Bishop or the Knight over there. }
6. Nf3
{ White continues with the Vienna hybrid set-up and prepares for the possible Na4 aiming to overtake the Bishop pair which would be enticing in an open position such as this one. }
6... O-O
{ Castling looks like a quite natural move but, in fact, it is suspicious since it immediately allows White to gain space, light-squares control, and dangerous attack on the Kingside all of a sudden! }
7. f5
{ I enjoy this move and concept a lot in the Bishop's opening! White limits the scope of Black's pieces @@StartBracket@@mainly Bc8@@EndBracket@@ and opens the way for the dark-squared Bishop which would be very uncomfortable for Black after Bg5 and the idea of Nd5.   Instead of 7.f5! the interesting move  7.Na4!?  gives a slight advantage to White thanks to the Bishop pair that White will gain later on. }
7... Na5
{ It looks like Black can resolve all the problems if they manage to exchange the light-squared Bishop, but as it will be shown soon, that is not easy as it sounds. Also, it looks like Black lacks time in terms of getting a counterattack in the center with c6 and d5 or c6 followed by b5. }
8. Bg5
{ White continues with active development and pressures the Knight on f6 with an idea to continue with Nd5! }
8... Nxc4 9. dxc4
{ Although it looks that White has pawn structure weakness, the fact is that Black can not use it. All pawns are placed on the light squares and Black's Bishop on c8 has no good spot to go to attack them. Meanwhile, White got space for the pieces and aims to continue with an attack on the Kingside and pinned Knight on f6. }
9... Bb4
{ This is practically the only move that gives some kind of play for Black. Black has a direct threat of Bc3 and aims to create tripled pawns on the c-file to White. Anyway, White can choose to ignore that threat, and can continue with an attack on the Kingside! }
10. Nd2
{ White supports the e4 pawn and threatens to go for Nd5! At the same time, Queen is ready to be developed with Qf3 and White will be able to continue with the attack! }
10... Bxc3
{ Black has to create some counterpart and at least create a possibly weak tripled pawns and weakness on e4. Although, it will not release him from the extremely annoying pin on f6! }
11. bxc3
{ It is a fact that White has weaknesses on the c-file, but it is also a fact that Black can not reach them easily. For that reason, White needs to hurry to create an attack on the Kingside, not letting Black take control over the board. }
11... h6
{ Black aims to move the Bishop which uncomfortably pins Black, but the point is that White does not need to move it away! If Black decided to play  11...b6  instead, White would go for  12.h4!  Which reaches a similar position as the one which appears in this line afterward.  12.h4!  is aimed against any possible h6, and White will continue with Qf3 and g4 and a great attack on the Kingside! }
12. h4
{ As it was mentioned, White does not need to move the Bishop away! With this clever 12.h4! White defends the Bishop, because every opening of the h-file would be fatal for Black! Whilst White has a simple plan of Qf3, g4, O-O-O, Rdg1 with a threat of Bf6 followed by g5, Black has no quick action on the Queenside, and White's King is safe after Kb1 with a Knight on d2 which could be a good defender with a possible Nb3! }
