[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2...Nc6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.d3 Bc5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Nf6
{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... Bc5
{ This is one of the main and most critical lines of the Bishop's opening. According to my playing experience, I faced this move frequently, and it seems that Black mostly chose 4...Bc5 with the idea to compromise White's King after Ng4. However, the positions reached afterward are maybe not so desirable according to the engines'. Still, I would say that they are a bit dangerous, and offer practical and interesting play with many tactical possibilities and attacking ideas. }
5. f4
{ White slides into a very aggressive Vienna Hybrid variation aiming to open the position and to develop an attack on the Kingside. If you have wondered where the White King is going to escape since it is obvious that O-O is not possible due to Bc5 which controls g1 square, of course, the answer is O-O-O! }
5... d6
{ It might look that this is just a solid move by Black, but actually White reaches a very interesting position to play afterward. Black aims to conquer the g4 spot very soon, going with the Bishop or the Knight over there. }
6. Nf3
{ White continues with the Vienna hybrid set-up and prepares for the possible Na4 aiming to overtake the Bishop pair which would be enticing in an open position such as this one. }
6... Be6
{ This solid move I did not want to cover in the course, but since in online practice lately, I have faced it quite a few times and found it pretty solid for Black, it definitely deserves its place and has to be covered. I have tried both  7.Bb5  and  7.Bxe6  , but it looks like that the first one gives White richer chances! }
7. Bb5
{ White pins the Knight on c6 and consequently threatens pawn on e5. Although, as my practice has shown, we are not interested that much in the pawn on e5 as in breaking the pawn structure after  7...--  8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.fxe5  dxe5  , in which case Black has lots of difficulties to continue and defend a position with a broken pawn structure and White has a small but long-lasting advantage! }
7... a6
{ This seems to be a more solid option than 7...Bd7?! Although, White gets a stable and long-term advantage in the middle-game, due to the better pawn structure! }
8. Bxc6+
{ This is exactly what White wants! With the broken pawn structure, White should have a long-lasting static pawn structure advantage which means that White should be ok with exchanges afterward. Black, on the other hand, gets a potentially dangerous weapon - Bishop pair, that could be used successfully if the game gets more open! Keep in mind, that Bc5 remains quite an annoying piece and White has to do something about it. There is no better idea besides Qe2 followed by Be3 eventually! }
8... bxc6
{ Black is forced to play with a quite weak pawn structure, but as mentioned before, hopes for some activity and to be able to open the game for his bishops somehow. White, had something else on his mind, though! }
9. f5
{ A very smart move by White which closes the game and gives White better positional chances to fight the Bishop pair as well as the move Bg5 becomes possible in some lines as an annoying threat since Black can not easily unpin himself and defend the Knight on f6. Even though we have stated how Bg5 could be an option, the main idea by White is Qe2 followed by Be3! }
9... Bd7
{ This was quite expected. I find  9...Bc8  also as a possible option, followed by a5 and Ba6, although, White could easily shut it off and block that Bishop with b3 while after Qe2 and Be3, Black would be left without Bishop pair and with fairly bad light-squared Bishop without activity. }
10. Qe2
{ An important concept in our opening! Not only here, but in the whole chapter where Black goes for 4...Bc5, this dark-squared Bishop feels strong on that diagonal. White has to fight against that and there is no better way but with Be3. Afterward, the game would be relatively simple due to the healthier pawn structure and easy game on the Kingside with even a possibility to go with g4! in some positions! }
10... Qb8
{ Black has to do something on the Queenside and with the last move hopes to create a possible counter-attack along b-file and against b2 pawn mainly against the activity of the Bishop on c1. Also, an idea could be Qa7!? which would prevent our main idea of Be3, as well as even plan like Qb7, followed by O-O-O!?   I found few games in the past where Black tried a similar plan with  10...Rb8  but after my improvement  11.g4!  White can hope for the best due to nice aggressiveness on the Kingside as well as a stable game on the Queenside after b3. }
11. Nd1
{ A move of great positional value. It allows White to defend the pawn on b2, solidifies White's pawn structure, and gives more pawn structure flexibility with the c-pawn. Altogether with the previously mentioned continuation, another absolutely fine move is  11.b3  with a hyper solid position and surely long-term advantage due to the better pawn structure or even  11.g4!?  for those who enjoy more risky pawn moves and attacking chess! }
11... Qb5
{ There is no specific reason for this move, Black just makes his Queenside more solid, could be that in the case of b3, prepares a5-a4 minority attack, at the same time allows Rb8 or O-O-O, but basically, it does not improve Black's position particularly. }
12. c3
{ A pretty unexpected move in a similar type of position and pawn structures. Gives White more solidity and Be3 is about to happen, while the b2 pawn remains properly defended.   While I was analyzing this game, I was expecting and I was more a fan of  12.a4  followed by  12...--  13.b3  or vice versa  12.b3  followed by  13.a4  , which would point out how weak is the light-squared Bishop on  d7  for the rest of the game. }
12... a5 13. Be3
{ White had clearly better position in the game Fedorov, A - Norri, J Pula 1997 and went on to win fast. White's idea could be to recapture by the Knight on e3, supporting the g4-g5 pawn push, and then afterward retreat with Nf3-Nd2 to get better control of the center, have better hold of e4 pawn, and support g4 as well. All things considered, White has a stable positional advantage and Black can not do much, besides sitting and waiting! }
