[White "Quickstarter "]
[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2...Nc6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.d3 Na5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Nf6
{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... Na5
{ I do not doubt that 4...Na5 is the best answer by Black and at the same time statistically the most common answer by Black. It prevents 5.f4 at the moment and leaves White without the light-squared Bishop. However, things are not that bad for us either, considering the fact how many top players lately use the Bishop's opening and how high they score in this line! }
5. Bb3
{ Although  5.Nge2  was the most popular approach for decades, and  5.Qf3!?  in the past looked quite interesting, I decided to continue with  5.Bb3  . This decision is based on the resulting pawn structure and the open a-file, instead of giving many other options for Black, such as  6...c6  followed by  d5  and losing advantage in the center. This was not an easy decision but my final vote goes to 5.Bb3! }
5... Nxb3
{ Black decides to remove the light-squared killer and inflicts doubled pawns on White. It also allows for an easier break with d5 in the center and the Bishop pair advantage. However, this gives some pluses to White as it will be seen later! }
6. axb3
{ As it was previously said Black aims to inflict a bad pawn structure on White, but one should not forget that after 6. axb3 White gains an open a-file for the Rook on a1, which pressures the a7 square, and with the possible idea of the Rook lift with Ra4 or Ra5, Black could face troubles because of the weaknesses in the center. }
6... d5
{ Black chooses the most principled reaction in the center aiming to take back some central control. }
7. Nf3
{ White accelerates development, prepares for castling, and, at the same time, attacks Black's e5 pawn. The idea is very simple, to conclude the development and to use the open files! }
7... dxe4
{ With this move Black hopes to exchange the Queens and to enter a solid endgame. Of course, White is not gonna bite that bullet! We keep searching for the initiative with lots of pieces still on the board! }
8. Nxe5
{ As we previously said, we are going to search for complications. Not only that White improves the position of the Knight, but aims to play d4 and O-O, gaining full central control and a weakness to attack, Black's pawn on e4.   It is important to point out that there is also the  8.dxe4  possibility, where the game is objectively equal, but White has scored perfectly so far. }
8... exd3
{ Black aims to open the position and to prevent White's idea of creating a big center after the previously mentioned d4. However, White does not need to react immediately, but keeps on developing! }
9. O-O
{ This is a very important move before taking the pawn on d3 back.   One should not forget that Black can not answer with  9...dxc2  due to  10.Qxd8  Kxd8  and after  11.Nxf7  White gains a winning position with a Rook up! }
9... Be7
{ Black supports the Queen on d8 and now threatens to take 10...dxc2 and to continue with development and O-O.   However, if  9...Bd6  was played instead, White reaches a nice position after  10.Nxd3  O-O  11.Qf3!  aiming to play Bg5, and after  11...Re8  White needs to answer with  12.h3  preventing 12...Bg4 and threatening to go for  12...--  13.Bg5  which would put Black's Knight on  f6  in an uncomfortable pin. }
10. Nxd3
{ It is time for White to take a pawn back and to continue with activation with Qf3, and the forthcoming Rd1, or Re1, gaining activity on the open files. }
10... O-O
{ Both sides are about to complete their development. Not a while ago, in February 2021, there was a game between Dubov and Vidit where Black found an improvement over the main game Firouzja - Carlsen and went for  10...Bg4!?  after which White went for  11.Qe1  O-O  but failed to recognize the chance to get a solid advantage after the improvement  12.h3!  Bf5  13.Qe3!  and in the case of  13...Bxd3?!  White would have  14.Rd1!  with a small but long-lasting advantage. }
11. Qf3
{ This is the most active move for White who activates the Queen. Not only that the Queen found the most active square, but White also pressures the b7 pawn and keeps Black's Bishop locked to the starting position. The rook on a1 still pressures the a7 pawn, and in one word, White buys time to activate Rook from f1 to d1. }
11... c6
{ Black blocks the diagonal h1-a8 and the attack on the b7 pawn, threatening to develop the light-squared Bishop with tempo attack on the White's Queen. }
12. h3
{ A very important move for White which prevents the 12...Bg4 move. White's idea is to conclude the development with 13. Rd1, pinning Black's Queen, and aiming to afterward discover-attack the d-file with Nf4, or a possible Nc5. }
12... Re8
{ Black also activates their pieces. Of course, a good alternative for Black would be  12...Be6  but that does not affect our plan of  13.Rd1! }
13. Rd1
{ White has almost finished the development and has two open files for the Rooks and nicely positioned pieces. With the idea of Be3, White aims to activate all of the pieces and to put pressure on the a7 weakened square. }
13... Be6
{ Black aims to reach the outpost on  d5  , with the ideas of  13.--  14...Nd5  or  14...Bd5  , which would at the same time blocks the semi-opened d-file for White's  Rd1  . }
14. Be3
{ White finishes development and gains a small advantage based on activity. The Rook on a1, altogether with Be3, controls, and pressures the a7 weakness, forcing Black to react, whilst Black's Queen on d8 is pinned by the Rook on d1 and Black also needs to think about Nc5 or Nf4 threats.   The full plan and forthcoming approach by White could be seen in the game Firouzja, A -Carlsen, M chess24.com INT 2020.   However, White can also go for a pretty solid alternative, such as  13.Nc5  instead of  13.Be3  . Mainly, Black's primary square for regrouping the pieces is d5 and the move  13.Nc5  directly prevents the good outpost and Black's idea of Nd5 or Bd5, which in some lines could be enough for Black to equalize the position. }
