{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White has not played Nf3 yet to place pressure on the e5 pawn. On the other hand, Black prepares his own central advance with d5. From my own experience, it turned out that the last move 3...c6 was mainly used by stronger players or players who were familiar with the opening theory. Also, one should not forget that after:   3...Nc6  4.Nc3  the game transposes into lines explained within the 1.e4 e5 2.Bc4 Nc6 chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... d5
{ Black builds a center with a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. If Black instead goes for  4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  the position transposes to a sideline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  c6  4...Be7  , covered in 4...Be7 }
5. Bb3
{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Nbd7
{ A normal developing move that also protects e5. However, I am always feeling skeptical when this Knight blocks the development of the Bishop on c8 and the contact between the Queen and d5-pawn. We will see the consequences soon! }
6. O-O
{ First of all, castling is always useful as White wants to place the Rook on  e1  , indirectly pressuring the central  e5  pawn! Right now, there is an obvious threat of  6...--  7.exd5  followed by Re1 or Nc3 which pressures the d5-pawn and makes Black's center quite exposed and weak. }
6... Bd6
{ Not only that Black goes for development, but they aim to support the e5-pawn as well. }
7. exd5
{ Like in many instances when the Black Knight is on d7, White uses development advantage to harass Black's central pawns! }
7... cxd5
{ Even though it looks that Black established full center control, the fact is that d5 and e5 pawns are vulnerable and will be targets of White's attacks! }
8. Nc3
{ White continues with active development and forces Black to advance with the d5-pawn. }
8... d4
{ Black practically goes for the only way to keep the pawn. Stubbornly defending d5 leaves e5 unprotected so  8...Nb6?!  would give a clear advantage to White after easy  9.Re1  . }
9. Nb5
{ This is a very useful move in many lines. Black's dark-squared Bishop has to keep contact with the e5-pawn in order to protect it and White will use that to transfer the Bishop to the a3-f8 diagonal. The fact that Black still has not castled is just a plus to our plan! Despite that, Black will have issues with very strong Bishop on b3 eyeing the f7-spot. }
9... Bb8 10. Bd2
{ As mentioned, White is ready to swing the Bishop to b4- stopping Black's castling! }
10... a5
{ The only way for Black to continue the game is to prevent Bb4 by any means. The drawback is that the Knight will remain on the wonderful b5-square. The alternatives for Black are bleak:  10...O-O?  Is losing to  11.Bb4  Re8  12.Ng5!  and Black can not defend the f7-pawn anymore!  Instead, if Black plays  10...Qb6  after  11.Na3  White has a clear advantage, and Nc4 comes in with a great effect. Undermining with the c-pawn is also promising here. }
11. Re1
{ With an important intermediary move, White develops another piece and once again threatens Black's central pawns due to a pinned King. }
11... O-O 12. a4
{ Not only that White secures a space advantage with this move, but it also improves eternal Knight on b5. Black is completely tied up. Soon, the c3 approach will come in, and then after the trade, the dark-squared Bishop will reach a perfect position on the c3 square, attacking the e5-pawn. On the other hand, Black's Rook might not be very mobile due to the weakness on f7, and Black will have difficulties activating the Queenside as well. White is clearly better! }
