{ Berlin defense by Black! This is absolutely the most frequent move by Black against the Bishop's opening. Another common option especially on the lower level is  2...Nc6  , but 2...Nf6 is by far way more common in the practice! With the last move, Black aims to stay active, threatens White's central pawn on  e4  , and enters the Berlin defense. }
3. d3
{ Already at the third move, White has an opportunity to pick up the aggressive approach with the Urusov Gambit  3.d4!?  or to choose a more peaceful approach with 3.d3 which enters the Bishop's opening. Both options are fully covered throughout the course.  The Urusov Gambit is very interesting for the players whose main weapon is the tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for blitz and rapid games, especially when the beginner seats on the other side and tries to find a proper plan to defend as Black.  On the other side, 3.d3 provides a stable and safe positional approach without sacrifices or material losses and it gives flexible positions where White has initiative and the attack which is mainly based on equal material and clear activity. Interestingly, it is used in almost 80% of the games at this point and while  3.d4  was used mainly only once by top players in a blitz or rapid games, nowadays 3.d3 move presents a bulletproof approach by literally all top players including Carlsen, Nepo, Caruana, Firouzja, Grischuk, and other top players! }
3... c6
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White has not played Nf3 yet to place pressure on the e5 pawn. On the other hand, Black prepares his own central advance with d5. From my own experience, it turned out that the last move 3...c6 was mainly used by stronger players or players who were familiar with the opening theory. Also, one should not forget that after:   3...Nc6  4.Nc3  the game transposes into lines explained within the 1.e4 e5 2.Bc4 Nc6 chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... d5
{ Black builds a center with a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. If Black instead goes for  4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  the position transposes to a sideline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  c6  4...Be7  , covered in 4...Be7 }
5. Bb3
{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Bb4+
{ Black has a large number of options but this check is one of the most frequent in this position. Black aims to stop White to develop the Knight to c3 from where it would press the d5 pawn. }
6. Bd2
{ This is practically the only option for White to block the check. Instead,  6.Nc3  runs into  6...d4  , while Black would be happy to see  6.c3  Bd6  when White will have issues with e4 pawn and lousy center. }
6... Bd6
{ If Black decides to retreat the Bishop, not only that he loses one tempo, but White is able to continue with the most active development, Nc3, O-O Re1. }
7. Nc3
{ Of course, White is not missing the opportunity to increase the pressure on d5, and now Black has a huge decision to make- shall they advance with d4, shall the center open up with dxe4, or shall they keep the tension by defending d5? }
7... dxe4
{ Although the position looks innocuous now, as it will be shown, White is able to launch a tremendous attack! }
8. Ng5
{ Get ready for a crushing attack and believe it or not, one of my favorite games in this opening! Because of this game, I started to like and play Bishop's opening! Everything happened, while I was a commentator for Montreal Chessbrah and who could be better to follow but at that time our first board - Fabiano Caruana back in 2018 when he was in his best shape ever! White wins a tempo now and attacks the vulnerable f7 spot. All White's pieces will move towards the Kingside as it will be shown soon! You should be aware that White's idea is not to move the Knight from g5 back to a center, but to continue with attack after Nce4, Bg5, and possibly Qh5 later on! }
8... O-O 9. Ncxe4
{ As it was already said, White keeps both Knight in play on the Kingside aiming to create a tremendous mating attack! Taking the pawn with  9.Ngxe4  would give Black chances to keep the tension with  9...Be7  , and he would have time for development and defense. }
9... Be7
{ Black is aware that White tends to continue the attack with Qh5 and Bh5. For that reason, he wants to make sure that Knight on c6 is supported for a while. Anyway, that does not stop White's attack who now turns to a pawn-storm attack! }
10. h4
{ A very important move for the White's setup as he will want to recapture on g5  @@StartBracket@@should Black take with the bishop or h6-hxg5@@EndBracket@@ with the pawn and open the h-file. }
10... Nbd7
{ Trying to exchange both pairs of knights on e4, if possible. Black would also be happy to trade one pair of knights and bring his defender to f6. }
11. Qf3
{ Since the h5 spot is not available anymore for the Queen, White goes for activation through the f3 square! This excellent move prevents exchanges and allows us to build a strong attack! }
11... Qe8
{ Black needs to cover the f7-spot before the trade with  Ne4  . If he immediately goes for  11...Nxe4  12.Bxf7!  comes with a check! }
12. O-O-O
{ Not only that White concludes development with this move, but goes for the further activation while Black is locked on the back rank! The Rook will come to the e-file with Rde1 pressuring the e5-pawn. There is also a possible center advance of d4, when the Black's Queen on e8 will be indirectly pinned. }
12... a5
{ Black needs to try to gain any activity and his only possibility is to hunt the light-squared Bishop with pawns. However, this is just a temporary threat that can be easily stopped. }
13. a3
{ White is ready for possible a4 advance and has a nice safe spot for the light-squared Bishop. That means that we can continue with the attack very soon! }
13... Nd5 14. Rde1
{ White just ignores Black's moves now and already threatens to go for d4!   Full line! }
