{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White has not played Nf3 yet to place pressure on the  e5  pawn. On the other hand, Black prepares his own central advance with d5. From my own experience, it turned out that the last move 3...c6 was mainly used against stronger players or guys who were familiar with an opening theory. Also, one should not forget that after  3...Nc6  4.Nc3  the game transposes into lines explained within the  chapter 1.e4 e5 2.Bc4 Nc6. }
4. Nf3
{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... d5
{ Black builds a center with a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. If Black instead goes for  4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  the position transposes to a sideline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  c6  4...Be7  , covered in the lines #1 to #9 }
5. Bb3
{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Bb4+
{ Black has a large number of options but this check is one of the most frequent in this position. Black aims to stop White to develop the Knight to c3 from where it would press the d5 pawn. }
6. Bd2
{ This is practically the only option for White to block the check. Instead,  6.Nc3  runs into  6...d4  , while Black would be happy to see  6.c3  Bd6  when White will have issues with e4 pawn and lousy center. }
6... Bxd2+
{ Black accepts the trade and assumes that White will need to go for Nbd2- putting the Knight on the clumsy square to defend the pawn on e4. However, this is not going to happen! }
7. Qxd2
{ This is a very important move for White. Not only that there is a threat of Qg5, with an attack on both the  g7 and e5 pawns, but White keeps an option to develop the Knight on the most active square with Nc3, eyeing Black's vulnerable central pawns. It is clear that the e4 pawn does not really hang here, since e5 hangs as well. }
7... a5
{ This is an important intermediate move that anticipates a long castle intending to disturb the coordination of White's  pieces. The key benefit of such intrusion is that for now it prevents the nasty plan of Qg5! }
8. a3
{ White opens the space for the Bishop's retreat and renews the threat against the e5 pawn. The idea is to continue with Qg5, eyeing both g7 and e5 spots! }
8... Qd6
{ Black needs to employ the Queen to defend the e5 pawn. Development of the Knight looks logical but it is suspicious, since after  8...Nbd7?!  9.exd5!  cxd5  10.Nc3  White gained a clear advantage with terrible pressure on Black's center, as it happened in the game Mamedov, R-Maurizzi, M EU-chT 2019. In the case of  10...Nc5  there are two possibilities:  -  11.Nxe5  Nxb3  12.cxb3   - or the calm  11.Ba2  when the pawns are still hanging.   10.Nc3  10...d4  is met by the strong  11.Nb5  with 12.O–O, 13.Rfe1 and a possible Ng5. }
9. Qg5
{ It is a fact that with this move, we break some opening rules by playing with the Queen twice, but it is all for a good reason. It is not a primitive urge to win a pawn. Actually, we are not even able to. Our idea is much more clever; we want to force the exchanges in a way that benefits us! }
9... O-O
{ Black decides to temporarily give the e5-pawn in order to speed up the development. However, there is a neat way for White to establish a strong outpost and seize the advantage here! }
10. Qxe5
{ White should not hesitate to enter an endgame with a pawn up! It is the truth that Black will be able to take the pawn back, but that will lead to other weaknesses, which White might use for creating a good play! }
10... Qxe5
{ Black has to trade the Queens in order to win the pawn back, but we are ready for that! }
11. Nxe5 dxe4
{ Just as in related lines,  11...Re8  would be bad for Black as after  12.f4  Black cannot take on  e4  because the f7-spot stays unprotected! }
12. d4
{ The whole point of White's logic behind 9.Qg5! is shown now! The files will remain closed, and the Knight is established on the e5 outpost. Meanwhile, Black's e4 pawn will come under attack, and f7 will be vulnerable as well. }
12... Nbd7
{ Black's only chance to finish the development is to challenge the Knight on e5. However, we do not need to escape from this trade since it will lead to an attack on the Knight on f6 that defends the e5 pawn! }
13. Nc3
{ White just continues with normal development, aiming to put King into safety after O-O-O, when the Rook will be nicely placed on the d-file! }
13... Nxe5
{ Black finds that he has the best chances if he trades. However, it is possible to avoid the exchange with  13...Nb6  14.O-O-O  , but here, White enjoys a clear advantage due to the weaknesses on  e4  and  f7  . The e4–pawn will be attacked by  Re1  , and if Black defends it with  Bf5  , then the  h3–g4  advance will be crushing. }
14. dxe5
{ Not only that with this trade, White gets to attack Nf6 that defends the e4 pawn, but also after the forthcoming O-O-O, White will have full control over the opened d-file! }
14... Ng4 15. Nxe4 Nxe5 16. O-O-O
{ The material is even, and the pawn structure is nearly symmetrical, but White's advantage is obvious. We are ahead in development, with the Bishop on the powerful diagonal @@StartBracket@@pressuring f7@@EndBracket@@ and the Rook conveniently castled on the open d-file. Black has huge trouble getting the light-squared Bishop out and connecting the Rooks. Black might continue here with  16...Bd7  17.f4  , but then he faces issues with them both hanging Knight and Bishop;   If he continues with  16...Bf5  ,  17.Nd6  comes with a double attack on the  b7  pawn and the Bishop on f5;   The last possibility for Black to develop is to continue with  16...Bg4  17.f3  comes, and Black once again faces difficulties with the position of the Bishop. Black's Knight is also shaky and will quickly come under attack utilizing Re1 or f4. Meanwhile, White's Knight has a range of great jumps, including d6, g5, and even c5. All White's ideas and possibilities can be seen in a game between Svidler, P-Navara, D chess24.com INT 2020. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Bishop's Opening 2...Nf6: Berlin Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's opening 2...Nf6: 3.d3 Bc5 4. Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nf6
{ Berlin defense by Black! This is absolutely the most frequent move by Black against the Bishop's opening. Another common option especially on the lower level is  2...Nc6  , but 2...Nf6 is by far way more common in the practice! With the last move, Black aims to stay active, threatens White's central pawn on  e4  , and enters the Berlin defense. }
3. d3
{ Already at the third move, White has an opportunity to pick up the aggressive approach with the Urusov Gambit  3.d4!?  or to choose a more peaceful approach with 3.d3 which enters the Bishop's opening. Both options are fully covered throughout the course.  The Urusov Gambit is very interesting for the players whose main weapon is the tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for blitz and rapid games, especially when the beginner seats on the other side and tries to find a proper plan to defend as Black.  On the other side, 3.d3 provides a stable and safe positional approach without sacrifices or material losses and it gives flexible positions where White has initiative and the attack which is mainly based on equal material and clear activity. Interestingly, it is used in almost 80% of the games at this point and while  3.d4  was used mainly only once by top players in a blitz or rapid games, nowadays 3.d3 move presents a bulletproof approach by literally all top players including Carlsen, Nepo, Caruana, Firouzja, Grischuk, and other top players! }
3... Bc5
{ This is a logical attempt by Black to castle quickly and start the fight in the center. At the same time, Black aims to use the lag of White's development on the Kingside, eyeing the f2 pawn. It is a common idea by a big number of players since they think our main 'Vienna-Hybrid idea' with f4 will not be possible afterward. Let us see if that is true... }
4. Nc3
{ Of course, White continues with normal development but still keeps the other Knight to the starting g1 position, getting ready for Vienna-Hybrid lines after f4! }
4... O-O 5. f4
{ White slides into a very aggressive Vienna-Hybrid variation aiming to open the position and to develop an attack on the Kingside. One can ask a logical question here, wondering where White's King settles since O-O is not possible due to Bc5, which controls the g1-square; the answer is that White will either go with O-O-O or even keeping the King in the center is a good solution, as it will be shown soon! }
5... d6
{ This looks like a normal developing move where Black supports the e5-pawn and opens up the Bishop. However, this is exactly what White wants! }
6. f5
{ White seizes space on the Kingside and limits the scope of Black's pieces, especially the Bishop on c8. At the same time, White opens up for the dark-squared Bishop which will go to the desirable g5-square, dropping an uncomfortable pin on the Knight on f6, with a threat of Nd5! }
6... c6
{ Black searches for the initiative in the center attempting the break with d5 that might be very uncomfortable with a double attack on e4 and the Bishop on c4. }
7. Qf3
{ White strikes back and easily prevents d5, transferring the Queen towards the opponent's King. In these types of games, Qf3 is a relatively standard idea since it fights for the central control @@StartBracket@@prevents d5@@EndBracket@@ and allows the even more important - attacking g4-g5 plan! }
7... b5
{ Black still tries to find a way to distract White's pieces from the attack and aims to hunt the light-squared Bishop which is one of the most important pieces for an attack. However, White does not face danger after a simple step-back move. }
8. Bb3 a5
{ Black continues to search for activity on the Queenside and hunts the Bishop on b3. However, White once again has an easy solution to keep the Bishop safe. }
9. a3
{ The Bishop is secured, and White can proceed with Kingside plans and the pawn-storm with g4, h4, and g5! }
9... Ba7
{ A normal move where Black wants to see White's main idea, but at the same time, Black wants to maneuver with Na6-Nc5 or Nbd7-Nc5 where we plan on harassing the Bishop on b3 with tempo and have a more active and better fight in the center. }
10. g4
{ As it could be seen in the game Gappel, H-Teipel, T Remote email 2013, White is set to storm with the g5, h4, and h5 pawns with a huge attack on the Black's King. On the other hand, Black doesn't have many possibilities for counterattack due to the badly positioned and locked-up pieces on the Queenside. An interesting fact is that the engine funnily gives Black slightly better chances in the game, and this is one of those positions where I am ready to bet with anyone that out of 10 games, you will win at least 9 since I'll just count a game that Black wins if we maybe blunder the Queen in one of them! }
*

