1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nf6
{ Berlin defense by Black! This is absolutely the most frequent move by Black against the Bishop's opening. Another common option especially on the lower level is  2...Nc6  , but 2...Nf6 is by far way more common in the practice! With the last move, Black aims to stay active, threatens White's central pawn on  e4  , and enters the Berlin defense. }
3. d3
{ Already at the third move, White has an opportunity to pick up the aggressive approach with the Urusov Gambit  3.d4!?  or to choose a more peaceful approach with 3.d3 which enters the Bishop's opening. Both options are fully covered throughout the course.  The Urusov Gambit is very interesting for the players whose main weapon is the tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for blitz and rapid games, especially when the beginner seats on the other side and tries to find a proper plan to defend as Black.  On the other side, 3.d3 provides a stable and safe positional approach without sacrifices or material losses and it gives flexible positions where White has initiative and the attack which is mainly based on equal material and clear activity. Interestingly, it is used in almost 80% of the games at this point and while  3.d4  was used mainly only once by top players in a blitz or rapid games, nowadays 3.d3 move presents a bulletproof approach by literally all top players including Carlsen, Nepo, Caruana, Firouzja, Grischuk, and other top players! }
3... Bc5
{ This is a logical attempt by Black to castle quickly and start the fight in the center. At the same time, Black aims to use the lag of White's development on the Kingside, eyeing the f2 pawn. It is a common idea by a big number of players since they think our main 'Vienna-Hybrid idea' with f4 will not be possible afterward. Let us see if that is true... }
4. Nc3
{ Of course, White continues with normal development but still keeps the other Knight to the starting g1 position, getting ready for Vienna-Hybrid lines after f4! }
4... O-O 5. f4
{ White slides into a very aggressive Vienna-Hybrid variation aiming to open the position and to develop an attack on the Kingside. One can ask a logical question here, wondering where White's King settles since O-O is not possible due to Bc5, which controls the g1-square; the answer is that White will either go with O-O-O or even keeping the King in the center is a good solution, as it will be shown soon! }
5... d5
{ Yuriy Krykun suggests this interesting counterstrike, and I have to say that White has to be well booked up if they want to fight properly for an advantage against quite a surprising and attractive suggestion by Black! Black could also go for the tame  5...exf4  , but that allows White to gain full central control after  6.Bxf4  c6  when Black wants to play d5 and disturb White's coordination while the King is still in the center, but after  7.d4  +/=, White is slightly better as he managed to build the center and pushed the Black pieces back.  Instead, Black can play and  5...Nc6  . Trying to develop the pieces while remaining flexible in the center, but the downside is that c6–d5 is no longer possible.  6.Nf3  White puts more pressure on the  e5  pawn in an attempt to force Black's  d6  , with a plan of f5–Bg5–Qd2 and O-O-O White will be able to start a powerful Kingside attack! }
6. Nxd5
{ The straightforward capture of the pawn provides White a stable advantage. Black can not develop the light-squared Bishop on g4 due to the threat of Nf6, leaving the Bishop unprotected, and it is questionable if Black can find a good compensation for a pawn here. }
6... Nxd5
{ Black tends to clear the way for the Queen check on h4, but White should not have concerns about that thanks to full center control! }
7. Bxd5 Bxg1
{ To be able to realize the benefit from Qh4, Black needs to first take the Rook away from the defense of the h2 pawn. }
8. Rxg1 Qh4+
{ Black proceeds with a counterattack on the Kingside, but White should not be worried about it. One should not forget that Black's Queen on  h2  will out of play. Instead of an immediate check, Black can also play intermediary  8...c6  9.Bb3  Qh4  10.g3  Qxh2  11.Be3  entering a similar position as it will be shown here, where White has a clear long-term advantage of the Bishop pair, while Black has a marginalized Queen on the h-file. }
9. g3 Qxh2 10. Be3
{ And White gains a clear advantage holding the Bishop pair in the fairly open position. Additionally, the Black's Queen is terribly sidelined, and one should not forget that Black traded the important central d-pawn for White's edged h-pawn. The opening of the h-file might be White's advantage with possible actions on the Kingside after f5, Rc1 or Bf2, Qf3 and Rh1 or even simple Qd2 with much better middlegame chances! }
