6... Ng4
{ Black is way too optimistic if they go for the material advantage with Nf2, for which White does not care! We can welcome Black's waste of time and effort by continuing with our own actions against Black's King! }
7. f5
{ Limiting the scope of the Black pieces and opens the way up for the dark-squared Bishop, White is ready for Qh5 followed by Bg5 and f6! }
7... Nf2
{ Black is forced to proceed with the previous idea and hopes to gain a decisive material advantage. However, there will be no escape for Black's King afterward! }
8. Qh5
{ As it was previously mentioned, White does not care about the Rook on h1, but prepares for Bg5 and f6, after the Queen has joined the attack with a powerful effect. White is ready to conquer dark squares around Black's King! }
8... Nxh1 9. Bg5
{ Despite being a Rook down, White has a decisive advantage with many pieces looming over the head of Black's King. Black obviously can not defend with  9...f6  due to a discovered check with  10.Nxf6+ !     If Black tries to move the Queen away with  9...Qe8  White wins after  10.Nf6+ !  gxf6  11.Bxf6  with an undefendable mate after  11...--  12.Qg5  or Qg7#!   Of course,  9...Qd6  would be met with  10.f6!  and White gains full control of the dark squares around Black's King!  This is an important note - this is one of the critical tactical motifs in the whole Bishop's opening - the setup with Bc4, Nd5, Bg5, and Qh5 and White has to be familiar with it and similar attacking ideas! }
