6... Be6
{ Black aims to force White to trade the active pieces, but with a pawn up, White has no problem to accept that offer! }
7. Nxf6+
{ White accepts the trades and simplifies the position with a pawn up on the board. Black needs to be precise to take the material back, but White will have full center control afterwards, as it will be explained soon! }
7... Qxf6 8. Bxe6 fxe6
{ Black managed to open the f-file for Queen and the Rook, stopping White to keep the material advantage. However, White continues with development and solid play, having a slight advantage based on Black's bad pawns on the e-file. }
9. Nf3
{ With a simple development move, White threatens Black's pawn on e5, and Black is forced to react. }
9... exf4 10. c3
{ As it was mentioned, White is ready to build a center fortress with full control. The game started quite sharp but after the dust has settled, White will enjoy a fine positional advantage, as it will be shown soon. }
10... Nc6
{ Black proceeds with development and prepares to join the Rook in a game after Rad8. However, that does not stop White to build the center! }
11. d4
{ White finally reaches full-center control! To better understand the position, it is important to emphasize that White's play is no longer oriented to a Kingside, but White will search for action on the Queenside after the forthcoming b4 and a4! }
11... Bb6 { Black steps back and keeps an eye on the White's center. } 12. b4
{ In anticipation of the Black's counterplay in the center, White seizes the space on the Queenside. The advance has more than this sole purpose:1@@EndBracket@@ it puts pressure on the Black's pieces that are targeting the center with an idea of a4.   2@@EndBracket@@ it takes away control of the a5 square from the Black's Knight.   3@@EndBracket@@ it clears the second rank for the Rook maneuver of Ra2, coming after a4! }
12... e5
{ Black's only chance for activation is to attack the center, but White has no issues after the Queenside activity! }
13. a4
{ With a direct threat to capture the Bishop on b6, White at the same time buys time for center support after Ra2 and Re2! }
13... exd4
{ With White's King in the center, Black tries to compensate the loss of a Bishop after a5, but White will have a possibility to hide the King with O-O after removing Black's dark squared Bishop. }
14. a5 dxc3
{ Black's idea is to double attack the Queen on  d1  and the Rook on  a1  after a forthcoming  15...c2  . However, thanks to a clever intermediary move which will be shown soon, White will be able to escape! }
15. axb6 c2 16. Qd5+
{ This elegant intermediate check secures the material advantage for White! We are ready to block the a1-h8 diagonal after e5 and castling, solving our  issues, and a better position! }
16... Kh8 17. e5
{ White should not be worried about the forthcoming pin Rae8, because the King is ready to go castle, and one should not forget that White has a Bishop on c1 as a main defensive asset! }
17... Rae8 18. O-O
{ With the King finally safe, White can enjoy the material advantage and a clearly better position. After the trades on e5 with  19...Nxe5  20.Nxe5  Rxe5  White should just take care and place the Queen on  d4  , preventing the discovered attacks along the a1-h8 diagonal. Thereafter, bxa7, Rxf4, and Bb2 will be strong threats. }
