[White "1) Bishop's Opening 2...Nf6: Berlin Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's opening 2...Nf6: 3.d3 Bc5 4. Nc3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nf6
{ Berlin defense by Black! This is absolutely the most frequent move by Black against the Bishop's opening. Another common option especially on the lower level is  2...Nc6  , but 2...Nf6 is by far way more common in the practice! With the last move, Black aims to stay active, threatens White's central pawn on  e4  , and enters the Berlin defense. }
3. d3
{ Already at the third move, White has an opportunity to pick up the aggressive approach with the Urusov Gambit  3.d4!?  or to choose a more peaceful approach with 3.d3 which enters the Bishop's opening. Both options are fully covered throughout the course.  The Urusov Gambit is very interesting for the players whose main weapon is the tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for blitz and rapid games, especially when the beginner seats on the other side and tries to find a proper plan to defend as Black.  On the other side, 3.d3 provides a stable and safe positional approach without sacrifices or material losses and it gives flexible positions where White has initiative and the attack which is mainly based on equal material and clear activity. Interestingly, it is used in almost 80% of the games at this point and while  3.d4  was used mainly only once by top players in a blitz or rapid games, nowadays 3.d3 move presents a bulletproof approach by literally all top players including Carlsen, Nepo, Caruana, Firouzja, Grischuk, and other top players! }
3... Bc5
{ This is a logical attempt by Black to castle quickly and start the fight in the center. At the same time, Black aims to use the lag of White's development on the Kingside, eyeing the f2 pawn. It is a common idea by a big number of players since they think our main 'Vienna-Hybrid idea' with f4 will not be possible afterward. Let us see if that is true... }
4. Nc3
{ Of course, White continues with normal development but still keeps the other Knight to the starting g1 position, getting ready for Vienna-Hybrid lines after f4! }
4... O-O 5. f4
{ White slides into a very aggressive Vienna-Hybrid variation aiming to open the position and to develop an attack on the Kingside. One can ask a logical question here, wondering where White's King settles since O-O is not possible due to Bc5, which controls the g1-square; the answer is that White will either go with O-O-O or even keeping the King in the center is a good solution, as it will be shown soon! }
5... d5
{ Yuriy Krykun suggests this interesting counterstrike, and I have to say that White has to be well booked up if they want to fight properly for an advantage against quite a surprising and attractive suggestion by Black! Black could also go for the tame  5...exf4  , but that allows White to gain full central control after  6.Bxf4  c6  when Black wants to play d5 and disturb White's coordination while the King is still in the center, but after  7.d4  +/=, White is slightly better as he managed to build the center and pushed the Black pieces back.  Instead, Black can play and  5...Nc6  . Trying to develop the pieces while remaining flexible in the center, but the downside is that c6–d5 is no longer possible.  6.Nf3  White puts more pressure on the  e5  pawn in an attempt to force Black's  d6  , with a plan of f5–Bg5–Qd2 and O-O-O White will be able to start a powerful Kingside attack! }
6. Nxd5
{ The straightforward capture of the pawn provides White a stable advantage. Black can not develop the light-squared Bishop on g4 due to the threat of Nf6, leaving the Bishop unprotected, and it is questionable if Black can find a good compensation for a pawn here. }
6... Be6
{ Black aims to force White to trade the active pieces, but with a pawn up, White has no problem to accept that offer! }
7. Nxf6+
{ White accepts the trades and simplifies the position with a pawn up on the board. Black needs to be precise to take the material back, but White will have full center control afterwards, as it will be explained soon! }
7... Qxf6 8. Bxe6 fxe6
{ Black managed to open the f-file for Queen and the Rook, stopping White to keep the material advantage. However, White continues with development and solid play, having a slight advantage based on Black's bad pawns on the e-file. }
9. Nf3
{ With a simple development move, White threatens Black's pawn on e5, and Black is forced to react. }
9... exf4 10. c3
{ As it was mentioned, White is ready to build a center fortress with full control. The game started quite sharp but after the dust has settled, White will enjoy a fine positional advantage, as it will be shown soon. }
10... Nc6
{ Black proceeds with development and prepares to join the Rook in a game after Rad8. However, that does not stop White to build the center! }
11. d4
{ White finally reaches full-center control! To better understand the position, it is important to emphasize that White's play is no longer oriented to a Kingside, but White will search for action on the Queenside after the forthcoming b4 and a4! }
11... Bb6 { Black steps back and keeps an eye on the White's center. } 12. b4
{ In anticipation of the Black's counterplay in the center, White seizes the space on the Queenside. The advance has more than this sole purpose:1@@EndBracket@@ it puts pressure on the Black's pieces that are targeting the center with an idea of a4.   2@@EndBracket@@ it takes away control of the a5 square from the Black's Knight.   3@@EndBracket@@ it clears the second rank for the Rook maneuver of Ra2, coming after a4! }
12... e5
{ Black's only chance for activation is to attack the center, but White has no issues after the Queenside activity! }
13. a4
{ With a direct threat to capture the Bishop on b6, White at the same time buys time for center support after Ra2 and Re2! }
13... a6
{ Black might also play  13...a5  14.b5  but White gains a clearly better position pushing Black's Knight back, and we will be able to simply take the  e5  pawn! }
14. Qb3+
{ It is useful to have the Queen here controlling the g8-square. With Black's King in the corner, Black cannot be very comfortable advancing the Kingside pawns as g5-h5 will be met by simple h3. Any opening of this flank could be fatal. }
14... Kh8 15. d5
{ The center is closed and the White's King is perfectly safe even without castling. White has a direct threat of c4-c5, with an immediate attack on the Black's dark-squared Bishop which will not be able to join the game afterward. Additionally, the Rook can move along the 2nd rank with the Ra2-Re2 maneuver to protect g2 and e4 pawns with a clear space advantage for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Bishop's Opening 2...Nf6: Berlin Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's opening 2...Nf6: 3. d3 c6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. O-O Qc7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nf6
{ Berlin defense by Black! This is absolutely the most frequent move by Black against the Bishop's opening. Another common option especially on the lower level is  2...Nc6  , but 2...Nf6 is by far way more common in the practice! With the last move, Black aims to stay active, threatens White's central pawn on  e4  , and enters the Berlin defense. }
3. d3
{ Already at the third move, White has an opportunity to pick up the aggressive approach with the Urusov Gambit  3.d4!?  or to choose a more peaceful approach with 3.d3 which enters the Bishop's opening. Both options are fully covered throughout the course.  The Urusov Gambit is very interesting for the players whose main weapon is the tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for blitz and rapid games, especially when the beginner seats on the other side and tries to find a proper plan to defend as Black.  On the other side, 3.d3 provides a stable and safe positional approach without sacrifices or material losses and it gives flexible positions where White has initiative and the attack which is mainly based on equal material and clear activity. Interestingly, it is used in almost 80% of the games at this point and while  3.d4  was used mainly only once by top players in a blitz or rapid games, nowadays 3.d3 move presents a bulletproof approach by literally all top players including Carlsen, Nepo, Caruana, Firouzja, Grischuk, and other top players! }
3... c6
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White has not played Nf3 yet to place pressure on the e5 pawn. On the other hand, Black prepares his own central advance with d5. From my own experience, it turned out that the last move 3...c6 was mainly used by stronger players or players who were familiar with the opening theory. Also, one should not forget that after:   3...Nc6  4.Nc3  the game transposes into lines explained within the 1.e4 e5 2.Bc4 Nc6 chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... Be7
{ Black refrains from the early confrontation in the center and wants to first complete the development with O-O. }
5. O-O
{ We continue with development as well, and do not buy into Black's trick to take  5.Nxe5  due to a  5...Qa5+  when Black wins a piece! }
5... Qc7
{ Black tries to remain as flexible as possible. He defends the e5-pawn and keeps the option of pushing d7-d5 in one go. However, the Queen appears somehow artificial on c7, since it is not a good square for the Queen in this system. }
6. Re1
{ This is a useful move in the open games that are resembling the Ruy Lopez or the Italian pawn structure. White fortifies the e4 pawn and clears the f1-square for the Knight to be able to complete the maneuver of Nbd2-Nf1-Ng3. Given time, White can choose to advance with d4 or to transfer the Knight from b1 to the Kingside. }
6... O-O
{ Black prepares to push d5 tucking the King to safety, away from the opposing White Rook on e1. }
7. Nbd2
{ As it was previously mentioned, White wants to reposition the Knight to g3, after Nf1-Ng3. }
7... d5
{ Black finally strikes in the center. After  8.exd5  Black's pawn on  e5  will not be hanging due to a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. }
8. Bb3
{ White keeps the tension in the center for at least one move longer putting the Bishop to a safe b3-square.  8.exd5?  would be a mistake as Black wins a tempo with  8...cxd5  and gains a space for the Knight to be developed at the wonderful c6-post. Now, White threatens exd5 followed by Ne5. }
8... dxe4
{ Black decides to release the central tension, but it is too early for such an action. This move is considered to be suspicious because it allows White to conquer the e4 outpost with a piece! }
9. Nxe4
{ White aims to recapture with a piece on the e4 square, keeping the e-file semi-opened with pressure on the vulnerable e5 pawn. It is important to note that Black will not be able to move the f7 pawn due to a pin by the Bishop on b3, and that helps White to gain full control over the most important central squares. }
9... Nxe4
{ If Black tries to remain solid and compact  9...Nbd7  10.Ng3!  is an excellent move that leaves Black all tangled up and gives a clear advantage to White. There is no good way for Black to prevent Nf5, and if Black's Rook leaves the f8 spot, then Ng5 comes in with a powerful impact! }
10. Rxe4
{ It might be a bit strange to see the White's Rook on e4 after only 10 moves of play, but the Rook is perfectly safe in the center of the board, putting Black's pawn on e5 in trouble. Black needs to switch plans and defend the pawn, but none of the possible options give a satisfying option for Black. }
10... Nd7
{ Aiming to protect the threatened pawn, Black will face issues with the pinned Bishop! White is ready to react in the center! }
11. d4
{ This motive is commonly seen. As soon as Black disturbs the eye-contact between the Queen on c7 and Bishop on e7,  the central advance comes in strong! }
11... Bd6
{ Black still tries to hold, but White can trade some material and still keeps the strong pressure on f7, h7, and e5! }
12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 { This exchange clears the way for the White Queen. }
13... Bxe5 14. Qh5
{ With centralized pieces and a clear idea of Rh4! White puts huge pressure on Black's overloaded pieces! }
14... Bd6
{ If Black chooses to play  14...Bf6  to prevent Rh4, White can first win a tempo by attacking the Queen with  15.Bf4  , and then continue overloading with  16.Rd1  and  16.--  17.Bd6  . }
15. Rh4
{ It is obvious that all White's pieces are eyeing Black's lone King and the pressure on the h-file will decide the outcome of the game! }
15... h6
{ Black has no other choice but to block an attack on the h-file. However, that does not stop White to continue with the overwhelming attack! }
16. Bxh6
{ Black lost control, and White dominates the position. Thanks to the active pieces and light-squared killer Bishop which constantly pressures Black's King, White uses the opportunity to open the Kingside and to conclude the game with sacrifice! }
16... gxh6 17. Qg6+
{ There is no defense from the forthcoming Rh6# and the game is over after only 18 moves of play! }
