{ It might be a bit strange to see the White's Rook on e4 after only 10 moves of play, but the Rook is perfectly safe in the center of the board, putting Black's pawn on e5 in trouble. Black needs to switch plans and defend the pawn, but none of the possible options give a satisfying option for Black. }
10... Bf6
{ Trying to play smart, Black moves the bishop away from the pins along the e-file and keeps the c8-h3 diagonal open for the Bishop on c8. }
11. Bg5
{ White gives no respite, once again pressing the defending piece, this time the Bishop on f6. Black is practically forced to accept the trade, helping White to toggle pieces on the Kingside! }
11... Bxg5
{ Do you think: 'Wait! This was a moment for Black to win the tempo by attacking the White Rook  11...Bf5  .'? Well, I would enjoy it so much if anyone played it against me! I would start with  12.Bxf6!  Bxe4  13.dxe4  gxf6  14.Nh4  with an idea of Qh5, followed by Qh6 and Nf6, and a clearly better position for White thanks to pressure on the weak King and more active pieces! }
12. Nxg5
{ Once again, the Queen is coming against the poorly defended King's flank, and after the forthcoming Qh5, Black will need to think about both the f7 and h7 vulnerable spots. }
12... Bf5
{ Black tries to get a break by relocating the bishop to g6, supporting the f7 and h7 pawns, but nevertheless, White's attack will be overwhelming! }
13. Re3
{ White steps back with an active move and keeps the idea of possibly swinging the Rook to the Kingside. After Qf3 and Rae1, doubling the Rooks on the semi-opened e-file, White will have an active position with a lot of threats, and one should not forget that Black still faces difficulties with development. }
13... Nd7
{ Black attempts to rush more pieces into defense and develops the Knight on the most active square. However, the connection between the Queen on  c7  and the pawn on  f7  is broken now, and White will be able to benefit from it. If Black instead played  13...h6?  as it was seen in the game Nevednichy, V-Saric, A Nova Gorica 2005, White gains a winning position after  14.Nxf7  Rxf7  15.Qh5  with a double attack on Rd7 and Bf5, and after  15...g6  16.Qxh6  Qd6  White has a decisive advantage with an exchange up after  17.Bxf7  Kxf7  18.Qh7  Kf8  19.Qxb7  winning another exchange forcing Black to resign! }
14. Qf3
{ White develops Queen with a tempo attack on the Bishop on f5 and keeps the pressure on the f7 square! }
14... Bg6 15. h4
{ After this key advance, Black's position is simply falling apart. There is no good defense against h4-h5 and White dominates the position. If Black continues with  15...h6  , White will not blink, and after  16.h5!  the f7 spot will be crushed.   If  15...Nf6  then simply  16.Qg3  with  16...--  17.Rae1  , and White is clearly better with a huge attack and great activity! }
