{ Black finally strikes in the center. After  8.exd5  Black's pawn on  e5  will not be hanging due to a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. }
8. Bb3
{ White keeps the tension in the center for at least one move longer putting the Bishop to a safe b3-square.  8.exd5?  would be a mistake as Black wins a tempo with  8...cxd5  and gains a space for the Knight to be developed at the wonderful c6-post. Now, White threatens exd5 followed by Ne5. }
8... dxe4
{ Black decides to release the central tension, but it is too early for such an action. This move is considered to be suspicious because it allows White to conquer the e4 outpost with a piece! }
9. Nxe4
{ White aims to recapture with a piece on the e4 square, keeping the e-file semi-opened with pressure on the vulnerable e5 pawn. It is important to note that Black will not be able to move the f7 pawn due to a pin by the Bishop on b3, and that helps White to gain full control over the most important central squares. }
9... Nxe4
{ If Black tries to remain solid and compact  9...Nbd7  10.Ng3!  is an excellent move that leaves Black all tangled up and gives a clear advantage to White. There is no good way for Black to prevent Nf5, and if Black's Rook leaves the f8 spot, then Ng5 comes in with a powerful impact! }
10. Rxe4
{ It might be a bit strange to see the White's Rook on e4 after only 10 moves of play, but the Rook is perfectly safe in the center of the board, putting Black's pawn on e5 in trouble. Black needs to switch plans and defend the pawn, but none of the possible options give a satisfying option for Black. }
10... Bd6
{ With an idea to defend the central pawn, Black gives chances to White to clear the path for the Kingside attack. The pawn on f7 will be vulnerable and White can use the position of the Rook to swing it on the h-file! }
11. Ng5 { We attack both f7 and h7 and clear the way for the Queen! } 11... Bf5
{ Black strikes back and tries to win a defensive tempo. However, White is not impressed with this threat! }
12. Qf3 { Who needs a Rook! Queen and Knight provide a strong battery! } 12...
Bxe4
{ Grabbing the material leads to quick disaster as it will be shown within only a few moves! }
13. Qxe4
{ With pressure on f7 and h7 squares, eyeing the Black's King, White has full compensation for an exchange. Black will not be able to hold all the weak spots and still faces issues to develop properly! }
13... g6 14. Qh4
{ Black was forced to weaken dark squares around the King and White swings the Queen over there forcing Black to push pawns around the King to make it weaker! }
14... h5 15. Nxf7
{ Whilst Black lags with development, White opens the Black's King gaining a winning position after the forthcoming Qf6! The light squared Bishop proves to be the most important piece of White's attack, as it was mentioned throughout the course! }
15... Rxf7 16. Qf6
{ White uses the light-squared Bishop to pin Black's King and gains a winning position with a tremendous threat of  16...--  17.Bh6  , followed by  17...--  18.Qg7!  One should not forget that Black can not unchain from the pins, and White can continue afterward with Qxg6! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Bishop's Opening 2...Nf6: Berlin Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's opening 2...Nf6: 3. d3 c6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. O-O Qc7 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nf6
{ Berlin defense by Black! This is absolutely the most frequent move by Black against the Bishop's opening. Another common option especially on the lower level is  2...Nc6  , but 2...Nf6 is by far way more common in the practice! With the last move, Black aims to stay active, threatens White's central pawn on  e4  , and enters the Berlin defense. }
3. d3
{ Already at the third move, White has an opportunity to pick up the aggressive approach with the Urusov Gambit  3.d4!?  or to choose a more peaceful approach with 3.d3 which enters the Bishop's opening. Both options are fully covered throughout the course.  The Urusov Gambit is very interesting for the players whose main weapon is the tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for blitz and rapid games, especially when the beginner seats on the other side and tries to find a proper plan to defend as Black.  On the other side, 3.d3 provides a stable and safe positional approach without sacrifices or material losses and it gives flexible positions where White has initiative and the attack which is mainly based on equal material and clear activity. Interestingly, it is used in almost 80% of the games at this point and while  3.d4  was used mainly only once by top players in a blitz or rapid games, nowadays 3.d3 move presents a bulletproof approach by literally all top players including Carlsen, Nepo, Caruana, Firouzja, Grischuk, and other top players! }
3... c6
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White has not played Nf3 yet to place pressure on the e5 pawn. On the other hand, Black prepares his own central advance with d5. From my own experience, it turned out that the last move 3...c6 was mainly used by stronger players or players who were familiar with the opening theory. Also, one should not forget that after:   3...Nc6  4.Nc3  the game transposes into lines explained within the 1.e4 e5 2.Bc4 Nc6 chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... Be7
{ Black refrains from the early confrontation in the center and wants to first complete the development with O-O. }
5. O-O
{ We continue with development as well, and do not buy into Black's trick to take  5.Nxe5  due to a  5...Qa5+  when Black wins a piece! }
5... Qc7
{ Black tries to remain as flexible as possible. He defends the e5-pawn and keeps the option of pushing d7-d5 in one go. However, the Queen appears somehow artificial on c7, since it is not a good square for the Queen in this system. }
6. Re1
{ This is a useful move in the open games that are resembling the Ruy Lopez or the Italian pawn structure. White fortifies the e4 pawn and clears the f1-square for the Knight to be able to complete the maneuver of Nbd2-Nf1-Ng3. Given time, White can choose to advance with d4 or to transfer the Knight from b1 to the Kingside. }
6... O-O
{ Black prepares to push d5 tucking the King to safety, away from the opposing White Rook on e1. }
7. Nbd2
{ As it was previously mentioned, White wants to reposition the Knight to g3, after Nf1-Ng3. }
7... d5
{ Black finally strikes in the center. After  8.exd5  Black's pawn on  e5  will not be hanging due to a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. }
8. Bb3
{ White keeps the tension in the center for at least one move longer putting the Bishop to a safe b3-square.  8.exd5?  would be a mistake as Black wins a tempo with  8...cxd5  and gains a space for the Knight to be developed at the wonderful c6-post. Now, White threatens exd5 followed by Ne5. }
8... dxe4
{ Black decides to release the central tension, but it is too early for such an action. This move is considered to be suspicious because it allows White to conquer the e4 outpost with a piece! }
9. Nxe4
{ White aims to recapture with a piece on the e4 square, keeping the e-file semi-opened with pressure on the vulnerable e5 pawn. It is important to note that Black will not be able to move the f7 pawn due to a pin by the Bishop on b3, and that helps White to gain full control over the most important central squares. }
9... Nxe4
{ If Black tries to remain solid and compact  9...Nbd7  10.Ng3!  is an excellent move that leaves Black all tangled up and gives a clear advantage to White. There is no good way for Black to prevent Nf5, and if Black's Rook leaves the f8 spot, then Ng5 comes in with a powerful impact! }
10. Rxe4
{ It might be a bit strange to see the White's Rook on e4 after only 10 moves of play, but the Rook is perfectly safe in the center of the board, putting Black's pawn on e5 in trouble. Black needs to switch plans and defend the pawn, but none of the possible options give a satisfying option for Black. }
10... Bd6
{ With an idea to defend the central pawn, Black gives chances to White to clear the path for the Kingside attack. The pawn on f7 will be vulnerable and White can use the position of the Rook to swing it on the h-file! }
11. Ng5 { We attack both f7 and h7 and clear the way for the Queen! } 11... Bf5
{ Black strikes back and tries to win a defensive tempo. However, White is not impressed with this threat! }
12. Qf3 { Who needs a Rook! Queen and Knight provide a strong battery! } 12...
Bg6 13. Re2
{ Transferring the Bishop to g6 only briefly helps Black, as then the flank advance h4-h5 comes in with even greater effect! White's idea is simple afterward, with a clear development advantage after Bd2 and Rae1, White will pressure e5, improving attack with possible Bc3. Very interesting would be  13.Nxh7!?  Followed by  13...Bxh7  14.Rg4  where White would build up a strong attack afterward mainly thanks to Bh6 idea. }
