{ Black finally strikes in the center. After  8.exd5  Black's pawn on  e5  will not be hanging due to a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. }
8. Bb3
{ White keeps the tension in the center for at least one move longer putting the Bishop to a safe b3-square.  8.exd5?  would be a mistake as Black wins a tempo with  8...cxd5  and gains a space for the Knight to be developed at the wonderful c6-post. Now, White threatens exd5 followed by Ne5. }
8... Nbd7
{ Since the c6 square is not available, Black is forced to develop the Knight on the less active position to protect the e5 pawn which would be hanging after dxe5! }
9. d4
{ This strike clears up the center in White's favor. The key fact is that when placing the Knight on d7 Black interrupted the link between the Queen and the Bishop on e7, more so the Bishop will be indirectly exposed to an attack by Rook on e1! }
9... dxe4
{ As it will be shown within this line, clearing all the central pawns will not help Black's cause. }
10. Nxe4
{ White has a clear initiative here with two different options for a Knight maneuver. White can go for either Ng3-Nf5 or Ng5, depending on Black's reaction! }
10... exd4 11. Qxd4
{ White centralizes the Queen with the idea of playing Bg5 and putting more pressure against Nf6 and Be7. }
11... Nxe4 12. Qxe4
{ Whilst White centralized and activated all of the pieces, Black's pieces are clumsy on the 7th and 8th ranks. }
12... Bd6 13. Be3
{ With simple development, White proceeds with the centralization plan after Rad1 and Bd4. All the pieces will be actively positioned, eyeing Black's King which does not have a lot of support. }
13... Nf6 14. Qh4
{ Black improved the Knight into a defending piece, but White does not step back and goes forward for an attack! The Queen reaches a desirable position on the h7 square, pressuring a vulnerable h7 pawn. One should not forget that White has a simple clever plan to remove Black's defender of the King after Bd4! }
14... Bf5
{ Black logically rushes to reinforce h7, but that is not that easy as it sounds. }
15. Bd4
{ Due to a deadly threat of Bf6, Black's only try might be  15...Be7  , which is met by  16.Be5  Qc8  17.Rad1  and total domination for White who has all the control of the open files, as well as the space control. White is clearly better as it could be seen in the game of Vorobiov, E in Kramatorsk 2001, against none else but in that time 11-years old Sergey Karjakin, the future World Championship Challenger. }
