6... O-O
{ Black prepares to push d5 tucking the King to safety, away from the opposing White Rook on e1. }
7. Nbd2
{ As it was previously mentioned, White wants to reposition the Knight to g3, after Nf1-Ng3. }
7... d5
{ Black finally strikes in the center. After  8.exd5  Black's pawn on  e5  will not be hanging due to a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. }
8. Bb3
{ White keeps the tension in the center for at least one move longer putting the Bishop to a safe b3-square.  8.exd5?  would be a mistake as Black wins a tempo with  8...cxd5  and gains a space for the Knight to be developed at the wonderful c6-post. Now, White threatens exd5 followed by Ne5. }
8... Nbd7
{ Since the c6 square is not available, Black is forced to develop the Knight on the less active position to protect the e5 pawn which would be hanging after dxe5! }
9. d4
{ This strike clears up the center in White's favor. The key fact is that when placing the Knight on d7 Black interrupted the link between the Queen and the Bishop on e7, more so the Bishop will be indirectly exposed to an attack by Rook on e1! }
9... exd4
{ Black cannot hold the center as White was threatening to win the pawn with  10.exd5  and  11.dxe5  . }
10. exd5
{ With lots of trades in the center, White aims to gain as many tempos as possible, forcing Black to play multiple times with the same pieces, which is considered to be bad, especially in an early middlegame. }
10... Bc5
{ Black is forced to defend the hanging d4 pawn, while White will continue to open the position, unblocking the light-squared Bishop! }
11. dxc6 bxc6 12. Ne4
{ By renewing the pressure on the Bishop and d4-pawn, White gains more time to build up the powerful attack! }
12... Nxe4 13. Rxe4
{ The Rook gets a perfect place with the ability to join the Kingside carnage! White is prepared to toggle the pieces on the Kingside with Rh4, followed by Ng5 or Bg5! }
13... Nf6
{ Black is forced to support the King with his pieces, at the same time preparing for further development. White is currently not interested in the d4 pawn, since it might cause troubles due to activation of Black after Rd8. }
14. Rh4
{ All of White's pieces joined the attack! White is ready for a brutally effective plan of Bg5, followed by Qd3, and it is questionable if Black will be able to hold the pressure! }
14... Bg4
{ Black is forced to react somehow, and he chooses the most active move. However, that does not stop White to continue with a great attack! }
15. Bg5
{ Knight on f5 is recognized as the only defensive piece, and White aims to destroy it! Both Bishop on g4 and Knight on d6 are hanging! }
15... Qd6 16. Bxf6 Bxf3
{ Black puts the last hopes to force trades with this intermediate move. But of course, White will not accept that offer! }
17. Qd3
{ White replies with his own intermediate move threatening mate with Qh7! Black is once again forced to defend with pawns, but that is not helpful! }
17... h6
{ For all of you who wondered what would happen in the case of  17...g6  , this is a very nice moment to check your skills and imagination -  18.Qxg6!  hxg6  followed by  19.Rh8!  Checkmate! }
18. Rxh6
{ White removes the final obstacle and the game will conclude with a checkmate after  18....gxh6  19.Qg6!#  as it happened in a game between Stubbs, M-Warnest, S ICCF email 2007. }
