{ We continue with development as well, and do not buy into Black's trick to take  5.Nxe5  due to a  5...Qa5+  when Black wins a piece! }
5... d6
{ Black chooses the more cautious plan of development, aiming to castle before starting the fight in the center. With a solid position, White does not face any threats or dangers, and continues with nice positional play with initiative in the center! }
6. Bb3
{ True, the Bishop is not attacked, so why are we wasting a valuable tempo on this retreat? For many reasons, this is a very useful prophylactic move. First of all, the Bishop is no longer exposed to direct attacks by means of d5 or b5. In addition, since Black is not playing d5, White will advance his own pawn to d4 and prevents all of the possible Nxe4-d5 tactics. }
6... O-O
{ Black continues with the plan of castling quickly putting the King in a safe zone. }
7. c3
{ This would be a typical Italian Game with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  Nf6  4.d3  , where Black instead of Nc6 has a pawn on c6! It does bear some bonuses for White, in particular as there is no longer the possibility for Black to play Na5 harassing our Bishop forcing Bc4-Bb3, and Black has no good control of the center and the d4-square. }
7... Nbd7
{ Black prepares for more active play with  Nc5  . If Black first brought the Bishop out with  7...Bg4  White would simply follow Ruy Lopez plan with  8.h3  Bh5  9.Re1  clearing the f1-square for a Knight maneuver with Nd2-Nf1-Ng3 and after  9...Nbd7  10.Nbd2  we emerge with a small advantage and follow-up wih the previously mentioned plan Nf1-Ng3. White has a safe spot for the light-squared Bishop, and after any Nc5, the answer would be Be2 additionally protecting the  e4  pawn. }
8. Re1
{ White goes for a good prophylactic move, defending the e4 pawn and prepares for the d4 central approach! }
8... Nc5
{ Black could also go for  8...Qc7  but that does not obstruct White's plans and after  9.d4  +/= White enjoys the better version of the Philidor defense thanks to the pawn being on  c3  instead of the Knight. The usual Philidor resource  9...exd4  here brings no fruit as White can recapture with the pawn with  10.cxd4  , maintaining the full center. }
9. Bc2
{ White keeps the light-squared Bishop safe and prepares for further development. }
9... Bg4
{ This pin is the most serious attempt to prevent or slow down the d4-advance. The odd-looking  9...Ne6  blocks the light-squared Bishop but does not prevent the central advance with d4. The Knight would make sense on e6 only if it adds pressure on d4 or if the d-pawns are already traded. In that manner, White does not need to hurry with d4 and after  10.Nbd2  has a small advantage with the idea of Nf1-Ng3. If Black instead goes for  9...Qc7  White continues developing normally with  10.Nbd2  and with the previously mentioned plan of Nf1-Ng3, putting Black's light-squared Bishop in an uncomfortable position. }
10. Nbd2
{ White certainly does not want to improve Black's Knight on c5, if it gets relocated to e6. For that reason, White keeps an option of d4 but does not hurry with it. }
10... Ne6 11. h3
{ We start a hunting the light-squared Bishop and we will continue with the idea of Nf1, followed by Ng3! }
11... Bh5 12. Nf1
{ Due to Black's clumsy light-squared Bishop, White should have in mind the well-known idea of Ng3 or even positionally aggressive g4 followed by Ng3. This is a typical Ruy Lopez or Italian idea against the Bishop on h5 known from the time's of Steinitz! }
12... Ne8
{ Black wants to gain trades after Bg5 or Ng5, but also aims to relocate the Knight to c7 controlling d5 square. However, Black's heavy pieces are now disconnected on the back-rank and that limits Black's options. }
13. Ng3
{ White conquers the main squares on the Kingside and forces Black to trade the light-squared Bishop. }
13... Bxf3
{ Of course, one could ask a question why is Black forced to trade the Bishop, and the answer is that  13...Bg6  is much inferior and mixes up Black's plans. First of all, occupying the f5-square gives a clear advantage to White @@StartBracket@@for example  14.Nf5  @@EndBracket@@, but the other option  14.Be3  is convincing as well, and now the planned  14...Ng5  is strongly met by  15.Nh2!  with idea  15...--  16.h4  . Otherwise,  14...Bg5  is losing to  15.Nxg5  Nxg5  16.h4!  and  16...--  17.h5  on the next move. }
14. Qxf3
{ White gained the Bishop pair advantage and if Black does not go for the mentioned idea of trades through the c1-h6 diagonal, White has a clearly better position. }
14... Bg5 15. Bxg5
{ It is a fact that Black succeeded in the Bishops trade, but his Knights will remain passive without outposts. }
15... Qxg5
{ Black prefers to keep the knight on  e6  keeping an eye on the f4-square. If Black decides to continue with  15...Nxg5  16.Qe3  Ne6  White activates and continues development with  17.Rad1  Qb6  18.Qxb6  axb6  White is at least slightly better after  19.a3  N8c7  20.Nf5  when Black's Knights have no good active outposts, whilst White can plan pawn breaks with  d4  or g3-f5 and the light-squared Bishop will be a huge influence on the a2-g8 diagonal as it could be seen in the game Lau, R-David, A Budapest 1992. }
16. Rad1
{ With this simple developing move White claims a slight advantage. White has plans to push d4 seizing the center and then transferring the Bishop to b3 since there are no longer Nc5 harassments. Black pieces are clumsy, in particular the Queen and the Knight on e8. Black's Rooks are disconnected and if Black continues with  16...Nf6  then  17.Nf5!  with the idea  17...--  18.h4  is very strong as the Queen is poorly placed.   If instead, Black goes for  16...Nf4  , White will not bother delaying his plans of  17.d4  with Nf1 next and preparing g3-h4 to knock Black's pieces back. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Bishop's Opening 2...Nf6: Berlin Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's opening 2...Nf6: 3. d3 c6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. O-O d6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nf6
{ Berlin defense by Black! This is absolutely the most frequent move by Black against the Bishop's opening. Another common option especially on the lower level is  2...Nc6  , but 2...Nf6 is by far way more common in the practice! With the last move, Black aims to stay active, threatens White's central pawn on  e4  , and enters the Berlin defense. }
3. d3
{ Already at the third move, White has an opportunity to pick up the aggressive approach with the Urusov Gambit  3.d4!?  or to choose a more peaceful approach with 3.d3 which enters the Bishop's opening. Both options are fully covered throughout the course.  The Urusov Gambit is very interesting for the players whose main weapon is the tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for blitz and rapid games, especially when the beginner seats on the other side and tries to find a proper plan to defend as Black.  On the other side, 3.d3 provides a stable and safe positional approach without sacrifices or material losses and it gives flexible positions where White has initiative and the attack which is mainly based on equal material and clear activity. Interestingly, it is used in almost 80% of the games at this point and while  3.d4  was used mainly only once by top players in a blitz or rapid games, nowadays 3.d3 move presents a bulletproof approach by literally all top players including Carlsen, Nepo, Caruana, Firouzja, Grischuk, and other top players! }
3... c6
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White has not played Nf3 yet to place pressure on the e5 pawn. On the other hand, Black prepares his own central advance with d5. From my own experience, it turned out that the last move 3...c6 was mainly used by stronger players or players who were familiar with the opening theory. Also, one should not forget that after:   3...Nc6  4.Nc3  the game transposes into lines explained within the 1.e4 e5 2.Bc4 Nc6 chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... Be7
{ Black refrains from the early confrontation in the center and wants to first complete the development with O-O. }
5. O-O
{ We continue with development as well, and do not buy into Black's trick to take  5.Nxe5  due to a  5...Qa5+  when Black wins a piece! }
5... d6
{ Black chooses the more cautious plan of development, aiming to castle before starting the fight in the center. With a solid position, White does not face any threats or dangers, and continues with nice positional play with initiative in the center! }
6. Bb3
{ True, the Bishop is not attacked, so why are we wasting a valuable tempo on this retreat? For many reasons, this is a very useful prophylactic move. First of all, the Bishop is no longer exposed to direct attacks by means of d5 or b5. In addition, since Black is not playing d5, White will advance his own pawn to d4 and prevents all of the possible Nxe4-d5 tactics. }
6... O-O
{ Black continues with the plan of castling quickly putting the King in a safe zone. }
7. c3
{ This would be a typical Italian Game with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  Nf6  4.d3  , where Black instead of Nc6 has a pawn on c6! It does bear some bonuses for White, in particular as there is no longer the possibility for Black to play Na5 harassing our Bishop forcing Bc4-Bb3, and Black has no good control of the center and the d4-square. }
