{ Black prepares for more active play with  Nc5  . If Black first brought the Bishop out with  7...Bg4  White would simply follow Ruy Lopez plan with  8.h3  Bh5  9.Re1  clearing the f1-square for a Knight maneuver with Nd2-Nf1-Ng3 and after  9...Nbd7  10.Nbd2  we emerge with a small advantage and follow-up wih the previously mentioned plan Nf1-Ng3. White has a safe spot for the light-squared Bishop, and after any Nc5, the answer would be Be2 additionally protecting the  e4  pawn. }
8. Re1
{ White goes for a good prophylactic move, defending the e4 pawn and prepares for the d4 central approach! }
8... Nc5
{ Black could also go for  8...Qc7  but that does not obstruct White's plans and after  9.d4  +/= White enjoys the better version of the Philidor defense thanks to the pawn being on  c3  instead of the Knight. The usual Philidor resource  9...exd4  here brings no fruit as White can recapture with the pawn with  10.cxd4  , maintaining the full center. }
9. Bc2
{ White keeps the light-squared Bishop safe and prepares for further development. }
9... Bg4
{ This pin is the most serious attempt to prevent or slow down the d4-advance. The odd-looking  9...Ne6  blocks the light-squared Bishop but does not prevent the central advance with d4. The Knight would make sense on e6 only if it adds pressure on d4 or if the d-pawns are already traded. In that manner, White does not need to hurry with d4 and after  10.Nbd2  has a small advantage with the idea of Nf1-Ng3. If Black instead goes for  9...Qc7  White continues developing normally with  10.Nbd2  and with the previously mentioned plan of Nf1-Ng3, putting Black's light-squared Bishop in an uncomfortable position. }
10. Nbd2
{ White certainly does not want to improve Black's Knight on c5, if it gets relocated to e6. For that reason, White keeps an option of d4 but does not hurry with it. }
10... Ne6 11. h3
{ We start a hunting the light-squared Bishop and we will continue with the idea of Nf1, followed by Ng3! }
11... Bh5 12. Nf1
{ Due to Black's clumsy light-squared Bishop, White should have in mind the well-known idea of Ng3 or even positionally aggressive g4 followed by Ng3. This is a typical Ruy Lopez or Italian idea against the Bishop on h5 known from the time's of Steinitz! }
12... Re8
{ Black chooses a different approach expecting the central break by White with d5. Black wants to be ready for that with a Knight on f6 and the Rook placed on the e-file. }
13. Ng3
{ White continues with the hunt of the light-squared Bishop and eyes the outpost on f5. }
13... Bxf3
{ Once again the retreat of the Bishop is inferior  13...Bg6  14.Nh4  +/= when White is firmly seizing the f5-square. The Queen will join the play via the f3-square and the light-squared Bishop will return to a2-g8 diagonal with  Bb3  . It should be noted that after  14.Nh4  Nxe4  is not possible as  15.Nxg6  Nxg3  16.Nxe7+  wins a piece. }
14. Qxf3 { White eyes the f5-square. } 14... g6 15. Nf1
{ This is my improvement over the few games that I've found in this position, and I recommend you to check the game between Brooks, M-Benjamin, J Saint Louis 2009 to get familiar with White's ideas here. With 15.Nf1! White aims to reposition the Knight to a better place. The plan is Nf1-Nh2-Qe2-Nf3  @@StartBracket@@or even Ng4!?@@EndBracket@@, together with a4 @@StartBracket@@to secure the light-squared on the a2-g8 diagonal@@EndBracket@@ and White has a slight positional advantage thanks to the space control and long-term advantage of the Bishop pair. }
