{ We start a hunting the light-squared Bishop and we will continue with the idea of Nf1, followed by Ng3! }
11... Bh5 12. Nf1
{ Due to Black's clumsy light-squared Bishop, White should have in mind the well-known idea of Ng3 or even positionally aggressive g4 followed by Ng3. This is a typical Ruy Lopez or Italian idea against the Bishop on h5 known from the time's of Steinitz! }
12... Nd7
{ Black aims to force a trade after Ng5 or Bg5, since the simplification of position would be beneficial for him. However, that does not stop White's ideas. }
13. g4
{ Of course, it was possible to continue  13.Ng3  like in similar lines, when Black has to give away the light-squared Bishop and it would certainly secure White small but long-lasting advantage.   But, when the World champion Magnus Carlsen plays  13.g4!  as it is shown here, we should follow his choice! He intended to keep the Knight on f3 and make a so-called 'non-linear exchange' on g5 as it will be shown soon! }
13... Bg6 14. Ng3
{ White relocated the Knight on an active square and prepares for a central break with d4 as well as a typical Kingside aggressive idea with Nf5! }
14... Ng5
{ Black could also try to trade with  14...Bg5  but after  15.Nxg5!  Nxg5  16.Kg2!  White is slightly better with a safe King and idea of d4 which provides full central control and the Bishop pair advantage. }
15. Bxg5
{ This is the non-linear exchange! White decides to trade a Bishop for a Knight instead of maybe a more logical Knight for a Knight. This way, White avoids to trade two pairs of pieces and keeps more material and more options on the board! }
15... Bxg5 16. d4
{ White builds a fortress in the center, and Black's Bishop pair is blocked due to a clumsy positioned light squared Bishop on g6. Although White pushed pawns around the King, White's King is perfectly safe since Black can not reach it! }
16... Bf4
{ Black still insists to trade pieces and to reveal more space for maneuvres. Instead  16...Bf6  would be more passive and after  17.Qd2  h6  18.Kg2  White is slightly better with an idea of  19.Rad1  and a patient build-up behind the spatial advantage. }
17. Ne2 { White trades on their own terms, aiming to go for Nf4! } 17... Qf6
18. Kg2
{ As it could be seen in a game between Carlsen, M-Wei, Y Wijk aan Zee 2017,  White takes a brief moment to protect Nf3. White will proceed with  18...--  19.Nxf4  Qxf4  20.Qc1!  Qxc1  21.Raxc1  . After the Rook comes to d1 Black will not be able to hold the center due to the dxe5 threat. And if Black blinks first with exd4, then White recaptures with the Knight. The Bishop on g6 will be very passive compared to its counterpart on c2. }
