{ Black takes a moment from the main battle in the center and gains some space while hunting White's light-squared Bishop. White needs to react immediately, delaying the development. }
6. a4
{ Always a dilemma for White, should do we play a3 or a4? In this particular position, White's plan is to trade the pawns on d5, thus securing b5-square as an outpost for the Knight. }
6... Bd6
{ This is a suspicious move by Black that allows White to pressure the d5-pawn with an active development move! }
7. Nc3
{ White puts pressure on Black's center and Black is practically forced to advance with the d-pawn which was not the initial plan. }
7... d4
{ If Black is stubborn and tries to keep the center after  7...Bc7  White would be able to continue with  8.exd5  cxd5  9.O-O  and with a simple plan of Re1, after gaining the outpost Nb5, Black's center would be vulnerable. }
8. Ne2 O-O 9. O-O
{ White gains a slightly better position with the possibility to undermine Black's center after c3. The Knight from e2 will be relocated to the g3-square, and White will be able to continue with active development whilst Black faces issues with activation of the Bishops and the Queenside minor pieces in general. }
