{ Although the engines are not delighted with White's position here, but give equal chances to both sides, I would say that White has a clear initiative with active pieces and a forthcoming plan of h3-Nh2-Ng4 which would put Black's Knight on f6 in an uncomfortable position. Black can not improve the defense over the Knight on f6, and the Queen will be stuck to its starting position square as a defender.  One should also notice that the connection between the Rooks and the Queen is disconnected by the Bishop on b8, and it is questionable where can Black search for action. Aronian, L proved that this position is good to be played in practice, defeating Duda, J in an online game played on chess24.com in 2020. }
