{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... d5
{ Black builds a center with a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. If Black instead goes for  4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  the position transposes to a sideline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  c6  4...Be7  , covered in 4...Be7 }
5. Bb3
{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Qc7
{ As mentioned in similar lines throughout the book, placing the Queen on c7 to protect the e5-pawn seems unnatural to me. Particularly as in such a way the d5-pawn loses protection. }
6. Nc3
{ Of course, White will take the advantage of the fact that the Black's Queen has left the d-file and immediately pounce on the d5-pawn. }
6... dxe4
{ Black has to release the central tension; otherwise White will get to play Bg5, O-O, and Re1 and inflict even greater damage. If 6...d4 7.Ne2 +/= with the plan of playing Ng3, O-O, Nh4, f4. The Queen looks very odd on c7, as White's c3-break will come with even greater force, as shown in the game Siegfried, W-Blankenship, J ICCF email 2015. }
7. Nxe4
{ It is of crucial importance to remove the Knight on f6 which is Black's good defender, having the options of Qh5 and Qf3 to directly attack the f7-pawn. }
7... Nxe4
{ Black is practically forced to accept this trade since development moves such as 7...Be7 would face 8.Ng3! and White will continue with normal development of O-O and Re1, putting pressure on the exposed e5 pawn. }
8. dxe4 { Too weak, too slow is } 8... Be7
{ This is a suspicious move by Black who tries to be fast with castling, but actually the connection between the Queen on c7 and f7 pawn is broken now, which allows White to be fast with an action on the Kingside! }
9. Ng5
{ Black faces lots of issues with development now and with hanging f7 pawn. }
9... Bxg5
{ Black has to exchange the powerful attacking piece, since O-O would leave both f7 and h7 spots undefended after the forthcoming Qh5! }
10. Bxg5
{ After this trade White gains a clear long-term advantage of the Bishop pair in an open position. Meanwhile, Black lags with development without being able to castle and no active minor pieces. }
10... Na6
{ To fight for equality, Black needs to get rid of the White's Bishop pair, aiming to play Nc5 to remove light-squared Bishop, but that is not easy as it sounds! }
11. Be3
{ Of course, White guards the Bishop pair and improves the position of the dark-squared Bishop, preparing for further development. }
11... O-O 12. Qd2
{ White chooses to go for O-O-O and attack on the Kingside! Of course,  12.O-O  would be a good move as well, but according to my chess style, that is just too peaceful. }
12... Qe7
{ Black still tries to force a trade of Bishops, either with Nc5 or Be6. } 13.
Qc3
{ Once again White prevents Black's threats and defends the Bishop pair. With Qc3 not only that we stopped Nc5, but also Be6 is not possible due to a hanging pawn on e5! }
13... Re8 14. O-O-O
{ White reaches a clearly better position with plenty of attacking motives, including f3 which supports central e4 pawn, and the advance of the h-pawn with h4-h5-h6, altogether with the possibility to double the Rooks on the d-file. The Queen and the Bishop pair are dominantly limiting the active scope of the Black pieces. World champion Magnus Carlsen won from this position in only 13 more moves after, and I recommend you to check the game Carlsen, M-Wang, Y Riadh 2017. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Bishop's Opening 2...Nf6: Berlin Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's opening 2...Nf6: 3. d3 c6 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3 Qc7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nf6
{ Berlin defense by Black! This is absolutely the most frequent move by Black against the Bishop's opening. Another common option especially on the lower level is  2...Nc6  , but 2...Nf6 is by far way more common in the practice! With the last move, Black aims to stay active, threatens White's central pawn on  e4  , and enters the Berlin defense. }
3. d3
{ Already at the third move, White has an opportunity to pick up the aggressive approach with the Urusov Gambit  3.d4!?  or to choose a more peaceful approach with 3.d3 which enters the Bishop's opening. Both options are fully covered throughout the course.  The Urusov Gambit is very interesting for the players whose main weapon is the tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for blitz and rapid games, especially when the beginner seats on the other side and tries to find a proper plan to defend as Black.  On the other side, 3.d3 provides a stable and safe positional approach without sacrifices or material losses and it gives flexible positions where White has initiative and the attack which is mainly based on equal material and clear activity. Interestingly, it is used in almost 80% of the games at this point and while  3.d4  was used mainly only once by top players in a blitz or rapid games, nowadays 3.d3 move presents a bulletproof approach by literally all top players including Carlsen, Nepo, Caruana, Firouzja, Grischuk, and other top players! }
3... c6
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White has not played Nf3 yet to place pressure on the e5 pawn. On the other hand, Black prepares his own central advance with d5. From my own experience, it turned out that the last move 3...c6 was mainly used by stronger players or players who were familiar with the opening theory. Also, one should not forget that after:   3...Nc6  4.Nc3  the game transposes into lines explained within the 1.e4 e5 2.Bc4 Nc6 chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... d5
{ Black builds a center with a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. If Black instead goes for  4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  the position transposes to a sideline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  c6  4...Be7  , covered in 4...Be7 }
5. Bb3
{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Qc7
{ As mentioned in similar lines throughout the book, placing the Queen on c7 to protect the e5-pawn seems unnatural to me. Particularly as in such a way the d5-pawn loses protection. }
6. Nc3
{ Of course, White will take the advantage of the fact that the Black's Queen has left the d-file and immediately pounce on the d5-pawn. }
6... dxe4
{ Black has to release the central tension; otherwise White will get to play Bg5, O-O, and Re1 and inflict even greater damage. If 6...d4 7.Ne2 +/= with the plan of playing Ng3, O-O, Nh4, f4. The Queen looks very odd on c7, as White's c3-break will come with even greater force, as shown in the game Siegfried, W-Blankenship, J ICCF email 2015. }
7. Nxe4
{ It is of crucial importance to remove the Knight on f6 which is Black's good defender, having the options of Qh5 and Qf3 to directly attack the f7-pawn. }
7... Nxe4
{ Black is practically forced to accept this trade since development moves such as 7...Be7 would face 8.Ng3! and White will continue with normal development of O-O and Re1, putting pressure on the exposed e5 pawn. }
8. dxe4 Bg4
{ Black limits the scope of the Knight on f3, not allowing it to compromise the f7 and h7 squares after Ng5. }
9. h3
{ It is important to immediately challenge the Black Bishop. If Black chooses to give Bishop pair with a trade over the f3-square, we will follow one line of the attack, and on the other hand, if he delays with  9...Bh5  , then we will have the g4-advance in the crucial moments! }
9... Bh5
{ As it was mentioned if Black went for  9...Bxf3  10.Qxf3  White would have a clear advantage of the Bishop pair, and on the other side, Black cannot develop his pieces in a regular fashion with Be7 or Nd7, due to the double attack on f7. If he continues with  10...Na6  aiming to play  Nc5  , White has a simple  11.a3!  +/- securing the continuing presence of the Bishop on the long a2-g8 diagonal, altogether with a long-lasting advantage of Bishop pair and great activity. }
10. Qe2
{ White prepares development with Be3 and long castle, and looks for a good moment to launch the g4-advance. }
10... Nd7 11. Be3
{ Not only that White follows up with development but also prevents Nc5 aimed against White's main asset - Bishop pair! }
11... Nc5
{ Black finally came to the desirable point, forcing White to give up on the Bishop pair advantage.  However, one should not forget that Black lost many tempos to get here, and White will be able to use development advantage to create active play now! If instead, Black goes for  11...Be7  12.a3  would be a good answer, creating a shelter for the light-squared Bishop, and after  12...O-O-O  13.g4!  Bg6  14.O-O-O  White has a nice initiative with a direct threat of Ng5, followed by pressure on the light-squared Bishop with g4 and h4.  One should not forget that Black's pawn on a7 is also hanging, and Black can not easily capture the hanging e4-pawn. }
12. Bxc5
{ It is still up to White to choose which Bishop to give away to benefit more from the position! As Black will not be able to castle long, then the f7-pawn becomes a more valuable target and for that reason, we choose to keep the light-squared Bishop on the board. }
12... Bxc5 13. O-O-O
{ And White is slightly better as Black cannot castle  13...O-O?  14.g4!  with the idea h4-h5 and Black is practically lost. The light-squared Bishop on b3 is extremely powerful and puts pressure on the vulnerable f7-pawn. Probably the best option for Black to fight for equal chances is to give away the Bishop pair with Bxf3, but White will then rely on the axiom that the combination of the Queen and the opposite-colored Bishop favors the attacking side. }
