{ We keep the pressure on Black's King with the Knight actively placed on g5, whilst another Knight gets centralized! Also, there is a tendency of removing Nf6 as a defender around the Black's King and clearing h5 square for Qd1-Qh5, and all of that with tempo! }
8... h6
{ Black inserts an intermediate h6 aiming to force trades on e4 in a way where White can not conquer it with a piece. However, White has an intermediary move, as well, aimed against this idea. }
9. Nxf6+
{ With a tempo check, White prepares to toggle the Knight from g5 to the e4-square, with a double attack on the f6 and d6 spots! }
9... Qxf6 10. Ne4
{ White takes control over e4 square and puts Black in trouble due to a threat of overtaking the advantage of the Bishop pair. Black is forced to find a good square for the Queen which would be helpful in defense of the Kingside since White's pieces are obviously ready for attack! }
10... Qg6
{ With this move Black aims to prevent Qh5 and keeps an eye on the g4 and g2 squares. However, the Queen is now a bit marginalized. }
11. Qf3
{ Not only that with this move White secures the g2-pawn, but aims to knock the Black Queen away after h4-h5. This advance will provide a g3-square for White's Queen and an attack will continue with a threat of Bxh6! }
11... a5
{ Black needs to search for a counterattack on the Queenside and tries to hunt the light-squared Bishop which is one of the most important pieces for White's attack. }
12. a3
{ White takes a short break from actions on the Kingside and makes a shelter for the light-squared Bishop before proceeding with the h4-h5 plan and afterward with Qg3.   White has a nice initiative with a mating attack. The light-squared Bishop which will stay on the long a2-g8 diagonal eyeing Black's King, while the Knight on e4 controls the center and all the important squares around it. One should not forget that Black's Queen on g6 is kind of clumsy, and if White manages to hurry with an attack on it, the connection between the Bishop on d6 and Queen on g6 will be broken, resulting in material advantage for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Bishop's Opening 2...Nf6: Berlin Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's opening 2...Nf6: 3. d3 c6 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3 Bd6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nf6
{ Berlin defense by Black! This is absolutely the most frequent move by Black against the Bishop's opening. Another common option especially on the lower level is  2...Nc6  , but 2...Nf6 is by far way more common in the practice! With the last move, Black aims to stay active, threatens White's central pawn on  e4  , and enters the Berlin defense. }
3. d3
{ Already at the third move, White has an opportunity to pick up the aggressive approach with the Urusov Gambit  3.d4!?  or to choose a more peaceful approach with 3.d3 which enters the Bishop's opening. Both options are fully covered throughout the course.  The Urusov Gambit is very interesting for the players whose main weapon is the tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for blitz and rapid games, especially when the beginner seats on the other side and tries to find a proper plan to defend as Black.  On the other side, 3.d3 provides a stable and safe positional approach without sacrifices or material losses and it gives flexible positions where White has initiative and the attack which is mainly based on equal material and clear activity. Interestingly, it is used in almost 80% of the games at this point and while  3.d4  was used mainly only once by top players in a blitz or rapid games, nowadays 3.d3 move presents a bulletproof approach by literally all top players including Carlsen, Nepo, Caruana, Firouzja, Grischuk, and other top players! }
3... c6
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White has not played Nf3 yet to place pressure on the e5 pawn. On the other hand, Black prepares his own central advance with d5. From my own experience, it turned out that the last move 3...c6 was mainly used by stronger players or players who were familiar with the opening theory. Also, one should not forget that after:   3...Nc6  4.Nc3  the game transposes into lines explained within the 1.e4 e5 2.Bc4 Nc6 chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... d5
{ Black builds a center with a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. If Black instead goes for  4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  the position transposes to a sideline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  c6  4...Be7  , covered in 4...Be7 }
5. Bb3
{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Bd6
{ Of all the fifth moves, this one turned out to be the most common in practice and there is a quite logical reason for it! Black continues development with a useful move that has a dual purpose - protecting e5 and preparing for O-O, Re8. }
6. Nc3
{ Of course, now that the contact between the Queen and the d5-pawn is severed, White uses the opportunity to immediately attack Black's center. There is also quite a good and solid alternative  6.exd5  cxd5  7.Bg5  where White has quite a simple game and keeps a slight advantage. }
6... dxe4
{ Black might also choose to open the center with this move, but White's light-squared Bishop gets active now, eyeing the vulnerable f7-pawn. }
7. Ng5
{ White wins a tempo by attacking the f7-pawn and prepares to conquer the e4-square with a piece with the idea to move minor and heavy pieces towards the Kingside. The light-squared Bishop gets the long diagonal to control and after Nce4 White will be ready to continue with Qf3 and attack on the Kingside! }
7... O-O 8. Ncxe4
{ We keep the pressure on Black's King with the Knight actively placed on g5, whilst another Knight gets centralized! Also, there is a tendency of removing Nf6 as a defender around the Black's King and clearing h5 square for Qd1-Qh5, and all of that with tempo! }
8... Nxe4
{ Black hopes to win some space with these trades, but White should not be worried since we won a valuable tempo after the forthcoming recapture. }
9. Nxe4
{ As it was previously mentioned, White takes control over the e4-square with a Knight and gains a nice outpost here. Not only that White's Knight is centralized on the perfect square, but White will soon be able to gain a long-term Bishop pair advantage! }
9... Be7
{ Black aims to keep Bishops on the board but White has time now to stop further Black activities and to create a mating attack on the Kingside! }
10. Qh5
{ The Queen actively joins the game and at the same time attacks e5 pawn and points out once again that the f7 pawn is vulnerable and that Black needs to think about defense here. }
10... Nd7
{ Black needs to protect the e5-pawn and has a plan to relocate Knight to  f6  , moving White's Queen away and supporting the King's defense. The advance of the pawns in front of the King loses on the spot since  10...h6?  faces a devastating sacrifice  11.Bxh6  gxh6  12.Qg6  Kh8  13.Qxh6  Kg8  14.g4!  and White is winning with the idea of g5 followed by Nf6;   While after  10...g6?  11.Qh6  White immediately gains a winning position with a direct threat of Ng5 when Black will be forced to take it with Bishop and White will have full control of dark squares around the King. }
11. O-O
{ White concludes development and still keeps an eye on the e5-pawn preparing to open f-file with f4! }
11... Qc7
{ With this move Black defends the e5-pawn and follows up with the previously mentioned plan of Nf6, hoping to move White's Queen away from the Kingside. }
12. f4
{ White is just that bit faster to prevent Nf6 and claims the advantage thanks to the active Bishops, centralized Knight, and the forthcoming attack on the Kingside. An immediate threat of White is to take fxe5 and the f7-pawn will be hanging. But be careful, if Black proceeds with logical  12...Nf6  White should not hurry to take the pawn with  13.Qxe5  due to  Qxe5  14.fxe5  Nxe4  15.dxe4  Bc5   But instead, White gains a clear advantage after  13.Nxf6  Bxf6  14.f5!  limiting Black's Bishops with a threat of Rf3-Rh3! }
*

