8... Nxe4
{ Black hopes to win some space with these trades, but White should not be worried since we won a valuable tempo after the forthcoming recapture. }
9. Nxe4
{ As it was previously mentioned, White takes control over the e4-square with a Knight and gains a nice outpost here. Not only that White's Knight is centralized on the perfect square, but White will soon be able to gain a long-term Bishop pair advantage! }
9... Bf5
{ Black realizes that there is no time for defending the Bishop pair and continues with active development, where the light-squared Bishop takes the role of a defender of the h7 and f7 spots after a possible Bg6. }
10. Qf3
{ With a tempo attack on the light-squared Bishop White relocates the Queen on the Kingside and forces Black to decide what to do with the Bishop on f5. }
10... Bg6
{ If Black tries to hold the Bishop pair White gets the opportunity to seize the advantage! Light-squared Bishop now becomes the target of White's actions! }
11. h4
{ Due to the threat of h5 Black needs to push the pawns around the King to follow up with the idea of keeping the Bishop pair on the board. }
11... h6
{ Black hopes to find a shelter for the light-squared Bishop but it is questionable if h6 is helpful in defense of the King. White will first continue with regular development, and afterward, the Kingside mating attack will be continued! }
12. Be3
{ Not only that we include the last minor piece into a game, but we are also ready for O-O-O, and at the same time, Black's possible idea of activation with Na6-Nf6 is stopped! }
12... Kh8
{ Black realizes that the only chance to save the King is to move the centralized Knight on e4 away. Since Be4 would not make sense now after all the efforts of Black to keep Bishops on the board, the only way to do this is to continue with f5. }
13. O-O-O
{ White ignores Black's idea of f5 and puts the King in the safe zone. It is questionable if Black is ready for central breaks since the Queenside pieces are still undeveloped, but White is certainly ready for that! }
13... f5 14. Nxd6
{ White has no problem to finally take Black's dark squared Bishop and gain a long-term advantage of the Bishop pair. In that manner, we do not need to be focused only on Kingside now, but also lookout for breaks in the center! }
14... Qxd6 15. d4
{ And White enjoys a clearly better position! According to the basic principles of chess, in a position with the Bishop pair, we are advised to open the center up and activate the Rook on d1. Black's Queen on d6 is exposed to a very uncomfortable pin and one should not forget that the opponent's Queenside is not developed yet, and Black doesn't have many possibilities to gain activity. }
