7. Bg5
{ White continues with the most natural follow-up, developing a dark-squared Bishop on the most active square. With a pinned Knight on f6, Black is once again faced with issues of the hanging d5 pawn. }
7... Nbd7
{ A typical mistake that is very easy to be made! I have won a couple of games from here, because the Black players thought that White can not take d5 pawn due to the double attack Qa5 threat. But we have other plans to gain a pawn-up advantage! }
8. exd5 cxd5 9. Bxd5
{ Of course, we won't fall into the trap of taking  9.Nxd5  and losing a piece after  9...Bxd5  10.Bxd5  Qa5  with a double attack on the King and Bishop on d5.  After this move, Black does not have this possibility and we gain a clear pawn up in the 9th move of play! }
9... Bxd5 10. Nxd5 Qa5+ 11. Nc3
{ And after a simple step-back move, White keeps a material advantage with a clearly better position and easy play. If Black proceeds with  11...Bb4  threatening the pinned Knight on c3, after  12.Bd2  White holds the position and aims to proceed with O-O and further development! }
