{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Bd6
{ Of all the fifth moves, this one turned out to be the most common in practice and there is a quite logical reason for it! Black continues development with a useful move that has a dual purpose - protecting e5 and preparing for O-O, Re8. }
6. Nc3
{ Of course, now that the contact between the Queen and the d5-pawn is severed, White uses the opportunity to immediately attack Black's center. There is also quite a good and solid alternative  6.exd5  cxd5  7.Bg5  where White has quite a simple game and keeps a slight advantage. }
6... Be6
{ With this simple development move Black stubbornly tries to maintain tension in the center. However, that doesn't stop White's development and White will keep pressure on  the d5 and e5 exposed pawns. }
7. Bg5
{ White continues with the most natural follow-up, developing a dark-squared Bishop on the most active square. With a pinned Knight on f6, Black is once again faced with issues of the hanging d5 pawn. }
7... Qa5
{ Black attempts to strikes back with an active move. Not only that there are no problems with the pinned Knight on f6, but d5 is defended and Black also has a direct idea of d4. However, White can escape from all these threats with one move! }
8. O-O
{ With this clever development move, White escapes from the pin and prepares for action over the e-file. Black toggled their pieces to defend the d5 pawn, but now they will face difficulties to defend e5-square! }
8... Nbd7 9. exd5
{ As White cannot further increase the pressure on Black's center, we decide to open up the position and use the e-file for further actions! }
9... cxd5 10. Qe1
{ Although  10.Re1  looks more logical, with this beautiful move White establishes geometrical relation between the Queens and introduces the idea of:   10...--  11.d4  e4  11.Nxe4! }
10... Qc5
{ Black escapes from the Queen pin and prevents any discovered attacks. However, the e5 pawn is weakened now. }
11. Bxf6
{ With this beautiful trade White forces Black to double pawns on the Kingside! }
11... gxf6
{ If Black insists on keeping a healthy pawn structure with  11...Nxf6  White strikes back with  12.Nxe5  d4  13.Nxf7!  and Black's Bishop on e6 would be hanging as well as the Rook on h8. }
12. d4
{ Since White concluded the development, we are able to continue with an effective center break! Black's King is still positioned in the center, and White's Queen indirectly pins it! }
12... exd4 13. Nxd5
{ White uses the terrible position of Black's King to permanently damage Black's pawn structure. }
13... O-O-O 14. Qe4
{ And with a direct threat of Nd4 and the idea of Rad1, White is clearly better. Black faces issues with their 4 pawn islands and it is questionable how he can improve defense over the weakest d4 pawn. The ideas of White are also shown in a game Tiviakov,S-Swinkels, R Vlissingen 2004. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Bishop's Opening 2...Nf6: Berlin Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's opening 2...Nf6: 3. d3 c6 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3 Bd6 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nf6
{ Berlin defense by Black! This is absolutely the most frequent move by Black against the Bishop's opening. Another common option especially on the lower level is  2...Nc6  , but 2...Nf6 is by far way more common in the practice! With the last move, Black aims to stay active, threatens White's central pawn on  e4  , and enters the Berlin defense. }
3. d3
{ Already at the third move, White has an opportunity to pick up the aggressive approach with the Urusov Gambit  3.d4!?  or to choose a more peaceful approach with 3.d3 which enters the Bishop's opening. Both options are fully covered throughout the course.  The Urusov Gambit is very interesting for the players whose main weapon is the tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for blitz and rapid games, especially when the beginner seats on the other side and tries to find a proper plan to defend as Black.  On the other side, 3.d3 provides a stable and safe positional approach without sacrifices or material losses and it gives flexible positions where White has initiative and the attack which is mainly based on equal material and clear activity. Interestingly, it is used in almost 80% of the games at this point and while  3.d4  was used mainly only once by top players in a blitz or rapid games, nowadays 3.d3 move presents a bulletproof approach by literally all top players including Carlsen, Nepo, Caruana, Firouzja, Grischuk, and other top players! }
3... c6
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White has not played Nf3 yet to place pressure on the e5 pawn. On the other hand, Black prepares his own central advance with d5. From my own experience, it turned out that the last move 3...c6 was mainly used by stronger players or players who were familiar with the opening theory. Also, one should not forget that after:   3...Nc6  4.Nc3  the game transposes into lines explained within the 1.e4 e5 2.Bc4 Nc6 chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... d5
{ Black builds a center with a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. If Black instead goes for  4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  the position transposes to a sideline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  c6  4...Be7  , covered in 4...Be7 }
5. Bb3
{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Bd6
{ Of all the fifth moves, this one turned out to be the most common in practice and there is a quite logical reason for it! Black continues development with a useful move that has a dual purpose - protecting e5 and preparing for O-O, Re8. }
6. Nc3
{ Of course, now that the contact between the Queen and the d5-pawn is severed, White uses the opportunity to immediately attack Black's center. There is also quite a good and solid alternative  6.exd5  cxd5  7.Bg5  where White has quite a simple game and keeps a slight advantage. }
6... Be6
{ With this simple development move Black stubbornly tries to maintain tension in the center. However, that doesn't stop White's development and White will keep pressure on  the d5 and e5 exposed pawns. }
7. Bg5
{ White continues with the most natural follow-up, developing a dark-squared Bishop on the most active square. With a pinned Knight on f6, Black is once again faced with issues of the hanging d5 pawn. }
7... Qa5
{ Black attempts to strikes back with an active move. Not only that there are no problems with the pinned Knight on f6, but d5 is defended and Black also has a direct idea of d4. However, White can escape from all these threats with one move! }
8. O-O
{ With this clever development move, White escapes from the pin and prepares for action over the e-file. Black toggled their pieces to defend the d5 pawn, but now they will face difficulties to defend e5-square! }
8... Nbd7 9. exd5
{ As White cannot further increase the pressure on Black's center, we decide to open up the position and use the e-file for further actions! }
9... cxd5 10. Qe1
{ Although  10.Re1  looks more logical, with this beautiful move White establishes geometrical relation between the Queens and introduces the idea of:   10...--  11.d4  e4  11.Nxe4! }
10... Rc8
{ And suddenly Black has no good move! The alternatives are not helping either.  10...O-O?  is a mistake that instantly loses a pawn after  11.Bxf6!  followed by  11...--  12.Nxd5  and White have a clear pawn up with a clear advantage! }
11. d4
{ White reacts in the center and aims to open the e-file, pinning Black's King. After possible exchanges or advances by Black, the pawn on d5 will be weakened. }
11... e4
{ Black is practically forced to block the center with this move, and the pawn on d5 will be a possible target now. If Black instead continues with  11...Bb4  aiming to damage White's pawn structure on the Queenside, after  12.Bd2  White threatens to play a3 putting Queen on a5 into a pin. The only move is  12...Bxc3  13.Bxc3  and in the game between Delchev, A-Jovanic, O Zadar 2004 Black went for an exchange sacrifice with  13...Rxc3  14.bxc3  e4  and White struck back with  15.Ng5!  and threats of  Ne6  and pawn break with  f3  or  c4  . After  15...O-O  16.c4  Qxe1  17.Raxe1  h6  18.Nxe6  fxe6  White is winning with  19.f3  with the decisive advantage of an exchange up. }
12. Nxe4
{ Thanks to the poorly placed Bd6 White wins a pawn, but we will not stop here! Black is in huge trouble with badly positioned pieces and White can use it to win the game within a few moves, as it will be shown here! }
12... Qb6 13. Nxd6+ Qxd6 14. Bd2
{ White gained the Bishop pair advantage and aims to continue with Bb4. Black can not castle anymore and there is no possible activity for him here! }
14... Ne4 15. Bb4
{ We took full control over dark squares and the Bishop on b4 can not be moved away! }
15... Qf4 16. c4
{ With the Bishop pair on the board every opening of the position is good for White. For that reason, we do not care about material, and we continue with pressure on the Black's King! }
16... dxc4 17. Ba4
{ White's Bishops are now perfectly positioned and we have a direct threat of Ne5! Black practically needs to move the King away, but there is no good way to escape the pins! }
17... Kd8 18. Ne5 Nb6 19. g3
{ And at the moment when it looked like Black will have a break from the Bishops, he faces issues with the hanging Knight on e4 which can not be defended anymore. Jones,R was forced to resign here against Giri,A in a game played in Warsaw 2013. }
*

