{ Black builds a center with a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. If Black instead goes for  4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  the position transposes to a sideline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  c6  4...Be7  , covered in 4...Be7 }
5. Bb3
{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Bd6
{ Of all the fifth moves, this one turned out to be the most common in practice and there is a quite logical reason for it! Black continues development with a useful move that has a dual purpose - protecting e5 and preparing for O-O, Re8. }
6. Nc3
{ Of course, now that the contact between the Queen and the d5-pawn is severed, White uses the opportunity to immediately attack Black's center. There is also quite a good and solid alternative  6.exd5  cxd5  7.Bg5  where White has quite a simple game and keeps a slight advantage. }
6... d4
{ Black decides that his best chance is to simply close the center before White accumulates small advantages while pouncing against the d5 and e5 pawns. }
7. Ne2
{ By forcing d4, White aims to exploit the a2-g8 diagonal for the light-squared Bishop, as well as the f5-square for the Knight. Of course, Black's center could be easily destroyed with a center break of c3! }
7... Na6
{ With this move Black aims to hunt White's light-squared Bishop, keeping the possibility to develop the Bishop from c8. }
8. c3
{ Not only that White decides to strike back in the center, making the d5 pawn weak, but also the Bishop from b3 has a safe spot now! }
8... dxc3 9. bxc3
{ Black was practically forced to accept this trade of pawns, and all of a sudden, White gains full control over the central squares! }
9... O-O 10. O-O Nc5 11. Bc2
{ The light-squared Bishop is a valuable asset and White keeps it on the board. With the idea of Ng3-Nh4 gaining control over the f5 outpost, White would have great initiative. It is important to emphasize that we should not hurry for center breaks of d4, since that would make the e4 pawn vulnerable. }
11... Bg4 12. Ng3
{ Knight on f3 and Queen are connected, and White is ready to move the Bishop away after h3. }
12... Nh5
{ This is actually not stopping h3, it is rather helping White to open the f-file. }
13. h3 Nxg3 14. fxg3
{ We have no issue to have double pawns on g-file as long as we have full control over the f-file eyeing the f7 weakness. Black's Bishop on g4 is under attack and Black needs to react. }
14... Bh5 15. g4
{ And after this move it is clear that Black has issues keeping the light-squared Bishop on the board. After  15...Bg6  White is ready to continue hunting with  16.h4  and Black's King will be under attack. As it was shown in a game Nunn, J-Kortschnoj, V Johannesburg 1981 White has an easy play with a clear advantage. }
