7... Nbd7
{ Although Black has the idea of  Nc5  as he would have with  7...Na6  , the difference is that light-squared Bishop is now blocked. }
8. c3
{ White aims to immediately open the center, forcing Black to proceed with c5 if he wants to keep center control. }
8... c5
{ And now it is clear that White aimed for this goal- to make Knight on  d7  weak. Black's Knight on  d7  looks clumsy now, as the perfect square for it would be  c6  . At the same time, Bishop on  c8  is still blocked, and Black needs to go for the suspicious Nb6 in order to keep up with development. If Black instead plays  8...dxc3  after  9.bxc3  O-O  10.O-O  Nc5  11.Bc2  the game transposes into 5...Bd6 6.Nc3 d4 7.Ne2 Na6. }
9. O-O
{ Without issues, White continues with simple development and aims to play Ng3, followed by the annoying Nf5! }
9... O-O 10. Ng3
{ Of course, there is no reason for White to give up on the idea of Nf5! }
10... b5
{ This is a suspicious move by Black who forgot that White has plans on the Kingside. After Nf5, N3h4, White will be ready to open the Kingside with f4! }
11. Nf5 { Finally, we reached the desirable outpost! } 11... Nb6 12. cxd4
{ With a clever trade of the central pawns, White prevents any possible c4 advance and turns to play on the Kingside! }
12... cxd4 13. N3h4
{ This is a very interesting move with the idea of f4, which was previously mentioned. At the same time, White also improves control over the f5-outpost and makes the path for the Queen to join the attack! }
13... Re8
{ Although this move might look clumsy, Black needs to prepare development of Be6 before playing it! }
14. f4
{ White has no reason to stop with the idea and opens the Kingside with a plan of Qf3 and possible Qg3! }
14... Be6 15. Qf3
{ Faced with a direct threat of Qg3 with a double attack on the g7 and e5 pawns, Black is forced to react aiming to stop this attack! }
15... exf4 16. Nxd6 Qxd6 17. Bxf4
{ White removes Black's Bishop from d6 and gains a clear advantage of the Bishop pair. After the forthcoming Be5 Black will face difficulties with defense of the Knight on f6! }
17... Qf8 18. Be5
{ Faced with a threat of Bf6 Black is forced to give up on the light-squared Bishop which held the f7 spot. After this trade, White will be able to fully use the open f-file for attacks. }
18... Bxb3 19. Bxf6 Be6 20. Qg3
{ With a tremendous attack on the Black's King and two direct threats of Bd4 and Nf5 White has a winning position as it could be seen in a game Miroshnichenko,E -Jedryczka,K Polanica Zdroj 2001. }
