{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White has not played Nf3 yet to place pressure on the e5 pawn. On the other hand, Black prepares his own central advance with d5. From my own experience, it turned out that the last move 3...c6 was mainly used by stronger players or players who were familiar with the opening theory. Also, one should not forget that after:   3...Nc6  4.Nc3  the game transposes into lines explained within the 1.e4 e5 2.Bc4 Nc6 chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... d5
{ Black builds a center with a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. If Black instead goes for  4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  the position transposes to a sideline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  c6  4...Be7  , covered in 4...Be7 }
5. Bb3
{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Bg4
{ Although this temporary pin guards the e5-pawn and also Black got his Bishop out before playing Nbd7, it is suspicious since he will be swiftly forced to surrender the Bishop pair! }
6. h3
{ Black is immediately forced to give up the light-squared Bishop. White can gain a slight advantage with  6.exd5  as well and after  6...cxd5  7.h3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  Nc6  White keeps up with the plan to attack Black's center  9.Nc3  Nd4  10.Qg3  with a slight advantage thanks to a perfectly placed Queen on  g3  that controls the g7-spot and stops Black to defend dark-squared Bishop. White might continue here with Bg5, renewing the pressure against d5, as well as with Ba4!?, which might be annoying for Black! }
6... Bh5
{ If Black stubbornly tries to keep Bishop here, this retreat is rather weak and Black will have to give the material for little or no compensation. }
7. exd5
{ White reveals from the possibly hanging pawn and prepares to capture on e5! }
7... cxd5 8. g4
{ Breaking the pin and forcing Black to attempt the speculative sacrifice. }
8... Nxg4
{ Clumsy  8...Bg6  instead would give easy advantage to White after  9.Nxe5  and White has a clear pawn up without any issues! }
9. hxg4
{ Of course, we should not hesitate to accept the suspicious sacrifice! } 9...
Bxg4 10. Rg1
{ With a very important move White tries to release the pin and forces Black to react with the Bishop. }
10... h5 11. Nc3
{ With a piece for two pawns, White needs to stay active! With development continuation, White, at the same time, attacks the d5 pawn! }
11... Bb4
{ Although this pin looks very uncomfortable, White has no issues after another development move with possible tactical engagements! }
12. Bd2 { Once again, the most important Black's central pawn is hanging! }
12... Bxc3
{ Of course, if Black instead goes for  13...d4  White would be happy to take control over a beautiful outpost with Ne4 and clear advantage with perfectly active light-squared Bishop! }
13. Bxc3 d4 14. Bd2
{ Not only that once again the light-squared Bishop got control over the longest possible diagonal, but White prepares for development after Qe2 and O-O-O and there will be no problems anymore! Just a piece up and winning position! }
14... Nc6
{ Of course after  14...Qf6  15.Rg3  White easily defends the Knight and continues with the same plan of Qe2 and O-O-O. }
15. Qe2 Qf6 16. Rg3
{ White is ready for O-O-O and to gain control over light-squares after Qe4, at the same time getting away from the pin. Black can not easily use the passed h-pawn and White has time to consolidate with a decisive advantage, as it could be seen in a game Sadler,M-Jowett, P Blackpool 2016. }
