{ Although this temporary pin guards the e5-pawn and also Black got his Bishop out before playing Nbd7, it is suspicious since he will be swiftly forced to surrender the Bishop pair! }
6. h3
{ Black is immediately forced to give up the light-squared Bishop. White can gain a slight advantage with  6.exd5  as well and after  6...cxd5  7.h3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  Nc6  White keeps up with the plan to attack Black's center  9.Nc3  Nd4  10.Qg3  with a slight advantage thanks to a perfectly placed Queen on  g3  that controls the g7-spot and stops Black to defend dark-squared Bishop. White might continue here with Bg5, renewing the pressure against d5, as well as with Ba4!?, which might be annoying for Black! }
6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3
{ White got the Bishop pair and the Queen landed on the excellent square from which it can press the d5-pawn, support g4 ideas against both f7 weakness and the Knight on f6, as well as it has just cleared d1-square for Nc3, Bd2/Bg5 followed by O-O-O. }
7... a5
{ Inserting a5 goes with an idea to harass the Bishop on b3. However, that does not work smoothly for Black! }
8. a4
{ The eternal question, a3 or a4? This dilemma is big, almost as 'which Rook to which file.' a3 is more reserved and is also used when White wants to provoke Black's over-extension on the Queenside with b5-a4, etc. On the other side, a4 might be more committing, but at the same time, very valuable when White can secure the b5 square for the Knight. We will see this soon. }
8... Bb4+
{ If Black tries to develop with tempo check, he will be blocked as you will see soon! }
9. c3
{ Of course, after obtaining the Bishop pair, White does not trade one of them with  9.Bd2  Bd2  . Black forced  c4  which is now useful for us, since it provides a potential safe spot for the light-squared Bishop, and gives us better central control. }
9... Be7
{ If Black goes for a 'more active' retreat with  9...Bc5  White has an easy play after  10.O-O  with the idea of Bg5 since the Knight on  f6  is vulnerable for pins. As it was played in a game Fortunato, L-Petria, F LSS email 2007,  Black needs to go for  10...dxe4  , otherwise White will capture on  d5  , and after  11.dxe4  O-O  12.Bg5  Nbd7  White just goes for normal development  13.Rd1  Qb6  14.Nd2  h6  with a simple step-back  15.Bh4  Rad8  16.Ba2  prepares the activation of the Knight and it is obvious that after  16...Qc7  17.Qf5  White has a clear advantage thanks to the Bishop pair and full control over the play! }
10. O-O O-O
{ The absence of Nf3 @@StartBracket@@which was pressing e5@@EndBracket@@ and the occupation of the c3-square @@StartBracket@@from where White was attacking d5@@EndBracket@@, changes White's plans a bit. }
11. Na3
{ White goes now for a flexible move that keeps options of jumping to c2 with maneuver of Ne3-Nf5, or to jump to c4 if Black trades the pawn on e4, and of course, there is an option for Nb5 if White captures on d5. }
11... Qb6 12. Bc2
{ White keeps Bishops safe and now it is obvious that we will go for a plan of ed5 followed by Nb5! }
12... Nbd7 13. exd5 cxd5 14. Nb5
{ And finally, the Knight got the perfect space from where it can not be moved! }
14... Rac8 15. Be3
{ White will continue Rae1 and Bg5 to threaten the central pawns. Of course, there is always possibility for d4 break, but White has no reason to hurry with it, as it was shown in a game Holdschik,J-Edighoffer,H Chessfriend.com 2003. }
