[White "1) Bishop's Opening 2...Nf6: Berlin Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's opening 2...Nf6: 3. d3 c6 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3 Bg4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nf6
{ Berlin defense by Black! This is absolutely the most frequent move by Black against the Bishop's opening. Another common option especially on the lower level is  2...Nc6  , but 2...Nf6 is by far way more common in the practice! With the last move, Black aims to stay active, threatens White's central pawn on  e4  , and enters the Berlin defense. }
3. d3
{ Already at the third move, White has an opportunity to pick up the aggressive approach with the Urusov Gambit  3.d4!?  or to choose a more peaceful approach with 3.d3 which enters the Bishop's opening. Both options are fully covered throughout the course.  The Urusov Gambit is very interesting for the players whose main weapon is the tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for blitz and rapid games, especially when the beginner seats on the other side and tries to find a proper plan to defend as Black.  On the other side, 3.d3 provides a stable and safe positional approach without sacrifices or material losses and it gives flexible positions where White has initiative and the attack which is mainly based on equal material and clear activity. Interestingly, it is used in almost 80% of the games at this point and while  3.d4  was used mainly only once by top players in a blitz or rapid games, nowadays 3.d3 move presents a bulletproof approach by literally all top players including Carlsen, Nepo, Caruana, Firouzja, Grischuk, and other top players! }
3... c6
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White has not played Nf3 yet to place pressure on the e5 pawn. On the other hand, Black prepares his own central advance with d5. From my own experience, it turned out that the last move 3...c6 was mainly used by stronger players or players who were familiar with the opening theory. Also, one should not forget that after:   3...Nc6  4.Nc3  the game transposes into lines explained within the 1.e4 e5 2.Bc4 Nc6 chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... d5
{ Black builds a center with a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. If Black instead goes for  4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  the position transposes to a sideline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  c6  4...Be7  , covered in 4...Be7 }
5. Bb3
{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Bg4
{ Although this temporary pin guards the e5-pawn and also Black got his Bishop out before playing Nbd7, it is suspicious since he will be swiftly forced to surrender the Bishop pair! }
6. h3
{ Black is immediately forced to give up the light-squared Bishop. White can gain a slight advantage with  6.exd5  as well and after  6...cxd5  7.h3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  Nc6  White keeps up with the plan to attack Black's center  9.Nc3  Nd4  10.Qg3  with a slight advantage thanks to a perfectly placed Queen on  g3  that controls the g7-spot and stops Black to defend dark-squared Bishop. White might continue here with Bg5, renewing the pressure against d5, as well as with Ba4!?, which might be annoying for Black! }
6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3
{ White got the Bishop pair and the Queen landed on the excellent square from which it can press the d5-pawn, support g4 ideas against both f7 weakness and the Knight on f6, as well as it has just cleared d1-square for Nc3, Bd2/Bg5 followed by O-O-O. }
7... a5
{ Inserting a5 goes with an idea to harass the Bishop on b3. However, that does not work smoothly for Black! }
8. a4
{ The eternal question, a3 or a4? This dilemma is big, almost as 'which Rook to which file.' a3 is more reserved and is also used when White wants to provoke Black's over-extension on the Queenside with b5-a4, etc. On the other side, a4 might be more committing, but at the same time, very valuable when White can secure the b5 square for the Knight. We will see this soon. }
8... dxe4 { Black continues with the plan of removing the d5-weakness. } 9.
dxe4 Nbd7
{ It might look that Black now has a dangerous threat of Nc5, pressuring both the e4 pawn and the Bishop on b3. Anyway, you should not be stressed about this threat, because White has great development and if Black tends to keep the King in the center while maneuvering with Knight, that would be good for us! }
10. O-O
{ White can also save time and allow Nc5, still achieving a good position. The alternative that saves the Bishop pair could be  10.c3  when White creates a c2 shelter for the light-squared Bishop. After  10...Be7  11.O-O  O-O  12.Nd2  White continues development with the idea of Nc4, or even Rd1 with Nf1.  12...Nc5  13.Bc2  Qc7  14.Nc4  and after  14...Ne6  White just continues with the activation  15.Re1  Rfd8  and finally  16.Qg3  when Black is forced to protect the  e5  pawn. The Queen is positioned against Black's King and supports the advance of h4-h5. You should have in mind that Queen can also go back to  f3  , with the idea of  g3  that prevents Black to activate with the  Nf4  jump. The game between Movsesian, S-Gashimov, V Sabadell 2008 continued with  16...Nd7  17.h4  when White has started the Kingside attack. }
10... Nc5
{ As we have assumed, Black goes for the Knight activation and attacks b3 and e4. Of course, that does not stop us to continue developing. }
11. Nd2
{ Defending the e4-pawn, the Knight is on the way to the excellent c4-square from where it attacks Black's central e5 pawn! }
11... Be7 12. Nc4
{ White is not afraid to trade the e-pawns because he already castled and is ready to play Re1, while Black's King is still in the center! }
12... O-O
{ If Black instead goes for  12...Ncxe4?!  13.Nxe5  O-O  14.Re1  White gains a clearly better position and Black is strongly pressed on f7 and along with the e-file. ;   Instead, Black can also play  12...Nxb3?!  13.Qxb3  and White has a clear advantage. The point is that whenever Black trades on b3, his weaknesses get into the spotlight. e5 is hanging @@StartBracket@@e4 not really as there is always Re1@@EndBracket@@, and b6 will be under pressure by White's Knight and Bishop. A sample line might be  13...Qc7  14.Be3!  Nxe4  15.Bb6  with idea Rfe1 and Black is overwhelmed. }
13. Re1
{ Even from this innocuous looking position White can develop a tremendous attack, as it will be shown soon! }
13... Qc7
{ Black needs to take care about the hanging central pawn and goes for development move that connects the Rooks. }
14. Bd2
{ Of course, White will not stop with pressure and Bishop can come to c3, improving the attack on the e5 pawn. }
14... Nfd7
{ One should not forget that if Black takes the light squared Bishop with  14...Nxb3  15.Qxb3  White swings the Queen on the Queenside, and Black again faces weaknesses on e5 and b6. }
15. Red1
{ White no longer needs to protect the e4-pawn and now we prepare a devious attacking plan! It is obvious that there are no defenders of the Black's King and White will have nice tactical engagements with possible Bh6, as it will be seen soon! }
15... b6 16. Ba2
{ We do not care anymore about the Queenside pawns, and idea is to keep Bishops on the board. The light-squared Bishop will be a very important piece for the attack, eyeing the f7-spot and indirectly pinning Black's King. }
16... Nxa4 17. Bh6
{ Out of nowhere, the attack on the Kingside has begun! White uses clumsy positioned Black pieces to open the g-file! }
17... Bf6
{ Black needs to improve defense over the  f7  spot, since the White's threat was  Bg7!  The point is that if Black takes  17...gxh6  18.Qg4!  comes with a double attack on the Knight on  d7  and check at the same time. The same would happen if Black allowed us to take with Bxg7. }
18. Rd6
{ As it was seen in the game between Semrl,M-Hofmann,G ICCF email 2014, White does not stop with pressure! The idea is Rad1, and Black will face issues with the Knight on d7. Due to a threat of Qg4, Black still does not threaten to take gh6. On the other hand, Black can not just move the Nd7 to defend, since in that case, White has a sacrifice with Rf6! and there will be no defense for Black's King! }
*

