{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White has not played Nf3 yet to place pressure on the e5 pawn. On the other hand, Black prepares his own central advance with d5. From my own experience, it turned out that the last move 3...c6 was mainly used by stronger players or players who were familiar with the opening theory. Also, one should not forget that after:   3...Nc6  4.Nc3  the game transposes into lines explained within the 1.e4 e5 2.Bc4 Nc6 chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... d5
{ Black builds a center with a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. If Black instead goes for  4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  the position transposes to a sideline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  c6  4...Be7  , covered in 4...Be7 }
5. Bb3
{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Bb4+
{ Black has a large number of options but this check is one of the most frequent in this position. Black aims to stop White to develop the Knight to c3 from where it would press the d5 pawn. }
6. Bd2
{ This is practically the only option for White to block the check. Instead,  6.Nc3  runs into  6...d4  , while Black would be happy to see  6.c3  Bd6  when White will have issues with e4 pawn and lousy center. }
6... Bd6
{ If Black decides to retreat the Bishop, not only that he loses one tempo, but White is able to continue with the most active development, Nc3, O-O Re1. }
7. Nc3
{ Of course, White is not missing the opportunity to increase the pressure on d5, and now Black has a huge decision to make- shall they advance with d4, shall the center open up with dxe4, or shall they keep the tension by defending d5? }
7... d4
{ Black takes a small psychological victory, forcing us to play with the Knight once again. Closing the center looks like the safest option for Black, but at this point, White revealed the Bishop on b3 eyeing the Kingside. }
8. Ne2
{ The Knight heads to g3, eyeing an opportunity to jump to f5 after preparation with Nh4. The pawn breaks c2-c3 and f2-f4 later are also on the cards, as White aims to open the position with actions on the Kingside. }
8... Nbd7
{ Black does not hurry with castling, and threatens Nc5 as White has only a few options to keep the light-squared Bishop in play. If Black plays instead 8...O-O White can continue with normal development 9.O-O, followed by Ng3, Nh4, Nf5. }
9. O-O
{ For sure we do not want to go here with the suspicious  9.c3?!  since it would lead anyway to  9...Nc5  when Black attacks the Bishop on b3 and d3-pawn. After  10.Bc2  Black has great initiative after  10...Nfxe4!  followed by d3. }
9... O-O
{ Black continues with development, putting the King into safety. However, it was possible for him to continue with  9...Nc5  as well, but after  10.c3  White has a nice possibility to undermine the center. If Black accepts to take the pawn on d3 with  10...Nxd3  after  11.cxd4  exd4  12.Bxf7!  is on the board, and after  12...Kxf7  13.Qb3  comes with a double attack on the King and Knight on d6. }
10. h3
{ White wants to be sure that Black will not have Bg4 after moving the Knight from d7. At this point, he is ready to continue with the plan of Ng3-Nf5.   A good alternative for White could be  10.a3  first, ensuring that light squared Bishop will stay in the game after  10...Nc5  11.Ba2  and if Black goes for suspicious  11...Be6?!  White would continue with  12.b4!  when Black needs to move the attacked Knight away, and after trades on e6, the doubled pawns will be problematic. }
10... a5
{ Black chooses different way to chase the Bishop on b3, and White has time now to create a shelter! }
11. a3
{ Now White is back on track and can obtain the advantage by storming the f5 outpost with a Knight. Afterwards, White can continue with a center break with f4, opening the f-file and gaining activity on the Kingside, as it was planned. }
11... a4 12. Ba2 b5
{ Black needs to search for a counterattack on the Queenside since he does not have well positioned pieces on the Kingside. However, that will not stop us to maneuver the Knight on the f5 outpost, and to go for the f4 advance. }
13. Ng3 { White is ready to jump with Nf5! } 13... Nb6
{ Black uses the opportunity to try to stop Nf5, but this will not be that easy as it sounds. It is a fact that White can not immediately proceed with the desirable move, because Black's light squared Bishop controls the f5 square now. But as it was mentioned before, White will use another Knight to improve control over this square. }
14. Nh4 c5 15. Nhf5
{ As mentioned, another Knight joined the game and Black could not stop this approach anymore. Besides that, White now aims to proceed with f4, opening the f-file, and starting the attack on the Kingside. Black is practically forced to trade, to make sure that White will not have enough pieces to gain the initiative. }
15... Bxf5 16. Nxf5 g6
{ At the first sight, Black holds the f5 square and moves the Knight away. On the other hand, one should not forget that White now gains a long-term Bishop pair advantage, and Black will face difficulties with weak dark squares around the King. }
17. Nxd6 Qxd6 18. f4
{ With the Bishop pair on the board, White certainly aims to open the position, and to make space for his Bishops. If Black accepts to take the pawn, White will gain full control over dark squares and the f-file, but have in mind that White might also continue here with  19.f5  instead, seizing space on the Kingside, and threatening to create a tremendous attack there! To get familiar with possible ideas here I would recommend to check the game Nouri, H-Kovalev, V Subic Bay 2016. }
