{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... d5
{ Black builds a center with a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. If Black instead goes for  4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  the position transposes to a sideline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  c6  4...Be7  , covered in 4...Be7 }
5. Bb3
{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Bb4+
{ Black has a large number of options but this check is one of the most frequent in this position. Black aims to stop White to develop the Knight to c3 from where it would press the d5 pawn. }
6. Bd2
{ This is practically the only option for White to block the check. Instead,  6.Nc3  runs into  6...d4  , while Black would be happy to see  6.c3  Bd6  when White will have issues with e4 pawn and lousy center. }
6... Bd6
{ If Black decides to retreat the Bishop, not only that he loses one tempo, but White is able to continue with the most active development, Nc3, O-O Re1. }
7. Nc3
{ Of course, White is not missing the opportunity to increase the pressure on d5, and now Black has a huge decision to make- shall they advance with d4, shall the center open up with dxe4, or shall they keep the tension by defending d5? }
7... Bc7
{ This retreat can only temporarily maintain the status quo. By taking on d5 and pinning the Knight on f6 after Bg5, White will create unbearable pressure on the Black's central pawns. }
8. O-O
{ First of all, before we start with an attack, we must be sure that King is safe and to be ready to place the Rook on e1 with a threat of exd5! }
8... O-O
{ Black has nothing better but to follow along with development. The Rook will be needed on e8 when White continues with previously mentioned Re1. }
9. exd5
{ You should realise now that Black is ready to protect the e5 pawn after Re8. It can be said that the position is stable. For that reason, we decide to harass the d5 pawn now, making it very weak after the forthcoming Bg5! }
9... cxd5
{ I would like to emphasize that Black can not take with  9...Nxd5  due to  10.Re1  with the forthcoming 11.d4 when Black's position collapses due to poor development and inactive pieces on the Queenside. }
10. Bg5
{ With a development move White pins the defender of the d5 pawn. This pin has a huge effect since the Black bishop is misplaced on c7, and can not go back to defense with Be7 as it was possible in the other lines explained within the course. }
10... Be6 11. Nb5
{ And when it looked like Black consolidated with 10...Be6 White goes for a timed jump attacking the defender of another central pawn! Black's dark-squared Bishop has no retreat to b8, and can not move away from the attack due to a hanging e5 pawn. In that manner, White will very soon enjoy a steady advantage of the Bishop pair in a fairly open position. It is obvious that the main targets of White's attack will be central e5 and d5 pawns as it was seen in the game Fenwick, J-Hofer, R W-ch ICCF email 2015. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Bishop's Opening 2...Nf6: Berlin Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's opening 2...Nf6: 3. d3 c6 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3 Bb4+ #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nf6
{ Berlin defense by Black! This is absolutely the most frequent move by Black against the Bishop's opening. Another common option especially on the lower level is  2...Nc6  , but 2...Nf6 is by far way more common in the practice! With the last move, Black aims to stay active, threatens White's central pawn on  e4  , and enters the Berlin defense. }
3. d3
{ Already at the third move, White has an opportunity to pick up the aggressive approach with the Urusov Gambit  3.d4!?  or to choose a more peaceful approach with 3.d3 which enters the Bishop's opening. Both options are fully covered throughout the course.  The Urusov Gambit is very interesting for the players whose main weapon is the tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for blitz and rapid games, especially when the beginner seats on the other side and tries to find a proper plan to defend as Black.  On the other side, 3.d3 provides a stable and safe positional approach without sacrifices or material losses and it gives flexible positions where White has initiative and the attack which is mainly based on equal material and clear activity. Interestingly, it is used in almost 80% of the games at this point and while  3.d4  was used mainly only once by top players in a blitz or rapid games, nowadays 3.d3 move presents a bulletproof approach by literally all top players including Carlsen, Nepo, Caruana, Firouzja, Grischuk, and other top players! }
3... c6
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White has not played Nf3 yet to place pressure on the e5 pawn. On the other hand, Black prepares his own central advance with d5. From my own experience, it turned out that the last move 3...c6 was mainly used by stronger players or players who were familiar with the opening theory. Also, one should not forget that after:   3...Nc6  4.Nc3  the game transposes into lines explained within the 1.e4 e5 2.Bc4 Nc6 chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... d5
{ Black builds a center with a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. If Black instead goes for  4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  the position transposes to a sideline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  c6  4...Be7  , covered in 4...Be7 }
5. Bb3
{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Bb4+
{ Black has a large number of options but this check is one of the most frequent in this position. Black aims to stop White to develop the Knight to c3 from where it would press the d5 pawn. }
6. Bd2
{ This is practically the only option for White to block the check. Instead,  6.Nc3  runs into  6...d4  , while Black would be happy to see  6.c3  Bd6  when White will have issues with e4 pawn and lousy center. }
6... Bd6
{ If Black decides to retreat the Bishop, not only that he loses one tempo, but White is able to continue with the most active development, Nc3, O-O Re1. }
7. Nc3
{ Of course, White is not missing the opportunity to increase the pressure on d5, and now Black has a huge decision to make- shall they advance with d4, shall the center open up with dxe4, or shall they keep the tension by defending d5? }
7... dxe4
{ Although the position looks innocuous now, as it will be shown, White is able to launch a tremendous attack! }
8. Ng5
{ Get ready for a crushing attack and believe it or not, one of my favorite games in this opening! Because of this game, I started to like and play Bishop's opening! Everything happened, while I was a commentator for Montreal Chessbrah and who could be better to follow but at that time our first board - Fabiano Caruana back in 2018 when he was in his best shape ever! White wins a tempo now and attacks the vulnerable f7 spot. All White's pieces will move towards the Kingside as it will be shown soon! You should be aware that White's idea is not to move the Knight from g5 back to a center, but to continue with attack after Nce4, Bg5, and possibly Qh5 later on! }
8... O-O 9. Ncxe4
{ As it was already said, White keeps both Knight in play on the Kingside aiming to create a tremendous mating attack! Taking the pawn with  9.Ngxe4  would give Black chances to keep the tension with  9...Be7  , and he would have time for development and defense. }
9... Nxe4
{ If Black tries to trade off one of White's attacking pieces immediately, White will just go on for the plan of Qh5 and pawn-storm on Black's King! }
10. Nxe4
{ White for sure does not want to take with a pawn here, since then Black would have time to toggle Knight into defense after Nd7-Nf6. This way, White keeps dark-squared Bishop open, with a threat of Bg5, Qh5, h4, g4, and a huge attack on Kingside! }
10... Bc7
{ With this move Black wants to be sure that he keeps contact with the  e5  pawn, and he will not lose any tempo defending it. On the other hand, Black completely surrendered the g5 square now. Instead, Black could go for  10...Be7  preventing Ng5 for the time being, but he will be tied up and the e5-pawn will fall down after  11.Qh5!  which comes with the idea of h4 and Ng5. If Black gets ready for it with  11...Nd7  White will simply gain a clearly better position with a developing move of  12.O-O  with a new plan now- Rae1 and Bc3, with huge pressure on the e5-pawn which can be hardly defended now. }
11. Qh5
{ White's idea is simple but brutal - play Bg5, Nf6, Bf6, and Qg5 checkmate! }
11... Qe7 12. g4
{ Since Black toggled the Queen into defense, White chooses to continue with a very important preparatory move that takes away f5 and g4 off from the Black's Queen. Immediate  12.Bg5  does not work due to  12...Qd7  when the Queen will get to  f5  or  g4  right on time to defend the Kingside. }
12... a5
{ Black puts the last hopes to create a counterattack on the Queenside, but White just does not care about it now! }
13. Bg5
{ Black can not block this attack with a pawn, due to a pinned Knight, and White takes full control over the dark squares and goes for the previously mentioned idea of Bg5, followed by Nf6! }
13... Qe8
{ If Black tries to attack the g4-pawn with  13...Qd7  White easily gains a huge advantage with  14.Rg1  killing all the hopes for Black. }
14. Nf6+ { And finally, there is no defense anymore! } 14... gxf6 15. Bxf6
{ Black needed to open the King, and there is no hope for him since we threaten to mate with Qg5-Qg7! The game is over after only 15 moves of play! }
*

