10. h4
{ A very important move for the White's setup as he will want to recapture on g5  @@StartBracket@@should Black take with the bishop or h6-hxg5@@EndBracket@@ with the pawn and open the h-file. }
10... Na6
{ This is an interesting attempt but it also falls short after precise play. Black's idea is to play Nc5 and trade the knight on e4, while keeping his other knight defending the Kingside from the good square f6. }
11. Nxf6+
{ White immediately trades the defender and clears the way for the Queen to reach the desired h5-square. }
11... Bxf6 12. Qh5
{ With a direct mate threat of Qh7 White also pressures the f7 pawn which is hanging now and Black needs to react! }
12... Bxg5
{ This is practically the only way for Black to keep the game going, as the Knight on g5 is too dangerous. One should not forget that Black immediately loses if he instead plays  12...h6  due to  13.Nxf7! }
13. hxg5
{ With a tremendous attack along the h-file and the Bishop pair on the board, White is clearly better. The idea for White is simple, O-O-O, Rde1, and of course Qf3 if Black moves it away after Bf5-Bg6. }
