10. h4
{ A very important move for the White's setup as he will want to recapture on g5  @@StartBracket@@should Black take with the bishop or h6-hxg5@@EndBracket@@ with the pawn and open the h-file. }
10... Nbd7
{ Trying to exchange both pairs of knights on e4, if possible. Black would also be happy to trade one pair of knights and bring his defender to f6. }
11. Qf3
{ Since the h5 spot is not available anymore for the Queen, White goes for activation through the f3 square! This excellent move prevents exchanges and allows us to build a strong attack! }
11... Qe8
{ Black needs to cover the f7-spot before the trade with  Ne4  . If he immediately goes for  11...Nxe4  12.Bxf7!  comes with a check! }
12. O-O-O
{ Not only that White concludes development with this move, but goes for the further activation while Black is locked on the back rank! The Rook will come to the e-file with Rde1 pressuring the e5-pawn. There is also a possible center advance of d4, when the Black's Queen on e8 will be indirectly pinned. }
12... a5
{ Black needs to try to gain any activity and his only possibility is to hunt the light-squared Bishop with pawns. However, this is just a temporary threat that can be easily stopped. }
13. a3
{ White is ready for possible a4 advance and has a nice safe spot for the light-squared Bishop. That means that we can continue with the attack very soon! }
13... Nd5 14. Rde1
{ White just ignores Black's moves now and already threatens to go for d4! }
14... h6
{ Black practically needs to go with direct activities. Any other move would be faced with  15.d4  and if Black accepts the sacrifice,  Nd6!  comes with an unbearable attack on the f7-spot! }
15. Ng3
{ Black's King is so weakened that White desirably waits for him to take the offer of the hanging Knight! With a beautiful relocation of the Knight to f5, White threatens to continue with well-known d4! }
15... Ra6
{ It is obvious that Black got lost here. Accepting the sacrifice leads to a winning position for White after  15...hxg5?  16.hxg5  Bxg5  17.Nf5  with a threat of Qh5 or Qh3 and there will be no defense of the h-file anymore! }
16. Nf5
{ At this point, it is clear that Black can not hold the pressure. All the White's pieces are active and turned to attack of the King, while Black has no possibility to strike back. }
16... f6 17. Ne6
{ Faced with such pressure, it is not surprising that Akobian, V blundered with 16...f6 in a game played against Caruana Fabiano in chess.com INT game 2017. White easily wins now with two threats- Nf8 or Nc7 and Black can not save the exchange! }
