11... c5 { Black decides to immediately undermine the well-positioned Knight. }
12. dxc5
{ White takes the pawn, although Black will take it back soon. Meanwhile, we will have time to improve the position of the pieces and to conclude development with an attack on the e4 weakness! }
12... Nbd7
{ After trades Black will improve the attack on the c5 pawn, but at the same time, the e4 pawn will be unprotected! }
13. Nxd7 Nxd7 14. Nc3
{ As it was previously mentioned, White just continues with active development moves and immediately pressures Black's central pawn. }
14... Nxc5 15. Bd5
{ Even though it looked like Black took the material back with tempo attack on the light-squared Bishop and with the defense of the hanging pawn, White strikes back with centralization! }
15... Be6 16. Bxe6 Nxe6 17. Nxe4
{ After the forced sequence White is a clear pawn up as it was seen in a game Leko, P -Gelfand, B Yerevan 2008, with a clear advantage and easy endgame. }
