{ Yes, we break some standard opening rules, playing with the Queen twice and even exposing it to possibly unpleasant attacks. We do not want to simply win a pawn, actually, we might even not be able to keep it. Instead, we want to force some sort of resolution in the center that would leave Black with a structural weakness! }
8... Nbd7
{ Black decides to defend the  e5  pawn, and he is not worried about the hanging g7-pawn because he would be able to create an initiative if White decides to take it. Instead,  8...dxe4?  would be bad since it opens the diagonal for the light squared Bishop and after  9.Qxg7  the f7-pawn hangs. Black needs to defend it with  9...Rf8  10.dxe4  and White is much better after Nbd2–Nc4, O-O-O, and decisive attack. }
9. exd5
{ By taking on d5 White has a very concrete idea on his mind- advance with d4! A quick reminder that with the closed Bb3 diagonal White cannot play  9.Qxg7  due to  9...Rg8  10.Qh6  and Black has an upper hand after Rxg2 or Nxe4. }
9... cxd5 10. d4
{ It is curious to note that in the mainline, with a7-a5 and a2-a3 included, this White's plan fails! A timely a5-a4 push would completely disrupt White's coordination and the long castling. But in this particular setup, Black cannot ignore the d4 pawn and just castle as White is very quick with 11. dxe5, 12.Nc3 and 13.O-O-O. }
10... e4
{ Black is practically forced to close the center now, but White does not go fall-back! }
11. Ne5
{ The Queen on g5 perfectly serves the purpose of establishing the Knight outpost on e5! }
11... O-O 12. Nc3
{ With simple developing moves White puts Black into problems. Black needs to think now about a direct threat of Nxd7 followed by Nxd5! }
12... Nb6
{ Although it looks that Black's center is safe now, White undermines it immediately as it will be shown with the forthcoming move! }
13. f3
{ The whole point of good positioned pieces is that White can wait with castling and uses the opportunity to attack Black's center as soon as possible. }
13... Be6
{ Black has no other option but to continue developing. One should not forget that after  13...exf3  14.gxf3  With Rg1 coming White will have a devastating attack on the g-file. }
14. O-O-O
{ With a long castle White puts the King into safety and prepares for an attack on the e4 pawn after Rhe1. It is questionable if Black can find a proper counterplay here. }
14... Rac8
{ This is probably the only attempt to counter-attack as Black threatens the nasty Dragon-like Rc3, with Qa3, Na4 or Nc4, Rc8. This is not the scenario which White wants to see and for that reason, White needs to stop with attacks for a while, and goes back into defense! }
15. Qd2
{ With a simple step-back move, the Knight on c3 is defended and we can easily continue with the previously mentioned plan of Rhe1! }
15... a6 16. Rhe1
{ And it is obvious that Black can not hold the center anymore. He needs to go for the opening of the g-file which will be used for the attack on the Black's King! }
16... exf3 17. gxf3
{ Not only that White managed to open the g-file, but also we prevent any kind of liberating Ne4 jumps. Meanwhile, the Knight on e5 is eternal and can not be moved away! }
17... Nfd7 18. h4
{ Black is late with counterplay and White starts a killer attack on the g and h-files as it could be seen in a game Xiong,J -Duda,J Khanty-Mansiysk 2019. The idea of White is simple, after the h5-h6 threat, we will toggle the pieces to a Kingside with Qg2-Rg1. One should not forget that in such positions, Kb1 is always a desirable prophylactic move that avoids possible complications on Queenside. }
