{ Black accepts the trade and assumes that White will need to go for Nbd2- putting the Knight on the clumsy square to defend the pawn on e4. However, this is not going to happen! }
7. Qxd2
{ This is a very important move for White. Not only that there is a threat of Qg5, with an attack on both the  g7 and e5 pawns, but White keeps an option to develop the Knight on the most active square with Nc3, eyeing Black's vulnerable central pawns. It is clear that the e4 pawn does not really hang here, since e5 hangs as well. }
7... dxe4
{ This is a suspicious move that takes Black straight into a bad position, as it will be seen soon! }
8. Nxe5
{ White takes the central pawn with an immediate attack on the f7 vulnerable square. It looks that Black has no many issues with it after a simple defending and developing move, but the truth is different! }
8... O-O 9. Nxf7 { This temporary sacrifice is the point of White's play! }
9... Rxf7 10. dxe4
{ White decides that there is no need to hurry, the Rook can't run away. The contact between the Queens makes this neat recapture possible. }
10... Qxd2+
{ It is a logical continuation for Black to trade Queens, thinking that he has a material advantage after White takes the Rook. But one should not forget that White has two pawns and a Rook against two pieces in a pretty simplified endgame. For that reason, the engine evaluation after the trades favors White! If Black decides to keep the Queens on the board  10...Qe7  11.Bxf7+  Kxf7  12.f3  White gains a clear advantage. Black's Bishop is severely limited by White pawns, while the Knights cannot get a hold of good outposts. White's heavy piece will breakthrough on the d-file @@StartBracket@@on  d6  or d8@@EndBracket@@, or he will get the passed pawns @@StartBracket@@e and f@@EndBracket@@ rolling. }
11. Nxd2
{ And once again, White is clearly better with an obvious follow-up of Bf7. With the e-passed pawn, after O-O-O, and Rhe1, White will have huge initiative and it is questionable if Black can hold the pressure with two pieces against the Rook and two dangerous pawns. }
