{ Black has a large number of options but this check is one of the most frequent in this position. Black aims to stop White to develop the Knight to c3 from where it would press the d5 pawn. }
6. Bd2
{ This is practically the only option for White to block the check. Instead,  6.Nc3  runs into  6...d4  , while Black would be happy to see  6.c3  Bd6  when White will have issues with e4 pawn and lousy center. }
6... Bxd2+
{ Black accepts the trade and assumes that White will need to go for Nbd2- putting the Knight on the clumsy square to defend the pawn on e4. However, this is not going to happen! }
7. Qxd2
{ This is a very important move for White. Not only that there is a threat of Qg5, with an attack on both the  g7 and e5 pawns, but White keeps an option to develop the Knight on the most active square with Nc3, eyeing Black's vulnerable central pawns. It is clear that the e4 pawn does not really hang here, since e5 hangs as well. }
7... Nbd7
{ This is a normal developing move that also protects e5. However, White has a great continuation, and we will use the fact that the Knight on d7 looks clumsy, closing the light squared Bishop on c8. }
8. exd5
{ White immediately tries to open up the center. The point is that we use the fact that Black's Knight can not transfer to the most active square on c6, after the trade of the central pawns! Despite that, Black's central pawns will be targets of White's attacks. }
8... Nxd5
{ If Black decides to give up on the center, looking to have more active pieces that are not tied to pawns' defense, White will put all the forces to pressure the e5 pawn! One should not forget that the Bishop on b3 takes the main role in this game now! }
9. O-O O-O
{ As usual, both players want to have the Rooks on the e-file as soon as possible. }
10. Nc3
{ Black faces difficulties already at this point of the game. The fact is that the Knight on d5 is tied for the e5 pawn and can not support the Knight on d5. At the same time, Black is late with development of the Queenside for the same reason! }
10... Nf4
{ Black tries to find another way to centralize the Knight. Instead, a natural move such as  10...Nxc3  loses practically by force to  11.Qxc3  with an attack on the e5-pawn, and after  11...Qf6  12.Rfe1  Re8  13.Re4  White is ready to double the Rooks on the e-file and ramp up the pressure on the vulnerable e5-spot. Black can not activate the Knight on d7 as well as the Bishop on c8, since his pieces are tied to the defensive duties. One should not forget that f6 is impossible due to a pin by Bb3, and Black can only wait for White to go for a central advance with d4! }
11. Rfe1
{ White just goes for natural moves concluding development. The plan is to overload the e5 pawn, transfer the Knight through e4 square to g3, from where we can make the timely jump with Nf5. As it is typical for these positions, White can always think about the d4 break, undermining Black's Knight on f4. }
11... Qf6
{ Black needs to try to protect both  e5  and  f4  squares. If he goes for the natural  11...Re8  , White has an immediate break with  12.d4!  and a huge advantage since Black can not handle the pressure on the e4 pawn anymore. Of course  12...Ng6  is met with  13.Ng5  followed by a harsh attack on the f7-spot! }
12. Ne4
{ White gets every opportunity to centralize pieces with tempo attacks. Black's Queen on f6 looks vulnerable now, and White wants to exploit as much as possible! }
12... Qh6 13. Qe3
{ Although this move might look weird, White just aims to improve the position of all the pieces. One should not forget that if White goes for  13.g3  Qh5  , Black takes chances for a good play, so do not fall into it! }
13... Kh8
{ Black finally decides to move the King from the pin, so he can be able to support the e5 pawn with f6. That is the only way for Black to unlock the Knight from d7 and the Bishop from the starting position! }
14. Ng3
{ Of course, this action does not stop us to continue with the previously mentioned plan of Ng3- with possibility of uncomfortable Nf5 and d4! }
14... f6 15. d4
{ And finally White takes full control over the game. Black is once again faced with an attack on the e5 square, and needs to accept to open the position. The Queen on h6 is placed badly and will be under attack after the forthcoming Nf5. The light-squared Bishop on b3 controls all the light squares in Black's position, and White is just clearly better. The further continuation from this point could be seen in a game Alekseenko, K -Zarnicki,P Moscow 2019. }
