{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... d5
{ Black builds a center with a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. If Black instead goes for  4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  the position transposes to a sideline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  c6  4...Be7  , covered in 4...Be7 }
5. Bb3
{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Bb4+
{ Black has a large number of options but this check is one of the most frequent in this position. Black aims to stop White to develop the Knight to c3 from where it would press the d5 pawn. }
6. Bd2
{ This is practically the only option for White to block the check. Instead,  6.Nc3  runs into  6...d4  , while Black would be happy to see  6.c3  Bd6  when White will have issues with e4 pawn and lousy center. }
6... Bxd2+
{ Black accepts the trade and assumes that White will need to go for Nbd2- putting the Knight on the clumsy square to defend the pawn on e4. However, this is not going to happen! }
7. Qxd2
{ This is a very important move for White. Not only that there is a threat of Qg5, with an attack on both the  g7 and e5 pawns, but White keeps an option to develop the Knight on the most active square with Nc3, eyeing Black's vulnerable central pawns. It is clear that the e4 pawn does not really hang here, since e5 hangs as well. }
7... Nbd7
{ This is a normal developing move that also protects e5. However, White has a great continuation, and we will use the fact that the Knight on d7 looks clumsy, closing the light squared Bishop on c8. }
8. exd5
{ White immediately tries to open up the center. The point is that we use the fact that Black's Knight can not transfer to the most active square on c6, after the trade of the central pawns! Despite that, Black's central pawns will be targets of White's attacks. }
8... cxd5
{ The two pawns only look nice, but it will be nearly impossible to defend them properly, as it will be shown later! }
9. O-O O-O
{ Of course, both sides conclude development and aim to put the Rook on the e-file. }
10. Re1 a5
{ Black struggles to find the lesser evil. A defensive move such as  10...Re8  is met with  11.Nc3  and Black is forced to play  11...d4  to save the pawn, but then White goes for  12.Nb5!  with the devastating threat of  12...--  13.Nd6! }
11. Nc3
{ White once again threatens Black's vulnerable center and Black can not keep it anymore! }
11... d4
{ This is practically the only way for Black to protect the pawn, since both e5 and d5 are hanging. }
12. Nb5
{ The e5-pawn is hopelessly weak and Black's pieces are terribly placed. White can continue with a4, establishing the Knight on the beautiful b5 outpost. One should not forget that Nd6 and Qg5 are both on the cards as it could be seen in the game Short, N -Anton Guijarro, D Madrid 2016. With all of the active pieces are in the game, Black is stuck with a problematic back rank and development difficulties, White has a clear advantage and easy play here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Bishop's Opening 2...Nf6: Berlin Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's opening 2...Nf6: 3. d3 c6 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3 Bb4+ #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nf6
{ Berlin defense by Black! This is absolutely the most frequent move by Black against the Bishop's opening. Another common option especially on the lower level is  2...Nc6  , but 2...Nf6 is by far way more common in the practice! With the last move, Black aims to stay active, threatens White's central pawn on  e4  , and enters the Berlin defense. }
3. d3
{ Already at the third move, White has an opportunity to pick up the aggressive approach with the Urusov Gambit  3.d4!?  or to choose a more peaceful approach with 3.d3 which enters the Bishop's opening. Both options are fully covered throughout the course.  The Urusov Gambit is very interesting for the players whose main weapon is the tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for blitz and rapid games, especially when the beginner seats on the other side and tries to find a proper plan to defend as Black.  On the other side, 3.d3 provides a stable and safe positional approach without sacrifices or material losses and it gives flexible positions where White has initiative and the attack which is mainly based on equal material and clear activity. Interestingly, it is used in almost 80% of the games at this point and while  3.d4  was used mainly only once by top players in a blitz or rapid games, nowadays 3.d3 move presents a bulletproof approach by literally all top players including Carlsen, Nepo, Caruana, Firouzja, Grischuk, and other top players! }
3... c6
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White has not played Nf3 yet to place pressure on the e5 pawn. On the other hand, Black prepares his own central advance with d5. From my own experience, it turned out that the last move 3...c6 was mainly used by stronger players or players who were familiar with the opening theory. Also, one should not forget that after:   3...Nc6  4.Nc3  the game transposes into lines explained within the 1.e4 e5 2.Bc4 Nc6 chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ White continues with a simple developing move, aiming to castle. It is important to emphasize that at the moment White does not threaten to capture the e5 pawn as such reckless advance Nxe5 would be met with the double attack Qa5+, winning the Knight on e5. }
4... d5
{ Black builds a center with a tempo attack on White's light-squared Bishop. If Black instead goes for  4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  the position transposes to a sideline @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  c6  4...Be7  , covered in 4...Be7 }
5. Bb3
{ White simply steps back with the light-squared Bishop, and one should not forget that Black now faces issues with hanging e5-pawn! }
5... Bb4+
{ Black has a large number of options but this check is one of the most frequent in this position. Black aims to stop White to develop the Knight to c3 from where it would press the d5 pawn. }
6. Bd2
{ This is practically the only option for White to block the check. Instead,  6.Nc3  runs into  6...d4  , while Black would be happy to see  6.c3  Bd6  when White will have issues with e4 pawn and lousy center. }
6... Bxd2+
{ Black accepts the trade and assumes that White will need to go for Nbd2- putting the Knight on the clumsy square to defend the pawn on e4. However, this is not going to happen! }
7. Qxd2
{ This is a very important move for White. Not only that there is a threat of Qg5, with an attack on both the  g7 and e5 pawns, but White keeps an option to develop the Knight on the most active square with Nc3, eyeing Black's vulnerable central pawns. It is clear that the e4 pawn does not really hang here, since e5 hangs as well. }
7... a5
{ This is an important intermediate move that anticipates a long castle intending to disturb the coordination of White's  pieces. The key benefit of such intrusion is that for now it prevents the nasty plan of Qg5! }
8. a3
{ White opens the space for the Bishop's retreat and renews the threat against the e5 pawn. The idea is to continue with Qg5, eyeing both g7 and e5 spots! }
8... a4
{ Black can also first insert this move, but the game will not change a lot. White keeps the same idea as before, Qg5 is a threat! }
9. Ba2
{ White's Bishop is safe and still pressures Black's center. Despite that, the a4 pawn might look clumsy later and could become the target of White's Knight on c3. }
9... O-O
{ Black realizes that quick development is the best option to defend the center. However, White will take the opportunity to remove one of the Black's central pawns, with the centralization of the Knight! Instead of development move,  9...dxe4?!  would be a mistake due to  10.Nxe5  O-O  11.Nxf7!  Rxf7  12.dxe4  Qe7  13.Bxf7  Kxf7  14.f3  with a slight advantage since Black's Bishop is severely limited by the white pawns. The Knights can not get a hold of good outposts while White's heavy pieces will break through on the d-file. Of course, with the central passed pawn, a Rook and two pawns against two minor pieces, White definitely does not have a material deficit. }
10. Nxe5
{ As previously mentioned, White does not hesitate to take the central pawn without fear that will hang. Whenever Black decides to take a material advantage back with dxe4, White's Bishop on b3 opens up with a harsh attack on the f7-square! }
10... Qe7 11. f4
{ White simply wants to keep the Knight centralized as long as possible! }
11... dxe4 12. O-O
{ White concludes development with two perfect pieces on the board- the Knight on desirable outpost  e5  and the Bishop that controls the long a2-g8 diagonal. Instead of 12.O-O, a good alternative could be  12.d4  , which was played in a top-level game by Pavel Eljanov. The idea of 12.d4 is that the e4-pawn is too far ahead, while Black's Queenside is under-developed. At the same time, the Rook on  f8  is tied to the f7-pawn. To get familiar with ideas afterward check the game Eljanov, P -Kuzubov, Y Gladiators INT 2020,  but at this point, I would suggest the more flexible 12.O-O as the better way to go. }
12... exd3 13. cxd3
{ White should not worry about the newly created 3rd pawn island, since Black has more issues than us here. The idea is simple, White wants to continue with Nc3, Rae1, establishing the e5 outpost with d4. If Black continues with  13...Be6  trying to trade White's good asset, we have no problems after  14.Bxe6  Qxe6  15.Nc3  Nbd7  16.Rae1  with normal development, and after  16...Qd6  17.Qf2  looks very good, with ideas like Kh1, g4, d4. Anyway, if you do not feel good after 13.cxd3 with the altered pawn structure, you can keep the pawns connected. This is also a viable possibility, but I would prefer to have the Knight on the e5-outpost as it greatly limits the Black's options. }
