{ This is the crucial move of this variation! We have to react aggressively and be on top of the task, so 4.Qg4 is mandatory for a serious opening advantage! Some of the players that go that far, claim how after the last move, White is close to being winning, I would not say so, but it is a huge opening advantage! White chooses the most aggressive approach with a direct threat to the g7 pawn and this continuation might look similar to a good version of the Patzers opening! }
4... g6
{ This is the most resilient move by Black who is desperate to secure the King's safety after Kf8 and Kg7. One should not forget that Black also has a threat of d5, which needs to be prevented. }
5. Qf3
{ Black is once again forced to find good defensive moves whilst White prepares for development after Nge2, g3, and Bg5, and of course - Scholars mate on f7! }
5... Nf6
{ Instead of 5...Nf6 Black might think it is useful to exchange Queens in an early opening, thinking that that would help gain some space for pieces.   However, every exchange in this position fits well for White, since after  5...Qf6  6.Nd5  Qxf3  7.Nxf3  Bb6  8.c3  White has a clear long-term advantage of the Bishop pair which will be gained after Nxb6, and Black will struggle with a worse pawn structure as well. }
6. Nge2
{ With a simple developing move, White prevents Black's threat of Nd4 and aims to keep pressure after d3 and Bg5. Unlike Patzer's opening, where Black's Bishop stands on g7 and defends the Knight on f6; here, Black looks way more vulnerable since Nf6 lacks proper defense, or they have to lose tempo to defend it! Also, while Bg7 improves the defense of the dark squares, not only around the Knight but most importantly around the King and the extremely vulnerable dark-squares on the kingside! }
6... d6
{ Black can search for the only activity with d6 followed by Bg4, trying to expose White's Queen to attacks. }
7. d3
{ White does not need to worry about Bg4, because the Queen has a lot of squares to go for.   For that reason, White chooses to continue with fast development and gains control of the dark squares! }
7... Bg4 8. Qg3
{ After a simple step back, Black is practically forced to once again play with the same Bishop due to the threat of Bg5, which would be very uncomfortable altogether with Nd5! }
8... Be6
{ Instead of 8...Be6, which comes with a hope that after an exchange of the light-squared Bishops Black can win back some activity. 8...h6 aimed against Bg5 is commonly played in practice.   However, after  8...h6  9.a3  White is at least slightly better with a safe spot for the light-squared Bishop, which might go to  a2  , and further plan of Bd2, O-O-O, and f4! }
9. Bg5
{ Of course White is not concerned about doubled pawns on the c-file if Black takes Bxc4. That would be for White's benefit since after O-O-O, we will have another file in control, and Black still needs to think about the defense of the Knight on f6 which faces lots of issues after Qh4 and Nd5! }
9... Nh5
{ Black might try to force a trade of the Queens aiming to save the King, which has obvious issues with development. Of course, White will not accept that offer! }
10. Qh4
{ We keep control of the dark squares, and the fact is that Black will face issues with a marginalized Knight on h5! }
10... Qd7 11. Ng3
{ As it was mentioned, White starts the hunt on the h5-Knight. Black is practically forced to trade the Knight for the dark-squared Bishop, giving a pawn away, just to retake control over the dark squares around the King. }
11... Nf4 12. Bxf4 exf4 13. Qxf4
{ Of course, with a clear pawn up on the board and a huge development advantage, White does not need to search for complications anymore, but aims to simplify position entering a winning endgame with material advantage. }
13... Bxc4 14. dxc4 O-O-O 15. O-O-O
{ As it was played in the game Watson, W-Murshed, N London 1992, White gained full center control and a position with a pawn up. With the forthcoming Nd4, Kb1, and Rhe1, White has an easy play based on the material advantage and control of the dark squares on the Kingside. }
