3... Bc5
{ This is a very common move by Black, who tends to develop the Kingside as soon as possible. Threatening the f2 pawn, Black might also choose to continue afterward with the tricky Qf6. Anyway, 3...Bc5?! is suspicious since g7 becomes vulnerable! I would like to point out that lots of weaker players go for it since it resembles the Italian Guicco Piano, and a majority of the players that like to do it hope that it is the same or at least very similar to it. Still, luckily for us, it is not! }
4. Qg4
{ This is the crucial move of this variation! We have to react aggressively and be on top of the task, so 4.Qg4 is mandatory for a serious opening advantage! Some of the players that go that far, claim how after the last move, White is close to being winning, I would not say so, but it is a huge opening advantage! White chooses the most aggressive approach with a direct threat to the g7 pawn and this continuation might look similar to a good version of the Patzers opening! }
4... Qf6
{ Although this is a suspicious move, it is the most frequent in my Blitz practice and games of my students online and, by stats, it was played in more than 300 games! White scored positively in 80% of the games, but to benefit from this suspicious attempt by Black, White has to understand that the pawn on f2 is not a priority! }
5. Nd5
{ White does not care about f2 hanging because Black has bigger issues with the c7 and f7 spots. Black is forced to continue with the original idea of Qxf2 and that would put Black's Queen into an uncomfortable position as it will be shown soon! }
5... Qxf2+ 6. Kd1
{ Whilst White's King is perfectly safe on d1 Black faces a lot of trouble trying to create or find available spots for the Queen. White's plan is simple, after Nh3 and Rf1 it is questionable if Black will be able to defend f7 and one should not forget that Nc7 is still there as a possible threat! On top of all that, if the Queen goes to d4, White should reply with d3 @@StartBracket@@to defend Bc4@@EndBracket@@ and afterward trap Queen with c3! }
6... Kf8
{ Almost all games from this line continued with 6...Kf8 by Black who aims to move the King away from a possible Nc7 check and to defend the g7 pawn from Qxg7 threat. Although, it does not stop us from executing our main attacking tricks... }
7. Nh3
{ We are ready to start the hunt on the Black's Queen that compromises Black's weak King as well which is miserably positioned on f8. Not only that White aims to continue with Rf1, but Black needs to figure out how to keep the Queen safe now! }
7... h5
{ In an already difficult position, this is the only move that does not immediately lead Black into a losing position.   Believe it or not, in more than 100 games, Black continued with  7...Qd4  and White were directly winning after  8.d3!  because Black's Queen was trapped in the center of the board! Black will be forced to move dark-squared Bishop from  c5  to make space for the Queen, and White will put undefendable pressure on  f7  after Rf1 and Qf3 or Qh5! }
8. Qg5
{ White certainly does not want to accept to exchange Queens in a position where Black's King is placed on f8 exposed to a pin after Rf1. Black is forced to go for the only moves to defend the position, but White, anyways, gains a huge advantage! }
8... Qd4 9. d3
{ Once again, White has a direct threat to win the game with c3 immediately. Queen is captured on d4 and Black is forced to move a Bishop away! }
9... Be7 10. Qg3
{ As it could be seen in the game between Mamedyarov, S-Harikrishnan, A 2020 chess.com, after a clever step back with 10.Qg3 White is ready for domination in a clearly better position with a plan of Rf1, Ng5, and c3. Whilst White's King is safe in the center on the d1 spot, Black's King is more than vulnerable and exposed to harsh attacks, altogether with the f7 pawn! }
