[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Nf6
{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... Bb4
{ The main idea that Black wants to accomplish after this move is based on central activity with d5. Basically, Black's idea is to centralize pieces, threaten the Knight on c3, and complete development fast with short castling. }
5. Ne2
{ This is the most flexible but at the same time solid developing move for White, who at the same time prepares for castling and f4, but also supports the Knight on c3 which could be pinned if Black decides to open the center with 5...d5. }
5... Na5
{ This is a very interesting approach by Black, who aims to gain the Bishop pair and to ruin White's pawn structure on the Kingside. }
6. a3
{ White kills two birds with one stone! At the same time, White threatens the Bishop on b4, and makes a safe spot for the light-squared Bishop! }
6... Bxc3+
{ Black is consistent with removing the light-squared Bishop and the doubled pawns on the c-file. Anyway, one should notice that Black would lose their Bishop pair, so Black gains nothing with this exchange! }
7. Nxc3
{ White threatens to escape with the light-squared Bishop to the a2 spot and to keep their Bishop pair. That means that Black is practically forced to take 7...Nxc4. }
7... Nxc4 8. dxc4
{ Disconnected pawns on c4 and e4 should not be taken as White's weaknesses, because after the trade of the light-squared Bishop White gained a new semi-opened file for the Rook, which will be achieved after Qe2, Be3, and O-O-O! Pawn actions and attacking moves aiming at Black's Kingside! }
8... d6 9. Qe2
{ White prepares for the previously mentioned plan of Be3 and O-O-O, and at the same time protects c4 pawn, which could be attacked with 9...Be6. }
9... h6 { Black simply aims to prevent the possible pin of Bg5. } 10. Be3 O-O
11. O-O-O
{ White castled long, put the Rook on the semi-opened d-file, and now prepares for the pawn storm on the Kingside with f3, g4, h4! }
11... b6
{ In the game between Rhodes, J -Segalla, J ICCF email 2007. Black went for this move, with the idea of Ba6. }
12. f3
{ White is ready for the pawn storm, and it is questionable if Black would be able to defend! }
12... Ba6 13. g4 Nd7 14. h4
{ While Black tried to gain some shred of activity on the Queenside with a Knight maneuver Nd7, followed by Nc5, White will try to open g-file with  14...--  15.g5!  and Black can not escape it! }
14... Nc5 15. g5
{ With an idea to take gxh6 and to put the Rook on the newly opened file, White forces Black to block the Kingside and to make a weakness on h5! }
15... h5
{ As it was mentioned, Black was forced to block White's pawns on the Kingside, but with this move, the pawn on h5 would be a new target exposed to attacks! }
16. f4
{ White uses the activity of the pieces and bad position of Black's pieces to put Black into trouble, threatening to play Qh5 or to take a free pawn on e5! }
16... exf4 17. Bd4
{ This is a significant move that proves the total dominance of White's pieces! Black can not protect h5 pawn anymore since  17...g6  would lead immediately to a lost position after  18.Nd5  and the forthcoming  18...--  19.Nf6! }
17... Ne6
{ Black aims to defend the weakened dark-squares around the King by removing the dark squares killer! Sorry, but it is too late for that! }
18. Bf6
{ I am sure that you didn't expect this one to come! White is completely winning after 18 moves. Bf6!! Since Black can not defend the opening of the Kingside anymore, and very soon it's checkmate! }
18... gxf6 19. Qxh5 Bb7 20. Rdg1
{ And Black should now consider resigning due to the threat of gxf6 and the opening of the g or h-file can not be stopped anymore as it could be seen in the game Rhodes, J -Segalla, J ICCF email 2007. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Sidelines in 2...Nc6: The Vienna Hybrid Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2...Nc6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.d3 Bb4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Nf6
{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... Bb4
{ The main idea that Black wants to accomplish after this move is based on central activity with d5. Basically, Black's idea is to centralize pieces, threaten the Knight on c3, and complete development fast with short castling. }
5. Ne2
{ This is the most flexible but at the same time solid developing move for White, who at the same time prepares for castling and f4, but also supports the Knight on c3 which could be pinned if Black decides to open the center with 5...d5. }
5... d5
{ Instead of the follow-up with the known idea of 5...d5, Black can also choose to play  5...d6  . In such a case, White is slightly better after  6.O-O  with a plan to enter the well-known Vienna hybrid positions after  7.f4  . }
6. exd5
{ Of course, due to Black's threat of d4, White can not consider any other move as an option here but accept to open the center. }
6... Nxd5 7. O-O
{ Whilst Black's King is still placed in the center, White aims to finish the development and to open the center with f4! One should not forget that Black's Knight on d5 is under attack, and Black needs to answer somehow. }
7... Bxc3
{ Although this is a very common move in practice, I would say that Black is not happy with the position afterward. White gains the advantage of the Bishop pair and does not care about double pawns on the c-file! }
8. Nxc3 Nxc3 9. bxc3
{ We can already here say that White gained a satisfying position with the Bishop pair, with the idea of Qf3, a4, gaining space control, and the further development ideas of Ba3, Rae1. }
9... O-O
{ Black aims to conclude development as well.   If Black decides to hurry up to overtake the advantage of the Bishop pair with  9...Na5  , White would gain a huge initiative after  10.Bb3  Nxb3  11.axb3  O-O  12.f4!  aiming to open the f-file, while one should not forget that White has another Rook active on the a-file, eyeing the a7 spot. }
10. Qf3
{ Faced with the very uncomfortable threat of Ba3, which attacks the only defender of the f7 spot, Black needs to take care of the dark squares that White fully controls, thanks to the Bishop pair.   I would also mention that  10.Qh5  Qf6  11.f4  has been played in the game between Rublevsky - Bezgodov, Cheboksary 2016,  where White had a clear advantage and an admirable open position for the Bishop pair - check 7...Nc3 }
10... Qd6
{ Black is forced to defend the a3-f8 diagonal.   If  10...Na5?  was played instead, White gains a completely winning position after  11.Ba3  Nxc4  12.Bxf8  Nd2  13.Qg3!  with Qg7# threat looming! And after  13...Qxf8  14.Rfd1  Black's Knight is trapped on the d2 spot!   Of course, after  10...Be6  11.Bxe6  fxe6  12.Qe3  White is clearly better with the superior minor piece @@StartBracket@@Bishop against Knight@@EndBracket@@ and Black needs to think about how to defend the e5 and e6 weaknesses. }
11. a4
{ Not only that, once again White creates space for the dark-squared Bishop who will be developed on the most active a3-f8 diagonal, at the same time White gains space control and gets a safe spot for the light-squared Bishop! }
11... Na5
{ Black tries to defend with the most active move, and hopes to get rid of the White's Bishop pair. Of course, this is kind of a passive move.   11...Qg6  could be played instead, after which White gains a clear advantage  12.Bd5  Bd7  13.a5!  with space control and desirable Bishop pair! }
12. Ba3
{ With this very important intermediary move, Black is forced to weaken light squares with 12...c5. That would leave the central light squares in our control! }
12... c5 13. Bd5
{ White gains an eternal Bishop placed on d5, which will be supported with c4! The further plan of White's activation should be Rfe1 and possible Bb2 which would put Black into trouble to defend e5 pawn. One should not forget that Black is currently locked to the defense of the b7 pawn and can not develop yet the light-squared Bishop! }
*

