7... Nxc3
{ Black gets rid of the attacked Knight buying a tempo for the next development move. Of course, if Black still aims to create doubled pawns for White on the c-file, they need to say goodbye to the Bishop pair! }
8. Nxc3 O-O 9. Qh5
{ White keeps putting pressure on the weakened f7 spot and aims to finish development with Be3, which could be followed with uncomfortable Knight maneuver Ne4-Ng5!   It needs to be mentioned that engines prefer  9.Ne4  instead of 9.Qh5!?, but if you are looking for an interesting position with initiative, I would recommend 9.Qh5, which showed to be better in practical play.   Of course, after  9.Ne4  Na5  10.a3  Nxc4  11.axb4  Nd6  12.Ng3  White can be satisfied with the position and has an idea to push f4! }
9... Na5
{ With this very interesting move, Black sacrifices a pawn willing to gain the Bishop pair and an open position. }
10. Qxe5
{ Of course, White accepts the gift and aims to escape from the attack with Bd5, followed by developing moves, such as Bg5, which comes with a tempo! }
10... Nxc4 11. dxc4 Re8 12. Qg3
{ White's Queen is in a safe spot on g3, and White threatens to play a3, Bg5 - tempo development move, followed by Rad1 which would put Black's Queen into an uncomfortable situation without space to escape from the attack. }
12... c6
{ This is practically the only move that gives Black chances for the intense fight.   If  12...Bf5?!  was played instead, White would be clearly better after  13.Bg5!  followed by Rad1. }
13. a3
{ After forcing Black to move the dark-squared Bishop away, White aims to finish development with Bf4 or Bg5, which will be finalized with Rad1. Since Black has some sort of minuscule compensation thanks to the Bishop pair, it is correct to say that with a pawn up, White is slightly better. }
