8. Nxc3 O-O 9. Qh5
{ White keeps putting pressure on the weakened f7 spot and aims to finish development with Be3, which could be followed with uncomfortable Knight maneuver Ne4-Ng5!   It needs to be mentioned that engines prefer  9.Ne4  instead of 9.Qh5!?, but if you are looking for an interesting position with initiative, I would recommend 9.Qh5, which showed to be better in practical play.   Of course, after  9.Ne4  Na5  10.a3  Nxc4  11.axb4  Nd6  12.Ng3  White can be satisfied with the position and has an idea to push f4! }
9... Bxc3
{ Black gives up on the Bishop pair searching for a way to create weaknesses into White's position. }
10. bxc3
{ As it was mentioned before, White's double pawns on the c-file can not be considered as a considerable weakness. White has a Bishop pair and a desirable open position to play. With a direct threat of Ba3, White threatens to expose the f7 pawn to the undefendable attack! As a curiosity, I have to mention that playing online I have faced this position at least ten times; it looks like Black, for some reason believes it could be good for them!? }
10... Qf6
{ Black gives an effort to hold the position with 10...Qf6 and at the same time defends the f7 pawn and wishes to play Be6, or to trade the Queens with Qg6. Of course, 10. ..Na5? ends up with the clearly better position for White after 11.Ba3! and Black can not support the f7 square anymore. }
11. f4
{ We do not give a break to our opponents! With 11.f4, White aims to open the f-file and improve an attack on the weakened f7 pawn. Black's Queen is pinned, and Black needs to think about defense! }
11... Be6
{ Black intends to exchange light-squared Bishops and to take off White's Bishop pair advantage. }
12. fxe5
{ With the move 11...Be6 Black finally activates the light-squared Bishop. Nevertheless, the possible exchange on e6 would be more beneficial for White if Black is forced to retake with a pawn after  12.Bxe6  fxe6  . The situation is different now, and White wants to enter a better endgame with the e6 weakness to attack. }
12... Qxe5
{ Black is practically forced to search for the draw possibility in an endgame, but as it was previously mentioned, we will have new weaknesses to attack! }
13. Qxe5 Nxe5 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. Re1
{ After a forced exchange, White gained a clear advantage in the game Rublevsky, S - Bezgodov, A Cheboksary 2016, with an open e-file for the Rook, and the idea of c4, followed by Bb2, which forces Black to move the Knight away and to expose the e6 weakness to an attack. Very pleasant type of endgame where apart from the better Bishop turned out that weakness on e6 and a little bit more active Rook give White a lot to hope for! }
