{ Black gives up on the Bishop pair and puts the hopes to create weaknesses for White on the Queenside. }
12. bxc3
{ White keeps the same idea of Qg4, but also can furtherly improve the center with a tempo after c4, and one should not forget that the dark-squared Bishop gets a more active a3-f8 diagonal after Ba3. }
12... Qd7
{ Interesting enough, this move has been the most popular in this position in the past. Black establishes a line of communication between the Rooks with a possible idea of Ne7, which piles up the pressure on the f5 pawn and abandons the shelter on c6 for the light-squared Bishop. Also, one should not forget that Qd7 could sometimes, make X-rays on Qg4 once we try to launch the attack on the Kingside. }
13. Rb1
{ This is a very interesting novelty of mine which forces Black to defend on the Queenside, White aims to afterward to gain full control of the game with c4, followed by Ne4 and a possible Qg4.   Do not forget, in the case of  13...Ne7  @@StartBracket@@where Black defends b7 by Bd5 and which gives Black a nice retreating square on c6 for the Bishop after any c4@@EndBracket@@, White could also include the Rook into the attack on the Kingside with a marvelous maneuver of  14.Rb4  14...--  15.Rh4!     Of course, in this position after  13...Ne7  , White has an alternative such as  13.c4  Bf7  14.Be3  Rad8  15.Ne4  with great initiative and the idea of g4, h4, followed by g5.   13.Be3  which was played by Karjakin Sergey against Kosteniuk Alexandra in Wijk Aan Zee 2005,  when after  13...b6  14.c4  Bf7  15.Ne4  White claims a massive action after Ba3 and g4, followed by g5. }
13... b6 14. c4
{ Black was forced to defend the pawn with  13...b6  and White strikes back in the center and forces Black to retreat with the Bishop. This way, the Knight from g3 gets a nice outpost after the upcoming  14...--  15.Ne4! }
14... Bf7 15. Ne4
{ With an idea to conclude the development with Be3, and forthcoming g4-g5, White has a very promising attack on the Kingside! Keep in mind, to support the attack on the Kingside better, in such positions, White usually goes for an idea with Rf2 @@StartBracket@@to stop checks on d4, prevent Nd4 with pressure on c2, and finally to go on g2 to launch g5 better@@EndBracket@@. }
