12... Qe7
{ Black simply connects the Rooks and stops White from activating the dark-squared Bishop with Ba3, at the same time cunningly stops the threat of Qc5 which comes with a check and an attack on the c3 pawn! }
13. c4
{ White kills two birds with one stone! Black does not have a threat of Qc5 anymore and at the same time needs to move the Bishop far away from the center whilst White gains an outpost on e4! }
13... Bf7 14. Be3
{ As I emphasized many times throughout the course, the threat is sometimes better than the execution. An outpost on e4 is clearly in possession of White, and Black can not stop us from going for Ne4, so we do not hurry to gain it but we keep developing actively! }
14... Rfd8 15. Qg4
{ After 14...Rfd8 Black had an idea to break the center with 15...e4. Of course, we are not allowing this, and we toggle the Queen to the Kingside with ideas of Ne4, Rae1, and previously mentioned possibility of Bh6, Re3, Rg3, or Rh3 with a devastating mating attack!   I would like to mention that 15.Qg4 is an improvement and reaches an interesting position that offers more practical play, compared to  15.Qf3  , which was played between Rublevsky, S and Wegerle, J in Germany in 2017,  where White claimed 'only' small advantage. }
