{ White relocates all the play to the Kingside, and not only that we want to reach an outpost on e4 with Nce4, but the idea is to continue with Qg4 and regular development of Be3, which would put pressure on the Black's abandoned King. }
11... Bf7
{ This is the most commonly played move by Black in this position. Black simply intends to keep the Bishop pair as long as possible and to try to make an advantage out of it. }
12. Nce4
{ As it is well-known, Bishop pair is not valuable in closed or semi-closed positions, such as this one. With 12.Nce4! not only that White gained an outpost on e4 for the time being, but also marginalized Black's dark-squared Bishop. As in previous similar positions, White has an idea to go for the mating attack with Qg4, Nh5, Rf3, followed up Rg3 or Rh3. }
12... Kh8
{ With this prophylactic move Black buys a tempo and ignores the forthcoming pin after Qg4, and leaves some space for Rg8 which will be useful in defense of the sensitive g7 square. }
13. Be3
{ In the game Heilala, T - Costa, F ICCF email 2008, White decided to conclude development before the mating attack on the Kingside commences. Once again, it is Black's turn to decide how to improve his pieces and how to prevent White's ideas. }
13... Re8
{ Black creates space for the dark-squared Bishop, which will turn into a defending piece from now on. }
14. Qg4
{ White starts with pressure on the g7 spot threatening to play the uncomfortable Nh5. }
14... Bf8 15. Rad1
{ It is clear that Black can not further improve the defense on the Kingside. In that manner, White does not hurry with particular operations but puts all the pieces in active positions, not leaving Black any opportunity to strike back with a counter-attack. }
15... a5
{ The only side where Black can accomplish to play is the Queenside, so with 15...a5 they prepare for a possible Nb4, or a4, followed by a3. }
16. Nh5
{ White starts the realization of the previously mentioned plan of Nh5, followed by Rf3, and again leaves Black to play Nb4 or Nd4, which will be useful for White since in that case, c3 will come with a tempo, and White anyway intends to play it before Rf3! }
16... Nb4
{ Black tries to catch the last straw of salvation and hopes to gain any counter-attack on the Queenside. }
17. c3
{ Not only White is not scared to lose a pawn on d3, but White keeps fingers crossed to face this scenario since after  17...Nxd3  18.Rf3  White is clearly better with a threat of Rg3, and it is questionable how will Black defends the Kingside. }
17... Nd5 18. Bc1
{ White has time to take a step back and to prevent all the Black's threats since Black can not defend the maneuver of Rf3, followed by Rg3 or Rh3. }
18... a4 19. a3
{ Once again, White restrains all of Black's activities and gets ready for an attack! }
19... b5 20. Rf3
{ And White is clearly better thanks to the raging mating attack, which comes after Rh3, Qh4, and an idea of Ng7. All of Black's actions were on the Queenside far away from the Kingside action, and Black is going to be forced to capture Bxh5, which would leave him with irrecoverable weaknesses on the light squares around the King. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Sidelines in 2...Nc6: The Vienna Hybrid Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2...Nc6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.d3 Bb4 #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Nf6
{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... Bb4
{ The main idea that Black wants to accomplish after this move is based on central activity with d5. Basically, Black's idea is to centralize pieces, threaten the Knight on c3, and complete development fast with short castling. }
5. Ne2
{ This is the most flexible but at the same time solid developing move for White, who at the same time prepares for castling and f4, but also supports the Knight on c3 which could be pinned if Black decides to open the center with 5...d5. }
5... d5
{ Instead of the follow-up with the known idea of 5...d5, Black can also choose to play  5...d6  . In such a case, White is slightly better after  6.O-O  with a plan to enter the well-known Vienna hybrid positions after  7.f4  . }
6. exd5
{ Of course, due to Black's threat of d4, White can not consider any other move as an option here but accept to open the center. }
6... Nxd5 7. O-O
{ Whilst Black's King is still placed in the center, White aims to finish the development and to open the center with f4! One should not forget that Black's Knight on d5 is under attack, and Black needs to answer somehow. }
7... Be6
{ With this logical development move, Black remains as flexible as possible and supports the centralized Knight on d5. Nevertheless, White aims to pounce at the opponent's position! }
8. Bxd5
{ It might look that with 8.Bxd5 we break some chess rules returning the Bishop pair back to Black. However, our idea is much more clever, and we want to force the exchanges in a way that benefits us. White will open the position with f4, opening the f-file for the Rook and using the opportunity to create tactical possibilities whilst the Black King is still in the center. }
8... Bxd5 9. f4
{ Innocuous looking, but White threatens to launch a tremendous attack on the Kingside with f5 afterward! One should not forget that White can trade the Bishop pair anytime he wants since the Bishop on d5 is under attack, and Black has no time to retreat but needs to escort the King to the safe zone. }
9... O-O
{ After quickly castling, Black attempts to revive the Bishop pair and does not care about the f-file anymore. However, we switch to another plan now and intend to close the Kingside and the center! }
10. f5
{ Black's light-squared Bishop is confined now, and White threatens to go forward with f6 putting the Black's King in an uncomfortable position. There is also a threat of Nd5 Qd5 followed by Ng3 with a promising Kingside attack. All things considered, the last move in practice, has given Black lots of problems in the past, and White has very nice attacking chances afterward. }
10... f6
{ Black prevents White's idea of f6 and creates a shelter for the light-squared Bishop that hopes to find salvation with Bf7. Anyway, White does not care anymore about the Bishop pair, since the position is blocked and Black has no good way to activate Bishops! }
11. Ng3
{ White relocates all the play to the Kingside, and not only that we want to reach an outpost on e4 with Nce4, but the idea is to continue with Qg4 and regular development of Be3, which would put pressure on the Black's abandoned King. }
11... Bf7
{ This is the most commonly played move by Black in this position. Black simply intends to keep the Bishop pair as long as possible and to try to make an advantage out of it. }
12. Nce4
{ As it is well-known, Bishop pair is not valuable in closed or semi-closed positions, such as this one. With 12.Nce4! not only that White gained an outpost on e4 for the time being, but also marginalized Black's dark-squared Bishop. As in previous similar positions, White has an idea to go for the mating attack with Qg4, Nh5, Rf3, followed up Rg3 or Rh3. }
12... Ba5
{ Black attempts to activate dark-squared Bishop with Bb6. Of course, Black could also play a defensive  12...Be7  , and after  13.Qg4  Kh8  14.Be3  White keeps an idea of Nh5, Rad1, and possible Rf2 which would give support to the c2 pawn if needed. }
13. Qg4
{ Black faces lots of troubles due to massive threats of Nh5 followed by Nf6, or Bh6. It is obvious that Black would need to escape the pin immediately if he wants to resist. }
13... Bb6+ 14. Kh1 Kh8 15. Nh5
{ Black temporarily escaped the pin, but the King is still exposed to an attack, as well as the weakened g7 pawn. White aims to go for Rf3, followed by Rg3 or Rh3 with Qh5 and Black would face plenty of issues trying to defend the h7 or g7 square. }
15... Bxh5
{ Practically the only way for Black to save the King is to give up on the Bishop pair and to let White conquer the light squares. }
16. Qxh5
{ With eternal Knight on e4 and a mating attack on the Kingside which will be accomplished after Rf3, followed by Rh4, White is at least slightly better.   The game between Fernandez Garcia, J - Valles Moreno, I,  Collado Villalba 2004, continued with  16...Qd4  17.a4  Rad8  18.Rb1  with a slight advantage for White, but I would recommend  18.g4!  to be played instead, and White can continue attacking with the idea of g5 taking full control of the light squares around Black's King. }
