[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2...Nc6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.d3 d6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Nf6
{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... d6
{ Although Black closes the path for the dark-squared Bishop, this is one of the most commonly played moves by Black who searches for a solid continuation, without complications. This is also a very common approach by players who are unfamiliar with the arising position and have no idea about any theory here. So, better get ready for it and learn the following plans well!   This continuation transposes into this line also after  4...Be7  5.f4  d6  6.Nf3  . }
5. f4
{ Since Black does not control the dark squares around White's King anymore, and the dark-squared Bishop is locked on the f8 square, White can go for the Vienna set up, aiming to develop the Kingside as soon as possible and gain activity on the semi-opened f-file. }
5... Be7
{ Black chooses to go for fast development as well, with the most common idea of Bg4 and O-O.   One should not forget that  5...Na5  6.Bb3  Nxb3  7.axb3  would be a transposition into the line with 4...Na5 5.Bb3 Nxb3 6.axb3 Be7. }
6. Nf3
{ As expected, White continues with active development and puts some pressure on the central e5 pawn. Also, short castle is coming too, with simple development. }
6... Bg4
{ With this move Black has a very direct threat of Nd4 and White needs to react!     I would say that natural follow-up  6...O-O?!  can be considered as a terrible move, since White blocks all of the possible routes for Black to activate the pieces after  7.f5!  and Black has difficulties finding space for the development of the light-squared bishop. If Black continues with  7...Na5  aiming to remove our Bishop from c4, White would be clearly better after  8.a4!  Nxc4  9.dxc4  c6  10.Bg5  with a space advantage, actively developed pieces, and a d6 target to attack. }
7. h3
{ Due to the previously mentioned threat of Nd4, White needs to react with 7.h3 and to kick out the light-squared Bishop from the h5-d1 diagonal. }
7... Bxf3
{ Black is practically forced to remove the Knight, since  6...Bh5??  would lead him straightly to a losing position after  7.g4  , followed by f5, and the light-squared Bishop has no square to escape to.   6...Bd7  would be met with  7.f5!  and a total clamp-on Black's pieces. }
8. Qxf3
{ We have activated the Queen which is now closer to Black's Kingside, and we are ready for the castle! It is very important to notice that White now has an advantage of the Bishop pair which is favorable in open positions, such as this one! }
8... Na5
{ It is a fact that Black can take the Bishop pair off very soon, but one should not forget that Black is already very late with development and it is questionable if they have time for such maneuvers. }
9. Bb3
{ This is a very important move, although it does not save the Bishop. White aims to keep a stable center and a healthy pawn structure which was threatened to be ruined after  9...Nxc4  10.dxc4  .   Of course, an alternative could be  9.f5  , and White would be still slightly better after  9...c6  10.a4  due to a huge space control and actively developed pieces. }
9... Nxb3 10. axb3
{ Not only White is ready to conclude development with O-O, but after an exchange, we gained another open file for the Rook on a1 which can attack the a7 pawn! }
10... c6
{ Black intends to prepare a counter-reaction in the center.   Also  10...Nd7  could be played instead, but after  11.O-O  O-O  , White is clearly better with  12.Nd5  and an idea of Bd2 and possible Knight maneuver with Ne3-Nf5! }
11. O-O O-O 12. Ne2
{ And it is clear that White is much more active than Black. With a threat of Ng3-Nf5, or possible fxe5, Be3, White is clearly better thanks to the active pieces, control of the open files, and huge space for possible maneuvers. }
