{ Due to the previously mentioned threat of Nd4, White needs to react with 7.h3 and to kick out the light-squared Bishop from the h5-d1 diagonal. }
7... Bxf3
{ Black is practically forced to remove the Knight, since  6...Bh5??  would lead him straightly to a losing position after  7.g4  , followed by f5, and the light-squared Bishop has no square to escape to.   6...Bd7  would be met with  7.f5!  and a total clamp-on Black's pieces. }
8. Qxf3
{ We have activated the Queen which is now closer to Black's Kingside, and we are ready for the castle! It is very important to notice that White now has an advantage of the Bishop pair which is favorable in open positions, such as this one! }
8... Nd4
{ This is the most solid move by Black in this situation who punches back with a double attack on White's Queen on f3 and the pawn on c2.   White is forced to slow up development and the previously mentioned activities in the center to take care of Black's threats. }
9. Qf2
{ After a simple step back, White is ready to castle and to go for Be3, which would expose the well-looking Knight d4 to an attack! }
9... c6
{ 9...c6 might look inadequate, since Black threatens nothing in the center, but actually Black's idea is to go for b5 which would force White to give up the Bishop pair!   I need to mention that I am sure you will face a lot of  9...Nh5?  moves here, as it is a very common mistake in practice, played 27 times! I am also sure that you will enjoy the winning position that will arise after  10.Bxf7!  Kxf7  11.fxe5  and White is much better after the forthcoming Qd4 and a clear pawn up, whilst Black can forget about castling and development.     Of course, Black can also choose instead to go for  9...O-O  and after  10.O-O  c6  10.a4!  White is clearly better with a Bishop pair advantage, better development, and space control. }
10. a4
{ This is a very important move seizing space from the Black's territory and preventing the b5 threat. White's Bishop pair is safe, and we can continue with regular development! }
10... O-O 11. O-O Nh5
{ Black threatens to activate the dark-squared Bishop with a very uncomfortable Bh4 which would put White into trouble to find a good spot for the Queen. }
12. g3
{ This is practically the only move that gives an advantage to White!   White keeps the Bishops pair with an idea to play Kg2 and consolidate the King, followed by Be3, additional space control after a5, and one should not forget that the light-squared Bishop has a safe spot on a2 after a possible 12...d5 by Black. }
12... d5 13. Ba2
{ White puts the Bishop back into safety and threatens to open the position up with fxe5, which would open up space on the board for our Bishop pair!     An alternative could be  13.exd5  Bc5  14.Kh2  which was played in the game Fernandez Ballon, A - Kirwald, F Remote email 2013,  and White is slightly better with an idea of Be3 and a pawn up. }
13... Bd6
{ Black aims to defend the e5 pawn with a threat of exf4 which would open the space around White's King.   If Black decides to go for  13...Bc5  14.Be3  would block all of the threats, and White has a clearly better position with a safe Bishop pair, threatening to take either the e5 or d5 pawn, since both are hanging! }
14. f5
{ And after the last move, all of Black's threats are blocked and Black needs to think about the safety of the d5 hanging pawn. The further plan for White can be Kg2 - tucking the King away to a safe spot, followed by a developing move, such as Be3, and White is clearly better with huge activity whilst Black's pieces are exposed to attacks! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Sidelines in 2...Nc6: The Vienna Hybrid Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2...Nc6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.d3 Na5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Nf6
{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... Na5
{ I do not doubt that 4...Na5 is the best answer by Black and at the same time statistically the most common answer by Black. It prevents 5.f4 at the moment and leaves White without the light-squared Bishop. However, things are not that bad for us either, considering the fact how many top players lately use the Bishop's opening and how high they score in this line! }
5. Bb3
{ Although  5.Nge2  was the most popular approach for decades, and  5.Qf3!?  in the past looked quite interesting, I decided to continue with  5.Bb3  . This decision is based on the resulting pawn structure and the open a-file, instead of giving many other options for Black, such as  6...c6  followed by  d5  and losing advantage in the center. This was not an easy decision but my final vote goes to 5.Bb3! }
5... Bb4
{ A very interesting attempt by Black. Black's idea is simple, he aims to develop the Bishop, pin the Nc3, prepare castling, and more so fight for the central d5 square with the final idea to push d5 especially when Bb3 is about to fall thanks to  Nxb3! }
6. Nf3
{ This is absolutely the best response. White strikes back in the center by attacking e5 and develops the Knight with an idea to castle and finish development as soon as possible. One should notice that with this move White gains an important development tempo. }
6... Nxb3
{ Black reduces material and trades his Knight for the strong light-squared Bishop. This way, Black has managed to remove one of the most important pieces for White, which was eyeing the most vulnerable square in Black's position - f7. However, White will gain an open a-file for the Rook, which would give White many opportunities for the initiative. }
7. axb3
{ To someone watching from the outside, it may look like Black has ruined White's pawn structure by creating doubled pawns, but one should not forget that White gained an open a-file for the Rook, which pressures the a7 square, and with the possible idea of a Rook lift with Ra4 or Ra5, Black could get into troubles with weaknesses in the center. }
7... O-O
{ If Black plays  7...d5  the position would transpose to 5...Nxb3 6.axb3 d5 7.Nf3 Bb4 8.O-O. }
8. O-O d5
{ One more time Black reacts actively in the center, playing 8...d5 instead of resilient  8...d6  which would transpose to 5...Nxb3 6.axb3 Bb4 7.Nf3 d6. Black aims to follow the well-known rule: 'Attack is the best defense'. }
9. Bg5
{ The development has been completed by White. The Bg5 indirectly defends a pawn on e4 and by pinning the Knight on f6, White forces Black to react. This part of the game could be decisive for the remainder of the game and it could lead to a very interesting position, full of tactical but also positional challenges.   You should not hurry to take the pawn with  9.Nxe5?!  because that would lead to an equal position after  9...Re8  and Black takes the pawn back, but also ruins White's center. }
9... Bxc3
{ As it was mentioned before, Black has to react after Bg5 due to the obvious threat of Nxd5 which could create serious weaknesses in Black's position. This is a logical response by Black, 'Kill the killer' and reduce the pressure in the center! }
10. bxc3 dxe4
{ Black continues reducing the material on the board, cleaning up the situation in the center, and threatens to win a pawn after  11.dxe4  Qxd1  12.Rfxd1  and 12...Nxe4 followed by 13...Nxc3. }
11. Nxe5
{ This is the only move for White that keeps an advantage. The pin of the Bishop on g5 is still there and very soon White will take control over the center aiming to play 12.d4! }
11... h6
{ Black intends to get rid of the pin and to move the Bishop from g5 away.   One should not forget that  11...exd3?!  would lead to a slight advantage for White after  12.cxd3  . White would have a full center control, open a-file for the Rook on a1 that pressures a7 spot, and with a simple idea of d4, followed by Re1, White has a nice position to play. }
12. Bh4
{ With a simple step back White keeps the pressure on the pinned Knight on f6, and still aims to play d4 which would lead to full central control. Of course, the Rook on a1 helps with the pressure on the weakened a7 pawn, and White can put Black into trouble after a nice Rook lift, such as Ra5. }
12... Bf5 { Black keeps developing and aims to consolidate after 13...Qd6. }
13. Ra5
{ This is a very interesting move that gives a lot of headaches to Black. With 13.Ra5!? White keeps the pressure on the a7 pawn, but also pins Black's Bishop on f5, threatening to play  13...--  14.Nxf7!  , followed by Rxf5, and to play a position with a clear advantage and a pawn up.  Black needs to think about defense and to put development aside for the moment.   I would like to mention that  13.Re1  gives a clear advantage to White, with the idea of d4 and Ra5, but I find  13.Ra5!?  more interesting and more uncomfortable for the Black side. }
13... g5
{ Black finally gets rid of the pin by Bishop on h4, but one should not forget that at the same time Black weakens the Kingside! }
14. Bg3 Bh7
{ Black puts the Bishop into safety and prevents the White's threat of Nxf7. With the main threat of 15...c6 Black aims to put our Rook into trouble, forcing us to go back. However, it is questionable if Black has time to accomplish all of their ideas, due to the weakened Kingside which we are going to use to create an attack! }
15. f4
{ With this amazing move White gains a clear advantage threatening to play  15...--  16.fxg5  , followed by Qc1!  Black can hardly defend the Kingside, and White's main advantage is the activity of pieces- Ra5 indirectly attacks the g5 weakened square, Knight on e5 is untouchable, while the Rook on f1 joins the game and threatens to put Black into trouble on the semi-opened f-file. Black has issues finding a good plan, as could be seen in the game between Dubov, D - Ding, L chess24.com INT 2020. }
*

