[Round "?"]
[White "2) Sidelines in 2...Nc6: The Vienna Hybrid Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2...Nc6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.d3 Na5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Nf6
{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... Na5
{ I do not doubt that 4...Na5 is the best answer by Black and at the same time statistically the most common answer by Black. It prevents 5.f4 at the moment and leaves White without the light-squared Bishop. However, things are not that bad for us either, considering the fact how many top players lately use the Bishop's opening and how high they score in this line! }
5. Bb3
{ Although  5.Nge2  was the most popular approach for decades, and  5.Qf3!?  in the past looked quite interesting, I decided to continue with  5.Bb3  . This decision is based on the resulting pawn structure and the open a-file, instead of giving many other options for Black, such as  6...c6  followed by  d5  and losing advantage in the center. This was not an easy decision but my final vote goes to 5.Bb3! }
5... Nxb3
{ Black decides to remove the light-squared killer and inflicts doubled pawns on White. It also allows for an easier break with d5 in the center and the Bishop pair advantage. However, this gives some pluses to White as it will be seen later! }
6. axb3
{ As it was previously said Black aims to inflict a bad pawn structure on White, but one should not forget that after 6. axb3 White gains an open a-file for the Rook on a1, which pressures the a7 square, and with the possible idea of the Rook lift with Ra4 or Ra5, Black could face troubles because of the weaknesses in the center. }
6... Bb4
{ Mainly, Black's idea with this move is to pin the White's Knight on c3 and to go for the center activity after 7...d5. }
7. Nf3
{ Certainly, we don't want to go here for 7.f4 which might look logical to you as a kind of transposition to some hypermodern Vienna gambit. Black is simply too active and  7.f4  would be dangerous for us at the moment.  For that reason, White continues with normal development, threatening to take Black's pawn on e5 and aims to castle as soon as possible. In fact, with the last move, White forces Black to go with the natural d6, but as the analysis will show, it might leave the Bishop on b4 'lost'! }
7... d6
{ Black chooses the more cautious plan of development and supports the hanging e5 pawn. One should not forget that  7...d5  transposes to the line  6...d5 7.Nf3 Bb4 8.O-O. }
8. O-O
{ White has a simple idea to swing the pieces on the Kingside, preparing for central action. The plan is to continue with Ne2-Ng3, h3, and possible c3-d4! }
8... Bxc3
{ Even though this might look like an unnatural move by Black, with 8...Bxc3 Black aims to prevent White's idea of Ne2 which would leave the dark-squared Bishop eyeing nothing. }
9. bxc3
{ You should not consider the doubled pawns on the c-file as weaknesses since White has a pretty clear and dangerous plan of c4, c5, with the idea to weaken the dark squares in Black's position. Obviously, that would lead to the activation of the Bishop on c1, which will become the most important piece very soon! }
9... O-O 10. c4
{ White is ready to crush Black's center after c5 and to create weaknesses on the dark squares, which will be under the control of our Bishop on c1! }
10... b6
{ Black aims to prevent the idea of c5, and creates some space for the light-squared Bishop and possible Knights maneuvers. However, you should not hurry to concretize the idea of c5.   For example after  10...a5  White can go for  11.h3  stopping Black from developing the light-squared Bishop on the most active g4 spot, and after  11...b6  White is slightly better with  12.Bb2  and the idea of Nh2, followed by f4! }
11. Qe2
{ White still waits to declare whether the dark-squared Bishop will be developed on the Kingside with Bg5 or it will be developed on the Queenside with Bb2 and the previously mentioned idea of h3-Nh2-f4. For now, White develops the Queen and prepares to connect the Rooks, letting Black decide how to continue. }
11... Nd7
{ Black apparently wishes to continue with f5, opening the Kingside in their own favor. However, this is the time to strike back on the dark squares!   If Black decides to play something more passive, such as  11...a5  , White can continue with an idea of f4, after 12.Nd2! }
12. Bg5
{ With this tempo development move, White forces Black to react and puts the f5 plan aside for the moment! }
12... f6
{ Black tries to keep the idea of f5, aiming to kick out the Bishop from g5.   If  12...Qe8  was played instead, White would gain plenty of counterattacking chances with  13.b4  White has a slight advantage and future plans of pressuring the weakened a7 pawn. }
13. Be3
{ After the last move White shows that they have no fear of 13...f5.   Another possibility could be  13.Bd2  , which supports b4 @@StartBracket@@aimed against a5@@EndBracket@@, which could give a potentially lethal Queenside action followed by doubling the Rooks on the a-file, pressure on the a7 pawn as well as possibilities on the Kingside with f4. }
13... Re8
{ Black's reaction might depend on the personal chess style of the opponent you face.   Of course Black could go for  13...f5  as it could be seen in the game Draskovic, M-Milutinovic I, Yugoslavia 1980, when after  14.exf5  Rxf5  White strikes back on the dark squares with  15.Bg5!  threatening to play Qe4! and after  15...Rxg5  16.Nxg5  Qxg5  17.Qf3  gives difficulties to Black forcing him to play  17...Rb8  and to leave the a7 pawn unprotected. After  18.Rxa7  , White is clearly better with the next pawn coming down-  c7  .   Instead in the game Edwards, K - Hux, R corr 1996,  Black chose to play  13...Nc5  and White gained a slightly better position after  14.Nh4  Ne6  15.g3  with an idea of f4. After  15...Bd7  16.f4  Nd4  17.Bxd4  exd4  White gains initiative with  18.g4!  aiming to conquer the light squares after f5! }
14. Nd2
{ Since Black chose to go for a solid position and a possible maneuvers of Nf8-Ng6, White can react in the center aiming to play f5 afterward, which would put Black into chains on the back rank. }
14... Nf8
{ Black tries to gain some fresh air for the pieces with the idea to continue with Ng6, Be6, however, White can not be stopped from proceeding with the prepared plan of f4! }
15. f4
{ Due to White's idea of f5, Rf3, followed by Rg3 and possible Qg4, Black is practically forced to continue with 15...exf4. }
15... exf4 16. Rxf4
{ With the activation of the Rook on the semi-open f-file, White is slightly better and prepared to swing the other pieces to the Kingside with the forthcoming Nf1-Ng3, and Raf1.   Black's pawn structure is unnatural, since all of the pawns are positioned on dark squares from where they can be easily exposed to attacks.   In the game between Wibe, T-Kvamme, K Norway 1978,  White gained a clear advantage and huge initiative after  16...Bd7  17.Nf1  Ng6  18.Rf2  a5  19.Ng3  with the same idea of Raf1 and  Nh5  which would force Black to think about possible sacrifices of Rxf6 or Nxf6. One should not forget that according to Capablanca's rule @@StartBracket@@where the pawns are placed on the color of the opposite side Bishop@@EndBracket@@, both Bishops are quite limited @@StartBracket@@Be3 & Bc8@@EndBracket@@, more so, White will organize a Kingside assault and strike on f6 and g7 pawns and weaken Kg8, Black does not stand a chance! }
