8... O-O
{ This is the most natural follow-up by Black who aims to conclude the development. }
9. Ne2
{ Not only that we follow the previously mentioned plan of Ng3 and h3, but White also renders Black's dark-squared Bishop useless and out of play on the b4 square. Black will hardly find a plan to use the Bishop on b4, and White can consider also blocking it once and for all after c3, Re1, d4!     It is worth mentioning that White can also choose to go for the more calm line with  9.Bg5  c6  10.d4  h6  11.Bh4  Re8  entering a slightly better endgame after  12.dxe5  dxe5  13.Qxd8  Rxd8  14.Rfe1  when Black will face difficulties to defend the  e5  pawn and against the ruining of the pawn structure on the Kingside after Bxf6. }
9... h6
{ Black prevents the possible pin of Bg5 although that was not the main plan by White.   Many times I faced  9...a5  here, but after  10.c3  Bc5  White can continue with the  11.Ng3  plan, followed by h3, d4, Re1 with a slight advantage. }
10. Ng3
{ White is ready to take advantage of the meaningless position of Black's dark-squared Bishop, aiming to continue with the idea of h3, c3, Re1, leading to a central action with d4! The arising position resembles a lot of Ruy Lopez games, where we lack the light-squared Bishop but the opponent has a lot of problems with the Bishop on b4 flying 'in the middle of nowhere'. }
