8. Nf3
{ After this simple development move Black is forced to react with the e5 pawn which is under attack, while White is ready to castle and to gain the f-line! }
8... exf4
{ This is the most common move by Black.   However, I would like to add that Black can choose to go for  8...Bg4  indirectly defending the e5 pawn by pinning the Knight on  f3  , yet White gains a solid initiative after  9.fxe5  dxe5  10.h3  Bxf3  11.Qxf3  with the idea of Ne2-Ng3, gaining afterward a strong outpost on f5! }
9. Bxf4 O-O 10. O-O
{ White concludes development and aims to play Qe1-Qf2, followed by h3 and a threat to take the a7 weakened pawn while slowly building up a solid game in the center. }
10... d5
{ A simple space grabbing move that opens up the position and gives the Bishops more space. Although, it allows White the e5 push as well, with the standard plan afterward with d4 and Kingside action. }
11. e5
{ White wants to take full control of the center after d4, followed by natural development moves, such as Qd2, Rae1. }
11... Nh5
{ It is clear that Black has only two options to move the Knight away from the attack. Of course  11...Nd7  is impossible due to  12.Nd5  .   So Black has to choose between  11...Nh5  and  11...Ne8  which is considered very passive. However, after  11...Ne8  White can improve the position with  12.Qe1  and idea of Qg3, followed by Rae1, d4 gaining a slightly better position with the initiative as it could be seen in the game Fortunato, L - Milde, L LSS email 2010. }
12. Be3
{ With this simple step back White pressures the a7 exposed pawn and we are ready to continue with our plan! }
12... a6 13. d4
{ We gain full control of the center and aim to play normal development moves, such as Qd2, followed by Rf2, Raf1, possible Ne2, and Nf4. The position would be unclear, but I would say that with lots of space and control of e and f-lines White has at least a nice initiative. }
13... g6
{ Black prepares for the possible maneuver of Ng7-Nf5, reaching an outpost on f5 either with the Knight or with the Bishop. White needs to focus on taking advantage of the slightly weakened dark squares now! }
14. Ne2 Bg4 15. Qd2
{ And as it was previously said, White follows up the idea of Rf2, Raf1, Bh6, with the main idea to conquer the dark squares with the initiative.   I would also like to mention that also  15.h3  is also possible for White, as it was played in the game Quakkelaar, M - Feroul, M ICCF corr 1995,  when after  15...Bxf3  16.Rxf3  White gains a slightly better position to play with Qd2 and Raf1 coming in next. }
