{ Black practically plays a waiting move to see White's response and at the same time prepares for a central reaction with d5. }
11. Qe1
{ White continues with the same threat of Qf2, followed by h3, aiming to take the pawn on a7 and to weaken the dark squares in Black's position. One should not forget that White can easily switch to a plan with Qg3 if Black moves the Knight from f6 away, or if they block the h5 square with Nh5. }
11... d5
{ Black is practically forced to react somehow and chooses to go for the central activity.   Of course  11...Bg4  would be met with  12.h3  followed by the 13.Qg3 idea. }
12. e5
{ White pushes Black's pieces back and starts grabbing space altogether with good center activity. }
12... Nh5 13. Be3
{ With an attack on the a7 pawn, Black is forced to weaken the dark squares on the Queenside which would give White additional opportunities for the initiative. I would like to emphasize that in this case White doesn't want to go for d4, which would block the dominant dark-squared Bishop, but White will keep control of the dark squares as long as possible with Qf2 and Rae1. }
13... a6 14. Na4
{ And White gains a clearly better position with the very direct threats of Qf2 and Bb6, which would be followed by Nc5. Black would need to give up on the Bishop pair, and White will be able to develop the play on the dark squares. Of course, White will continue to improve the pieces with Rae1 with some pretty easy play. }
