8... a6
{ Black creates a safe square for the dark-squared Bishop and keeps the idea of Ng4 in the back pocket. Anyway, after 8...a6, White gains an important tempo to continue with our normal yet poisonous development! }
9. Qe2
{ This is a very important intermediate stage of development. White needs to get rid of the dark-squared Bishop aiming to play Be3, followed by O-O. Meanwhile, Black's pawn on e5 will be under attack and Black needs to consider defending it passively. }
9... Qe7
{ Black supports the central pawn and has the idea to continue with development, but White has time now to prepare for O-O.   If Black played  9...exf4  instead, White would gain a small advantage after  10.Bxf4  O-O  11.d4!  with full central control and ideas of O-O, Be3, or Bg5. It is clear that White has a very nice position with plenty of initiative and all of the pieces activated. }
10. fxe5 dxe5 11. Be3
{ And after  11.Be3  White accomplishes the idea to finally remove Black's dark-squared Bishop, aiming to castle. With a possible target to attack  e5  , control of the two a and f-open files, White has at least a slight advantage and a clear and easy position to play.   I need to mention that White can also proceed with  11.Bg5!?  instead, with an idea to make the best out of Black's pinned Knight with Nd5, Black then would be forced to react with  11...c6  which would make the dark squares very weak on the Queenside and it also gives White relatively easy game after  12.O-O-O  followed by Rhf1! }
