{ As it was already mentioned, White, intends to conclude development with Nf3, Qd2, and O-O-O! The attack on the Kingside will be accomplished afterward with Rf1 and possible central action with d4. }
6... d6
{ Black establishes the control of e5 square and opens the space for the light squared Bishop to be developed. }
7. Nf3
{ White logically continues developing and as it was said, continues going for Qd2, O-O-O. A possible d4 can also be played at some moment. }
7... Be6
{ Black intends to exchange the light-squared Bishops even before castling. But White has an opportunity to escape it now! }
8. Bb5
{ This move showed to be more uncomfortable for Black although White could gain a slightly better position after  8.Bxe6  fxe6  9.d4  with full central control and the idea of  Qd3  which leaves the possibility to White to castle either on the Queenside or on the Kingside.   However, after  8.Bb5!  White has a direct threat of d4, followed by d5, and Black needs to delay the development to defend. }
8... a6
{ This is practically the only way for Black to defend a previously mentioned threat of d4 followed by d5.   There is also the possibility of  8...d5  , but after  9.e5  Nd7  10.d4  as it was seen in the game Shabalov - Payen World open 1999,  White easily crushed Black's counter-chances in the center afterward. }
9. Bxc6+
{ We capture the Knight and force Black to weaken the pawn structure on the Queenside which will be targeted with attacks later on. }
9... bxc6 10. d4
{ Whilst White overtakes the full central control Black is once again forced to step back and to delay development. Not only that White has better pieces here, but White also has a better development. }
10... Bb6 11. O-O
{ With full central control and a healthy pawn structure, White has at least a slight advantage whilst Black needs to take care of the a6, c7, and c6 long-term weaknesses. White threatens to conquer the h4-d8 diagonal and to pin Black's Knight on f6 with Bg5, aiming to continue with logical development and activation with Qd2, Rad1, Kh1 and e5! }
