{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... Bc5
{ This is one of the main and most critical lines of the Bishop's opening. According to my playing experience, I faced this move frequently, and it seems that Black mostly chose 4...Bc5 with the idea to compromise White's King after Ng4. However, the positions reached afterward are maybe not so desirable according to the engines'. Still, I would say that they are a bit dangerous, and offer practical and interesting play with many tactical possibilities and attacking ideas. }
5. f4
{ White slides into a very aggressive Vienna Hybrid variation aiming to open the position and to develop an attack on the Kingside. If you have wondered where the White King is going to escape since it is obvious that O-O is not possible due to Bc5 which controls g1 square, of course, the answer is O-O-O! }
5... exf4
{ White should feel like a happy camper when they encounter this move as it serves into White's agenda of Bf4, Nf3, and O-O-O.   We do not need to lose any tempo now to open the space for the dark-squared Bishop, but we immediately develop it on the very active square on f4. }
6. Bxf4
{ As it was already mentioned, White, intends to conclude development with Nf3, Qd2, and O-O-O! The attack on the Kingside will be accomplished afterward with Rf1 and possible central action with d4. }
6... d6
{ Black establishes the control of e5 square and opens the space for the light squared Bishop to be developed. }
7. Nf3
{ White logically continues developing and as it was said, continues going for Qd2, O-O-O. A possible d4 can also be played at some moment. }
7... Bg4
{ Black chooses the most active developing move with a threat of Nd4 which would put White into trouble to defend the f3 square. }
8. Qd2
{ White escapes the pin and continues with development aiming to play O-O-O! }
8... O-O
{ Black as well continues with the logical development moves. I frequently faced here  8...Bxf3  9.gxf3  Nh5  10.Bg5  Qd7  11.O-O-O  and White is clearly better with a Bishop pair and idea to settle the King in a safe zone with Kb1, and to continue activating with Rf1 and Qg2;   while after  8...Bxf3  9.gxf3  Nd4  10.O-O-O!  does good enough job and gives White full activity since Black can not take  10...Nxf3?  due to  11.Qg2!  with a completely winning position. }
9. O-O-O a6
{ Black has the idea to play b5. It is clear that White looks for action on the Kingside, and Black's only possibility to strike back is to look for a counterattack on the Queenside, which is quite a typical strategy when castling on opposite sides of the board.   There is also a possibility of  9...Ne5  but after  10.Rhf1!  White continues to pressure along f-file both f7 square and even more vulnerable Nf6.  10...Nxc4  11.dxc4  should not scare us due to the inability of Black to put the Bc5 back to e7 and hold the Knight on f6. }
10. Bg5
{ This is a very important move that gives White active play and advantage. Black faces trouble to escape from the pin which will be even made stronger after Nd5! }
10... Ne5
{ Sounds unbelievable but this is the only way for Black to keep the position dynamically balanced while any other move leads to a decisive advantage for White.   For example, if Black tries to kick out the Bishop with  10...h6?  11.Bxh6  gxh6  12.Qxh6!  comes right away and White is winning with the idea to play Rhf1, followed by Ng5!   If Black decides to play  10...Bxf3?!  11.gxf3  Ne5  White keeps the threat of Nd5 after  12.Qg2!  Nxc4  13.dxc4  and has a much better position to play with another direct threat of e5!   Even more so, White also gains a winning position after  10...b5?  11.Nd5!  bxc4  12.Bxf6  gxf6  13.Qh6!  and Black can not escape from the forthcoming Nf6! }
11. Nxe5
{ Even though the engine gives us a good enough possibility with  11.Rhf1  , I strongly believe that 11.Nxe5! leads to direct advantage and is pretty simple and straightforward to remember. }
11... dxe5
{ Now it gets clear why Black's saving move from the pin is only 10...Ne5. By forcing White to exchange, Black clears up some space for the Bishop to go back and to help with the defense! Of course,  11...Bxd1  is not possible due to  12.Nxf7!  and after all of the exchanges, White keeps the better position with a pawn up. }
12. Rdf1
{ White simply puts the Rook on the open f-file and piles up the attack on the pinned Knight! }
12... Be7
{ Black is happy enough to have this move up his sleeve, although, it seems is not enough... }
13. Qf2
{ It was expected that Black will answer with 12...Be7, defending against the pin, but White continues to swing the heavy pieces to the Kingside, intending to play Qg3 or Qh4! White has very promising attacking chances after the last move! }
13... h6 14. Bd2
{ If Black decides to kick out the Bishop from the most active g5 square, they create two targets for the possible attack. Pawns on f7 and h6 are exposed, and White aims to play Qg3, indirectly pinning Black's King with an attack on the e5 pawn and the always annoying Bh6 ideas! }
