{ This is one of the main and most critical lines of the Bishop's opening. According to my playing experience, I faced this move frequently, and it seems that Black mostly chose 4...Bc5 with the idea to compromise White's King after Ng4. However, the positions reached afterward are maybe not so desirable according to the engines'. Still, I would say that they are a bit dangerous, and offer practical and interesting play with many tactical possibilities and attacking ideas. }
5. f4
{ White slides into a very aggressive Vienna Hybrid variation aiming to open the position and to develop an attack on the Kingside. If you have wondered where the White King is going to escape since it is obvious that O-O is not possible due to Bc5 which controls g1 square, of course, the answer is O-O-O! }
5... d5
{ This is a very interesting move by Black which is commonly played Online in Blitz games. Black aims to open the light squared Bishop with tempo, and intends to play Ng4. Although 5...d5?! can be considered as suspicious, White may encounter a dangerous position if they do not know how to gain an advantage out of it! }
6. Nxd5
{ To avoid any possible complications, it is imperative to play this move 6.Nxd5! White gains a pawn up, material advantage, and starts forcing Black to trade pieces. One should not forget that the side who has a material advantage aims to trade everything, I often say, even underwear! }
6... Nxd5
{ Black accepts to exchange and opens the d8-h4 diagonal for the Queen and possible Qh4+. At the first sight, this might look uncomfortable, but as it will be shown, White has no reason to fear! }
7. Bxd5
{ Not only that White improves the position of the light-squared Bishop and that aims to conclude development after Nf3, but White also threatens to take Bc6, to simplify the position with trade and to make double pawns to Black on the Queenside. }
7... Bxg1
{ White deflects the defender of the h2 pawn and hopes to get the initiative after Qh4+. Meanwhile, White will create weaknesses on the Queenside, and that will be more than enough for the clear advantage. }
8. Rxg1 Qh4+ 9. g3
{ Whilst Black loses time to collect unimportant pawns, such as h2, White threatens to take Bc6 with a check, forcing Black to double pawns on the c-file with lack of the pieces to gain any action. }
9... Qxh2 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Be3
{ And as it was mentioned, the position is close to an endgame, and Black has an unfixable pawn structure on the Queenside with a7, c7, and c6 weaknesses. White is clearly better with an intention to marginalize Black's Queen after Bf2 and Qf3 when Black will be faced with a threat of Rh1! }
