2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Nf6
{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... Bc5
{ This is one of the main and most critical lines of the Bishop's opening. According to my playing experience, I faced this move frequently, and it seems that Black mostly chose 4...Bc5 with the idea to compromise White's King after Ng4. However, the positions reached afterward are maybe not so desirable according to the engines'. Still, I would say that they are a bit dangerous, and offer practical and interesting play with many tactical possibilities and attacking ideas. }
5. f4
{ White slides into a very aggressive Vienna Hybrid variation aiming to open the position and to develop an attack on the Kingside. If you have wondered where the White King is going to escape since it is obvious that O-O is not possible due to Bc5 which controls g1 square, of course, the answer is O-O-O! }
5... d5
{ This is a very interesting move by Black which is commonly played Online in Blitz games. Black aims to open the light squared Bishop with tempo, and intends to play Ng4. Although 5...d5?! can be considered as suspicious, White may encounter a dangerous position if they do not know how to gain an advantage out of it! }
6. Nxd5
{ To avoid any possible complications, it is imperative to play this move 6.Nxd5! White gains a pawn up, material advantage, and starts forcing Black to trade pieces. One should not forget that the side who has a material advantage aims to trade everything, I often say, even underwear! }
6... Ng4
{ This is just another example of how a suspicious move can look dangerous if we do not know how to answer it. Black's idea is to play Bf2 or Nf2, but we do not care about that! White looks for action against the Black's centralized King! }
7. f5
{ White seizes the space for Black and closes the light-squared Bishop, and at the same time, we open a c1-h6 diagonal for the dark-squared Bishop! The Knight on g4 hangs, and needs to be moved, which would result in unleashing the d1-h5 diagonal for White's Queen! }
7... Nf2
{ It is clear that Black will gain the material advantage out of this, but White has a huge initiative and will delay Black's development to benefit out of it! }
8. Qh5
{ White adroitly attacks the f7 square aiming to develop  Bg5 with a tempo and to uncover the light-squared Bishop with Nf6! }
8... Nxh1 9. Bg5
{ And as it was previously mentioned, Black faces troubles to defend f7 square. White threatens to unveil the light-squared Bishop after Nf6! }
9... Qd6
{ If you have wondered what would happen if Black defends the f7 square with  9...Qd7  the answer is simple! White goes for  10.Bf6!  and Black can not defend against Bxg7, with the forthcoming fork Nf6! }
10. Nf6+
{ Even though Black has a full rook-up, they are forced to resign on the 10th move! The withdrawal could be delayed for a few more moves with  10...gxf6  11.Qxf7  Kd8  12.Bxf6  and ends up with a hopeless position for Black due to a hanging Rook on h8 and upcoming Qf8 followed by Be6#! }
*

