{ White continues with the Vienna hybrid set-up and prepares for the possible Na4 aiming to overtake the Bishop pair which would be enticing in an open position such as this one. }
6... a6
{ The main idea of the last move is that Black makes a safe shelter for the dark-squared Bishop and makes the idea of Na4 quite useless. }
7. Nd5
{ Black's dark-squared Bishop controls the dark squares on the White's Kingside so White intends to play against it with an idea to take full control of the center after c3 making the safe path for the light-squared Bishop after Bb3 and Bc2 if necessary.   A very interesting alternative to this move is 7.f5!? where White seizes the space of Black's light-squared Bishop and prepares the field for the pawn storm actions on the Kingside. For example, after  7.f5!?  Na5  8.Bb3  Nxb3  9.axb3  White has a slightly better position with an idea to conclude development with Qe2, Be3, O-O-O, and then they can turn to the Kingside actions after Rg1, followed by g4. }
7... h6
{ This is a prophylactic move by Black who intends to stop f5 followed by Bg5 which would put Black's Knight on f6 into an uncomfortable pin. }
8. f5
{ White occupies the light squares and blocks the Bishop on c8. Black's pieces look cramped on the back rank and they do not have enough space to be actively developed. }
8... Nd4
{ The only way for Black to relieve the pressure is to go for exchanges which would open some space for development moves. However, White chooses with which exchanges they can benefit from! }
9. c3
{ Whilst White improves central control, Black is forced to lose time making several moves with the same pieces only to trade them! Black is late with development, and White looks for a way to punish the development delay! }
9... Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3
{ White used the exchange to develop the Queen and prepares for Bd2, O-O-O, followed by pawn storm on the Kingside with h4-g4! }
10... c6
{ It is obvious that Black can not search for action on the Kingside, so they look for a counter-attack on the Queenside. With 10...c6 Black forces another exchange and aims to open some more space for his pieces after b5.   However after  11.Nxf6  Qxf6  White will take advantage of the bad positioning of Black's Queen! }
11. Nxf6+ Qxf6 12. g4
{ White starts with the activation of the dark-squared Bishop and aims to continue with uncomfortable h4-g5 which would put Black's Queen into trouble. }
12... b5
{ As it was previously mentioned, Black looks for a way to conclude development and needs to fight for the action on the Queenside. After b5, Black will most likely go for solid Bb7 and O-O-O, but that would not stop White to accomplish the advantage on the Kingside! }
13. Bb3 Bb7 14. h4
{ White is ready for g5, followed by f6! You may question yourself why do we delay the castle in this position, but the answer is that White needs to find the fastest way to seize the initiative! White's King is untouchable in the center, and we do not need to hurry to move it away. }
14... O-O-O
{ Black escaped into a safe zone, but can not defend the Kingside! } 15. g5
{ With a huge space control, White does not stop the harassment! Black is forced to play the only moves, and we continue with the pawn storm! }
15... Qe7 16. f6
{ With an unbeatable pawn string, Black is once again forced to go for the only move! White will get a passed pawn as the main asset very soon! }
16... gxf6 17. gxh6
{ With two passed pawns on the h-file and an idea to proceed with Bd2, O-O-O, White puts Black in trouble, trying to defend the doubled pawns on the f-file after Rhf1. Not only that White has more active pieces than Black, and controls a lot of space, henceforth giving White a decisive advantage.   As it could be seen in the game Tomescu, V - Bracaglia, C, Padova 1999,  Black does not have a way to defend. After  17...Kb8  18.Bd2  d5  19.O-O-O  White is ready for Rhf1 and Black can not defend the f6 spot. }
