8. c3
{ Not only that White prevents Black's idea of Nd4, but also prepares to gain space control after b4. }
8... Nh5
{ This is the most resilient answer by Black who intends to open d1-h4 diagonal for possible checks and prevents any h3 moves by White, since that would lead to outposts on the dark squares around the King. }
9. f5
{ White strikes back with well-known move f5, and closes Black's light-squared Bishop, but also opens for the dark-squared Bishop on g5 forcing Black to react. }
9... h6
{ Black blocks all the actions on the Kingside and seems to be active. For that reason, White toggles the play on the Queenside! }
10. b4
{ White gains space with a tempo move and forces Black to multiply play with the same piece which would lead afterward to exchange of dark squares Bishops. }
10... Ba7 11. Be3
{ Not only that White proved the marginalization of Black's Bishops, but Black is forced to accept that an exchange of the dark squares Bishops will be done and another piece will be stuck to the a7 square soon. It seems that Black has no time for normal development, while White improves the position all the time. }
11... Ne7
{ Black's only possibility is to save the light-squared Bishop is to exchange the centralized Knight from d5. However, that does not stop White to continue with normal development, and the space control is in White's possession. }
12. Bxa7 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Rxa7 14. O-O
{ After all the exchanges, White concludes the development, whilst Black's King is still in the center. Of course, one should not forget that the Rook on a7 needs time to get back into the game, and that White is ready for reaction in the center! }
14... Nf4
{ This is Black's only chance to gets activated. He aims to remove the light-squared Bishop and to simplify the position. Of course, White does not want to allow that and intends to keep the tension in the center. }
15. Bb3 h5
{ Black searches for activity on the Kingside, but White's King is safe with many pieces surrounding it. As it is known, that sometimes the best defense is to counter-attack your opponent forcing him to react, so White strikes back with the center reaction! }
16. d4
{ White maintains the space control and puts pressure on  e5  square with a simple idea of  16...--  17.dxe5  dxe5  18.Qxd8  Kxd8  19.Nxe5  which would lead to a position with a clear pawn up and d7 weakness will be undefended. }
16... Qe7 17. Qd2
{ White includes the last piece into the game and on the next move will have all of the pieces activated after 18.Rae1. It is clear that Black can not castle safely anymore, and that Black's King is convicted to stay in the center. }
17... h4 18. Rae1
{ White simply ignores Black's actions on the Kingside, since White's King is pretty safe there.   There is no fear from  18...h3  which will be easily blocked after  19.g3  Ng2  and White is better after  20.Rd1  since Black can not use the Knight anymore. }
18... Bxf3 19. Rxf3 Qg5 20. Rd1
{ And as it could be seen in the game between Fedorov, A @@StartBracket@@2659@@EndBracket@@-Fyllingen, R @@StartBracket@@2410@@EndBracket@@ Aars 1999 White is clearly better with active pieces, full space control, and the threat of opening d-file after de5, while Black still needs to resolve development problems mainly due to inactive Ra7 and the King being exposed in the center. }
