7... exf4
{ Black simply wants to get rid of the pressure in the center and not to think about the e5 pawn anymore. However, this allows White to overtake full center control and to block Black's dark-squared Bishop! }
8. d4
{ As it was previously mentioned, White uses the opportunity to gain full central control and forces Black to react with the dark squared Bishop. }
8... Ba7
{ This is the most common move by Black who escapes into safety. Of course, it should be noticed that White's central e4 pawn hangs now, but as we could see in this course, White prefers to take care of development than to care about the material! }
9. c3
{ With this move, White not only improves the center control, but kills Black's dark-squared Bishop which does not have any space to play on. We do not care now about the e4 pawn, but we aim to castle as soon as possible, and material can be easily retreated due to hanging f4 pawn. }
9... Nxe4 10. O-O
{ White follows up with fast development and threatens to continue with a hunt on the exposed Black's Knight on e4. A direct threat would be Re1, but also Qc2 and of course, White will get the pawn back after Bf4 very soon. }
10... O-O 11. Qc2
{ Not only that White simply attacks the Knight, but has an idea to toggle the Bishop on dangerous b1-h7 diagonal after Bd3. Hanging f4 pawn can not escape from the attack, so white does not need to hurry to take it. However, Bf4, followed by Rae1 will come soon and gives to White a nice play. }
11... Bf5 12. Bd3
{ White conquers the b1-h7 diagonal and pins Black's Knight and Bishop. Black needs to be dedicated to defense for a moment. }
12... Re8 13. Bxf4
{ Whilst White is ready to get the last piece into the game with 14.Rae1 Black still needs to think about the pin and exposed Knight on e4. }
13... Bg6 14. Rae1
{ White is at least slightly better in this position, despite the pawn down, due to all pieces completely activated and positioned on the most active squares. One should not forget that Black's dark-squared Bishop is blocked for any action and does not have a spot to move on. Additionally Black has issues with the further development of Queen and another Rook.   The only move which could save Black here would be  14...Ne7  but White has a nice strike with  15.Nxc7!  Qxc7  16.Bxe4  Nd5  17.Bxg6  hxg6  18.Bg5  and Black has two serious pawn weaknesses:  d6  isolated pawn and doubled pawns on g-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Bishop's Opening 2...Nc6: Vienna Hybrid Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2...Nc6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.d3 Bc5 #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Nf6
{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... Bc5
{ This is one of the main and most critical lines of the Bishop's opening. According to my playing experience, I faced this move frequently, and it seems that Black mostly chose 4...Bc5 with the idea to compromise White's King after Ng4. However, the positions reached afterward are maybe not so desirable according to the engines'. Still, I would say that they are a bit dangerous, and offer practical and interesting play with many tactical possibilities and attacking ideas. }
5. f4
{ White slides into a very aggressive Vienna Hybrid variation aiming to open the position and to develop an attack on the Kingside. If you have wondered where the White King is going to escape since it is obvious that O-O is not possible due to Bc5 which controls g1 square, of course, the answer is O-O-O! }
5... d6
{ It might look that this is just a solid move by Black, but actually White reaches a very interesting position to play afterward. Black aims to conquer the g4 spot very soon, going with the Bishop or the Knight over there. }
6. Nf3
{ White continues with the Vienna hybrid set-up and prepares for the possible Na4 aiming to overtake the Bishop pair which would be enticing in an open position such as this one. }
6... a6
{ The main idea of the last move is that Black makes a safe shelter for the dark-squared Bishop and makes the idea of Na4 quite useless. }
7. Nd5
{ Black's dark-squared Bishop controls the dark squares on the White's Kingside so White intends to play against it with an idea to take full control of the center after c3 making the safe path for the light-squared Bishop after Bb3 and Bc2 if necessary.   A very interesting alternative to this move is 7.f5!? where White seizes the space of Black's light-squared Bishop and prepares the field for the pawn storm actions on the Kingside. For example, after  7.f5!?  Na5  8.Bb3  Nxb3  9.axb3  White has a slightly better position with an idea to conclude development with Qe2, Be3, O-O-O, and then they can turn to the Kingside actions after Rg1, followed by g4. }
7... exf4
{ Black simply wants to get rid of the pressure in the center and not to think about the e5 pawn anymore. However, this allows White to overtake full center control and to block Black's dark-squared Bishop! }
8. d4
{ As it was previously mentioned, White uses the opportunity to gain full central control and forces Black to react with the dark squared Bishop. }
8... Nxd4
{ Although 8...Nxd4?! is considered as a suspicious move, it can be very uncomfortable for White if you don't know how to answer it! Black aims to ruin White's center and to open the position, while the White's King is not in a safe zone. }
9. Nxd4
{ Of course, we accept the sacrifice and we are ready to castle. That means that Black needs to hurry to take action to try to benefit from the sacrifice. }
9... Nxd5
{ With this exchange, Black keeps the White's King in the center and opens space for the Queen to come on h4 with a check. However, it is questionable if the whole piece is worth castle wrecking. }
10. Bxd5 Qh4+
{ White is forced to play with a King and it is clear that there is no castling anymore. However, White has the material advantage, and Black needs to fight harshly to find compensation.   I would mention that the same position which we will consider along this line can be reached after  10...c6  11.Bb3  Qh4  12.Kf1  d5  . }
11. Kf1
{ White has a piece up and simple idea to support an exposed Knight on d4 with c3, followed by Qe1, and the trade offer. Certainly, if White reaches an endgame without Queens on the board, the position would be easy to win. }
11... c6
{ Due to a previously mentioned idea of c3, followed by Qe1, Black needs to react in the center and to try to exploit the White's King as soon as possible. }
12. Bb3
{ White has nice activity and promising initiative in the game So, W - Sales, J PHI-ch 2004, I decided to analyze it a bit more and improve on Black's play but looks like after all, White has better chances! }
12... d5
{ Although a move such as  12...Bg4  looks logical and uncomfortable, White would have a much better position after  13.Qd2  with the same idea of c3 and Qf2- Queen trade! }
13. c3
{ It is a fact that White has no time to have fun with pawns, but needs to support the King very soon. For that reason, the idea of c3-Qe1 is followed straightly! We need to be satisfied with a piece for three pawns. }
13... dxe4 14. Qe1 Qxe1+ 15. Kxe1
{ White's King in the center becomes an asset in the endgame and White has a direct threat to overtake the pawn on f4. The attack on this pawn will be improved after Ne2, and it is questionable if Black can defend it. Although three pawns for a piece are considered to be good compensation, Black faces problems to defend one of the pawns, and in practice, such endgames with a slight advantage of White are incredibly hard to hold. }
*

