8. d4
{ As it was previously mentioned, White uses the opportunity to gain full central control and forces Black to react with the dark squared Bishop. }
8... Nxd5
{ This move looks like the most natural follow-up by Black who trades pieces to create space for further development and activation. }
9. Bxd5
{ White keeps the full central control and seizes space for Black's dark-squared Bishop. White is ready to continue with development, and one should not forget that the f4 pawn is hanging, so White will get the material back very soon. }
9... Bb6 10. Bxf4
{ With centralized pieces and a complete center, White is ready to complete development with O-O, Qd2, Rae1. It is clear that Black has no concrete actions here and that White will have at least a slight advantage thanks to better space control. }
10... Be6
{ Black intends to exchange light-squared Bishops and to open f-file which would make the Bishop on f4 exposed to attacks. For that reason, White does not force the exchange and waits for Black to take the first step. }
11. O-O O-O 12. Kh1
{ White plays a clever prophylactic move and escapes from the pin from the dark-squared Bishop. Of course, White did not change from the original plan of Qd2, followed by Rae1. }
12... h6 13. Qd2
{ With a nice idea of the familiar Bh6 sacrifice and normal development continuation of Rae1, White is at least slightly better. One should not forget the importance of a good center, and that Black's dark-squared Bishop is marginalized with no actions on the Queenside as it could be seen in the game Wei, Y-Vallejo Pons, F, Leon 2014. }
