7... Nxd5
{ With this 7...Nxd5 move Black prevents all of the possible problems which might appear if White manages to get Bg5 in. However, with this move, White's light-squared Bishop gets centralized and active. }
8. Bxd5
{ It is the fact that White is not ready for castling yet, due to control of dark squares by Black, but White keeps the same idea of c3, followed by d4, which would not only block the Bishop but will give the full center control to White. }
8... Bg4
{ Black keeps active play with a direct threat of Nd4. Anyway, that does not stop White to continue with the previously mentioned idea of c3 and possible d4 afterward. }
9. c3
{ White prevents the threat of Nd4 and continues with the same follow-up. It must be noted that White does not want to rush with the d4 move, but now has another idea to proceed with f5 to weaken Black's light-squared Bishop and to force a trade. }
9... Bxf3
{ Black is familiar with the f5 move in such a position and prevents any possible problems with the light-squared Bishop with this immediate trade.   In the case of natural  9...O-O  both moves  10.h3  and even  10.f5!?  gives White better chances mainly due to a powerful Bishop on  d5  in the center! }
10. Qxf3
{ It is obvious that White is not interested in the d4 approach, but switches the action on the Kingside aiming to create a pawn storm with f5, followed by h4 and g4. Of course, White has an easy solution for the King which could be brought to safety after Bd2 and O-O-O. }
10... O-O 11. Qg3
{ As it was mentioned a few times throughout the course, sometimes the threat is better than the execution. White exposes Black's King to a pin and still has the same idea of f5, followed by a possible uncomfortable pin of Bh6. }
11... Ne7 12. Bb3
{ With a simple step back White keeps the Bishop pair as the main asset in the position. Threatening to open things up, with Black's exposed e5 pawn, White is ready to create action on the Kingside. }
12... exf4 13. Bxf4
{ With the Bishop pair eyeing Black's Queen and activated Queen on g3, Black can not be comfortable playing such a position. Nevertheless, White has easy play after O-O-O and possible d4, which would lead to full center control and total domination. }
13... a5
{ Black keeps searching for a way to get activated and aims to move the light-squared Bishop away from the dangerous a2-g8 diagonal. }
14. d4
{ White is ready to swing the Bishop on the other active diagonal b1-h7, still eyeing the Kingside, and one should not forget White's dominance in the center. }
14... a4 15. Bc2 Bb6 16. O-O
{ After Black's action on the Queenside with a4 which could be possibly followed with a3, White does not take any risk to compromise the long-term advantage of the Bishop pair and keeps the King safe on the Kingside. With 16.O-O, White also activates the Rook and aims to bring another one in the game soon. }
16... Ng6 17. Be3
{ And once again with a simple step back, White keeps the Bishop pair on the board, with the idea to double the Rooks on the f-file with pressure on the f7 weakened square. With full central control, active pieces, and a Bishop pair, White is clearly better. The forthcoming plan of White was shown in a game between Alagna, L-Epiney, F IECG email 2004. }
