8... Qe7
{ This is a very interesting move by Black who keeps the same threat of Bg4 and Nd4, but also prepares for possible Bd7 and O-O-O. Mainly, with 8...Qe7 Black tries to escape from the pressure on the Kingside, and aims to put the King in a safe zone on the Queenside. }
9. c3
{ Once again White closes the path for counterattack by Black and prepares to seize up light squares control with f5. At the same time, after f5, the dark-squared Bishop will get an open diagonal to pounce on! }
9... Bd7
{ This is the most resilient move by Black who just wants to castle on the Queenside.  .   Instead,  9...Bg4?!  would be considered as a suspicious move, due to  10.f5!  and Black's light-squared Bishop would be problematic. After  10...f6  11.Qa4!  White is clearly better with undefendable pressure on Nc6 and indirectly attacked pawn on e5. }
10. f5
{ Not only that White improves the position of the light-squared Bishop on d5, but also makes Black's Bishop on d7 look miserable. White has new opportunities to weaken the f7 square after a possible Ng5, so Black needs to be careful here. }
10... O-O-O
{ Black follows up with the idea to put the King in safety on the Queenside.   However, Black could also choose to play  10...g6?!  11.Ng5!  White is clearly better here due to the huge burden on the f7 square.   White gains a clearly better position also after  10...f6?!  11.b4  Ba7  12.a4  with full space control and a plan of Qe2, followed by Be3 and castle. }
11. b4
{ It is clear that White does not search for action on the Kingside anymore, but aims to threaten Black's King on the Queenside. 11.b4 comes with a tempo and will be followed by a4 and the idea of b5 which would put Black into an uncomfortable position to search for good squares to move his pieces away. On the other hand, you should not have fears about the King in the center, because White's King is safe there, and White does not need to hurry with castling. }
11... Bb6 12. a4
{ White keeps pressuring the Queenside and Black needs to figure out whether the threat is a5 or b5. I would always recommend keeping the plan of the very dangerous 13.b5! in mind here which would open the light square Bishop to attack b7 square. }
12... Nb8
{ Black prevents b5 which would come with a tempo and aims to exchange the light squares Bishops after Bc6. That would reveal Black from the pressure, but White has time to answer on this one! }
13. b5
{ We do not care about the pawn, but only how to open the Queenside! White has a deadly threat of a5, followed by bxa6 and Qb3 so Black needs to react here! }
13... axb5
{ This is practically the only move for Black because after  13...a5  14.Nd2  White is clearly better with the idea of Nc4 and Black will not be able to defend dark squares. }
14. axb5
{ White reached a goal to open Black's King and has full control of a-file. One should not forget that Bishop on d5 dominates the position and that f7 square is still exposed to attack after possible Ng5. Black would be crisscrossed between defending the Queenside and the Kingside! }
14... Bxb5 15. Ng5
{ White uses the opportunity to gain activity while Black is crowded on the back rank. The f7 pawn will be undefendable after the forthcoming Qb3 with a double attack on the Bishop on b5 and f7! }
15... Rhf8 16. Qb3
{ White does not care about the d3 pawn but searches for a path to conquer the Black's side after Ra8 and Nf7! Black can not do a lot to take the counter-play and practically waits for White's actions! }
16... Bxd3 17. Ra8
{ As it could be seen in the game Palmiero, O-Fragola, H ICCF email 2018 White is clearly better with a simple plan of Nf7, followed by Bg5! Black is locked down on the back rank and has no possibility to unchain from pins! }
