[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Bishop's Opening 2...Nc6: Vienna Hybrid Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2...Nc6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.d3 Bc5 #18"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Nf6
{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... Bc5
{ This is one of the main and most critical lines of the Bishop's opening. According to my playing experience, I faced this move frequently, and it seems that Black mostly chose 4...Bc5 with the idea to compromise White's King after Ng4. However, the positions reached afterward are maybe not so desirable according to the engines'. Still, I would say that they are a bit dangerous, and offer practical and interesting play with many tactical possibilities and attacking ideas. }
5. f4
{ White slides into a very aggressive Vienna Hybrid variation aiming to open the position and to develop an attack on the Kingside. If you have wondered where the White King is going to escape since it is obvious that O-O is not possible due to Bc5 which controls g1 square, of course, the answer is O-O-O! }
5... d6
{ It might look that this is just a solid move by Black, but actually White reaches a very interesting position to play afterward. Black aims to conquer the g4 spot very soon, going with the Bishop or the Knight over there. }
6. Nf3
{ White continues with the Vienna hybrid set-up and prepares for the possible Na4 aiming to overtake the Bishop pair which would be enticing in an open position such as this one. }
6... a6
{ The main idea of the last move is that Black makes a safe shelter for the dark-squared Bishop and makes the idea of Na4 quite useless. }
7. Nd5
{ Black's dark-squared Bishop controls the dark squares on the White's Kingside so White intends to play against it with an idea to take full control of the center after c3 making the safe path for the light-squared Bishop after Bb3 and Bc2 if necessary.   A very interesting alternative to this move is 7.f5!? where White seizes the space of Black's light-squared Bishop and prepares the field for the pawn storm actions on the Kingside. For example, after  7.f5!?  Na5  8.Bb3  Nxb3  9.axb3  White has a slightly better position with an idea to conclude development with Qe2, Be3, O-O-O, and then they can turn to the Kingside actions after Rg1, followed by g4. }
7... Nxd5
{ With this 7...Nxd5 move Black prevents all of the possible problems which might appear if White manages to get Bg5 in. However, with this move, White's light-squared Bishop gets centralized and active. }
8. Bxd5
{ It is the fact that White is not ready for castling yet, due to control of dark squares by Black, but White keeps the same idea of c3, followed by d4, which would not only block the Bishop but will give the full center control to White. }
8... Be6
{ If Black tries to exchange the light-squared Bishop, White reaches a nice position with a slight positional advantage after this exchange. }
9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. fxe5
{ Black is forced to take the pawn and to double the pawns on the e-file. }
10... dxe5 11. c3
{ With a slight advantage, White stops further trades with Nd4 and prepares for development after Qe2. Doubled pawns on the e-file are targets now, and White can attack them easily with Ng5. With a long-term advantage and a better pawn structure, White has a nice and easy position to play. }
