{ It is the fact that White is not ready for castling yet, due to control of dark squares by Black, but White keeps the same idea of c3, followed by d4, which would not only block the Bishop but will give the full center control to White. }
8... O-O
{ If Black decides to continue with natural development, White goes back to the idea of limiting the scope of Black's pieces! }
9. f5
{ It is clear that Black has issues to develop the light-squared Bishop and that the Queen will have no good square to escape after Bg5! }
9... Ne7
{ Black tries to block the d8-h4 diagonal and the forthcoming Bg5, but this move does not stop White to continue developing actively.   Instead of this move,  9...Nd4?!  was played in a game Hresc, V-Wiechert, H Kirchheim 1990,  and White got a clearly better position after  10.Nxd4  Bxd4  10.Qh5  c6  12.Bb3  d5  13.c3  with an attack on the Kingside after Rf1 and f6!   I would like to mention as well that White does not need to worry about  9...h6  because after  10.c3  White has a clear path to the Kingside after Bb3, g4, g5, and Rf1. }
10. Bg5
{ Not only that White puts a pin on the Knight on e7, but also clears a space for development on the Queenside. White is ready to continue with Qd2 and O-O-O, and well-known pawn storm on the Kingside with g4, he, and g5! }
10... h6 11. Bxe7
{ This is one of the crucial moves in this constellation of pieces. Although, it makes full sense to use this tempo to remove the best defender in chess around the King - the Knight! }
11... Qxe7 12. a3
{ White concentrates all of the efforts to keep the light-squared killer which pressures Black's King. With a clever prophylactic move, White creates a shelter for the Bishop! }
12... c6 13. Ba2
{ The light-squared Bishop is now untouchable and White is ready to go on with Qd2 and O-O-O! }
13... Re8 14. Qd2
{ 13...Re8 might look illogical, but in fact,  Black Doesn't have many options to continue development and just waits for White to play. As it was previously mentioned, White has easy play after O-O-O, g4, followed by g5! }
14... b5 15. O-O-O Rb8 16. g4
{ As it could be seen in a game Urban, M -Narciso, M ICCF email 2017 White has, by now, a pretty traditional attack on the Kingside after g5 and h4, aiming to open space around Black's King. Meanwhile, Black searches for a way to create a counterattack on the Queenside, but White's King is safe and Black simply does not have active pieces to join the attack. }
