{ This move is very tempting and is a very common answer by lower-rated players. Black has a simple idea to ruin White's castle after Nf2 or Bf2 and the position might look uncomfortable, but actually, with a correct answer, White has great play here! }
7. Ng5
{ White has to react in the same fashion! There is no time for White to be stressed about Nf2 or Bf2! We just go forward with pressure on the f7 square! There are two move crucial ideas: f5! @@StartBracket@@to cancel out the connection between Bc8 and Ng4@@EndBracket@@ and in the case of any  7...Nf2  8.Qh5  with an even stronger attack on the f7 square! }
7... Bf2+
{ Black goes for the idea to ruin White's castling, but as I previously mentioned, White should not have any fears after this move! }
8. Kf1
{ In fact, Black needs to think about how to protect both Knight on g4 and Bishop on f2 due to a threat of 9.h3! At the same time, the pawn on f7 still hangs! }
8... exf4
{ Black temporarily defends against h3, with a threat to proceed with Ne3. Of course, one should not forget that White's Knight on g5 is hanging now, so White needs to take quick action! }
9. Bxf7+
{ White has the same motives as Ne6 which would leave Black's Knight on g4 undefended! }
9... Kf8 10. Ne6+ Bxe6 11. Bxe6
{ White dominates the light squares after these exchanges and has a very important tempo that allows us to gain control over the play! }
11... Ne3+ 12. Bxe3 Bxe3 13. Qh5
{ The position looks symmetrical since both sides have Kings in the center and active Bishops. However, as it was mentioned, White has an important tempo and dictates the game. With the direct threats of Qf7# and Nd5, Black needs to defend and does not have time to be operative. }
13... Ne5
{ Black keeps the Queen undeveloped aiming to continue with c6 which would stop possible Nd5 and would allow Black to develop and support the King with Qf6.   Instead, Black could go for  13...Qf6  14.Bb3  Ne7  15.Ke2  and White is clearly better with a plan to open f-file with g3 and Raf1! }
14. Nd5
{ White finally puts pressure on the dark-squared Bishop and Black cannot defend both e3 and f5 squares. The idea is to open f-file and conquer it after Ke2 and Rae1! }
14... c6 15. Nxe3 Qf6
{ Black hangs on the last straw of salvation and threatens to create a discovered check with fxe3, at the same time attacking the light-squared Bishop. Having this in mind, White moves the King to safety and proceeds with the previously mentioned idea of Ke2 and Raf1!   Of course, if  15...fxe3  was played instead, White would just continue with  16.Ke2  with a clear advantage and the threat of Raf1! }
16. Ke2
{ White's King is safe since White controls all of the light squares, and Rf1 is coming! }
16... Qxe6 17. Rhf1
{ In the game between Nepomniachtchi, I-Anand, V chess24.com INT 2020 White did not give any chance to Black after 17. Rhf1, keeping the a2 pawn safe. White is winning since Black can not defend the f4 pawn anymore and after the forthcoming Rf4, White will double the Rooks on the f-file, with total domination. }
