{ Black just wants to clear the path for the Queen which could possibly be uncomfortable after Qh4. }
8. f5
{ You should not fall for the trick of playing  8.Nxf7?  instead, which would directly lead to a losing position after  8...Qh4  9.g3  Qh3!  and White can not defend due to a threat of Qg2!  With 8.f5! instead, White keeps the pressure on the f7 spot, and the Knight on g4 is now no longer protected! }
8... hxg5
{ This is practically the only move which gives hope to Black, although the position can hardly be saved due to the dominant White pieces and the many weaknesses on the Black side, such as g5 pawn, and weakened light squares around the King which does not have a safe spot anymore. }
9. Qxg4
{ White immediately threatens to take the long-term advantage with a pawn up after Bg5. Black is forced to defend the pawn, and that would lead him into trouble as it will be shown! }
9... f6
{ Of course, if Black does not defend the pawn and plays for example  9...Rh4  White is clearly better after  10.Qxg5  , entering an endgame with better pieces and a clear pawn up. }
10. h4
{ White simply keeps the pressure on the newest g5 weakness and threatens to continue with Rh3! Black will not be able to keep the pawn anymore so they need to search for a counter-attack on the Queenside. }
10... Nd4 11. Rh3
{ We simply do not care about the Queenside! Black's King is undefendable in the center due to the light-squared killer which controls the a2-g8 diagonal. With ideas to open h-file and swing the Queen over there, White is clearly better even with a Rook down!     Of course, White could play a safer move such as  11.Bb3  which was played in a game Gromov, S-Semenov, V ICCF email 2015,  and a better position with a pawn up, but you can win the game a lot faster with 11.Rh3! }
11... Nxc2+ 12. Kd1 Nxa1 13. hxg5
{ And Black can not hold the pressure on the weakened light-squares. The h-file will be conquered by White, and Black will not be able to defend the checks leading to mate. }
13... Rxh3
{ Black is forced to pass the h-file to White, since after  13...Rf8  a bitter end awaits Black after  14.gxf6  Qxf6  15.Nd5!  and a beautiful tactical blow after  15...Qf7  16.Nxc7!  Qxc7  17.Qg6  followed by Bg5! }
14. Qxh3
{ And White is winning with full control over the Kingside, threatening to continue with Qh8 or Qh7, followed by Nd5. Black can not defend the pawns and at the same time can not use the material advantage, since all of the pieces are locked to the back rank without any possibility to activate them. }
