{ Although Black gets rid of the annoying Bishop on g5, this is a suspicious move. Black will be forced to place the Queen on f6 after a trade, and the very same Queen will be vulnerable for threats of g4 followed by h4 and g5! }
9. Bxf6
{ Even though keeping the pin with  9.Bh4  would look absolutely normal, our text move gives White huge initiative, and an important tempo to take action on the Kingside with g4, h4, and g5! }
9... Qxf6 10. a3
{ This is a very important intermediary move for White. Not only that White wants to keep the light-squared Bishop on the board after Ba2, but also prevents Bb4! }
10... Nxc4
{ Of course, if Black chose to play any other move, for example,  10...c6  11.Ba2  is coming, and White keeps the light-squared Bishop on the board, aiming to proceed with an attack on the Kingside, after g4, h4, and g5! }
11. dxc4 c6 12. g4
{ White is ready for a tremendous attack! Black's Bishop on c8 will be out of play for a long time and White will simply continue with development and opening the Kingside with Qd2, h4, and g5. Of course, White's King will be safe after O-O-O, and the other Rook will be included in the game afterward! }
