{ As it was already mentioned, White should not be worried about double pawns on c-file because Black's Bishop from c8 has no square to move and compromise those pawns. White is ready to continue with Qd2, g4, h4, and O-O-O, with huge pressure on the Black's King. }
10... h6 11. Bxf6
{ I find this move as an improvement over the  11.Bh4  gives a slightly better position for White and was seen in the game between Nun, J-Lehner, O Oberwart 1992. With 11.Bfx6! White forces Black to expose the Queen to attack after g4, h4, and g5! }
11... Qxf6 12. g4
{ And White continues with a great attack on Black's King after the forthcoming Qd2, h4, and g5! As it was mentioned, Black's Queen will be exposed to attack, and Black will not be able to stop the opening of g or h-file around the King. }
