2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Nf6
{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... Bc5
{ This is one of the main and most critical lines of the Bishop's opening. According to my playing experience, I faced this move frequently, and it seems that Black mostly chose 4...Bc5 with the idea to compromise White's King after Ng4. However, the positions reached afterward are maybe not so desirable according to the engines'. Still, I would say that they are a bit dangerous, and offer practical and interesting play with many tactical possibilities and attacking ideas. }
5. f4
{ White slides into a very aggressive Vienna Hybrid variation aiming to open the position and to develop an attack on the Kingside. If you have wondered where the White King is going to escape since it is obvious that O-O is not possible due to Bc5 which controls g1 square, of course, the answer is O-O-O! }
5... d6
{ It might look that this is just a solid move by Black, but actually White reaches a very interesting position to play afterward. Black aims to conquer the g4 spot very soon, going with the Bishop or the Knight over there. }
6. Nf3
{ White continues with the Vienna hybrid set-up and prepares for the possible Na4 aiming to overtake the Bishop pair which would be enticing in an open position such as this one. }
6... Be6
{ This solid move I did not want to cover in the course, but since in online practice lately, I have faced it quite a few times and found it pretty solid for Black, it definitely deserves its place and has to be covered. I have tried both  7.Bb5  and  7.Bxe6  , but it looks like that the first one gives White richer chances! }
7. Bb5
{ White pins the Knight on c6 and consequently threatens pawn on e5. Although, as my practice has shown, we are not interested that much in the pawn on e5 as in breaking the pawn structure after  8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.fxe5  dxe5  , in which case Black has lots of difficulties to continue and defend a position with a broken pawn structure and White has a small but long-lasting advantage! }
7... Bd7
{ This seemingly more logical move @@StartBracket@@since it avoids the break of the pawn structure as seen in line 7...a6@@EndBracket@@, turned out to be worse in the practice. Although, in order to find out the best idea in this position, I had to dig deep into the past in the games of Spassky from the '60s and Spielmann from the '30s of the last century! Why is that so bad, you might wonder, well because it leaves the Bishop on c5 hanging with the wind! }
8. Na4
{ There we go! Black cannot control an a7-g1 diagonal anymore @@StartBracket@@Bc5 is about to fall@@EndBracket@@ and looks like Black's center is about to crack! }
8... Nd4
{ This is quite an active attempt by Black to get some counterplay but White solves this problem thanks to a forced sequence of moves after 9.Nxc5! }
9. Nxc5
{ Just in time! One of the crucial pieces in Black's position - the Bishop on c5 has just fallen and White is about to reap the benefits of that soon. White can afterward easily make castle short, e5 pawn is about to be taken and Black is in serious trouble. }
9... dxc5
{ This seems like the only move since after  9...Bxb5?!  10.Nxb7!  Qb8  11.fxe5!  White temporarily takes a pawn, but more importantly after  11...dxe5  takes the important  c5  square for the Knight and Black is in a bad place positionally. }
10. Bc4
{ And after the last move White had great game and went on to win in the game Spielmann,R - Selezniev,A Merano 1924. White has the Bishop pair advantage, threatens fxe5, as well as Bc4 becomes a strong weapon eyeing the weakness on f7 and allowing White a big advantage due to the Bishop pair! }
