{ This is one of the main and most critical lines of the Bishop's opening. According to my playing experience, I faced this move frequently, and it seems that Black mostly chose 4...Bc5 with the idea to compromise White's King after Ng4. However, the positions reached afterward are maybe not so desirable according to the engines'. Still, I would say that they are a bit dangerous, and offer practical and interesting play with many tactical possibilities and attacking ideas. }
5. f4
{ White slides into a very aggressive Vienna Hybrid variation aiming to open the position and to develop an attack on the Kingside. If you have wondered where the White King is going to escape since it is obvious that O-O is not possible due to Bc5 which controls g1 square, of course, the answer is O-O-O! }
5... d6
{ It might look that this is just a solid move by Black, but actually White reaches a very interesting position to play afterward. Black aims to conquer the g4 spot very soon, going with the Bishop or the Knight over there. }
6. Nf3
{ White continues with the Vienna hybrid set-up and prepares for the possible Na4 aiming to overtake the Bishop pair which would be enticing in an open position such as this one. }
6... Bg4
{ According to my experience in the Bishops opening, Black's favorite line is this one with 6...Bg4. Black aims to play Nd4 with pressure on the Knight on f3, which would put White into an uncomfortable position.   White can choose here between two possibilities: a solid approach with slight advantage or wild play with crazy evaluations! Both will be considered deeply within the course. }
7. h3
{ This is a very interesting move for White and it was played by many chess legends, such as Kasparov, Fischer, Rubinstein... I would recommend this approach to all the players who enjoy creative positions with plenty of desirable attacking ideas, tricks, and tactical opportunities! Although the engines would give a small advantage in different variations for Black, in practice it was shown that 7.h3!? is very unpleasant for Black, especially during the short time control games @@StartBracket@@it is my favorite one in Blitz!@@EndBracket@@ }
7... Bxf3
{ This is the most logical follow-up by Black who removes the defender of the d4 spot and prepares for Nd4.   7...Bd7?!  instead would be suspicious due to  8.Na4!  which immediately provides a clear advantage for White who gains a Bishop pair. White can even proceed with Kasparov's idea of  8.f5!?  followed by Bg5, Nd5, and a harsh attack on the Kingside after g4! }
8. Qxf3
{ White is not worried about Nd4 possibility and swings all the activities on the weakened Kingside! }
8... Nd4 9. Qg3
{ The whole idea of White's plan is to take advantage out of Black's late development and weakened Kingside. Possible Qg7 would come with a double attack on the Rook on h8 and f7 pawn, and with 9.Qg3! White ignores the Nc2 threat! }
9... Nxc2+
{ This might look like the most dangerous line for White, since the Rook on a1 hangs. However, after moving the King away from the check White starts action on the Kingside! }
10. Kd1 Nh5
{ Black chooses to play an important intermediary move to defend the g7 pawn at the same time attacking White's Queen. It is a fact that White will play a position down material but the point is that Black can not use this advantage due to the inactive and undeveloped pieces! }
11. Qf3
{ Both Black's Knights are under attack now and Black has no more intermediary moves to play. It is clear that after Black takes the Rook on a1, the Knight will not have a place to escape from the corner, and on the other hand, after White's Qh5 the pawn on f7 will be hanging. }
11... Nxa1 12. Qxh5
{ It is obvious that White has a very interesting position to play and it can be already now said that White's compensation for an exchange is huge! With a direct threat of Qf7 and a plan of Rf1 and possible fxe5, White will have a deadly attack on Black's King. Meanwhile, Black's Knight on a1 is trapped and can not be activated, and Black will need to focus on defense instead of material advantage! }
12... O-O 13. f5
{ White seizes space for Black's pieces and continues with an attack aiming to play Rf1 with threats of Nd5 and f6, and of course, the Rook can easily swing to g-file after Rf3 and Rg3. Even though White's King is in the center, you should not have concerns about it, because Black has no possibility to reach any activity and to compromise King's position! }
13... c6
{ Black's only opportunity to search for a counterattack is to start to push pawns on the Queenside. With c6, Black prepares for b5 which would solve the problem of the trapped Knight on a1. If Black manages to go for b5 and White moves the Bishop away on the only available square-b3, Black would be good after Nb3. However, White is on the move! }
14. Rf1
{ With a very direct threat of f6, White aims to conquer the dark squares on the Kingside, because Black will not be able to defend the g7 square. In that manner, with this clever development move, White stopped Black's idea of b5 and starts proving that White's play is clearly better here! }
14... Kh8
{ Black's retreat from the possible pin on g-file leads to disasters now! If someone wondered what would happen if Black chooses to conclude the previous idea of b5, here is an answer:   14...b5  White dives into Black's Kingside with  15.f6!  and Black is forced to take it with  15...gxf6  due to a threat of Qg5 and Qg7#, after  16.Bxb5  cxb5  17.Nd5  White is easily winning with the forthcoming Nf6 and Black's pawn on h7 will be undefendable! }
15. Bxf7
{ And White has a decisive advantage and a winning position with the idea of Bg6. One should not forget that if Black defends the h7 pawn with h6 there is a beautiful tactical possibility thanks to the dark-squared Bishop and Black can not defend after Bxh6! }
