14... Qd7
{ Black gives the Knight on f6 away and hopes to resolve all of the problems with the King after the forthcoming O-O-O having an exchange as the material advantage. }
15. Bxf6
{ White takes on the offer and grabs the material and has a plan to gain an even bigger material advantage after taking the Knight on a1 which can not escape after a simple attacking move! }
15... O-O-O
{ White should not worry about the possibility of  15...Bxf6?!  because White gains a clearly better position after  16.Qxf6  and Black can not defend the threat of Nd5 or the idea of Kd2 when the Knight on a1 would not have space to escape from an attack. }
16. Bxe5
{ Of course, White does not need to hurry to take the trapped Knight on a1, because Black can not do anything about it! }
16... c6
{ Black tries to use the attack on the d3 pawn and prepares b5. This might look dangerous at the moment but with a simple move, White covers everything and enjoys a winning position!   If instead of 16...c6 Black went for  16...Qc6  threatening to use the pin on White's King, after a very important intermediary check of  17.Qg4  Kb8  White is winning with a simple  18.Kc1  putting King into safety and threatening to proceed with Kb1 and Ka1 with great control of the center provided by the Bishop pair! }
17. Rf3
{ Thanks to this amazing move 17.Rf3! Black is practically in a stalemate without a good move to play! With a trapped Knight on a1 and hanging f7 pawn, Black has no hopes for b5 anymore, since the Rook on f3 controls d3 square and still controls the f-line. It is questionable how Black can proceed here and meanwhile White has a completely winning position with a simple plan of Bf7 and Kc1.   I would emphasize that instead of 17.Rf3! the move of  17.Qg4!?  is very interesting from a practical point of view and after  17...Qxg4  18.hxg4  b5  White is clearly better after  19.Nxb5!  cxb5  20.Bxb5  , since Black will lose a Knight on a2 and White, will keep Bishop and three pawns for a single Rook, and that is besides having the Bishop pair on the board! }
