9... Qe7
{ Black tries to establish control of the center before taking the pawn on c2. For that reason, after the opening of the f-file for the Rook, White will not allow Nxc2! At the same time, the last move gives Black wide options of both short and long castles, but of course Black only dreams of long castling, otherwise, the Kingside attack by White would be unstoppable! }
10. fxe5 dxe5 11. Kd1
{ Even though the King in the center without possibility to castle might look bad, the fact it is that White's King is safe on d1 and on the other hand, Black has issues with an opened f-file which will be conquered by White after Rf1 and the forthcoming Bg5 will put Black into trouble! One should not forget that the Bishop pair that gives us a relatively easy game afterward and Black does not have enough resources to jeopardize it! }
11... c6
{ Not only that with c6 Black prevents any possible Nd5 which would be uncomfortable after Bg5, but also threatens to put White's light-squared Bishop into danger after b4.   Instead,  11...Nh5  would be a bit bland after  12.Qg4  Nf6  13.Qh4  and White has a nice position and initiative with the idea of Bg5, Nd5, and Rf1! }
12. a4
{ White prevents the b5 threat aiming to continue with Rf1 as well as keeping the strongest piece in this position - the Bishop on c4!. One should not forget that Black's pawn on g7 still hangs and Black will need to defend it now. }
12... Rg8 13. Rf1
{ White is ready to develop the dark-squared Bishop to g5 with pressure on the Knight on f6. }
13... h6 14. Ne2
{ Since Black defended against the threat of Bg5 and stopped White's initiative for a moment, White turns to another plan of simplifying. Not only that White aims to exchange Knights, but also has an idea to gain full central control after c3, which can come along with b4 and space control on the Queenside. }
14... O-O-O 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. c3
{ With a Bishop pair as the main asset White will continue with the hunt on Black's dark-squared Bishop with b4 and a5 and the King will be safe after simple Kc2. }
16... Bb6 17. a5 Bc7 18. Be3
{ Taking every opportunity to develop and improve the activity of pieces, White attacks the a7 pawn and gains a tempo after a development move. }
18... Kb8 19. Kc2
{ As it was shown in a game Rubinstein, A-Hromadka, K Moravska Ostrava 1923 White is clearly better with a long-term advantage of the Bishop pair and control of the f- and a-file. Meanwhile, Black has no opportunity for counterattack or activity. }
