9... exf4
{ Black plays a tricky move aiming to open the position and to force the move Bf4 losing the dark-squared Bishop as the main asset of the initiative after Nh5. Of course, White does not buy that and proceeds aggressively! }
10. Qxg7
{ Black is faced with a double attack on the Rook on h8 and pawn on f7 and needs to react with a defensive move. }
10... Rf8 11. Kd1
{ White moves the King to a safe spot and defends the c2 pawn and we are ready to create an action on the semi-opened f-file! }
11... Qe7
{ This is a clever move by Black who improves the defense of the f7 pawn and prepares for Rg8 to conquer g-file with a tempo and g2 pawn would be hanging. }
12. Qh6 { White prevents the attack with Rg8 with the idea of Qf4 and Rf1! }
12... Rg8 13. Qxf4
{ Without concerns about the hanging g2 pawn White searches for the initiative on the f-file aiming to expose Black's centralized King to attacks, as well as a vulnerable Knight on f6 and pawn f7. }
13... Rxg2 14. Rf1
{ According to the engines, the position is unclear with equal chances for both sides. In practice, White has more direct threats with full control of the f-file. To search for the initiative on the 2nd rank Black would be forced to sacrifice Knight on f6 entering an interesting position. Of course, it is questionable if in the real game Black will be ready to give up the Knight for an unclear position, but it is important to understand that even in that case, Black will be forced to play the best moves to keep it equal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Bishop's Opening 2...Nc6: Vienna Hybrid Variation"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2...Nc6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.d3 Bc5 #41"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Nf6
{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... Bc5
{ This is one of the main and most critical lines of the Bishop's opening. According to my playing experience, I faced this move frequently, and it seems that Black mostly chose 4...Bc5 with the idea to compromise White's King after Ng4. However, the positions reached afterward are maybe not so desirable according to the engines'. Still, I would say that they are a bit dangerous, and offer practical and interesting play with many tactical possibilities and attacking ideas. }
5. f4
{ White slides into a very aggressive Vienna Hybrid variation aiming to open the position and to develop an attack on the Kingside. If you have wondered where the White King is going to escape since it is obvious that O-O is not possible due to Bc5 which controls g1 square, of course, the answer is O-O-O! }
5... d6
{ It might look that this is just a solid move by Black, but actually White reaches a very interesting position to play afterward. Black aims to conquer the g4 spot very soon, going with the Bishop or the Knight over there. }
6. Nf3
{ White continues with the Vienna hybrid set-up and prepares for the possible Na4 aiming to overtake the Bishop pair which would be enticing in an open position such as this one. }
6... Bg4
{ According to my experience in the Bishops opening, Black's favorite line is this one with 6...Bg4. Black aims to play Nd4 with pressure on the Knight on f3, which would put White into an uncomfortable position.   White can choose here between two possibilities: a solid approach with slight advantage or wild play with crazy evaluations! Both will be considered deeply within the course. }
7. h3
{ This is a very interesting move for White and it was played by many chess legends, such as Kasparov, Fischer, Rubinstein... I would recommend this approach to all the players who enjoy creative positions with plenty of desirable attacking ideas, tricks, and tactical opportunities! Although the engines would give a small advantage in different variations for Black, in practice it was shown that 7.h3!? is very unpleasant for Black, especially during the short time control games @@StartBracket@@it is my favorite one in Blitz!@@EndBracket@@ }
7... Bxf3
{ This is the most logical follow-up by Black who removes the defender of the d4 spot and prepares for Nd4.   7...Bd7?!  instead would be suspicious due to  8.Na4!  which immediately provides a clear advantage for White who gains a Bishop pair. White can even proceed with Kasparov's idea of  8.f5!?  followed by Bg5, Nd5, and a harsh attack on the Kingside after g4! }
8. Qxf3
{ White is not worried about Nd4 possibility and swings all the activities on the weakened Kingside! }
8... Nd4 9. Qg3
{ The whole idea of White's plan is to take advantage out of Black's late development and weakened Kingside. Possible Qg7 would come with a double attack on the Rook on h8 and f7 pawn, and with 9.Qg3! White ignores the Nc2 threat! }
9... Nh5
{ With this intermediary move Black defends the g7 pawn with a tempo attack on White's Queen hoping to force a Queen exchange and at the same time, Black keeps a threat of Nc2. Of course, it is not White's interest to exchange Queens, but White turns to hunt of the Black's Knight on h5. }
10. Qg4
{ Queen keeps eyeing the pawn on g7 and puts pressure on the Knight which defends that spot. }
10... g6
{ It would be illogical for Black to move the Knight back leaving the g7-pawn unprotected, and  10...Nxc2  instead would not be the happiest line for Black after  11.Kd1  Nxa1  12.Qxh5  with a double attack on f7 and e5 pawns. White would have full compensation for an exchange with a plan of fxe5 followed by Rf1! }
11. fxe5
{ White forces the opening of the f-file eyeing the vulnerable f7 pawn. With the idea of Bb3 White aims to support the c2 pawn and after Rf1, Black will have issues with further development. }
11... Nxc2+
{ I believe that Nxc2 is the biggest concern for all the players in such a position, but as it was said before, White reaches a desirable position in every line where Black chases material advantage. In that manner, 11...Nxc2?! is a suspicious move and White takes full control over the game after the forthcoming Bg5 and Rf1! }
12. Kd1 Nxa1 13. Bg5
{ Black has a Rook up but faces lots of issues with development thanks to White's active pieces. White is ready to place a Rook on the f-file and pawn on f7 will be undefendable. One should not forget that Black's Knight on a1 is trapped and White can take it anytime after Kc1-Kb1-Ka1. }
13... Qc8 14. Rf1
{ Even though Black has a material advantage, White should not worry about the Queen exchange. First of all, Black's pawn on f7 hangs and can not be defended and White will have full compensation after Kc1-Kb1-Ka1. However, there is no need to hurry with a plan of overtaking the Knight on a1, because that Knight has no place to escape, so White can keep the activity with Nd5 and has an immediate threat of Qf3, or even Qh5 with full control of the game. }
