13... dxe5 14. Qxe5
{ Of course, the Knight on a1 can not escape, so White does not hurry to take it but keeps going for the initiative! }
14... Bd4 15. Qd5
{ With the idea of Qd8 White aims to enter an endgame with the huge activity of the Bishop pair and a simple plan of Bg5, Rf1 and the possibility of Kd2 attacking the Knight on a1 and gaining two pieces against a Rook which is considered to be a decisive advantage. }
15... c6 16. Qxd8 Raxd8 17. a4
{ Preventing Black's idea of b5 which might be uncomfortable, White is ready to develop with Bg5 and keeps an option to take the trapped Knight on a1 after Kd2 and Rxa1. I must emphasize that the engines do not admire the position for White here, but in practice, as it could be seen in the game Pichushkin, V-Nadeev, S ICCF email 2012, it was shown that both sides have chances for an interesting play and a fight for the win. }
