[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the second-most played move after 2...Nf6, which allows the Vienna game but prevents the Urusov Gambit. }
3. Nc3
{ Many players who choose The Bishop's opening as their main weapon would play 3. d3, but I have no difficulty admitting that 3.Nc3 is the better option, since it is a developing move that leaves the same opportunities for White.   3.Nc3 saves an option to transpose into the favorable variation of the Vienna hybrid game or even some favorable lines of the King's gambit.   So, Black is forced to carefully choose his next move and plan in general! }
3... Nf6
{ Normal and logical developing move that supports the fight for the central squares and follows the old and unwritten rule 'Develop the Knights before Bishops!'. }
4. d3
{ Everything is ready for f4! which leads this game into a better Vienna Game. 4.d3 is like a milestone for Black.   Will Black let us achieve our favorable position or react somehow to prevent it? }
4... Bc5
{ This is one of the main and most critical lines of the Bishop's opening. According to my playing experience, I faced this move frequently, and it seems that Black mostly chose 4...Bc5 with the idea to compromise White's King after Ng4. However, the positions reached afterward are maybe not so desirable according to the engines'. Still, I would say that they are a bit dangerous, and offer practical and interesting play with many tactical possibilities and attacking ideas. }
5. f4
{ White slides into a very aggressive Vienna Hybrid variation aiming to open the position and to develop an attack on the Kingside. If you have wondered where the White King is going to escape since it is obvious that O-O is not possible due to Bc5 which controls g1 square, of course, the answer is O-O-O! }
5... d6
{ It might look that this is just a solid move by Black, but actually White reaches a very interesting position to play afterward. Black aims to conquer the g4 spot very soon, going with the Bishop or the Knight over there. }
6. Nf3
{ White continues with the Vienna hybrid set-up and prepares for the possible Na4 aiming to overtake the Bishop pair which would be enticing in an open position such as this one. }
6... Bg4
{ According to my experience in the Bishops opening, Black's favorite line is this one with 6...Bg4. Black aims to play Nd4 with pressure on the Knight on f3, which would put White into an uncomfortable position.   White can choose here between two possibilities: a solid approach with slight advantage or wild play with crazy evaluations! Both will be considered deeply within the course. }
7. Na4
{ This is a resilient approach by White who gets rid of the dark-squared Bishop and solves the problem of the weakened King and the a7-g1 diagonal. White will not have worries after Nd4 and have no difficulties with doubled pawns on the f-file. By now, you could have seen, that the Bishop on c5 is not as strong as it seems at first, but somehow as a Bishop's opening player, we always feel kind of annoyed by its existence there! }
7... O-O
{ Black castles, trying to dictate the pace hoping for some solid play. White has no troubles here and puts the King into safety with O-O after removing the dark-squared Bishop. }
8. Nxc5 dxc5 9. O-O
{ White's King is safe and White has a long-term advantage of the Bishop pair and better pawn structure. White's play will be aimed against Black's weak pawn structure and the light-squared Bishop which will be blocked with 10.f5. }
9... Qd6
{ Black tries to activate all the pieces aiming to continue with Nd4 and Rad8. Of course, that does not stop White from playing against the Bishop on g4. }
10. f5
{ White prepares the field for the opening of the Kingside because Black will be forced at some moment to take the Knight on f3. The idea of White is simple, after a4 which creates a safe spot for Bishop on c4, and c3 which prevents Nd4, White will be able to continue with Qd2, Qg5, Kh1 and Rg1 afterward. }
10... Bxf3
{ If Black takes the Knight immediately, hoping that they will gain activity after Nd4, White will just go for the same plan of opening the g-file! }
11. gxf3
{ Although it might look that White unnecessarily opened up the King, there is a clever plan of Kh1 followed by Rg1, and Black's King would be suddenly in trouble. White's attack will be improved when the Queen joins the Kingside after Qe1 and Qh4! }
11... Na5
{ Black's only possibility is to find counter-play on the Queenside by taking the light-squared Bishop which is eyeing Black's King. Anyway, White will keep enough pieces after this trade to attack Black's King. }
12. Bb3
{ Of course, White will not allow Black to open the d-file and to activate the Queen and Rook. If Black insists on a trade, they will have to open the a-file for White, which might be useful later on. }
12... Nxb3 13. axb3
{ Black is stuck to a point where White controls all of the board. The a-file is opened for the Rook on a1 stopping Black's actions on the Queenside, and at the same time, White still wants to continue with an attack on the Kingside after Qe1, Qh4, Kh1, and Rg1 toggling all of the heavy pieces against Black's lonely King. }
13... a5 14. Qe1
{ Not only that White swings the Queen to h4, but does it with an attack on the exposed a5 pawn. While White prepares further prepares the attack while Black needs to defend the Queenside! }
14... b6 15. Qh4 Nd7
{ Black is forced to search for the defense of the King and aims to create space for the Knight after Re8. However, it is questionable if that could be helpful. }
16. Kh1
{ Learn how to attack when the pawn structure is broken! King goes on h1, one Rook goes on g1 and then g3, while the other one's path is a1 to g1 altogether with the idea of Bc1-Bh6, and all of that already looks extremely promising! }
16... Rfe8 17. Rg1
{ As it was shown in a game Averell-Brener playchess. com INT 2008 White is clearly better with a harsh attack after Rg3, Bh6, Rag1, and a possible Rh3. All of White's pieces are eyeing Black's King and Black has no good defender. Additionally, as my experience has shown, such positions are practically extremely hard to defend in real games, although engines give 'only' a clear advantage to White. }
*

