6... Bg4
{ According to my experience in the Bishops opening, Black's favorite line is this one with 6...Bg4. Black aims to play Nd4 with pressure on the Knight on f3, which would put White into an uncomfortable position.   White can choose here between two possibilities: a solid approach with slight advantage or wild play with crazy evaluations! Both will be considered deeply within the course. }
7. Na4
{ This is a resilient approach by White who gets rid of the dark-squared Bishop and solves the problem of the weakened King and the a7-g1 diagonal. White will not have worries after Nd4 and have no difficulties with doubled pawns on the f-file. By now, you could have seen, that the Bishop on c5 is not as strong as it seems at first, but somehow as a Bishop's opening player, we always feel kind of annoyed by its existence there! }
7... Bxf3
{ This move was played in a correspondence game between Schmidt, G-Andexel, H ICCF corr 1990. With 7...Bxf3 Black aims to gain the d4 square for the time being and steals a tempo from White who needs to take the Bishop with the Queen, and then to move it back after the Nd4 attack. }
8. Qxf3
{ White can not even think about gxf3 in such a position, because the lag in development is huge. White needs to keep a healthy pawn structure and will base the whole play on the long-term advantage of the Bishop pair which will be gained soon. }
8... Nd4 9. Qd1
{ Black's 8...Nd4 was expected and White retreats the Queen to the starting square to keep the pawn on c2 protected. In a position with a Bishop pair on the board, such a move should not be considered as a loss of a tempo, but as a move that provides a stable position with long-term advantage. }
9... exf4
{ Black intends to open the position punishing White for a late development and aiming to proceed with b5. However, one should not forget that the f7 pawn is weakened and that b5 can not be realized without good preparation. }
10. Bxf4 Qd7 11. Nxc5
{ White finally reaches a goal to take the Bishop pair and has an idea to proceed with c3 to kick out Black's Knight from the center and of course, development afterward. }
11... dxc5 12. c3
{ It is obvious that Black does not have a nice spot for the Knight and that they will start to feel pressure in the center by White's Bishops and pawns fortress. If Black does not find a way to remove the Bishop pair, White has an easy play with a clear advantage. }
12... b5
{ This is practically the only move that gives Black hopes to have any counter-play. White's light-squared Bishop does not have a good spot to step back to but there is a useful tactical motive that provides a clearly better position to White! }
13. Bxf7+
{ White certainly does not want to open d-file after  13.Bb3  Nxb3  because the pawn on d3 would be a target. This way, White keeps a healthy structure and reaches position with a better dark-squared Bishop which controls Black's c7 pawn as a possible weakness. }
13... Qxf7 14. cxd4 cxd4 15. Qc2
{ As it was shown in a game Schmidt, G-Andexel, H ICCF corr 1990, Black will not be able to defend all of the pawns on the Queenside. White has a direct threat of Qc6 and at the same time, the c7 pawn hangs. White has a clear advantage and can proceed patiently with O-O, Rfc1, and Black will not be able to hold pressure. }
