7. Na4
{ This is a resilient approach by White who gets rid of the dark-squared Bishop and solves the problem of the weakened King and the a7-g1 diagonal. White will not have worries after Nd4 and have no difficulties with doubled pawns on the f-file. By now, you could have seen, that the Bishop on c5 is not as strong as it seems at first, but somehow as a Bishop's opening player, we always feel kind of annoyed by its existence there! }
7... Nd4
{ This looks like both the most tempting and the most natural follow-up by Black who previously played 6...Bg4 to threaten with a pin. In spite of that, 7...Nd4?! is suspicious because it allows White to gain full central control, better pawn structure, and a Bishop pair advantage! }
8. c3
{ White threatens the Knight and gets rid of the pin forcing Black to react. Possible double pawns on the f-file should not concern you because White will take the Bishop pair immediately afterward, and pawns on the f-file will not be doubled for a long time due to the possibility of fxe5. }
8... Nxf3+
{ If Black instead goes for  8...Bxf3  9.gxf3  Nc6  10.fxe5  Nxe5  11.Bb3  White would be clearly better with a direct threat of  d4  , full central control, and the Bishop pair as the main asset. }
9. gxf3
{ As it was previously mentioned, White should not worry about the doubled pawns on f-file because Black has issues controlling the center. With both Bishops under attack, Black cannot defend e5 pawn after the forthcoming Nc5! }
9... Bh5 10. Nxc5
{ We are quite happy to remove this Bishop! Also, it gives us a healthier pawn structure and the Bishop pair advantage! }
10... dxc5 11. fxe5
{ Despite the Bishop pair, White now has a material advantage of a clear pawn up which will be supported with a simple developing move of Bf4! }
11... Nd7
{ Black could also go for a tricky  11...Nxe4?  since  12.dxe4  does not work for White due to  12...Qxd1  13.Kxd1  Bxf3!  , but after  12.O-O!  White is clearly better since Black has issues finding a good spot for the Knight. White's plan is simple afterward, we will conclude development with Qe2, Be3 and Rad1, and the center will be fully controlled after d4! }
12. Bf4
{ The advantage of White is clear, with a pawn up, Bishop pair, and easy plan of O-O, followed by d4 and further development, such as Qe2 and Rad1.   Despite the dominance of White, it needs to be said that Black has no possibility for counter-play, for example,  12...Qh4  is met with  13.Bg3! }
