[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) The Wild Alternative: The Urusov Gambit"]
[Black "Urusov Gambit Accepted: 4...c6 5.Qe2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever - The Bishop's opening, which is deeply analyzed within this course.   However, entering the Bishop's opening also gives you the opportunity to enter aggressive and wild lines, such as the Urusov gambit. As an introduction to the wild play within this opening, 2.Bc4 controls the important d5 square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, attacks the most vulnerable spot in Black's position on f7, and prepares White to complete development with O-O afterward. }
2... Nf6
{ This move is the most consequential continuation by Black, and believe it or not, it happens in more than 80% of the games after 2.Bc4 according to the statistics! It is also very important to mention that the Urusov gambit would not be possible without it! Line 2...Nc6 leads to a Vienna Hybrid variation and it is covered in the Bishop's opening part. }
3. d4
{ Already on the third move, White has an opportunity to pick the aggressive approach with the Urusov gambit 3.d4!? or to choose a more peaceful 'bulletproof' approach with 3.d3, which enters the Bishop's opening, which will be analyzed in another chapter.  I would like to emphasize that the Urusov gambit, in the beginning, was a tricky 'joke' opening, but through time it has developed to a very high level.   The Urusov Gambit is an exciting option for the players whose main weapon and asset is their tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for Blitz and Rapid games, especially when lower-rated players are seated on the other side hopelessly trying to find a proper plan to defend as Black! On the other side of the pond, many top-level professional players used the Urusov Gambit as a surprise weapon during significant tournaments. They showed their opponents that they are ready to go into the wilderness to snatch the win!   So, fasten your seat belts and get ready to embark on an adventurous journey! }
3... Nxe4
{ The last move is not Black's happiest answer to our gambit: In more than 65% of games it ended in White's favor. And yet it was a very common approach against me in Blitz lately! Also, in the past, it was even played by top Grandmasters, such as Mamedyarov Shakhriyar! }
4. dxe5
{ Our main answer is an immediate threat of Qd5 and a double attack on Black's Knight and weakened f7 square. Black is in an uncomfortable situation and must be thinking about their badly positioned Knight and a direct mate threat - already on the 4th move! }
4... c6
{ The main idea of this move is to prevent the Qd5 threat, as well as to play ...d5 in order to maintain control of the center and support the Knight on e4. }
5. Qe2
{ This accurate move is very important! White continues with dynamic play, attacking the compromised Knight and preparing for the upcoming piece activity and devastating attack. Also, this move is aimed against the previously mentioned  5...d5  plan by Black due to  6.exd6  , which puts the Knight on  e4  in a pin.   Instead,  5.Qf3  might look tricky, but unfortunately, after  5...d5  6.exd6  Nxd6  Black gains a solid position where their King gets to easily escape after Be7 and O-O. }
5... Nc5
{ 5...Qe7?!  would lead to a winning position for White after  6.Qxe4  d5  7.Bxd5  cxd5  8.Qxd5  with a clear material advantage. }
6. Nf3
{ This move is an improvement over  6.a3!?  which Fedorov used against Mamedyarov in Moscow in 2004, where the game ended in a draw. The idea of  6.Nf3  is to complete development as soon as possible and start an attack on the Kingside while Black is still displeased with the poor activity of their pieces. }
6... Be7
{ Black tries to develop and escape their central problems, which are visible to the naked eye. }
7. O-O b5
{ With 6...Be7 Black wants to escape and castle as soon as possible. On the other hand, if they indeed go for castling instead of 7...b5:  7....O-O  8.Rd1!  They would be facing huge difficulties to complete their development! White would be controlling the center with a lot of space for the pieces, while Black went into a deep dark forest of development problems. That is why Black decides to chase the light-squared killer which pressures the weakened f7-square. }
8. Bb3 O-O
{ Black has also an option to continue with a hunt on the Bishop and play  8...a5  , but then  9.c4!  gives a safe spot for the light-squared Bishop and opens the position up while Black's King is still exposed in the center. After c4 White is much better thanks to the active piece and great development, which will be further improved with Nc3. Another option for Black might be  8...Nxb3  9.axb3  but with the open a-file and previously mentioned development advantages for White, Black can not be happy over here either! }
9. Rd1
{ A great prophylactic move that doesn't allow Black to develop and activate the Bshop on c8 with d5 and makes sure that the opponent's pieces stay miserable! }
9... Nxb3
{ If Black is stubborn to give some space to its Bishop with  9...d5  they will face  10.exd6  Bxd6  11.Bg5  exposing the bad position of the Queen and after  11...Qc7  12.Rxd6!  Qxd6  13.Be7  Re8  14.Bxd6  Rxe2  15.Bxc5  White will enjoy a piece up and a winning position. }
10. axb3
{ Don't forget that after the exchange we got another open file for the Rook! }
10... Na6 11. Nc3
{ And White is clearly better with the two Rooks positioned on the opened files, active Knights, and an immediate threat of Nd4-Nxc6. It shouldn't be forgotten that Black doesn't have a solution for activating the Bishop on c8 nor the Rook on a8, this was seen in the game Craciun,G -Nestianu,R ICCF email 2008. }
*

