{ This move is an improvement over 6.a3!? which Fedorov used against Mamedyarov in Moscow in 2004, where the game ended in a draw. The idea of  6.Nf3  is to complete development as soon as possible and start an attack on the Kingside while Black is still displeased with the poor activity of their pieces. }
6... b5 { Black simply wants to get rid of the light-squared killer. } 7. Bb3
{ It is important to keep the Bishop on the killing diagonal a2-f7 from where it keeps the pressure on the f7-square. You should not worry about Black's possibility to go for Nb3 because that opens the a-file for the Rook on a1 after axb3! }
7... a5 8. c4
{ Another very important move for White! We take advantage of the opportunity to sharpen things out, while the Black's King is in the central unsafe zone. At the same time, we make additional fresh air for our light-squared Bishop which is considered to be one of the most important pieces for the attack! }
8... a4
{ If Black decides to go for a trade instead, with 8...Nb3 9.axb3, we are reaching the position with clear positional advantage with better development, central and space control, and simple plan of Nc3, O-O, and Ne4, compromising the dark-squares holes on the black side such as d6 and c5 squares. On the other hand, one should not forget that the Rook on a1 gets activated on the open line. }
9. Bc2 bxc4 10. O-O
{ We are getting close to finishing our full development, while Black is still stuck with only one active piece in the game - the Knight on c5. With a d6-hole and weak exposed pawns on c4 and a4, White has many targets to attack. }
10... Nba6 { Black's idea is to hunt our light-squared Bishop after Nb4. } 11.
Qxc4 Rb8 12. Nc3
{ After putting the Knight on the active square from where it controls the center, we also make pressure on the a4 weakness which is hanging. However, our main idea will be exposing the weak Black King in the center, with a possible Ng5. }
12... Nb4 13. Ng5
{ We ignore Black's attack on the Bishop at the moment, giving a headache to our opponent who faces the mate threat of Qf7. After Black's defense, White is better with a huge initiative, and the main idea is Nce4 followed by Re1, and we keep the pressure on the opponent's miserable pieces tightly positioned on the back rank, which was shown in the game Tedesco, M -Schweikert, E ICCF email 2018. }
