4... Qh4
{ Judging by my Online experience lately, this move turns out to be a common answer by Black, and even though it might look dangerous with a mating threat Qxf2#, and at the same time eyeing the Bishop on c4, it is a bad move if White knows how to answer! }
5. Be3
{ There we go - this is the move that puts Black into serious trouble. Bishop on e3 defends the weakened square f2, threatens Nf3 which would put Black's Queen in an uncomfortable position with difficulties to escape the attack. }
5... Nxf2
{ With this tactical attempt Black tries to launch a discovered attack by the Queen on our light-squared Bishop, but they forget that there is also some tactics on the other side of the board! If Black decides to discover-attack with the Queen with  5...Nd6  we would answer with simple Bishop escape  6.Bb3  Nc4  7.Qe2  which defends the Bishop and prepares for castling  Nxe3  8.Qxe3  with a clear development advantage and the idea of Nf3, Nc3, O-O-O. }
6. Bxf7+
{ We take the f7 pawn with check and force Black to expose the King to attacks from the widely opened center. Black will not be able to escape and castle till the end of the game. }
6... Kxf7 7. Bxf2
{ White is clearly better with the simple plan of Qd5, Ne2, and O-O which would put the Rook on f1 on the open f- file with many direct mate threats. Black is locked down on the 8th rank without possibilities to avoid the final scenario-mortified. You shouldn't worry about Black's checks, such as  7...Qb4  , since there is defending development move  Nc3  and the plan, stays the same- Ne2, O-O, and Qd5! }
