{ Aiming to punish Black's mistake, with a move typical for the Fried Liver Attack, White immediately takes action with this very uncomfortable move. More so, besides the direct threat of Nf7, followed by Qf3 or Qh5, Black also needs to think about possible Re1 and many pins dropping. }
7... Be6
{ Although Black tries to protect the weakened f7 square, this is a suspicious move because it allows us to once again pin the Black's pieces. }
8. Re1
{ Not only that White here threatens the obvious Ne6, but there are also tactical opportunities coming up, such as Nxf7! }
8... Qd7
{ Once again, Black attempts to escape the lockage with O-O-O and to stabilize. }
9. Nxf7
{ As it was previously mentioned, good development and active pieces allow us to open up the position by sacrificing! It is pretty obvious that Black is forced to accept the sacrifice, but however they choose to continue, it leads to trouble. }
9... Kxf7
{ This is practically the only possibility for Black, because after  9...Qxf7  there is  10.Bxd5!  and once again, Black faces trouble to escape from the pins and to defend the Be6. }
10. Qf3+
{ After a logical check, Black has no options but to play with the King once again, which would not resolve the pin problems. Once again, it is confirmed how much the light-squared Bishop is important for us, and how many problems it makes to our opponent. }
10... Kg8
{ Of course,  10...Nf6??  would be immediately losing after  11.Bxe6  .   While  10...Ke8  would once again pin the Black's King, and White is completely winning after  11.Bxd5 }
11. Rxe6 { The butchering is ongoing and Black can not escape out of it! }
11... Rd8
{ If Black tried to accept the Rook sacrifice with  11...Qxe6  the very same Queen would be in a very uncomfortable position after  12.Bxd5  . If instead, Black tries to move the Knight on  d5  from the attack with  11...Nb6  that would lead to a discovery by our light-squared killer  Bc4  and after  12.Re7  with a check, there will be  Qf7  mate coming. }
12. Qe4
{ It is pretty obvious that in the position with equalized material and so many active threats for White, such as Re8 followed by Bd5, Black's terrible King would be compromised to a pin coming from Bc4. However, although we have a direct threat, we shouldn't forget about development, which could be concluded later on with Bg5 and Nd2. White is much better here and this is an easily winning position. }
