7... Ne5
{ Black tries to defend the weak f7-square with an attack on the light-squared killer, but one should not forget that Black's King is still positioned in the center and the Knight on e5 can be exposed to a pin. }
8. Re1
{ After this simple Rook activating move, Black has a problem defending the pinned Knight. White should not be in a hurry to return the material with 8.Qd4, but should keep focusing on activation, since the exposed d4 pawn can not be defended for a while. }
8... Ne3
{ This is practically the only move in which Black tries to escape the pin and make some complications to gain any activity. If  8...f6?  was played instead, White would be much better after  9.Nf3  , and both the e5 and d4 squares will be impossible to defend by the Black side. }
9. Nxf7
{ A totally unexpected Knight sacrifice gives lots of problems to Black. This move opens the position up, and with many threats, puts Black into new pins. White does not want to go for  9.fxe3  since it would give Black opportunities to stabilize after  9...Qxg5  . Instead, we continue with the butchering! }
9... Nxf7
{ If  9...Nxd1  was played instead, White would be completely winning after  10.Rxe5  which comes with a check. One should not forget that after  10...Qe7  11.Rxe7  Bxe7  the Rook on  h8  is hanging and White enters the position with a clear material advantage after  12.Nxh8  , piece up. }
10. fxe3
{ Now we have entered the position with equal material, but White is much better. Although Black's d4 pawn hangs on, after Rf1 and Qf3, Black would be in a problem to find a proper solution for the King's safety. }
10... Be7 11. exd4
{ Since Black is ready to castle, we simply capture the pawn and play an extremely active position with a pawn up and the previously mentioned idea of Rf1. }
11... O-O 12. Rf1
{ Crossing the path from sacrifices to material advantage, White reaches a good position with a pawn up, full central control, active pieces such as the Bishop on c4 and Rook on f1, while Black is still chained due to the pin of the King and the Knight. The idea for White will be to stabilize the centralized pawn with c3, and a simple continuation of development and attacking actions with Qf3 or Qh5, Nd2, Ne4. Getting closer to the end of development would lead also to the end of the game, with a score of 1:0. }
