{ Black takes the pawn and defers the decision whether to enter the Urusov gambit accepted for a couple of moves! We are ready for a road full of attacking opportunities and tactical possibilities! Practically this is the only good move here by Black and other moves such as  3...d6?  and  3...Nxe4?!  lead to dubious play for Black, while  3...Nc6  leads to the Scotch gambit type of positions! }
4. Nf3
{ The main idea of the Urusov gambit is to let Black take the pawns, while we develop pieces. One may think that White permits this material advantage to Black, but don't forget that sometimes one needs to give in order to gain! Whilst Black collects the pawns, they create the space for our developed and centralized pieces, and at the same time, White builds up an attack on Black's King, which still stands exposed in the center. }
4... d5
{ Black escapes from the Urusov gambit accepted and decides to answer as actively as possible, with an attempt to create a counter-attack in the center and to develop the pieces quickly. However, an open position gives opportunities to both sides, but keep in mind that White has a small development advantage. }
5. exd5
{ We answer logically by accepting an offer to open the e-file and we are prepared to castle and create some action! The idea is to complete development with O-O and Bg5 and to make some pressure on Black's inactive pieces. }
5... Nxd5
{ Although this looks like a natural move, it is questionable if Black has time to care about the pawns, while White is actively developing and eyeing the King, which is still positioned in the center. The Urusov Gambit is a race with time, and while White tries to be fast with development and activity, Black needs to hurry to hide the King in the safe spot. After  5...Nxd5?  Black is just too late. }
6. O-O
{ It is already clear that Black faces lots of problems. Despite the development advantage, White has a direct threat of Qxd4, Re1, and Ng5, eyeing the weakened and unprotected f7 pawn, while Black doesn't have many options to defend. }
6... Nb6
{ Black tries to remove the light-squared killer, but he can not be happy with all of the pieces placed on the back rank and with the King in the center, while we are fully developed and ready for the real action!  If, instead, Black tried to escape into and tries to castle the King with  6...Be7  it would be too late. After  7.Qxd4  White attacks both g7-square and the Knight on  d5  and the only defense is  7...Nf6  after which we can enter an endgame with  8.Qxd8  Bxd8  and take an advantage thanks to the more active pieces with  9.Re1  Be7  10.Nc3  and White is clearly better with ideas of Nb5, Ng5, Bf4, Rad1 which will be unbearable for the Black side.  One shall not forget that Black's King is locked to the e8-square and can not castle due to a pin by Re1. All the advantages of White's position may be seen through the game Perunovic Mio-Khatanbaatar, Chess.com, January 2021. }
7. Bg5
{ This is a very important intermediary move. With such an advantage and huge initiative, it is not the time to step back, White is going forward to weaken Black's poor pieces! }
7... f6
{ This is practically the only move for Black, because after  7...Be7?!  Black would be facing  8.Bxe7  Qxe7  9.Re1!  and that would lead to losing the Queen. }
8. Re1+
{ Besides the fact that 8.Re1 is a great developing move, it puts some pressure on Black's centralized King. One should not forget that Black cannot castle the King anymore since the Bc4 controls g8-square. }
8... Be7 9. Bb3
{ Light-squared Bishop needs to stay on a2-g8 diagonal! This is a quiet move that will give a lot of headaches to the Black players who must be thinking how to proceed now, and it is not easy to find an answer to that question. }
9... Nc6
{ If Black steps on the mine and accept to take the hanging Bishop with  9...fxg5?  after  10.Nxg5  and the idea of Qh5 it would be impossible to defend everything. With a piece down and mate threats, White is winning. }
10. Bf4
{ After another quiet move, it becomes obvious that Black is locked down, and that White is extremely active with almost all pieces developed. After Nh4, White will threaten to win with Qh5 immediately, but if Black manages to stop that idea, White can keep a normal play with Qd3, Na3, Rad1. Eventually, a pawn from d4 will fall down, but White will keep the activity of the pieces, while Black will still be searching for a way to the castle. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) The Wild Alternative: The Urusov Gambit"]
[Black "Urusov Gambit Accepted: 3...exd4 4.Nf3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever - The Bishop's opening, which is deeply analyzed within this course.   However, entering the Bishop's opening also gives you the opportunity to enter aggressive and wild lines, such as the Urusov gambit. As an introduction to the wild play within this opening, 2.Bc4 controls the important d5 square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, attacks the most vulnerable spot in Black's position on f7, and prepares White to complete development with O-O afterward. }
2... Nf6
{ This move is the most consequential continuation by Black, and believe it or not, it happens in more than 80% of the games after 2.Bc4 according to the statistics! It is also very important to mention that the Urusov gambit would not be possible without it! Line 2...Nc6 leads to a Vienna Hybrid variation and it is covered in the Bishop's opening part. }
3. d4
{ Already on the third move, White has an opportunity to pick the aggressive approach with the Urusov gambit 3.d4!? or to choose a more peaceful 'bulletproof' approach with 3.d3, which enters the Bishop's opening, which will be analyzed in another chapter.  I would like to emphasize that the Urusov gambit, in the beginning, was a tricky 'joke' opening, but through time it has developed to a very high level.   The Urusov Gambit is an exciting option for the players whose main weapon and asset is their tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for Blitz and Rapid games, especially when lower-rated players are seated on the other side hopelessly trying to find a proper plan to defend as Black! On the other side of the pond, many top-level professional players used the Urusov Gambit as a surprise weapon during significant tournaments. They showed their opponents that they are ready to go into the wilderness to snatch the win!   So, fasten your seat belts and get ready to embark on an adventurous journey! }
3... exd4
{ Black takes the pawn and defers the decision whether to enter the Urusov gambit accepted for a couple of moves! We are ready for a road full of attacking opportunities and tactical possibilities! Practically this is the only good move here by Black and other moves such as  3...d6?  and  3...Nxe4?!  lead to dubious play for Black, while  3...Nc6  leads to the Scotch gambit type of positions! }
4. Nf3
{ The main idea of the Urusov gambit is to let Black take the pawns, while we develop pieces. One may think that White permits this material advantage to Black, but don't forget that sometimes one needs to give in order to gain! Whilst Black collects the pawns, they create the space for our developed and centralized pieces, and at the same time, White builds up an attack on Black's King, which still stands exposed in the center. }
4... d5
{ Black escapes from the Urusov gambit accepted and decides to answer as actively as possible, with an attempt to create a counter-attack in the center and to develop the pieces quickly. However, an open position gives opportunities to both sides, but keep in mind that White has a small development advantage. }
5. exd5
{ We answer logically by accepting an offer to open the e-file and we are prepared to castle and create some action! The idea is to complete development with O-O and Bg5 and to make some pressure on Black's inactive pieces. }
5... Bb4+
{ Black tries to make the path for castling by checking us and tries for the best hope to exchange some pieces, which would be a relief for our opponent. However, with this move, Black also exposes its Bishop to an attack. }
6. c3
{ Of course, we do not follow Black's hopes to offer any pieces for exchanges. We block the check with a pawn, attacking the Bb4 at the same time, but one should not forget that we also open the Queen threatening Qa4+. }
6... Qe7+
{ This is the only move for Black which does not go straight into a losing position. I am sure that you will be facing  6...dxc3  very often, and with a lot of pleasure, you will win a piece in the 7th move after  7.Qa4+! }
7. Be2
{ Basically, we are forced to step back with a Bishop, since  7.Qe2  instead is out of the question because we do not want to trade pieces. However, this move should not be taken as a retraining move, because it also improves the Bishop's position since at c4 it lost a role of the attacking piece eyeing our own d5 pawn. }
7... dxc3
{ Black had no many options except to take this pawn, since White had a serious threat of Qxd4. }
8. Nxc3
{ Once again, we use the opportunity to develop our pieces at the most active possible squares. Since Black keeps up with development as well, we begin to improve the position by choosing the positional approach, and for the moment, we put the aggressive style aside. }
8... O-O 9. O-O Nbd7
{ Black's idea is to play  Nb6  and attack our isolated pawn. Someone might think it was more logical for Black to first develop the Bc8, but on a deeper look, Black has no good option to settle the Bishop down. If  9...Bg4  was played instead, White would be able to answer with  10.h3  , followed by Bf4, which would impede Black's development with Nbd7, due to the c7-weakness. }
10. Bg5
{ This is a very uncomfortable move for the Black side since now Black needs to think about the pin and White's threats. However, White could also continue more peacefully with  10.Re1  , which gives a slight advantage and a nice position for play. }
10... Bxc3
{ If Black is in a hurry to remove the Bishop, we can easily overtake the advantage. }
11. bxc3
{ After this move, we are able to establish the center control with c4, and to start playing for a win with the long-term Bishop pair advantage! }
11... Qc5 12. c4
{ Black is searching for any possible activity, but White has no troubles here. Oppositely, after reaching an outpost with Nd4, we would have active and developed pieces, while Black needs to think about how to develop Bc8 since if they decide to move the Knight from d7, they would face Bf6 and ann extremely bad pawn structure around the King. }
12... b6
{ This is practically the only way for Black to conclude the development, but this move creates new outposts. }
13. Nd4
{ After White reached a desirable outpost with Nd4, Black must be thinking about Nc6 or Nf5 possibilities. }
13... Ne4
{ Black is desperately trying to overtake the Bishops pair, but White is already too active, and now can turn to the other advantages. }
14. Be3
{ Instead of being stubborn and keeping Bishops pair, we are taking another opportunity to gain the initiative and attack Black's exposed Queen by pinning it! Of course, the main threat now is 15.Ne6 winning an exchange! }
14... Nc3 15. Qc2 Nxe2+ 16. Qxe2
{ As it was previously mentioned, White's threat is Ne6, discovery-attack thanks to the pin which leads to a material advantage, so Black is forced to once again step back and put development aside. }
16... Qe7 17. Nc6
{ We have reached the newest outpost à tempo thanks to the hunt on Black's exposed Queen! While White improves his pieces, Black tries to escape the attack. }
17... Qd6 18. Bd4
{ With this move, White has reached a perfect and the longest possible diagonal for the Bishop which is now eyeing the Black's lone King. }
18... Bb7 19. Ne7+
{ And finally, when Black tried to unchain and activate the pieces, White used the opportunity to cash out on our own activity, winning material advantage after an upcoming Nf5 when the g7-pawn would be undefended, as it was shown in the game Laes, C-Flores Gutierrez, C ICCF corr 1975. }
