{ This is a very uncomfortable move for the Black side since now Black needs to think about the pin and White's threats. However, White could also continue more peacefully with  10.Re1  , which gives a slight advantage and a nice position for play. }
10... Nb6
{ Black is ready to remove the Bishop and after Bc3 to surround and capture the pawn with Nd5. }
11. Rc1
{ Although Black has a threat to take the material advantage, White shouldn't be blindfolded on the other aspects of the position. If Black intends to take the pawn, he needs to give up the Bishop pair, which is more than enough compensation for the material loss. Instead of Rc1, the alternative was  11.Re1  , X-raying Black's Queen on  e7  , but after  11...Qd6  12.Nb5  Qd8  White is forced to go back with  13.Nc3  and be satisfied with equal position. }
11... Bxc3 12. bxc3
{ This is a very important move for White, although someone might think that it is more natural to take the pawn with the Rook and gain an open file. One should not forget that in that case, Black would be able to take Nbd5 with tempo, and would have time to conclude the development and establish full control of the center before White takes proper action. }
12... Nbxd5 13. c4
{ With this move, not only that we force Black to step back from the center, but we open the space for our pieces and the Bishop pair which is our main weapon here. At the same time, we overtake the control in the center. }
13... Nb4
{ Black's best try to keep the pieces active. For example, if  13...Nb6?!  was played instead, the aggressive  14.c5!  would be possible with the idea of Re1, Qb3, slowly starting to cut the space for Black's pieces. }
14. Qb3
{ After 14.Qb3 White is about to finish development and aims to play Re1 and establish the lines of communication. The position is not clear, as Black has a material advantage, but White on the other hand with the Bishop pair, which is an especially good weapon in open positions, such as this one. With lots of opportunities to create complications, and the initiative on the White side, these positions are very interesting to be played. }
