{ This move is the most consequential continuation by Black, and believe it or not, it happens in more than 80% of the games after 2.Bc4 according to the statistics! It is also very important to mention that the Urusov gambit would not be possible without it! Line 2...Nc6 leads to a Vienna Hybrid variation and it is covered in the Bishop's opening part. }
3. d4
{ Already on the third move, White has an opportunity to pick the aggressive approach with the Urusov gambit 3.d4!? or to choose a more peaceful 'bulletproof' approach with 3.d3, which enters the Bishop's opening, which will be analyzed in another chapter.  I would like to emphasize that the Urusov gambit, in the beginning, was a tricky 'joke' opening, but through time it has developed to a very high level.   The Urusov Gambit is an exciting option for the players whose main weapon and asset is their tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for Blitz and Rapid games, especially when lower-rated players are seated on the other side hopelessly trying to find a proper plan to defend as Black! On the other side of the pond, many top-level professional players used the Urusov Gambit as a surprise weapon during significant tournaments. They showed their opponents that they are ready to go into the wilderness to snatch the win!   So, fasten your seat belts and get ready to embark on an adventurous journey! }
3... exd4
{ Black takes the pawn and defers the decision whether to enter the Urusov gambit accepted for a couple of moves! We are ready for a road full of attacking opportunities and tactical possibilities! Practically this is the only good move here by Black and other moves such as  3...d6?  and  3...Nxe4?!  lead to dubious play for Black, while  3...Nc6  leads to the Scotch gambit type of positions! }
4. Nf3
{ The main idea of the Urusov gambit is to let Black take the pawns, while we develop pieces. One may think that White permits this material advantage to Black, but don't forget that sometimes one needs to give in order to gain! Whilst Black collects the pawns, they create the space for our developed and centralized pieces, and at the same time, White builds up an attack on Black's King, which still stands exposed in the center. }
4... Bb4+
{ Black's idea is to develop the piece with tempo, escaping quickly trying castle and gain some stability. Also Black intends to force some unwanted exchanges, but this is not what we are going to allow. }
5. c3
{ We are pushing the Bishop back without allowing Black to develop quickly and we go for what we wanted: a sharp and open position with a lot of possibilities and activity! }
5... dxc3 6. bxc3
{ Once again we push the Black Bishop back, but it is worth mentioning that also 6.O-O!? would be very interesting for White with a lot of activity and nice initiative, although the engines wouldn't evaluate that position in White's favor. The position would be very similar to positions coming out from the Danish gambit, which might be a surprise for your opponents! }
6... Bc5
{ Black is putting the Bishop back at the most active square available. Instead, an immediate  6...d5  would be an interesting and sharp answer, but after  7.exd5  Bd6  White can simply go for  8.O-O  O-O  followed by  9.Bb3  and the idea of c4-Nd2-Bb2, with an uncertain evaluation but a clear initiative for White. The recently developed Bb2 would be the main piece for the upcoming activities directed to Black's King.   Lately, lots of players went for  6...Bc5  against my students, but after  7.e5!  White seems to get a promising position! }
7. O-O
{ And within the spirit of the Urusov Gambit, White looks for activity with the better developeded and nicely positioned Bc4 and Nf3, and with the upcoming e5 and Bg5 which would put Black in an inconvenient position. }
7... d5
{ Black is following the common rule in chess 'Attack is the best defense' and reacts in the center aiming to block the light-squared killer Bc4. If Black instead goes for  7...d6  , White would have the interesting  8.Ng5  attacking the f7-weakness and after  8...O-O  9.e5!  dxe5  there comes the hidden  10.Bxf7!  It seems that black still resists with  10...Kh8  but actually after the exchange  11.Qxd8  Rxd8  12.Bc4!  gives the advantage to White, since Nf7 can not be protected. }
8. exd5
{ After the logical answer of exd5, we opened the e-file for the Rook. Although it looks that Black managed to succeed in the plan to block the Bc4, our idea will be based on the further development of Bg5, followed by Bb3-c4 and Bc2 with activation of the light-squared Bishop on the other diagonal eyeing Black's King! }
8... O-O 9. Bg5
{ White aims to finish the development by pinning the Black's Knight with Bg5 and at the same time get better control of d5-pawn. With an open e-file for the Rook and full center control with a space advantage, we go into a pleasant position, where, at the same time, the lack of activity of Bc4 should not be forgotten! }
9... Nbd7
{ Black threatens to play Nb6 with a double attack on the Bc4 and exposed d5 pawn. }
10. Re1
{ Although we are familiar with the threat of Black, we will go for the most active move in the position, activating the Rook on the open file. Instead, it was possible to play 10.Bb3 with c4 and Nbd2 next, but after Rd1, thanks to our active light pieces, it would be hard for Black to gain activity with Nb6. }
10... Nb6 11. Bb3
{ It is very important to save the light-squared Bishop and to understand the importance of this piece. Bb3 is not only a defensive piece that currently protects exposed pawn placed at d5, but it is also a piece with huge attacking potential after c4-Qd3 and Bc2! }
11... Qd6
{ Black activates the Queen and releases the pin aiming to develop the Bishop on  c8  and connect the Rooks. However, we will continue with the plan of light-squared Bishop activation, targeting Black's King. You shouldn't worry about  11...Nbxd5?!  because out of nowhere your opponent will face  12.Re5!  and a pin on the Knight on  d5  and Bishop on  c5  . After  12...c6  13.c4!  with a nice initiative! }
12. c4
{ We reach a position with a nice play after the conclusion of the plan Nc3, Qd3, Bc2, and complete development after Rad1, as it was played in the game between Bauer, R - Zhak, B, ICCF email 2014. }
