[White "4) The Wild Alternative: The Urusov Gambit"]
[Black "Urusov Gambit Accepted: 3...exd4 4.Nf3 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever - The Bishop's opening, which is deeply analyzed within this course.   However, entering the Bishop's opening also gives you the opportunity to enter aggressive and wild lines, such as the Urusov gambit. As an introduction to the wild play within this opening, 2.Bc4 controls the important d5 square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, attacks the most vulnerable spot in Black's position on f7, and prepares White to complete development with O-O afterward. }
2... Nf6
{ This move is the most consequential continuation by Black, and believe it or not, it happens in more than 80% of the games after 2.Bc4 according to the statistics! It is also very important to mention that the Urusov gambit would not be possible without it! Line 2...Nc6 leads to a Vienna Hybrid variation and it is covered in the Bishop's opening part. }
3. d4
{ Already on the third move, White has an opportunity to pick the aggressive approach with the Urusov gambit 3.d4!? or to choose a more peaceful 'bulletproof' approach with 3.d3, which enters the Bishop's opening, which will be analyzed in another chapter.  I would like to emphasize that the Urusov gambit, in the beginning, was a tricky 'joke' opening, but through time it has developed to a very high level.   The Urusov Gambit is an exciting option for the players whose main weapon and asset is their tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for Blitz and Rapid games, especially when lower-rated players are seated on the other side hopelessly trying to find a proper plan to defend as Black! On the other side of the pond, many top-level professional players used the Urusov Gambit as a surprise weapon during significant tournaments. They showed their opponents that they are ready to go into the wilderness to snatch the win!   So, fasten your seat belts and get ready to embark on an adventurous journey! }
3... exd4
{ Black takes the pawn and defers the decision whether to enter the Urusov gambit accepted for a couple of moves! We are ready for a road full of attacking opportunities and tactical possibilities! Practically this is the only good move here by Black and other moves such as  3...d6?  and  3...Nxe4?!  lead to dubious play for Black, while  3...Nc6  leads to the Scotch gambit type of positions! }
4. Nf3
{ The main idea of the Urusov gambit is to let Black take the pawns, while we develop pieces. One may think that White permits this material advantage to Black, but don't forget that sometimes one needs to give in order to gain! Whilst Black collects the pawns, they create the space for our developed and centralized pieces, and at the same time, White builds up an attack on Black's King, which still stands exposed in the center. }
4... Nxe4
{ Black takes the challenge and dives into Urusov gambit accepted! The Urusov Gambit accepted is a fun line that can give many opponents lots of trouble, so It might be wise for Black to decline this gambit, as there’s certainly nothing wrong with going back into the Scotch gambit. One thing is sure, when Black accepts the Urusov Gambit and takes on e4, White can easily launch a big attack on the Kingside, so get ready for slamming! The show must go on! }
5. Qxd4
{ This move gives White one of the most important pieces into the action in the Urusov gambit - The Queen! It will later move onto the Kingside Qd4-Qh4, from where it will attack the h7-square @@StartBracket@@usually with Bd3@@EndBracket@@, in addition with Bg5 and White will be able to complete his development with O-O-O with further possibilities for the attack on the Kingside! From this move onwards @@StartBracket@@for the next 6 moves@@EndBracket@@, I decided to put an exclamation mark on each move that presents a crucial part of the attacking plan Qd4-Nc3-Qh4-Bg5-O-O-O-Rhe1! }
5... Nd6
{ I've faced this move a lot playing Online Blitz lately. Not only that low-rated players went for it, but also IMs and even few GM's! However, this move can be characterized as very bad if White proceeds properly! Obviously, Black's idea is to remove the light-squared killer Bishop, but at the same time, it leaves the Kingside weakened, especially the g7-spot. Just few more moves and reality will hit them! }
6. O-O
{ We ignore Black's threat due to much better development. While Black has only one piece in the game, we have three centralized pieces and a direct threat of Re1! One shall not forget that Black can not simply block the check with Be7 since the g7 pawn would be hanging! }
6... f6
{ I saw this idea by Black in a game I would recommend you to check: Knorr, B - Schmidt, H Germany 1989. Black played this move in a desperate attempt to defend exposed g7 weakness, but with poor development could not find an escape from harsh attack! }
7. Re1+
{ While Black has only one piece properly developed, we don't want to lose time by stepping back. With Re1 not only that we develop one more piece with tempo, but we force Black to make more weaknesses. }
7... Be7 8. Qg4
{ White forced Black to leave g7 square undefended and went for it! One should not forget that Black's King can not escape and castle due to Bc4! }
8... Nxc4 9. Qxg7
{ With much better development and the upcoming threat of Bh6, White uses the opportunity to sharpen things. Although the white squared killer was sacrificed, Black can not control the outposts of the black squares. }
9... Rf8 10. Bh6
{ Due to the pinned centralized King, White has a direct mate threat of Qf8 which is very uncomfortable. If Black wants to stay alive for a little bit more, he must play the only moves! }
10... Ne5
{ This is the only move for the Black side to stop the threat of Qf8. However, this is just prolonging the punishment. }
11. Nxe5
{ With a beautiful threat of Ng6 followed by Qf8, Black's having a headache to defend. }
11... fxe5 12. Rxe5
{ The very same threat of Qf8 is appearing all the time! It's obvious that it can not be defended anymore. }
12... d6 13. Qxf8+
{ And White is easily winning with the forthcoming 14.Qxd8, going into an endgame with clear exchange and pawn up. However, in the game between Knorr, B - Schmidt, H, Germany 1989, White decided to make a joke of his opponent:  13...Kd7  15.Qf5+  Ke8  16.Rxe7+  If Black chose to play  16...Kxe7  instead, he would be facing  16.Bg5  and after  16...Ke8  White wins with  17.Qe4  , since Black cannot defend the Queen anymore.   The game continued with  13...Kd7  15.Qf5+  Ke8  16.Rxe7+  Qxe7  17.Qxc8  Kf7  18.Nc3  and White is completely winning with a clear piece up. Additionally, Black can not include the Rook and the Knight in a game. }
