6... Nc6
{ Although it looks that Black develops the piece with a tempo and that White needs to step back with the Queen, the idea of the Nc6 move is different. Black simply tries to defend the King from the upcoming Re1 by covering it with a Knight! }
7. Re1+
{ In a position with such a development advantage and many active pieces, White shall not even think about getting back with the pieces! }
7... Ne7
{ It is pretty obvious that this is the only move for Black to defend. If  7...Be7?  was played instead White easily wins after  8.Qxg7  Rf8  9.Bh6!  with the undefendable threat of Qf8! }
8. Bb3
{ Despite saving the most important piece of Urusov gambit -  Bc4  - with this move White is turning a ball to Black. Black is in a lot of trouble deciding how to continue and we can enjoy while our opponent suffers! It is not clear how Ng5 or Ne5 threats can be defended. It is worth mentioning how I defeated a GM in the Online Blitz game after a very tricky  8.Ng5?!  h6  9.Qxd6!!  threatening  Bf7  mate, and after  9...hxg5  Black could not defend mate due to  10.Qd5!  Although,  8.Bb3  leads to a winning position without a chance for Black to save their soul. }
8... f6
{ Black gives a desperate try to defend but only makes new light-squares weaknesses. If  8...h6  was played instead Black would face issues after  9.Ne5  and threat of  Qd6  followed by  Bf7  mate! }
9. Nc3
{ White is much better after this final touch which includes another piece into the game. Black went out of moves due to cruel pins and doesn't have many options to continue. White's plan is simple Bf4 followed by Qd5 and Qf7 mate threat. }
