{ Black takes the challenge and dives into Urusov gambit accepted! The Urusov Gambit accepted is a fun line that can give many opponents lots of trouble, so It might be wise for Black to decline this gambit, as there’s certainly nothing wrong with going back into the Scotch gambit. One thing is sure, when Black accepts the Urusov Gambit and takes on e4, White can easily launch a big attack on the Kingside, so get ready for slamming! The show must go on! }
5. Qxd4
{ This move gives White one of the most important pieces into the action in the Urusov gambit - The Queen! It will later move onto the Kingside Qd4-Qh4, from where it will attack the h7-square @@StartBracket@@usually with Bd3@@EndBracket@@, in addition with Bg5 and White will be able to complete his development with O-O-O with further possibilities for the attack on the Kingside! From this move onwards @@StartBracket@@for the next 6 moves@@EndBracket@@, I decided to put an exclamation mark on each move that presents a crucial part of the attacking plan Qd4-Nc3-Qh4-Bg5-O-O-O-Rhe1! }
5... Qe7
{ This is a very suspicious move, although my students faced it a lot in Online games against lower-rated opponents. I suppose that Black thinks that it is quite logical to pin our King and continue afterward with Nc6, developing with a tempo, but what actually happens is that Black is lagging too much with Kingside development and safety. }
6. O-O
{ White escapes the pin, trying to castle, and threatens Re1 which would put Black in a lot of trouble and difficulties to defend the exposed Ne4. }
6... Nc6
{ Black uses the opportunity to develop with an idea to move our Queen back from the center. }
7. Qd1
{ This is a quiet move, but at the same time very cunning! White escapes all the possible attacks by putting the Queen back to a starting position, and threatens silent Re1 followed by Ng5! }
7... Nc5
{ Black is trying to establish the position and cover the pin with Ne6, but the Queen is already exposed! }
8. Bg5
{ A simple developing move yet very strong with a tempo that forces Black to push pawns around the King, since the Queen has no space to escape. Naturally, I see nothing wrong with  8.Re1  Ne6  9.Nc3  -Nd5 with relatively easy middlegame and lots of problems for Black to complete his development. }
8... f6
{ The only way to defend the Queen for Black, although  8...Qd6  looks possible, after  9.Qe2!  it is clear that Black didn't resolve the issues with the Queen's position which will be seized sooner or later. }
9. Bh4
{ With a small step back we keep activity and the very same plan of development with Nc3, Re1, and possible Nd5. At the same time, Black has no chance to strike back. }
9... Ne6 10. Nc3
{ Although Black has a material advantage, White is clearly better thanks to better development, opened center, and miserable Black's pieces positioned on the back rank. Black is locked down and it is hard to imagine how he could unchain. With simple ideas of Re1, Bg3 - eyeing the c7 weakness and Nd5, White gains huge initiative and enters a very enjoyable position. }
