{ Already on the third move, White has an opportunity to pick the aggressive approach with the Urusov gambit 3.d4!? or to choose a more peaceful 'bulletproof' approach with 3.d3, which enters the Bishop's opening, which will be analyzed in another chapter.  I would like to emphasize that the Urusov gambit, in the beginning, was a tricky 'joke' opening, but through time it has developed to a very high level.   The Urusov Gambit is an exciting option for the players whose main weapon and asset is their tactical ability and aggressive style, and it was shown to be a great decision for Blitz and Rapid games, especially when lower-rated players are seated on the other side hopelessly trying to find a proper plan to defend as Black! On the other side of the pond, many top-level professional players used the Urusov Gambit as a surprise weapon during significant tournaments. They showed their opponents that they are ready to go into the wilderness to snatch the win!   So, fasten your seat belts and get ready to embark on an adventurous journey! }
3... exd4
{ Black takes the pawn and defers the decision whether to enter the Urusov gambit accepted for a couple of moves! We are ready for a road full of attacking opportunities and tactical possibilities! Practically this is the only good move here by Black and other moves such as  3...d6?  and  3...Nxe4?!  lead to dubious play for Black, while  3...Nc6  leads to the Scotch gambit type of positions! }
4. Nf3
{ The main idea of the Urusov gambit is to let Black take the pawns, while we develop pieces. One may think that White permits this material advantage to Black, but don't forget that sometimes one needs to give in order to gain! Whilst Black collects the pawns, they create the space for our developed and centralized pieces, and at the same time, White builds up an attack on Black's King, which still stands exposed in the center. }
4... Nxe4
{ Black takes the challenge and dives into Urusov gambit accepted! The Urusov Gambit accepted is a fun line that can give many opponents lots of trouble, so It might be wise for Black to decline this gambit, as there’s certainly nothing wrong with going back into the Scotch gambit. One thing is sure, when Black accepts the Urusov Gambit and takes on e4, White can easily launch a big attack on the Kingside, so get ready for slamming! The show must go on! }
5. Qxd4
{ This move gives White one of the most important pieces into the action in the Urusov gambit - The Queen! It will later move onto the Kingside Qd4-Qh4, from where it will attack the h7-square @@StartBracket@@usually with Bd3@@EndBracket@@, in addition with Bg5 and White will be able to complete his development with O-O-O with further possibilities for the attack on the Kingside! From this move onwards @@StartBracket@@for the next 6 moves@@EndBracket@@, I decided to put an exclamation mark on each move that presents a crucial part of the attacking plan Qd4-Nc3-Qh4-Bg5-O-O-O-Rhe1! }
5... d5
{ I have faced this tricky move a few times during Online play. Black's idea is to give up the pawn aiming to open up some space for the pieces. However, 5...d5?! is considered suspicious if White answers correctly. }
6. Bxd5
{ We do not want to go into an endgame with 6.Qxd5, but we will accept Black's generous offer to take a pawn back. With 6.Bxd5! Black's Knight placed on e4 is under attack and he needs to step back, while we will continue with active development. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3
{ White keeps up with development and active play! It is very important to be wise and not to go for a tricky line with  7.Bxf7?!  which is suspicious due to  7...Kxf7  8.Qxd8  Bb4  9.Qd2  and after  9...Re8!  leads to an uncomfortable position for White and initiative with full compensation for Black. }
7... Nxd5
{ This is practically the only possible continuation for Black. If he tries to go for  7...Be7  instead, aiming to castle as soon as possible, White is clearly better after  8.Bg5  followed by 9.O-O-O and huge initiative. }
8. Nxd5
{ Once again, Black faces development problems. Due to the g7-weakness, Black is not able to develop with 8...Be6, and he needs to think about the direct threat of 9.Qe5! }
8... Be6
{ Threatening exposed Knight on  d5  , Black develops and aims to force the Queen's exchange. Going into an endgame would give Black a solid play and relief. One shall not forget that  8...c6?  instead is met with  9.Qe5!  with a double attack to Black's King and the c7-weakness. }
9. c4
{ White supports the Knight on d5 and at the same time takes center control. Threatening 10.Bg5 Black once again faces trouble due to badly positioned pieces. }
9... Nc6
{ With this move, Black at the same time develops and wants to kick out White's Queen from a1-h8 diagonal from where it attacks g7-square and does not allow Black to develop Bishop from  f8  . Anyway, White's pieces are very active and this is not going to stop White's activity. If Black tries with  9...c6?!  after previously mentioned  10.Bg5!  he is forced to play  10...Qd7  and White takes full control of position after  11.O-O-O  with a clear advantage and direct threat of  11...--  12.Nc7  Qxc7  13.Qd8!  Qxd8  14.Rxd8# }
10. Qe4
{ Forced to swing from the a1-h8 diagonal, the Queen swings to an open e-file pinning Black's King exposed in the center. White has a simple plan of 11.Bg5 followed by O-O-O gaining a position with all pieces activated while Black still handles development issues. }
10... Qd7
{ Black escapes from the upcoming attack of 11.Bg5 and prepares for the castle. However, White has another target to attack now, c7 is weakened! }
11. Bf4
{ After another developing tempo move, White is ready to go for the 12.O-O-O which would put Black's Queen into huge trouble. White will finish his development with the forthcoming 13.Rhe1 and all the pieces will actively control the center. Engines evaluate the position as a little better for White, but I would say that in practice, White has easy play, clear plans, easy development, and on top of all that space advantage! }
*

