9. Rhe1
{ Take a look carefully at this position - the last piece of White came into a game on the most active possible square! This is an ideal development for White and the last move has just concluded one of the crucial principles in chess - Centralisation! We are ready for the Butchering! One should not forget that  9...dxc4??  is not possible due to  10.Qxd8  Checkmate! Also, the last move gives White apart from the centralization another great tactical shot  Re7!  afterward, which usually happens after Qd4-Qh4 and Bd3 where the move h6? would be bad due to Bxh6! and g6? would be disastrous in a view of Re7! followed by Bf6! }
9... O-O
{ This move can look like a logical answer by Black, who puts the King in a safe zone and at the same time gives support to Qd8, threatening dc4. However, 9...O-O?! is considered suspicious due to the relocation of White's pieces eyeing the King right away! }
10. Bd3
{ White improves the position of the light-squared Bishop with a simple idea of Qh4 which would put pressure on h7-weakened square. It is extremely important to emphasize that  10.Qh4?!  leads to unclear position without much chances for attack anymore due to  10...Bf5!  which guards King's position very convincingly and the rest of the game would be hard for White to claim the compensation! }
10... h6
{ Black wants to resolve the problems of the h7 weakness by kicking out the Bishop from g5, but we ain't gonna go back there! }
11. Bxh6
{ I am sure that by now you got familiar with this sacrifice which puts Black into an uncomfortable position and defending issues. Black is forced to accept the sacrifice which makes the King naked! }
11... gxh6 12. Qe3
{ To avoid any complications I recommend 12.Qe3 move here instead of already seen  12.Qh4  . With a double attack on the Bishop on  e7  and a pawn  h6  , Black has no time for the defense of the Kingside. }
12... Re8
{ The only way for Black to defend the Bishop and leave some space for optional Bf8 defense of the King. }
13. Qxh6
{ White shows dominance aiming to play Ng5, followed by Bh7, or the idea of Re3-Rg3. With the late development of the Queenside, Black is not in a position to defend properly, and soon he will need to shake the hands and sign the result of 1:0. }
13... Nbd7
{ One should not forget that after  13.Qxh6  move the idea of  13...Bf8?  is stopped due to  14.Rxe8  which puts Black in a position to choose between two losing positions:  14...Qxe8  15.Qxf6  , or  14...Nxe8  15.Qh7#! }
14. Ng5
{ Faced with a direct threat of Bh7! Black is forced to passively defend with only moves, whilst White is ready for action with Re3, followed by Rg3. }
14... Nf8 15. Re3
{ And White is winning since Black can not escape from Rg3 and the upcoming mate threat of Ne6 or mating combinations on h7 once one of the Knights either on f6 or f8 move. It is quite interesting to point out that throughout the whole line, the engine was claiming that the position is equal, and after we reached the final position, it says close to winning for White! }
