{ White should realize that Black's idea of this move is not to move the Bishop from g5 away, since hg5 is not a threat due to a pinned Rook, but Black aims to play Nfd7!? followed by exchanges. }
11. Bd3
{ White prepares the pieces for when Black's King journeys on to the Kingside, which would be the most logical 'human move', aiming to create an attack on the Kingside. This move is mainly there to prevent castles, due to the now already obvious threat of the Bxh6 break! }
11... Nfd7
{ Even though it does not look natural, this is the most dangerous move for White in this position. Black threatens to go for  12.--  12...Bxg5  13.Nxg5  Qxg5  . }
12. Bxe7
{ White is forced to remove the dark-squared Bishops and hopes to make use of the semi-opened e-file and possible pins by the Rook on e1. }
12... Qxe7 13. Qg3
{ I would like to mention that the engines suggest  13.Qxe7  for White as the best computer move, and after  13...Kxe7  14.Nd4  gives initiative to White. However, I think that the best way to gain an active position for White is to continue with an attack with Queens on the board and therefore the natural 13.Qg3 move which puts pressure on the g7-weakened square. }
13... O-O
{ Black castles immediately where the King is seemingly safe due to the lack of the dark-squared Bishop in White's position. Anyway, there is still the active Rook on e1 and the uncomfortably positioned Bishop on e6 which is exposed to several pins. }
14. Ne2
{ White aims to relocate the pieces on the Kingside with the idea of Nf4 or Nd4. It is clear that Black has no time to escape the pin, so he must search for another way of activation. }
14... Nc5
{ At the same time, Black supports the Bishop on e6 and threatens to remove our Bishop from d3. However, this exchange would lead to a possible activation of White's Rooks, so White does not need to defend here. }
15. Nf4
{ Not only that White finally puts pressure on Be6, but also has a hidden threat of Nh5, compromising Black's Kingside. }
15... Nxd3+ 16. Rxd3
{ White aims to go for Nh5 and to double the Rooks afterward with the full control of the e-file and e6 square. }
16... Nd7
{ Black grabs the last ticket for active play and development aiming to play Rae8 and to give support to the e6 square. }
17. Nh5
{ With this move White forces Black to push the pawns around the King and to make new targets for an attack. At the same time, Black has no time to develop due to an immediate Qg7 mate threat. }
17... g6 18. Nf4
{ Although engines do not cheer for White's position, I am sure that in practice the position promises very nice play for White. It is not clear how Black can strike back and free up the position from the pins. With White's upcoming idea of Rde3 and weakened squares to prey on - e6 and g6, White has a nice compensation and the possibility to continue with h4, as it was shown in the game between Filipchenko, V - Volodarsky, Y ICCF email 2015. }
*

