{ White is swinging the Queen over to the kingside and keeps the Black's Queen pinned by the Rd1. Despite that, d4 square is now available to a Knight which will put Be6 into trouble, while Bc4 remains untouchable! }
10... Nbd7
{ 10...Nbd7 is the most natural follow-up for Black who develops the last minor piece and breaks the Queen's pin at last. }
11. Bd3
{ White retreats the Bishop back onto the most active square and aims to stop Black from going with  11...O-O??  due to  12.Bxh7! }
11... Qa5
{ I have seen a lot of games where Black attempts to play on the Queenside with the O-O-O. But one should not forget that Black's Bishop on e6 does not have any support anymore and it is exposed to attacks. }
12. Nd4
{ Due to the lack of the squares for an escape with the Bishop, Black is forced to give the pawn back to White and to enter this terrible position with equal material, and lots of activity for White }
12... O-O-O
{ Of course,  12...Nc5  instead would allow  13.Bf5!  and once again Black can not protect the Bishop on  e6  . If he chooses to continue with  13...Bxf5  14.Nxf5  there is no salvation for the poor Bishop on  e7! }
13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Rxe6
{ With full control of the e-file White can go for a smooth plan with Kb1 as a prophylactic move that defends the a2 point, followed by Rde1. }
14... Bb4
{ The most resilient move for Black who threatens to ruin our pawn structure around the King. Have in mind that  14...Rhe8  can be answered with the previously mentioned plan,  15.Kb1  , followed by  15...--  16.Rde1  and White is much better due to the active pieces and issues for Black to open up some space for any type of action. }
15. Ne2
{ With the idea of Nd4 or Nf4, White takes control of the play. One should not forget that a2 is not really hanging since  Bb4  would be undefended,  15...Qxa2??  16.Qxb4! }
15... Rhe8
{ Black keeps the fight for e-file and has the support by Bishop on b4, since White is not able anymore to go for Rde1. Anyway, Black can not benefit a lot from it, as you will see later. If  15...h6  was played instead, after  16.Bxf6  gxf6  White puts the King in a safe zone, defending the a2-square with  17.Kb1  and has a slight advantage due to our space control, active Rook on  e6  , and a majority with 3 pawns against 2 on the Kingside, which leaves White with the option of creating a passed pawn later on. }
16. Rxe8 Rxe8 17. Kb1
{ I am sure that you are already familiar with this prophylactic move, which keeps White's King in a safe zone, and at the same time, gives support to the attacked a2-pawn. White is slightly better with more chances to play for a win thanks to the possibility of creating a passed pawn on the Kingside as it was previously mentioned.   One should not forget that White has a Bishop pair here, which is considered to be an advantage in semi-opened positions such as this one. It is very important to notice that h7 weakness is not really hanging due to Rxe2, so we should not hurry to take it, but White should focus on the idea of Nd4, possibly followed by Nf5 which would provoke weaknesses on Black's Kingside. }
