9. Rhe1
{ Take a look carefully at this position - the last piece of White came into a game on the most active possible square! This is an ideal development for White and the last move has just concluded one of the crucial principles in chess - Centralisation! We are ready for the Butchering! One should not forget that  9...dxc4??  is not possible due to  10.Qxd8  Checkmate! Also, the last move gives White apart from the centralization another great tactical shot  Re7!  afterward, which usually happens after Qd4-Qh4 and Bd3 where the move h6? would be bad due to Bxh6! and g6? would be disastrous in a view of Re7! followed by Bf6! }
9... Be6
{ Black chooses the most resilient move aiming to block our Rook nicely placed on the open e-file and makes final preparations for the castle. }
10. Qh4
{ White is swinging the Queen over to the kingside and keeps the Black's Queen pinned by the Rd1. Despite that, d4 square is now available to a Knight which will put Be6 into trouble, while Bc4 remains untouchable! }
10... Nbd7
{ 10...Nbd7 is the most natural follow-up for Black who develops the last minor piece and breaks the Queen's pin at last. }
11. Bd3
{ White retreats the Bishop back onto the most active square and aims to stop Black from going with  11...O-O??  due to  12.Bxh7! }
11... Nc5 12. Nd4
{ I need to emphasize that here White's threat is not to remove the light-squared Bishop on  e6  but to play  12...--  13.Bf5!  and to further add on the attack on Be6. That would force Black to open the e-file for the Rook on  e1  , and Black's Be7 would be in an uncomfortable pin. }
12... Ng8
{ With this very interesting move, Black intends to trade as many pieces as possible and to enter an endgame with a pawn up. Of course, we are not going to allow that, as you will see soon. }
13. f4
{ White defends the Bishop on  g5  and keeps the same threat of Bf5! Additionally, Black would be in an uncomfortable situation if he tries to chase the dark-squared Bishop with  13...h6?!  due to  14.Bxe7  Qxe7  and after  15.Qg3  White has a double threat of f5, and Qxg7!   Of course, if instead, Black plays  13...h6?!  14.Bxe7  Nxe7  White is winning after  15.f5!  Bd7  16.f6!  and White will dominate all of the dark squares, while the Black King will be locked in the center. }
13... Bxg5
{ Faced with the previously explained threats of Bf5 and Be7, followed by f5, Black is forced to go for  13...Bxg5 }
14. fxg5
{ We gained what we wanted! The position is open, and Black's King is still in the center without a proper plan of development. Of course, the idea of White is the same, Bf5 is the threat that Black needs to stop if he wants to stay alive! }
14... h6
{ Black keeps chasing a pawn and wants to exchange the Queens. With all the centralized pieces, which control all the important squares, White can finally realize the long-prepared plan! }
15. Bf5
{ White accepts to go into an endgame with equalized material, but the huge activity of the pieces, and lots of weaknesses for Black. However, if you insist to avoid an endgame, it is possible to continue with  15.Nxe6!?  Nxe6  16.Re5  defending the  g5  pawn, and after  16...Qd6  White has initiative after  17.Rde1  , aiming to play against  17...O-O-O  with  18.g6!  followed by Bf5 and pressure on Black's pinned Knight on e6. }
15... Qxg5+ 16. Qxg5 hxg5 17. b4
{ This is a very important intermediary move that gives White chances for a win. We do not hurry to take the pawn back since all the exchanges would allow Black to stabilize, but we aim to keep Black's King pinned as long as possible. }
17... Nd7 18. Bxe6 fxe6 19. Nxe6
{ And White has a small advantage thanks to active pieces and three threats at the same time: Nc7, Ng7, and Ng5. One shall not forget that Black is unable to go for O-O-O since Ne6 controls the d8 square, and Black still faces difficulties to avoid the pin of Re1. }
