9. Rhe1
{ Take a look carefully at this position - the last piece of White came into a game on the most active possible square! This is an ideal development for White and the last move has just concluded one of the crucial principles in chess - Centralisation! We are ready for the Butchering! One should not forget that  9...dxc4??  is not possible due to  10.Qxd8  Checkmate! Also, the last move gives White apart from the centralization another great tactical shot  Re7!  afterward, which usually happens after Qd4-Qh4 and Bd3 where the move h6? would be bad due to Bxh6! and g6? would be disastrous in a view of Re7! followed by Bf6! }
9... Be6
{ Black chooses the most resilient move aiming to block our Rook nicely placed on the open e-file and makes final preparations for the castle. }
10. Qh4
{ White is swinging the Queen over to the kingside and keeps the Black's Queen pinned by the Rd1. Despite that, d4 square is now available to a Knight which will put Be6 into trouble, while Bc4 remains untouchable! }
10... Nbd7
{ 10...Nbd7 is the most natural follow-up for Black who develops the last minor piece and breaks the Queen's pin at last. }
11. Bd3
{ White retreats the Bishop back onto the most active square and aims to stop Black from going with  11...O-O??  due to  12.Bxh7! }
11... Nc5 12. Nd4
{ I need to emphasize that here White's threat is not to remove the light-squared Bishop on  e6  but to play  12...--  13.Bf5!  and to further add on the attack on Be6. That would force Black to open the e-file for the Rook on  e1  , and Black's Be7 would be in an uncomfortable pin. }
12... h6
{ It is obvious that Black does not threaten to take the Bishop with  gxh5  , because the Rook on  h8  would be hanging, but aims to play  13...Nfd7!  with an idea to force the trades. Also, it is important to understand the position and know that Black will not go for the castle on the Kingside, because of the previously mentioned threats of Bxh6! but also, it is not easy for Black to try to escape with the King by castling long.   For example,  12...Qd7?!  would be met with  13.f4!  and Black can not defend the threat of  13...--  14.f5! }
13. Bf5
{ Nothing can stop us now to continue with the previously mentioned plan of Bf5 and Black needs to think about saving the Bishop on e6. }
13... Nfd7
{ Black shows that he is tough with this move! He defends the weakened spot on e6 with an attack on the black squared Bishop on g5, threatening to take it with Bg5! Don't forget that  13...O-O?!  would face the well-known motive of  14.Bxh6!  sacrifice and after  14...gxh6  15.Qxh6  Black has issues defending White's idea of  Re3  , followed by  Rg3  .   Also,  13...Nh7?!  instead would lead to a clearly better position for White after  14.Bxe7  Qxe7  15.Qxe7  Kxe7  and with  16.b4!  Black needs to step back and the  e6  spot will not be defended anymore. }
14. Bxe7
{ White is obviously forced to go for a trade, but of course, we will keep the Queens on the board with compensation for the pawn thanks to the active pieces! }
14... Qxe7 15. Qg4
{ White steps back and avoids the Queen exchange, and with the idea of b4, White wants to take full control over the light squares. Of course, the attack on the Kingside can be improved by Re3, followed by Re1 and Rg3, and White has nice compensation for a pawn as it can be seen in the game between Bauer, R - Grabliauskas, V ICCF email 2014. Although the engines are not delighted to evaluate this position in favor of White, I would say that according to my long chess coaching experience, this position is hard to be defended by a human in a real game, and that in real chess without engines, White has nice chances for the desirable result 1-0! }
