{ White develops the third minor piece, cunningly prepares for Bg5, followed by the long castle. To one, it might look logical to hurry up with putting the King into a safe zone @@StartBracket@@Kingside castle@@EndBracket@@, but the whole idea of the Urusov Gambit is to make the best out of the position by going into long castles! It is very important to follow the most accurate moves that did not allow Black to consolidate promptly. In that fashion, it is important to point out that  6.Bg5?!  would be suspicious due to  6...Nc6!  7.Qh4  and Black stabilizes and looks even better after  7...d5!  while after  6.Bg5?!  Nc6  if White goes for  7.Qe3  Black is better after  7...Qe7!  with a clear pawn up! }
6... Nc6
{ From my Online experience you are going to get this move in most of your games. There is a logical reason for that, it is developing move, it chases Queen on d4 away with the tempo and looks like Black gains an important move to consolidate himself. In the reality, things do not seem to work that easy for Black, as you are about to see... }
7. Qh4
{ After Black has developed a Knight with a tempo, White swings the Queen to the Kingside where the action will be taken.  7.Qh4  will be followed by Bg5 and O-O-O, altogether with Rhe1, which will conclude White's development.   The alternative  7.Qd3!?  deserves attention too. With the idea of  7...--  8.a3  stopping Black's 8...Nb4, and followed by  8...--  9.Bf4  and  9...--  10.O-O-O   White has an interesting position, as it can be seen in the game played between Tomek, D - Sydlik, J email 2012. }
7... Bb4
{ This move by Black deserves attention since they threaten to take on c3 doubling the pawns our pawns. Anyway, this exchange would not give only a weakness to White, but also the Bishop pair which is very valuable in open positions such as this one. }
8. O-O
{ White is concluding the development and threatening Re1+, not worrying a lot about Bc3 exchange, since the Bishop pair would be a nice weapon to gain. }
8... Bxc3 9. bxc3
{ With the Bishop pair and development advantage, White for sure has compensation for the pawn. After Re1, Bg5, Rad1, Black will be stuck trying to find a plan while White has all of the pieces activated. }
9... O-O 10. Re1
{ White has a lot of options here. With the interesting 10.Re1!? we prepare for Bg5 and Rad1. However, also  10.Rb1!?  could be played with initiative and plan of Re1, Bd3, Bg5, or  10.Bg5!?  when after  10...h6  Black gets into problems after  11.Bxh6  gxh6  12.Qxh6  with nice play for White, as it was played in a game between Nightingale, D - Serazeev, A ICCF email 2013. }
10... Ne7
{ Black's idea is to swing the Knight from e7 to g6, giving a support to its King and giving an attack to the Qh4. }
11. Bg5
{ Meanwhile, White continues with development and activates the Bishop pair. }
11... Ng6 12. Qg3
{ We put the Queen into safety and we will continue with the activation of the pieces. It is already obvious that Black has difficulties with development and how to find a proper plan to continue. }
12... d6
{ Basically, this is the only continuation for Black with the idea of Bd7, Bc7, Qd7, and consolidation. However, that plan can not be realized easily. }
13. Rab1
{ Putting the last piece into a game, White takes control of the b7-square and does not allow Black to develop. With two rooks on the open files, Bishop pair, and the idea of h4 and h5 at some moment, White has a nice position to play and a well-looking initiative. }
