7. Qh4
{ After Black has developed a Knight with a tempo, White swings the Queen to the Kingside where the action will be taken.  7.Qh4  will be followed by Bg5 and O-O-O, altogether with Rhe1, which will conclude White's development.   The alternative  7.Qd3!?  deserves attention too. With the idea of  7...--  8.a3  stopping Black's 8...Nb4, and followed by  8...--  9.Bf4  and  9...--  10.O-O-O   White has an interesting position, as it can be seen in the game played between Tomek, D - Sydlik, J email 2012. }
7... Ne7
{ Black aims to relocate the Knight to the Kingside with the idea to create a safe environment for the King. At the same time, Black wants to hunt White's Queen and move it away from the h4 square. However, White will now punish Black's repeated moves with the same piece in the opening. }
8. Bg5
{ In order to gain the advantage against Black's slow action, White keeps developing and wishes to castle long as soon as possible. One shall not forget that after O-O-O, White will have only one piece undeveloped, which will be activated after Rhe1, but Black will be jammed. }
8... Ng6
{ Black successfully concluded the idea of relocation with an attack on our Queen, but it is questionable how much did he benefit from this maneuver. }
9. Qd4
{ White puts the Queen back, on the most active available square. The idea stays the same, fast O-O-O followed by Rhe1 which would put Black into trouble. }
9... c6
{ Black picks up the resilient move with the idea of d5 which would block our light-squared Bishop. Anyway, it is obvious that Black is late with development, and White needs to use that to create an attack. }
10. O-O-O
{ Certainly, we can be satisfied with White's position here. With all active pieces and forthcoming Rhe1, it is clear that White will have more than enough compensation for a pawn. }
10... Be7
{ Black wishes to castle and to avoid any checks on the open e-file. If  10...d5?!  was played instead, White would have a huge initiative after  11.Nxd5!  cxd5  12.Bb5  when Black is forced to play  12...Bd7  and after  13.Rhe1  Be7  14.Bxf6  O-O  15.Bxe7  Nxe7  White is clearly better with  16.Bd3!  and the idea of  17.Bxh7!  Black has an isolated  d5  pawn, lone King, and needs to find a way to prevent the Bxh7 threat. }
11. Bxf6
{ This is a very good move which forces Black to once again delay castling. Although White gives up the Bishop pair, one should not forget that Black will have an outpost on d6 which can be easily conquered by White. }
11... Bxf6
{ It is clear that Black wouldn't resolve the problem after  11...gxf6  due to  12.Rhe1!  and huge development advantage for White. }
12. Rhe1+
{ With this very important intermediate check, we force Black to once again take a step back. }
12... Ne7
{ This is practically the only move for Black, since  12...Be7?  doesn't work because of hanging  g7  pawn. On the other hand,  12...Kf8  would be met with  13.Qc5!  and after  13...Be7  White takes it all with  14.Rd6!!  Bxd6  15.Qxd6  Kg8  and after  16.h4  , the threat of  Ng5  , White is winning. Mainly, Black can not defend weakened  f7  square, and it looks impossible to develop Bc8, Ra8 and Rh8. }
13. Qc5
{ Once again, White chooses the most active square for the Queen, putting Black into development problems. The plan is Rd6, stopping Black from unchaining the pieces, followed by Ne4, Re3, and Black will have lots of difficulties getting the pieces out. }
