{ Black takes the pawn and defers the decision whether to enter the Urusov gambit accepted for a couple of moves! We are ready for a road full of attacking opportunities and tactical possibilities! Practically this is the only good move here by Black and other moves such as  3...d6?  and  3...Nxe4?!  lead to dubious play for Black, while  3...Nc6  leads to the Scotch gambit type of positions! }
4. Nf3
{ The main idea of the Urusov gambit is to let Black take the pawns, while we develop pieces. One may think that White permits this material advantage to Black, but don't forget that sometimes one needs to give in order to gain! Whilst Black collects the pawns, they create the space for our developed and centralized pieces, and at the same time, White builds up an attack on Black's King, which still stands exposed in the center. }
4... Nxe4
{ Black takes the challenge and dives into Urusov gambit accepted! The Urusov Gambit accepted is a fun line that can give many opponents lots of trouble, so It might be wise for Black to decline this gambit, as there’s certainly nothing wrong with going back into the Scotch gambit. One thing is sure, when Black accepts the Urusov Gambit and takes on e4, White can easily launch a big attack on the Kingside, so get ready for slamming! The show must go on! }
5. Qxd4
{ This move gives White one of the most important pieces into the action in the Urusov gambit - The Queen! It will later move onto the Kingside Qd4-Qh4, from where it will attack the h7-square @@StartBracket@@usually with Bd3@@EndBracket@@, in addition with Bg5 and White will be able to complete his development with O-O-O with further possibilities for the attack on the Kingside! From this move onwards @@StartBracket@@for the next 6 moves@@EndBracket@@, I decided to put an exclamation mark on each move that presents a crucial part of the attacking plan Qd4-Nc3-Qh4-Bg5-O-O-O-Rhe1! }
5... Nf6
{ Practically the only move! Black decides to stay solid by moving the piece back into safety. Our main aim is to take advantage of the opportunity to play active and force Black to pay out the price while he was collecting pawns. It is quite interesting that engines already favor Black a lot here, but we won't bite that! }
6. Nc3
{ White develops the third minor piece, cunningly prepares for Bg5, followed by the long castle. To one, it might look logical to hurry up with putting the King into a safe zone @@StartBracket@@Kingside castle@@EndBracket@@, but the whole idea of the Urusov Gambit is to make the best out of the position by going into long castles! It is very important to follow the most accurate moves that did not allow Black to consolidate promptly. In that fashion, it is important to point out that  6.Bg5?!  would be suspicious due to  6...Nc6!  7.Qh4  and Black stabilizes and looks even better after  7...d5!  while after  6.Bg5?!  Nc6  if White goes for  7.Qe3  Black is better after  7...Qe7!  with a clear pawn up! }
6... Nc6
{ From my Online experience you are going to get this move in most of your games. There is a logical reason for that, it is developing move, it chases Queen on d4 away with the tempo and looks like Black gains an important move to consolidate himself. In the reality, things do not seem to work that easy for Black, as you are about to see... }
7. Qh4
{ After Black has developed a Knight with a tempo, White swings the Queen to the Kingside where the action will be taken.  7.Qh4  will be followed by Bg5 and O-O-O, altogether with Rhe1, which will conclude White's development.   The alternative  7.Qd3!?  deserves attention too. With the idea of  7...--  8.a3  stopping Black's 8...Nb4, and followed by  8...--  9.Bf4  and  9...--  10.O-O-O   White has an interesting position, as it can be seen in the game played between Tomek, D - Sydlik, J email 2012. }
7... Be7
{ Black chooses the most resilient move aiming to castle, but then they would be facing the same threats coming after Bg5 and O-O-O. }
8. Bg5
{ From this position, where White obviously has way better development, it is of great importance to once more remind Black of our plan - an attack on the Kingside and putting Rooks on the open d and e files after O-O-O! }
8... d5
{ Black tries to get some fresh air for the pieces and to consolidate after  9...Be6  . Anyway, one should not forget that White will have now a new target for attacks, and that is exactly  d5  pawn! }
9. O-O-O
{ White defends the Bishop on c4 with the most active move, castling! Black is now forced to think about the defense of d5 weakened pawn! }
9... Be6
{ It looks like that after 9...Be6 Black got stabilized, but the activity of White's pieces allows us to proceed with an aggressive approach! }
10. Bxd5
{ Thanks to good positioned Rook on d1, and pinned Black's Queen, White is in a position to sacrifice the piece and get it back very soon as it will be shown later. }
10... Nxd5
{ No matter how Black chooses to accept the sacrifice, both options lead to the same position. After  10...Bxd5  11.Nxd5  Nxd5  12.c4!  the position transposes to 10...Nxd5 which we consider here as the main move for Black. }
11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. c4
{ And as it was said, White uses the advantage of good development and active pieces to equalize the material and keep the activity, after this little tactical blow. }
12... h6
{ You should notice that Black does not threaten to immediately take the Bishop on g5 with a pawn, but he aims to gain the material after Bxg5, Nxg5 and Qxg5! }
13. Rxd5
{ White equalizes the material and gives support to hanging Bishop on g5, aiming to continue actively with Re1, which would put Black into an uncomfortable pin. }
13... Bxg5+ 14. Rxg5
{ This is a very important move which gives Black difficulties to decide how to continue. Due to pinned Rook on  h8  , Black can not proceed with  14...hxg5?  and he is forced to think about how to keep the King safe which is stuck in the center.   However, the alternative for White can be  14.Nxg5  , when after  14...Qf6?!  Black faces  15.Re1  Ne7?  when White takes control after  16.Nf3  Rd8  17.Rde5  Rd7  18.Qg4  threatening Re7! }
14... Qf6
{ This is practically the only move that gives Black equal chances for a play.  14...O-O?  would be met with  15.Qxh6!  so Black needs to search for the development of the King on the Queenside. }
15. Qe4+ Qe7 16. Rg4
{ White accepts to enter objectively drawish endgame, but with better-positioned pieces. It must be said that a tiny activity advantage is not for sure granted of a victory, but with pressure on the open files, it can be possible for White to win the game.   I want to mention that engines suggest for White  16.Qxe7  evaluating the position around equal, and after  16...Nxe7  17.Rg4  is recommended.   However, I think that in practical chess, White has more chances for a win with a human move such as  16.Rg4  . If Black insists on entering an endgame now, due to the hanging g7-pawn, White would gain two open files for the Rooks and a more active position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) The Wild Alternative: The Urusov Gambit"]
[Black "Urusov Gambit Accepted: 3...exd4 4.Nf3 #38"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever - The Bishop's opening, which is deeply analyzed within this course.   However, entering the Bishop's opening also gives you the opportunity to enter aggressive and wild lines, such as the Urusov gambit. As an introduction to the wild play within this opening, 2.Bc4 controls the important d5 square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, attacks the most vulnerable spot in Black's position on f7, and prepares White to complete development with O-O afterward. }
2... Nf6
{ This move is the most consequential continuation by Black, and believe it or not, it happens in more than 80% of the games after 2.Bc4 according to the statistics! It is also very important to mention that the Urusov gambit would not be possible without it! Line 2...Nc6 leads to a Vienna Hybrid variation and it is covered in the Bishop's opening part. }
