11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. c4
{ And as it was said, White uses the advantage of good development and active pieces to equalize the material and keep the activity, after this little tactical blow. }
12... Bxg5+ 13. Nxg5
{ Of course, White takes the piece with a Knight and declines the offer to exchange the Queens. One shall not forget that Black still needs to deal with the pinned Bishop on d5, and that after Rxd5 White will have another active piece that joined the attack. }
13... Qf6
{ Black decides to move the Queen away from the upcoming Rd5.  If Black plays  13...h6  instead, aiming to take the Knight on g5 with a Queen, White has an important intermediate move  14.Rhe1  which comes with a check, and after  14...Kf8  15.Rxd5  Qf6  White is clearly better with  16.Re3!  threatening to play Rf3 with an attack on  f7  weakness.   On the other side, Black can go for  13...Qe7  escaping the forthcoming attack of Rd5, but then White keeps the clear advantage with  14.cxd5  Ne5  , followed by  15.Qa4!  and the idea of Rhe1. }
14. Rxd5
{ With pieces positioned in the center and a huge pressure on Black, White threatens to play Re1. Black has problems putting the King in a safe zone, due to a weakened h7 pawn fully controlled by White. }
14... h6 15. Re1+
{ After this check Black can forget about putting the King in a safe zone and the Rook from h8 will hardly get active. }
15... Kf8 16. Re3
{ And White is clearly better with a threat of Rf3 which puts pressure on the f7 weakness. Black is too inactive and can not unchain for a while, and the Rook on h8 does not have a bright future. }
