9. O-O-O
{ White has just completed his development with the Queenside castle and only one piece left to be developed - Rhe1 is coming soon into the game as well! }
9... O-O
{ Even though the 9... O-O? looks like a natural development move, it can be harshly punished by White thanks to active pieces eyeing the Black's King! }
10. Bd3
{ A very important move which gives a headache to the Black side. With a simple threat of Bf6, White wants to mate with Qh7! }
10... g6
{ This is the only defense from the mate threat, but now Black has weak dark squares around the King. Have in mind that  10...h6?!  in such positions always faces  11.Bxh6!  gxh6  12.Qxh6  and White is winning with the idea of Nd5 which would attack Black's Nf6 defender. Black can not defend against the Qh7 mate, or he needs to give up the material. }
11. Rhe1
{ White starts to pressure dark squares on the Black's side. With a threat of Re7, followed by Bf6, Black would not be able to defend mate after Qh6 and Qg7. Black is practically forced to play the only defending moves now. }
11... Be6
{ At the same time, Black develops and blocks the previously mentioned idea of Re7. }
12. g4
{ I recently came up with this novelty which appeared to be undefendable by Black. White threatens Bf5, compromising Black's blocker on the e-file. Practically, the idea is to force Black to open e-file and to give us the possibility to gain the dark-squares after Rxe7 followed by Bxf6! }
12... Bxg4
{ This is not the happiest answer for Black, but other options would not help him a lot. If he plays  12...Nxg4?  instead, White wins after  13.Rxe6!  followed by Qg4 and two pieces for the Rook, which is considered to be a material advantage.   12...Re8  would face previously mentioned  13.Bf5!  and White again forces Black to clears the way for  Re7  motive! }
13. Rxe7
{ And finally White takes the full control of the dark squares. However Black decides to continue, he would not be able to defend after Bf6 with ideas of Qh6-Qg7#. }
