{ White goes for the previously mentioned plan, keeps the King safe on b1 square, and prepares for Nd2 with Ne4, at the same time avoiding the pin which would possibly be achieved by Black after Bg5. }
13... g6
{ This is a very good prophylactic move by Black who is now basically stoping the idea of Kb1, Nd2 and Ne4. However, with g6 Black gave another target to be attacked. }
14. h4
{ White is set to storm with a pawn! With the idea of h5, White threatens to open the space around Black's weakened King.   As an alternative,  14.c3  was played in a game between Burkett, M - Helmbrecht, J LSS email 2010, where White had an idea to play against dark-squared Black's Bishop.  14...Bg7  15.h4!  threatening h5, Black answered with  15...Qd7  with an idea of Rae8, and the game continued with  16.h5  Rac8  17.hxg6  hxg6  18.Qh4  with great initiative and attack for White, and the idea of Ng5 and Rh1. }
14... h6
{ Black tries to block White's attack and wants to play g5 if White continues with the idea of h5.   However, that would make new outposts on the light squares for the White's pieces. If Black decides to block White's attack with  14...h5?  he faces  15.g4!  which puts Black's King into an uncomfortable situation. }
15. h5
{ White goes further with the idea to open the space around Black's King. As an alternative, White can also go for  15.g4!  and after  15...Bg7  16.g5  h5  17.Kb1  White puts the King into safety and has decent initiative. }
15... g5 { After 15.h5! Black is forced to try to block the Kingside. } 16. Nh2
{ This is a very important move with the idea of Ng4, threatening black squares around Black's King, and opening space up for the upcoming f4 which weakens the pawn structure around the Black's King. }
16... Bg7
{ Black escapes from the attack of possible Ng4 and tries to surround the weakened King with a defending piece.   In a few games, I saw that Black has played  16...Kh8  and after  17.f4!  gxf4  White is slightly better with  18.Nxf4!  - pawn on f4 is hanging and White has a simple plan of Kb1 and c3 which blocks black squared Bg7. }
17. f4
{ White keeps an attack on Black's bad pawn structure. A simple idea of the further action is Kb1- a very important move that puts King in a safe zone from where it avoids any checks from the dark squares, followed by g4 and Nf3. }
17... gxf4 18. Qxf4
{ White has very nice initiative and compensation for a pawn. With the newest h6 weakness, which will be easily targeted with the upcoming Ng4, White has a plan to go for Re3-Rg3, or Rf1 eyeing f7 weakness. One shall not forget that the Knight on d5 stands very proud in the center @@StartBracket@@takes quite a big space@@EndBracket@@, pressures the c7 pawn @@StartBracket@@which turns out to be a weakness for the rest of the game@@EndBracket@@ and Black can not move it out of there that just like that! }
