9... Bb4
{ Black plays twice with the same piece in the opening, but he tries to stop mentioned Ne4 idea with a pin of the Knight and the Rook. }
10. a3
{ As the Bishop bothers us with the plans, we simply kick it out. Black is basically forced to take the Knight and clear the way through the dark squares. }
10... Bxd2 11. Bxd2
{ The position may look solid, but White has nasty threats I want to introduce. The idea is  11...--  12.Nxd4  and if Black naturally responses with  12...Nxd4  it will be game over after  13.Bb4  Kg8  14.Qxd4!  Black cannot take back due to a weakened back rank and Re8 mate threat! }
11... Qxf6
{ Taking a pawn does not prevent the described threat of Nd4! White dives into a clearly better position with a beautiful sacrifice! }
12. Nxd4
{ Black has a hard time deciding what to do here. White threatens to proceed with 13. Nc6 and 14. Bb4 as the position of the King on f8 cannot be improved.   If Black continues with  12...Nxd4  he faces the previously mentioned line with  13.Bb4  and back rank mate after  13...Kg8  14.Re8  .   On the other hand, if Black goes with  12...Qxd4  13.Bb4!  comes with a similar follow-up as Black still faces issues with the defense of the 8th rank and practically needs to proceed with  13...Nxb4  giving up the Queen  14.Qxd4  ,  with winning position for White. }
