{ Although this move may look illogical, it can be dangerous. Black aims to activate pieces through the g-file eyeing our King on g1. However, this will not end up that way, as you will see soon! }
9. Nbd2
{ Whenever you have a chance to develop with a tempo attack - you should do it! An active development move buys time for future actions. Not only that Black's pawn on c4 hangs, but we want to centralize and cover important dark squares after the forthcoming Ne4! }
9... Bb4
{ Black plays twice with the same piece in the opening, but he tries to stop mentioned Ne4 idea with a pin of the Knight and the Rook. }
10. a3
{ As the Bishop bothers us with the plans, we simply kick it out. Black is basically forced to take the Knight and clear the way through the dark squares. }
10... Bxd2 11. Bxd2
{ The position may look solid, but White has nasty threats I want to introduce. The idea is  11...--  12.Nxd4  and if Black naturally responses with  12...Nxd4  it will be game over after  13.Bb4  Kg8  14.Qd4!  Black cannot take back due to a weakened back rank and Re8 mate threat! }
11... Bg4
{ Black uses a development move to stop the threat of 12.Nd4, but we will practice the same 'kick-out' rule to move the pieces that stops to take actions! }
12. h3
{ With a simple 12. h3 we force Black to step back but also we might accomplish more. If Black proceeds with  12...Bxf3?!  here, White gains a clearly better position with  13.Qxf3  Qxf6  and after an exchange of the Queens with  14.Qxf6  gxf6  Black faces issues with bad pawn structure and weak dark squares. After  15.Bh6  Kg8  White has nasty threats after  16.a4  of Ra3-Rg3. }
12... Bh5
{ Black practically needs to keep the tension and to hold the Knight on f3. But as you will see, this does not work either! }
13. Bg5
{ We continue with active development and frightening threats. The idea is, of course, fxg7 and the Queen on d8 would be hanging. Black needs to react immediately. }
13... gxf6 14. Bh6+
{ It is the fact that Black has two paws up here, but thanks to better pieces and exposed King on f8, White has a better position. }
14... Kg8 15. Nxd4
{ Once again, White uses the weakened back rank to sharpen the things, as it could be seen in the game Bischof,G-Rades,A DESC email 2006.   If Black accepts the Queen's sacrifice with  15...Bxd1  there is a beautiful answer of  16.Nxc6  bxc6  and  17.Raxd1  that puts Black's Queen into huge trouble. The threat is Re3-Rg3# and it is questionable if Black can defend it. }
