9... Qd6
{ It looks that Black keeps the Bishop on c5 protected with this move, and prevents the Qh5 move after trades through the e6 square, However, it will be shown soon that White anyway gets the winning position following the same path. }
10. Nxe6 fxe6
{ Black's King has opened again and that is what we aimed for. Anyway, you should not rush here with a check, but first put Black into double trouble! }
11. fxg7
{ With an important intermediary move, White moves the Rook from the h7 pawn. Not only that the pawn on h7 will hang after the forthcoming Qh5, but Black's King will end up in the mating net due to the Bg5 threat. }
11... Rg8
{ Black needs to follow the only move, putting the Rook in a clumsy position. }
12. Qh5+
{ White has several threats with a single check. The hanging pawn on h7is the less important here, as we have more dangerous ideas. First of all, Black needs to search for a proper square for the King, but this is impossible to reach. White can continue with either Qf7, Bg5, or further developing, depending on Black's answer here. However, all the moves lead to a winning position now. }
12... Kd7
{ This is the most solid square for King at this point and Black hopes to include the Rook from a8 in the game, as soon as possible. If  12...Kd8  instead, Black would face huge troubles with  Rg8  after  13.Qf7  as there is no defense from all the threats: Qg8; Bg5-Re6.   After a possible  12...Ke7  White wins in a similar way with  13.Bg5  and the forthcoming Qf7. }
13. Nd2
{ Once again, Black faces an unstoppable threat of Ne4. It is clear that everything hangs in Black's position and he simply doesn't have time to consolidate. After the Ne4 move, there will be Nf6 as an option, but of course, the main idea will be to double attack Qd6 and Bc5. }
