{ This is practically the only move for Black that gives them a solid position. Many times I faced suspicious  6...Ng4?!  instead which leads to very good play and initiative for White after simple  7.Bf4  White holds the pawn and threatens to move a clumsy Knight from g4 with a possible 8. h3 move.   Sometimes you might be able to see Black playing  6...Ng8?  here as well. Not only that 6...Ng8 looks bad, indeed it is a bad move that opposes development rules. With  7.Ng5!  ,  White will immediately put the pressure on the weakened f7 pawn and after  7...Nh6  8.Re1  is almost game over as White has a huge advantage. The plan is simple: Qh5 or Qf3- improving the pressure on the f7 pawn, c3- with breaking the center, centralizing pieces with possible Ne4. }
7. exf6
{ As a natural follow-up, White opens the e-file for the Rook and puts pressure on Black's King. Black needs to delay development for a while and White will try to benefit out from it. }
7... dxc4 8. Re1+
{ I must emphasize the  8.fxg7!?  is an alternative option for those who intend to play the Max Lange attack for a long time. The 8. Re1 move is a surprising weapon that can be used from time to time with great success. However, if you wish to have Max Lange as one of the main weapons, you would need to bother more with the previously mentioned 8. fxg7!? In this course, I would put 8. Re1 is important, as it would shorten your preparations a lot and it will make this opening easier to learn. Do not be suspicious, you will continue butchering! }
8... Be6
{ This is the most logical and the most common answer for Black here. Not only that it blocks the check, but gives hope to Black that he will be just on time to castle alongside and keep the King safe. }
9. Ng5
{ White shall use all the instruments to try to keep Black's King in the center. Not only that we immediately pressure just developed Bishop on e6, but more importantly, Queen gets space to play, eyeing h5 square especially. With many tricks hanging in the air, this is a very dangerous position for Black who needs to follow the exact moves to keep it up. }
9... Qd7
{ Black has a nice idea to proceed with long castle here and hopes to hold the 7th rank after the Be6 trade. Anyway, White has something else in the mind here! }
10. fxg7
{ If the Black's idea was to hold the g7 spot with the Queen, we will not allow it! Faced with a slightly different order of moves, Black has no way to escape. Of course, immediate   10.Nxe6  would be winning as well as after  10...fxe6  11.Qh5  Black cannot defend the Bishop on c5 while he is under the check. However, 10. fxg7 is a little bit more precise. }
10... Rg8
{ Black must feel miserable here facing the threat of Ne6 and Qh5. He did not have a better choice after bad 9...Qd7? }
11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Qh5+
{ And after only 12 moves of play White got a winning position with a clear piece up. There are no dangerous threats for us here, and Black will be forced to resign as soon as we conclude the development. }
*

