7. exf6
{ As a natural follow-up, White opens the e-file for the Rook and puts pressure on Black's King. Black needs to delay development for a while and White will try to benefit out from it. }
7... dxc4 8. Re1+
{ I must emphasize the  8.fxg7!?  is an alternative option for those who intend to play the Max Lange attack for a long time. The 8. Re1 move is a surprising weapon that can be used from time to time with great success. However, if you wish to have Max Lange as one of the main weapons, you would need to bother more with the previously mentioned 8. fxg7!? In this course, I would put 8. Re1 is important, as it would shorten your preparations a lot and it will make this opening easier to learn. Do not be suspicious, you will continue butchering! }
8... Be6
{ This is the most logical and the most common answer for Black here. Not only that it blocks the check, but gives hope to Black that he will be just on time to castle alongside and keep the King safe. }
9. Ng5
{ White shall use all the instruments to try to keep Black's King in the center. Not only that we immediately pressure just developed Bishop on e6, but more importantly, Queen gets space to play, eyeing h5 square especially. With many tricks hanging in the air, this is a very dangerous position for Black who needs to follow the exact moves to keep it up. }
9... g6
{ This is a very interesting move for Black that might give them a solid play. But according to my experience, only experienced correspondence players and top engines are aware of this move. Black has a direct threat to overtake the f6 pawn and to slide into a quick castle. }
10. Qf3
{ There are several interesting moves here for White, but I prefer 10. Qf3 is a developing move that holds the f6 pawn safe. White prepares the battlefield for possible sacrifices or trades through e6 square.   One of the interesting alternatives would be  10.Nd2  here, with an attack on the c4 pawn, as the Be6 stays pinned. After  10...Qd5  11.Nxe6  fxe6  12.Ne4  Black has a solid play, but this is an interesting position for a human game after  12...O-O-O  and  13.b3  break through the Queenside.   I want to note here that you should not fall into logical  10.Nxe6  as after  10...fxe6  11.Rxe6  Black keeps everything safe with a simple  11...Kf7 }
10... O-O
{ It looks dangerous to castle Kingside here, but as I mentioned in the beginning, this is an engines' line, and it is hard to expect these moves to be played by a human in regular games. With a very precise move, this can lead to an equal chances position.   If Black continued here with  10...Qd6?!  which is considered to be suspicious, White would have a very good play after  11.Bf4  - development move to come with a tempo attack, and after  11...Qd7  Black faces a very nice sacrifice  12.Rxe6!  as it was shown in the game Miralles,G-Fontaine,R France 2004. Black needs to continue with  12...fxe6  giving  nice play to White after  13.f7  and the forthcoming Be5. White controls all the dark squares there, while Black faces issues with the exposed King. }
11. Rxe6
{ White needs to take control here, faced with Black's potentially dangerous asset of Bishop pair. }
11... fxe6 12. f7+
{ Since the pawn on f6 hangs, White needs to go for an intermediary move before taking on e6. }
12... Kh8 13. Nxe6
{ The main idea of our play is to include the dark-squared Bishop, putting Black's King into problems again. Black needs to be precise to equalize the game... }
13... Qe7 14. Bg5
{ Another sacrifice forcing the only moves for Black. After trades through the f7 square with  14...Qxf7  15.Qxf7  Rxf7  White takes the piece with  16.Nxc5  but Black holds the position after  16...Re8  and the position are evaluated equally by engines after  17.Nd2  Of course, in the real human game, it would be very hard to hold the position with a piece down. Further plans could be seen in the game Aldrete Lobo,J-Ruefenacht,M ICCF email 2000. }
