9... Qd5
{ I consider this move as the most common answer for Black. The idea is logical: Black aims to castle alongside as soon as possible, revealing the g-file and Kingside for attacking options. }
10. Nc3
{ White uses all the opportunities to develop actively. Knight goes in the center and Black's Queen is under attack, so he needs to think again about good options for pieces. Black is again faced with many tricks and has to find a proper way to avoid them! }
10... Qd7
{ At the first sight  10...Qd7?  looks natural as Black holds the weakened e6 square and still prepares for the castle. However, after a few moves only, Black will be stuck with losing position!   You should not forget that Knight on c3 is not hanging as after  10...dxc3??  Black loses the Queen with a simple  11.Qxd5!  due to the pinned Be6. }
11. Nce4
{ The Knights are connected and Black is faced with another direct threat:  11...--  12.Nxc5!  With King in the center, Black is not comfortable to delay the development furthermore, but he is left without other choices. }
11... Bb6
{ 11...Bf8  instead does not make a huge difference for us, as we still reach the winning position after forced  12.fxg7  Bxg7  13.Nc5!  Black cannot survive the upcoming 14. Nxe6 due to a pinned King on e8, clumsy Bishop on e6, and Queen on d7 hangs as well. Black's King will after trades stay in the center for a long time, and White will find an easy way to use an open e-file for discovered checks to win material advantage. }
12. fxg7
{ White's strength over dark squares is finally visible! Black cannot hold everything as White threatens several things at the moment: Nf6 comes, as well as an active gh8 which immediately wins. It is game over with our favorite 1:0 result! }
