{ Once again we improve the position of our pieces with a tempo attack. Do not be naive to trust that our idea is only to take  11....--  12.Nxc5  with following 13. Ne6,   but we have a cunning threat of  11...--  12.fxg7  with 13. g4! This would put Black's Queen into trouble since the Qf5 won't be able to hold both f6 and Bc5. }
11... Bf8
{ This might look like a passive move, but Black holds important squares afterward. He aims to proceed with long castle and quick activity through the Kingside, so we are forced to react as soon as possible! }
12. Nxf7
{ White uses the badly positioned King on e8 to open the position up just one step before Black managed to put the King on the safe spot. Black is now forced to drag the King out from the shelter, losing an option to castle after during the game. }
12... Kxf7 13. Ng5+
{ Only one move after, White takes the material back and manages to keep the initiative. Meanwhile Black will face issues with undeveloped pieces- Bf8, Rh8, and bad King. }
13... Kg8 14. Nxe6
{ Thanks to a nicely positioned Knight on e6, Black's center hangs. We directly threaten to take  14...--  15.Nxd4  and Black's position would fall apart. }
14... Re8
{ Black finds an active move to deal with the Nd4 threat. Using the back rank and not connected Rooks there, Black pins the Knight on e6 and hopes to forces as many trades as possible. Namely, trades and entering an endgame will neutralize Black's problem with a bad King, and Black will have more space for maneuvring and activation. }
15. Nxf8
{ As previously mentioned, face with an issue of the hanging Knight on e6, White is forced to accept this trade of a good Knight for a bad Bishop. However, we will stabilize the position soon after. }
15... Rxf8
{ Of course Black cannot expect to trades rooks here as well, since  15...Rxe1  instead would lead to  16.Qxe1  and after  16...Kxf8  Black's King would be very exposed through the weakened dark squares. }
16. Qe2
{ With two pieces on the f-file, Rook and the Queen, Black was ready to put the pressure on the f2 pawn. This is a simple prophylactic and development move that keeps the f2 pawn safe and prepares White for further development. }
16... d3
{ Black certainly does not want to let us stabilize and get initiative. He wants to activate and makes space for Nd4. Anyway, White will not have trouble here after removing these threats. }
17. cxd3 cxd3 18. Qd1
{ After a simple trade of pawns, White turns to control of the light squares. Queen gets an option to be activated through the b3 square when Black's King has problems. It is important to understand that here White has a long-term small advantage thanks to a better Bishop than Knight in an endgame. The Bishop will be easily developed through the e3 square, and we will include another Rook in the game with a possible Rc1-Rc5 lift. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) The Max Lange Attack"]
[Black "Max Lange attack #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 Nc6
{ This move, simply defending the d4 pawn, is one of the drawbacks of the Urusov Gambit because it basically forces White to play either the Scotch Gambit or the Max Lange attack. }
5. O-O
{ The afore-mentioned drawback is that  5.e5  d5  is a transposition to the Scotch Gambit, which is outside of the scope of this repertoire. }
5... Bc5
{ With this move, Black forces a transposition to the Max Lange Attack.  5...Nxe4  would lead to the Scotch Gambit - an opening that is beyond the scope of this repertoire. }
6. e5
{ With the 6. e5! move, White enters the Max Lange attack opening! This is a very nice option for the club players as well as rapid and blitz players to complicate their games and win by following tactical lines. Max Lange offers interesting attacking positions, with many aggressive chances, and what makes it special - it is not that common in the practice! Would it be more surprising for you or for your opponent to end up there?! }
6... d5
{ This is practically the only move for Black that gives them a solid position. Many times I faced suspicious  6...Ng4?!  instead which leads to very good play and initiative for White after simple  7.Bf4  White holds the pawn and threatens to move a clumsy Knight from g4 with a possible 8. h3 move.   Sometimes you might be able to see Black playing  6...Ng8?  here as well. Not only that 6...Ng8 looks bad, indeed it is a bad move that opposes development rules. With  7.Ng5!  ,  White will immediately put the pressure on the weakened f7 pawn and after  7...Nh6  8.Re1  is almost game over as White has a huge advantage. The plan is simple: Qh5 or Qf3- improving the pressure on the f7 pawn, c3- with breaking the center, centralizing pieces with possible Ne4. }
7. exf6
{ As a natural follow-up, White opens the e-file for the Rook and puts pressure on Black's King. Black needs to delay development for a while and White will try to benefit out from it. }
7... dxc4 8. Re1+
{ I must emphasize the  8.fxg7!?  is an alternative option for those who intend to play the Max Lange attack for a long time. The 8. Re1 move is a surprising weapon that can be used from time to time with great success. However, if you wish to have Max Lange as one of the main weapons, you would need to bother more with the previously mentioned 8. fxg7!? In this course, I would put 8. Re1 is important, as it would shorten your preparations a lot and it will make this opening easier to learn. Do not be suspicious, you will continue butchering! }
8... Be6
{ This is the most logical and the most common answer for Black here. Not only that it blocks the check, but gives hope to Black that he will be just on time to castle alongside and keep the King safe. }
9. Ng5
{ White shall use all the instruments to try to keep Black's King in the center. Not only that we immediately pressure just developed Bishop on e6, but more importantly, Queen gets space to play, eyeing h5 square especially. With many tricks hanging in the air, this is a very dangerous position for Black who needs to follow the exact moves to keep it up. }
9... Qd5
{ I consider this move as the most common answer for Black. The idea is logical: Black aims to castle alongside as soon as possible, revealing the g-file and Kingside for attacking options. }
10. Nc3
{ White uses all the opportunities to develop actively. Knight goes in the center and Black's Queen is under attack, so he needs to think again about good options for pieces. Black is again faced with many tricks and has to find a proper way to avoid them! }
10... Qf5
{ The only move that saves Black from the powerfull pin through the e-file is 10... Qf5. White needs to be careful here about the f6 pawn which is the main asset in the desirable Kingside attack. More than that, not only that Black threatens to take Qf6, but he has an even more dangerous threat for us- dc3, taking the whole piece. }
11. Nce4
{ Once again we improve the position of our pieces with a tempo attack. Do not be naive to trust that our idea is only to take  11....--  12.Nxc5  with following 13. Ne6,   but we have a cunning threat of  11...--  12.fxg7  with 13. g4! This would put Black's Queen into trouble since the Qf5 won't be able to hold both f6 and Bc5. }
11... Bb6
{ Black simply steps back from the attack and aims to continue with the development of 0-0-0. As the main White's mission is to slow down Black's actions, White will once again search for tempo moves and quick activity. }
12. Ng3
{ Knight gets an active square with an attack on the Black's Queen. Despite that, the Rook on e1 once again controls the open file and pins the Be6 and Ke8. Black needs to think about the defense of the e6 square, as well as g7 pawn and possible Nh5 jumps. }
12... Qg6
{ If you have been wondering why Black cannot simply proceed with  12...Qxf6?  - the answer is simple: White directly wins after with  13.Nh5!  Black will have issues to defend both e6 and g7 spots, and there will be plenty of winning tactical chances for White. }
13. fxg7
{ White again delays Black's development and ruins the Kingside pawn structure. More than that, dark squares around the Black's King start to be vulnerable and there are open chances for Nh5 or Qh5 moves! }
13... Rg8
{ One should not forget that Black cannot recapture the g7 pawn with  13...Qxg7  as the Bishop on e6 would stay unprotected.  14.Nxe6  would come with the forthcoming  14...fxe6  15.Rxe6  and Black will be in huge trouble with the King in the center. }
14. Qh5
{ A very good move by White that could be seen in the game Pilgaard,K-Sodoma,J Plovdiv 2010. White clears the way for the Knight to come with the uncomfortable threat of Nf6. Of course, Black now needs to think about vulnerable h7 and f7 pawns and still undeveloped King. }
14... O-O-O
{ The best choice for Black is to give up from hopes that he can create any action over Kingside. By accepting the Queen trade Black dives into an endgame where White has a small advantage, but he can try to hold the position and reveal from the pressure. }
15. Qxg6
{ Of course, White should not be scared of trades. With a much better pawn structure and plenty of weaknesses to attack we will have nice initiative and possibilities to improve pressure on Black's pieces. }
15... hxg6 16. Nxe6
{ With another exchange, we kill Black's Bishop pair and create two additional weaknesses- e6 and g6 pawns! }
16... fxe6 17. Bh6
{ There is no reason to hurry with overtaking the e6 pawn as it hangs anyway. We should first defend the 7th rank passed pawn which can put Black into hard times very soon. White has many squares to play through- Ne4-Nf6 could be a potential plan. One should not forget that White's pieces are better positioned than Black's as it was proven in the previously mentioned game Pilgaard,K -Sodoma,J Plovdiv 2010. }
