{ The only chance for Black to escape issues is to put the King into safety as soon as possible. With a quick castle, Black wants to activate Kingside Rook and possibly use the g-file for activation. However, we will take control from here, not letting Black get more initiative. }
12. g4
{ White uses a beautiful motive to force Black to play only moves. Black still faces issues with the defense of f7 square, Be6, and Bc5, and now the Queen that held all of those hangs! }
12... Qd5
{ It just looks that with 12... Qd5 Black keeps control over the important squares that are previously mentioned, but this is a bad move that we can use immediately to benefit a lot. }
13. fxg7
{ With issues to find a good position for the Rook on h8, Black also has to think about the forthcoming Nf6. There is no defense anymore. }
13... Rhg8 14. Nf6
{ White wins the material advantage, taking an exchange. Not only that we can resolve all the problems afterward with simple trades, but Black still has Be6, f7, and h7 under pressure. White is clearly better! }
