12... Qe5
{ This is practically the only move for Black that can save him from this position. Although the Queen on e5 looks very clumsy as it is confronted by the Rook on e1, this cannot be directly used by White. }
13. Nxe6
{ White first decides to remove the Bishop on e6 and to clear things on the Kingside. Black will again have issues defending both g7 and Bc5. }
13... fxe6
{ Black is forced to take with 13...fxe6, giving us a chance to weaken the Kingside even more.   If  13...Qxe6  was played, both  14.Nxc5   or  14.fxg7  with the forthcoming Nc5 lead White to a winning position with a piece-up advantage. }
14. fxg7 Rhg8
{ Of course, Black cannot recapture the pawn as the Bishop on c5 would be hanging. After  14...Qxg7  15.Nxc5  White would have a winning position with a piece up. }
15. Bh6
{ White keeps the pawn on g7 safe as it is only one square in front of promotion! This pawn will also stop Black from taking any actions while we will have time to activate Re1 and possibly use the pin of the Queen on e5. Queen from d1 and Rook from a1 will soon join the game as it was shown in the game Aldrete Lobo,J-Herrera,G corr 1992. }
