[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Odds and Ends"]
[Black "Odds and Ends: 2...f5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... f5
{ Black might choose a wild play and enter the Calabrese countergambit, which is basically a King's gambit reversed. But do not worry, we are ready to strike back with an aggressive approach! }
3. d4
{ White takes action in the center and opens the position, and Black is now forced to react with some of their central pawns action! This is usually the best strategy vs. gambit moves and players - on sharp moves - play even sharper and throw them off from their comfort zone! }
3... exd4
{ If Black decides to instead go for  3...fxe4  I think that you would be delighted to win the game after  4.Qh5  and Black loses a Rook after  4...g6  and  5.Qxe5! }
4. Nh3
{ It is obvious that the light-squared Bishop on c4 dominates the light-squares and makes the f7-spot the most vulnerable for Black. That is why we try to punish our opponent as soon as possible and with the move 4.Nh3! White aims to play Ng5 but at the same time prepares himself for short castling! }
4... Nf6
{ This is the most resilient move for Black, who attacks White's pawn on  e4  . One should not forget that  4...fxe4  would lead to the already mentioned idea of  5.Qh5  , and Black loses a Rook after  5...g6  and  6.Qe5!  Although, Black could also choose to play  4...Nc6  instead, but after  5.Ng5!  White threatens to play Nf7! Black needs to answer with  5...Ne5  and after  6.Bxg8  Rxg8  White gains a massive initiative after  7.Qxd4  d6  8.Nc3  h6  and finally  9.Qd5!  Rh8  10.Ne6  gives a clear advantage to White due to a hanging pawn on f5 which can not be defended anymore. }
5. e5
{ White punishes Black for the late development and wild play. It is obvious that Black's Knight doesn't have so many options to jump away and escape an attack! }
5... Ne4
{ Black might choose to centralize the Knight with  5...Ne4  or to go for  5...Ng4  instead and attack the pawn on  e5  . However, after  5...Ng4  White can keep developing with  6.O-O  and an idea of Re1, and after  6...Nc6  7.Re1   @@StartBracket@@Black cannot capture a pawn with  7...Ngxe5  or  7...Ncxe5  due to  8.f4  !@@EndBracket@@  Of course, Black can try to continue with  7...Be7  instead, but after  8.Nf4!  Ngxe5  White gains a clearly better position with  9.Bb3  and straightforward ideas of Nd5, Qh5, and c3. One should not forget that Black is not able to castle and faces lots of troubles due to pinned and exposed pieces. }
6. O-O
{ While White developed the pieces and put a King into a safe zone, Black lags behind with the development and will face troubles after the forthcoming Re1 and Qh5! }
6... Nc6
{ Black tries to follow up with development and threatens to take the e5 pawn. However, late development has consequences, as it will be shown soon. }
7. Re1
{ White keeps with activation and puts all the pieces in a position to eye Black's King, which is exposed to an attack in the center! Ideas are Nd2, Nf4 followed by Qh5, in some positions even Rxe4!? }
7... Nxe5
{ Although 7...Nxe5?! is not the happiest solution for Black, this is the move I mostly faced during Online games. I would say that  7...Be7  would be better instead, but it is hard for Black to pick that one since they cannot castle. Anyways, we would face that move with  8.Nf4  with a practically winning position, mainly due to the powerful light-squared Bishop! }
8. Qh5+
{ And while Black went for collecting the pawns, White prepared for the attack on the centralized King! Black is practically forced to block the check with 8...g6, and we will dive into the typical butchering position! }
8... g6 9. Rxe4
{ And here it is! White sacrifices the Queen and punishes Black for their development delay! }
9... gxh5
{ This is the most logical move for Black, although engines would say that the best answer is  9....d6  . Anyway, even after  9...d6  White is winning after  10.Re5!  dxe5  and  11.Qe2  with two light-pieces for a Rook, which is considered to be an advantage. Of course, Black still faces development problems and can not castle any time soon. Also, one should not forget that  9...fxe4?  is not possible due to  10.Qe5!  and White takes full advantage with two pieces up after the forthcoming  Qh8  . }
10. Rxe5+
{ White keeps forcing Black to go for the only moves in the position! } 10...
Be7 11. Bg5
{ And White is clearly better after the forthcoming  11...--  12.Rxe7  Qxe7  13.Bxe7  Kxe7  having the advantage of two minor pieces for a Rook! Also, one should not forget that Black pieces are all on the back rank and that it should take a lot to get some development harmony. Objectively, White should not have problems in the final position, but the proper technique should be shown still! }
