1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Qg5
{ Even though 2...Qg5? is considered as a bad move for Black; it can be very tricky and uncomfortable for White if you do not answer properly! It is quite interesting that my lower-rated students faced this move quite often, so get ready to learn its refutation precisely! }
3. Nf3
{ White should simply continue with development and activation giving a double attack to the Black's exposed Queen and undefended pawn on e5! }
3... Qxg2
{ Black practically is forced to proceed with 3...Qxg2 attacking the Rook on h1.     If  3...Qe7  was played instead, White has a clear development advantage after  4.Nc3  c6  5.d4  gaining central control, and after  5...d6  6.Ng5!  Black is forced to defend the f7 square with  6...Nh6  passing the initiative to White after  7.O-O! }
4. Rg1
{ White simply attacks Black's exposed Queen and opens up opportunities for tactical engagement! }
4... Qh3 5. Bxf7+
{ While Black went for tricky lines and collected pawns, White was actively developing and creating the environment for a nice tactical blow gaining a winning position after only five moves of play! }
5... Kd8
{ Black can forget about castling, and they have issues with further development. One should not forget that  5...Kxf7?  instead would lead to a whole Queen up for White after  6.Ng5! }
6. Rg3
{ Once again White puts Black in trouble, how to find a proper square for the Queen? }
6... Qh6 7. d4
{ And White gains a winning position after 7.d4! Black needs to think about the relocation of the Queen, with a terribly placed King in the center, while the e5 pawn is hanging, and will be captured with the forthcoming 8.Nxe5, followed by normal development with Bg5 and Nc3. }
