1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... Qh4
{ This suspicious move surprisingly scores well for Black, which tries to gain a position of the Patzer's opening, but Black is a tempo down. In that manner, White should not be afraid of this tricky move and should only think about the fast development! }
3. Nc3
{ White goes for a natural developing move, defending the e4 pawn and threatening to play Nf3, exposing Black’s King to an attack! }
3... Bc5
{ Black keeps it tricky with a mate threat of 4...Qxf2! However, it would be best if you did not worry a lot about that, since White already has a development advantage, and it is only going to be increased! }
4. Qe2
{ Once again, White actively defends the Black's threat of Qxf2 and aims to play 5.Nf3 with a double attack on the exposed Queen on h4 and undefended pawn on e5. }
4... d6
{ This is basically the only resilient move for Black since  4...Nc6?  would lead to a clear advantage for White after  5.Nf3  Qd8  and  6.Bxf7!  followed by Qc4+ and a double attack on the King and Bishop on c5. White would be a clear pawn up after only six moves! }
5. Nf3
{ White keeps developing with a tempo attack on Black's Queen, and with three developed light pieces, White is ready to castle and a strike in the center where the Black's King is still stuck. Also, White will use the opportunity to attack the exposed Bishop on c5, which does not have any space to escape. }
5... Qd8
{ No matter what square Black decides to escape to with the Queen, they would be met with the same response! }
6. Na4
{ And White gains a clearly better position with all of the activity and an attack on Black's exposed Bishop on c5. One should not forget that all of the Black's pieces are locked on the back rank, while White is ready for O-O and striking in the center! Also, keep in mind by now the infamous princinple, we are about to get the Bishop pair advantage! }
