1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... b5
{ Black chooses to play for activity and goes for what is known as the Anderssen's gambit!   Black's mission here is to let White take the pawns while they actively develop and gain central control. However, that is not easy as it sounds! }
3. Bxb5
{ Of course, White accepts the gift and aims to get the Bishop back on the a2-g8 diagonal from where it controls the f7 spot! }
3... c6
{ As it was previously mentioned, Black aims to gain the center control after d5 while we need to carry the Bishop back onto the most active diagonal a2-g8. }
4. Ba4
{ One should not forget that immediate  4.Bc4  would be met with  4...d5  , which comes with a tempo for Black, while  4.Ba4!  prevents Black's idea of d5. }
4... Bc5
{ Black certainly does not want to play  4...d5  since after  5.exd5  Black would be forced to take the pawn with the Queen, and they can not accomplish anymore their idea of central control. In that manner, after  5...Qxd5  White gains a clear advantage after  6.Qf3!  aiming to trade pieces with a pawn up, and now if Black tries  6...e4  7.Qe3  with the idea of Nc3 and f3, and Black would need to worry about the hanging e4 pawn. }
5. Nf3
{ White strikes back with active development forcing Black to defend the weakened e5 pawn. White aims to go for simple ideas like O-O, c3, followed by d4 and full center control with a pawn up! }
5... d6 6. O-O Nf6 7. c3
{ Thanks to better development, White can ignore the attack on the e4 pawn wishing to gain an open position while the Black's King is exposed in the center. One should not forget that White's idea is to play d4- gaining the center control, followed by Re1! }
7... Nxe4 8. d4
{ As we mentioned previously, White gives the pawn back to gain a huge activity and wants to create an attack on Black's exposed King. }
8... Bb6 9. Re1
{ White is obviously better while Black has no time to conclude development due to a hanging Knight on e4. Moreover, moving the Knight away would result in the opening of the e-file for White's Rook, and one should not forget that Black's pawn on e5 is hanging, while Ke8 remains exposed in the center for the time being! }
