1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... c6
{ Lately, I keep facing this move more and more. Black aims to take central control with d5. It requires certain precision by White so, it would be good to remember the following two moves!   However,  2...c5?!  is considered a suspicious move, since Black plays against the basic rules of chess, which is that development is the most important thing to be followed in the opening. }
3. Nc3
{ With a simple developing move, White prevents the threat of d5, completes development, and aims to strike back in the center with the idea of d4! }
3... b5
{ Pressuring the Bishop on c4, Black wants to move the Bishop away from the dangerous diagonal a2-g8 with an aggressive approach of b5, followed by a5-a4. }
4. Bb3
{ With a simple step back, White keeps the Bishop safe on the most active square. At the same time, with two minor pieces developed, White aims to conclude development with Nf3, O-O, and to react in the center with d4! }
4... a5
{ Once again, Black pressures the light-squared Bishop threatening to trap it after  5.--  5...a4  .  It is worth mentioning that also  4...b4  is possible for Black and after  5.Nce2  a5  White can create a safe spot for the light-squared Bishop with  6.c3  , and at the same time planning to go for Nf3, d4, and O-O, as it could be seen in the game Dickl, E - Ryska, J Remote email 2011. }
5. a4
{ White strikes back as actively as possible, and forces Black to react with the pawn on b5, which is now under attack. And while Black needs to push the pawns away from danger, this creates outposts in Black's camp that White can use; we keep on with our development plans. }
5... b4 6. Nce2
{ After a simple step back, White is ready to finalize his development with Nf3, O-O, and d4. One should not forget that the light-squared Bishop is perfectly placed, safe, and has full control of the light squares, eyeing the f7 weakness. }
6... Nf6
{ Black follows up with normal development and attacks the e4 pawn. However, thanks to our more active pieces, White will once again ignore Black's threats! }
7. Nf3
{ At the same time, White develops the Knight, prepares to castle, and attacks the e5 pawn. Of course, White keeps the idea of playing d4 later on opening up the center and aiming to reach Black's exposed King. }
7... Nxe4 8. Nxe5
{ With three White pieces actively develop and an attack on the f7 weakened square, it is obvious that White has a clear development advantage. To understand the position better, it is important to know the further plan for White, which is to play d4, O-O, Re1, and possible Ng3 or Nf4. }
8... d5
{ Black blocks the light-squared Bishop and prepares for development as well. However, White still has a small positional advantage due to an outpost on e5 which is already conquered by the Knight! }
9. d4
{ White gains central control and reaches a position with a small advantage based on the better development and Black's weakened Queenside. The idea of White is simple: O-O, Bf4, followed by Ng3, and a possible c4 would put Black in deep trouble. }
