1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This move represents one of the oldest analyzed openings ever, The Bishop's opening. Namely, this opening was used and analyzed by famous old masters Lucena, Ruy Lopez, Philidor, Larsen, and the new generation of grandmasters, Nunn, Kasparov, and Leko all the way to the nowadays super GMs Carlsen, Nepomniatchi, Firouzja, and many others.  Why Bc4? What are the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats? Answers to all of these questions will be revealed throughout the course. Nevertheless, in few words, Bc4 on the second move controls the important d5-square, takes advantage of the a2-g8 diagonal, and attacks the most vulnerable spot in the Black's position, f7. In addition to these basic and obvious pluses of the move Bc4, White does not block the f-pawn. With a possible f4 later, we have several opportunities to transpose into favorable lines of the King's Gambit or Vienna game.  Simultaneously, this move manages to avoid the Petroff, which is notoriously known as very 'boring' or 'dry' for many players. What is the downside of  2.Bc4  compared to  2.Nf3  ? well with Bc4 we don't create any direct threat as opposed to the move Nf3 @@StartBracket@@attacks e5@@EndBracket@@, which subsequently allows Black to have more flexibility with their second-move responses. }
2... c6
{ Lately, I keep facing this move more and more. Black aims to take central control with d5. It requires certain precision by White so, it would be good to remember the following two moves!   However,  2...c5?!  is considered a suspicious move, since Black plays against the basic rules of chess, which is that development is the most important thing to be followed in the opening. }
3. Nc3
{ With a simple developing move, White prevents the threat of d5, completes development, and aims to strike back in the center with the idea of d4! }
3... Nf6
{ Black might choose to go for a development move, threatening to play d5 which would put White into an uncomfortable position since both Bc4 and pawn on e4 would be hanging. }
4. d4
{ White chooses to defend the position with activity! Due to the lag in Black's development, White aims to open the center and maintain control over the d5 square. }
4... Bb4
{ Black strikes back using active play as well, pinning a Knight on c3 and threatening to take the e4 pawn. However, I would like to mention that Black can also choose other options.   For example, after  4...exd4?!  5.Qxd4  d6  6.Bf4!  White is clearly better with a threat of O-O-O and e5.     If instead, Black goes for  4...b5  5.dxe5!  bxc4  6.exf6  Qxf6  7.Nf3  Bb4  8.O-O  White would have a clear advantage due to Black's weakened pawn structure and inactive pieces on the Queenside.   Additionally, if Black decides to play  4...d5?!  White gains a much better position after  5.exd5  cxd5  6.Bb5  Nc6  7.dxe5  since Black cannot defend the d5 pawn anymore. }
5. dxe5
{ White should not hesitate to open the center and can ignore Black's threat due to the weak Kingside, which will be exposed to our deadly attacks very soon! }
5... Nxe4 6. Qg4
{ Due to Black's lag with development, White puts Black in trouble with an attack on the g7 square, at the same time, attacking the Knight on e4. It is obvious that White is ready for an aggressive approach and the Butchering! }
6... d5
{ This might look like an uncomfortable move for White due to a double-attack on the White's Queen on g4, and the Bishop on c4. But one should not forget that g7 pawn is hanging in the air right now!     Also, if you are questioning what happens if Black goes for  6...Nxc3?!  , I would say that it would be a suspicious move, as after  7.Qxg7  Ne4  8.c3  Rf8  , White gains full control over the position and gets a huge initiative after  9.Bd3  Nxc3  10.a3  Be7  and  11.bxc3  , due to the fact that almost all of Black's pieces are locked on the back rank, whilst White aims to get activated with Nf3, Bh6, O-O. }
7. Qxg7
{ With this significant intermediary move, White gives a hard time to Black, who needs to find out how to support the Rook on h8 or the pawn on f7. }
7... Ke7
{ Even though 7...Ke7 looks unnatural, Black aims to connect the Queen and the Rook, and hopes to play Rg8, followed by Rg2, which would lead to a very sharp position.   However, the move  7...Rf8  is also possible, and after  8.Bd3  Nxc3  White is clearly better thanks to the move  9.Bd2!  taking the piece back next move, but Black's King will still be positioned in the center and exposed to an attack. }
8. Bg5+
{ White shows no mercy with an attack on Black's exposed King, and forces Black to play the only possible moves! }
8... Nxg5 9. Qxg5+ Ke8 10. Qg7
{ Once again, Black is forced to defend the Rook on h8, while White is ready to go for O-O-O, aiming to stop once for all the threat of dxc4. }
10... Rf8 11. O-O-O
{ And while White has almost all the pieces activated and developed, Black is chained to the back rank, and it seems that there is no hope to move the King into safety any time soon. One should not forget that Black's h7 pawn is hanging, and it can hardly be defended, and White would have the unstoppable passed h-pawn, which will be most likely promoted to a Queen!     If Black continues with  11...Bxc3  as it happened in a game Ruefenacht, M - Sicker, R GER email 2013,  White gains a clearly better position after  12.bxc3  Qa5  13.Bd3  Qxc3  14.Ne2  Qa3  15.Kd2  and the pawn on h7 can not be defended anymore, and White will go for h4-h5 very soon! }
