1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. Qg4 g6 5. Qf3 Nf6 6. Nge2 d6 7. d3 Bg4 8. Qg3
Be6 9. Bg5 h6 10. Qh4 Ng4 11. Bxe6 Bxf2+ 12. Qxf2 Nxf2 13. Bxd8 Nxh1 14. Bf6
{ The arising position that we already analyzed here is completely winning for White! I decided to take this game as a model game, just to show you how even top players, in Rapid games, failed to find the best answer to the Bishop's opening.   Here, believe it or not, Black was almost hopeless after 4.Qg4! - move four! It can rarely happen in any other opening, not to mention the boring Ruy Lopez :@@EndBracket@@ }
14... fxe6
{ For Black it doesn't make any sense to play anything else besides the text move. For example, if  14...Rf8?!  15.Bg4  and White, in the worst-case scenario, would have at least two pieces for the rook @@StartBracket@@which is more than enough to claim that the arising position is winning@@EndBracket@@, but keep in mind, the Knight on h1 is trapped and it is about to get trapped as well! }
15. Bxh8
{ Mamedyarov is now up a Bishop, and the Knight on h1 is about to fall, and for a player of that class even being up a pawn is enough, not to mention this gigantic material advantage. Although, it is always nice to see how fast and precise top players realize their decisive advantage... }
15... Kf7 16. Kd2
{ Threatening Rxh1.  16...Nf2  would not be enough since after  17.Rf1  it falls anyway. }
16... Rxh8 17. Rxh1 a6 18. Rf1+ Kg7 19. Nd1 Rf8 20. Rxf8 Kxf8 21. c3 Kf7 22.
Ke3 Kf6 23. h4
{ I have to express my big satisfaction when, last year, while I was following the Rapid tourney in Sharjah, I saw this game.   It clearly showed me that this variation can be used at the top-level, that this seemingly logical approach by Black with 1...e5 2...Nc6 and 3...Bc5 @@StartBracket@@where lots of weaker guys tend to play like this because they think they can play in the same manner as vs. a Guiocco Piano@@EndBracket@@ really does not seem to be working!  Enjoy your future games and feel free to share your positive experience with us soon! Thank you :@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Karjakin, Sergey vs. Kosteniuk, Alexandra"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d3 Nc6 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Ne2 d5 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. O-O Be6 8.
Bxd5 Bxd5 9. f4 O-O 10. f5 Bxc3 11. bxc3 f6 12. Ng3 Qd7 13. Be3
{ Even though in the Course I suggested 13.Rb1!? as my novelty, I was very excited and happy when I saw this game for the first time a long time ago.   It clearly shows us an idea of what are we supposed to do in similar positions. With the last move, White threatens nothing, but completes his development and slowly but surely is getting ready for his final action on the Kingside!  In some positions, dark-squared Bishop might go on a3, although having it placed on e3, White seems solid too. }
13... Ne7
{ The Ne7 retreat is something that I like and fear from Black players! It gives better protection to the b7 pawn @@StartBracket@@in case White goes with Rb1@@EndBracket@@, pressures the f5 pawn in some circumstances, but the most important idea behind it, it gives either Bc6 or b6 followed by Bb7 to the Black's bishop! Why does Black need that Bishop on this diagonal? In most positions, after c4 happens LightSquared Bishop goes on f7 or g8 and along with not stoping any Ne4 ideas by Black, it does not have particularly strong defensive Kingside resources either! So, having the Bishop on an a8-h1 diagonal helps Black to execute Ne4 whenever they want! }
14. c4
{ The last move would be way more efficient if there was no Ne7 , but this still gives White decent central advantage and space control. }
14... Bc6
{ Do not forget, this Bishop belongs on the a8-h1 diagonal, so Black can always eliminate Ne4 if needed! }
15. Qg4
{ Quite a typical move in similar positions. It allows White better control of the e4 square @@StartBracket@@Ne4 becomes posssible since it will be protected by Queen@@EndBracket@@, gives White possible attack with ideas such as Bh6 or Nh5, opens up back rank for the more flexibile rook movement and finally gives White better control of the Kingside with a possibility to set it on the right place and support Kingside pawn storm! }
15... Kh8
{ Defensive precaution measures aimed against Nh5 and Bh6. Also, it opens up Rg8 followed by g6 in some positions, as long as Queen stands on g4. }
16. Rae1
{ Karjakin has just completed his development and the first part of the game came to an end! Follow carefully how Karjakin moved his forces and the way he built up his attack on the Kingside - this is why I took this game as a model one! }
16... b6
{ Quite a logical prophylactic move. It gives the Black possibility, to put its Bishop back to b7, prevents Ne4-Nc5-Ne6 ideas by White @@StartBracket@@if Black wants to avoid taking on e4 and keep his light-squared Bishop at all costs@@EndBracket@@ and in some positions, it avoids having pawn on a7 being under the attack. }
17. Re2
{ Another important move in White's strategy! White gives this rook a very valuable role and it might go to g2 after Ng3 goes to either e4 and after Qh4-g4-Rg2 it will support Kingside attack coped with g5 eventually! }
17... Rf7
{ A pretty logical defensive move that does not look that bad, although, it is hard to see any other particularly special moves for Black but defensive and passive ones. }
18. Qh5 { Getting tempo for Ne4 and g4 - Kingside attack! } 18... Nc8
{ Another typical move by Black. This Knight goes towards d6 where it would certainly have better control of both f5 pawn and e4 central square. }
19. c5
{ White temporarily prevents Nd6, but more importantly echaging his big weakness - doubled pawns! }
19... Rf8 20. Ne4
{ Finally move that presents one of the key attacking resources by White! All of a sudden the whole strategy coped with the attack on the Kingside becomes realistic and g4-Rg2 followed by g5 is about to happen! }
20... Qf7 21. Qh4
{ White surely does not want to exchange the Queens! We would dry out our attacking sources otherwise! }
21... Qxa2 22. g4
{ Now, we can clearly see the benefits of strong Rook on e2! Along with g4-Rg2 and g5 idea, it also protects the c2 pawn and minimizes Black counter chances! }
22... Ne7 23. g5 fxg5 24. Nxg5 Qg8 25. Ref2 { Threatening break with f6 } 25...
Bd7 26. Nxh7
{ Removes one of the main defenders of the previously safe King on h8 and gets the pawn back. Looks like White gets unstoppable initiative after this move! }
26... Qxh7 27. Qxe7 Bxf5 28. Qg5 g6 29. h4 Rae8 30. d4
{ In an already winning position, Karjakin failed to find the fastest and easiest way to open the Black's King and weaken Bf5. Although, opposite-colored Bishops with the rooks and Queen on the board usually favor one side! This time White had hardly stoppable initiative! }
30... bxc5 31. dxe5 Rf7 32. h5 Re6 33. Bxc5 Qg7 34. Rh2 Qh7 35. Qd8+
{ This is a remarkable example of White's plans in a similar type of positions, the one that I like a lot and find very typical. I believe learning plans and ideas from this game, could help you a lot in better understanding of White's concepts and can bring you lots of joy and nice wins. Good luck! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Fedorov, Alexei vs. Fyllingen, Roy Harald"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 Bc5 3. Nf3 d6 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Bc4 Nc6 6. d3 a6 7. Nd5 Bg4 8. c3
Nh5 9. f5 h6 10. b4 Ba7 11. Be3 Ne7 12. Bxa7 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Rxa7 14. O-O Nf4 15.
Bb3 h5 16. d4 Qe7 17. Qd2 h4 18. Rae1 Bxf3 19. Rxf3 Qg5 20. Rd1
{ As I stated in the trainable Course part, in this position, White was clearly better mainly thanks to the active pieces, full space control, and the threat of opening the d-file after dxe5, while Black still needs to resolve developing problems mainly due to the inactive Rook on a7, the King being exposed in the center, as well as the inability to push h3 due to g3 where Knight on f4 or Queen on g5 would be seriously weakened. }
20... f6
{ Black takes prophylactic measures against having the Queen on g5 under attack, although, if one is forced to make such a move at the cost of opening a monster Bishop on b3, I believe things are pretty clear. }
21. Kh1
{ White also takes prophylaxis in order to keep his position untouchable and avoid all kinds of tricks by Black including Nh3 discovered check, a possible weak g2 square, or some other similar tactical trick. }
21... Rh6 22. Rdf1
{ Looks like White forgot about the ideal placement of his pieces and that he could have gone with simple a  22.c4!  followed by c5 with a dominating position along d-file and lots of mating threats afterward. }
22... g6
{ Black puts the ball back in our half and again gives White a chance to take the initiative. It was better to go with  22...Nh5!  and a slightly better game for White. }
23. dxe5
{ This time GM Fedorov plays the most accurate move and takes advantage of Black's inactive pieces. With the last move, he tries to open the d-file, points out how weak is the Rook on a7 and that he will not hesitate anymore and will take action finally. }
23... fxe5 24. Rxf4
{ White is winning! Even though it does not seem that forced, this move shows how badly the Black pieces were placed and that with the exposed King on e8, the Rooks stuck in the middle of nowhere @@StartBracket@@on a7 and h6@@EndBracket@@, Black can not hope for anything but a few more additional moves on the scoresheet! }
24... exf4 25. Rxf4 { Threatens three lethal moves: fxg6, e5 or Qf2. } 25...
gxf5 26. exf5
{ A position has arisen where our Bishop became more active, e-file open for the Rook or Queen and this certainly can not be any good for Black. Re4 is a threat as well with a simple follow-up of h3 followed by other active mating moves. }
26... Kf8
{ Black removes his King and hopes for salvation, although, White has all the time in the world... }
27. h3
{ Usually, similar moves bring White a decisive advantage and definitely cuts Black's counter chances off! }
27... c6 28. Be6
{ Nice move which blocks the activity of the Rook on h6 and threatens Qxd6. }
28... d5 29. Qd4
{ Threatens the Rook on a7 and improves Queen's positioning to the maximum. Now even Rg4 becomes a threat! }
29... Ra8 30. Rg4 Qf6 31. Rg8+
{ I had to include this game for a couple of reasons: first of all, it was a really well-conducted initiative by White in the middlegame, while at the same time, it shows how we should fight in a very common situation where Black goes for Bc5 idea and even tries to keep the strength of the dark-squared Bishop with a6, creating a shelter for its further action along that diagonal. }
