[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Firouzja, Alireza vs. Carlsen, Magnus"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nc6 4. d3 Na5 5. Bb3 Nxb3 6. axb3 d5 7. Nf3 dxe4 8.
Nxe5 exd3 9. O-O Be7 10. Nxd3 O-O 11. Qf3 c6 12. h3 Re8 13. Rd1 Be6 14. Be3
{ White was slightly better in the current position, as we already analyzed in the theoretical section of the course.   The Rook on a1, altogether with Be3 pressuring the a7 weakness, forcing Black to react, whilst Black's Queen on d8 is pinned by a Rook on d1 and Black also needs to think about Nc5 or Nf4 threats. }
14... Qc7
{ A logical Queen move in order to put his Queen into safety and avoid unpleasant Nf4 and Nc5 threats. }
15. Bf4
{ This was a very nice tempo move that improves White's Bishop and gives White better development and piece activity. }
15... Qc8 16. Be5
{ This is the point of previously seen 15.Bf4. By placing the Bishop on e5, Nf6 becomes potentially vulnerable, the Bishop on e7 is tied up to the defense of the Nf6, and the whole plan with Be3-Bf4-Be5 looks very active and prophylactically improves White's position in the center. }
16... Nd7 17. Bd4
{ One might say that White has not done much with the maneuver Be3-Bf4-Be5-Bd4, although  a7  remains weak,  17...c5?!  by Black would create a weakness on d5, while solid and logical  17...Bf6  18.Bxf6  Nxf6  19.Re1  would secure White tiny but long-lasting middlegame advantage. }
17... b6 18. Ne4
{ Young Firouzja slowly but surely taking his pieces towards the Kingside and generates attack! Nf4 has just become a dangerous threat! }
18... c5
{ Carlsen blundered in an already difficult position. Although, he was lucky enough that this was Blitz game and due to that, Firouzja even being considered a great tactician missed the following tactical shot! }
19. Bc3
{ Here a possibility was  19.Bxg7!  Kxg7  20.Nf4  followed by  20...--  Nh5  , but we have to be honest and point out that there is nothing that obvious for White yet, so missing that move was quite reasonable. }
19... f6 20. Nf4 Bf7 21. Rd2
{ With a simple idea of doubling the rooks along the d-file and slowly penetrating into Black's game. }
21... Nf8 22. Rad1 Qc7 23. Qg3
{ Even though, the silicon machine prefers in a couple of moments other moves for White throughout the game, I really have to say that I enjoyed Firouzja's attack in this game!   Keep in mind, this was a Blitz game and his opponent was one of the best players and defenders in the history of this game, where even Carlsen could not find an equalization in this game! White threatens Bxf6 or Nxf6, with the decisive mating attack. }
23... Qc6 24. Nxf6+
{ Great tactical shot that decides the game in White's favor! I have always claimed how after good strategy or patient play, comes easy tactics! }
24... Bxf6 25. Rd6 Qe4 26. Bxf6 Ng6 27. Nh5
{ The final nail in the coffin! The rest was just Carlsen's attempt to catch his opponent off guard in some mess. }
27... Qxc2 28. Bxg7 Bxb3 29. Bc3 Re7 30. Nf6+ Kf7 31. Nxh7 Rae8 32. Ng5+ Kg8
33. Ne4 Qxe4 34. Rxg6+ Kf8 35. Rdd6 Rf7 36. Rgf6 Ke7 37. Rxf7+
{ The whole concept by White after this game became playable, and I have to admit that even though I did not find it particularly attractive at first, the more I studied it, the more I analyzed it with the engines, I realized how serious this weapon could be!  All things considered, after this game, I played this same variation a lot of times, and it turns out to be way more venomous than it looked like! }
