[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Edwards, Jonathan vs. White, David V"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d3 c6 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3 Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 dxe4 8.
dxe4 Nbd7 9. c3 Nc5 10. Bc2 Qc7 11. Nd2 Be7 12. Nf1
{ This Knight usually goes to g3 @@StartBracket@@or e3@@EndBracket@@, eyeing to jump on the nice f5 outpost, sometimes even on c4 and g4 @@StartBracket@@from e3@@EndBracket@@. White's position looks slightly better mainly thanks to the Bishop pair.   Of course, everything up to this point has been analyzed in the theoretical part of the course. }
12... O-O-O
{ Black completes his development and with the last move prevents Ne3, due to Nd3. Also, the decision to play 0-0-0 shows that he was not ready to allow attack on the Kingside. }
13. Ng3
{ Threatens Nf5. Interestingly enough, in the case of logical  13...g6  , White would have lethal  14.Bg5!  with huge initiative since the f7 pawn looks already very weak. }
13... Ne6 14. Nf5
{ Every Ruy Lopez or Italian player should be more than happy with the Knight being positioned on f5! White has a wide variety of possibilities such as Ne7 @@StartBracket@@with the Bishop pair advantage@@EndBracket@@ or Be3 followed by a4 and b4 with possible Queenside attack afterward. }
14... Bf8 15. Be3
{ A logical follow-up of previously made moves by White. White would like to go for a4-a5 with the idea of Queenside expansion as well as Ba7 possibility. }
15... g6 16. Ng3
{ The knight on f6 is threatened and this is the precious tempo for White to carry on with initiative with 0-0. }
16... Bg7
{ In my opinion, even more, logical was probably  16...Be7  which would keep an eye on the Knight on f6 as well as controlling the Queenside and diagonal a3-f8. }
17. O-O
{ It is time to draw the line! White has completed his development very successfully, with good control of the center, potentially powerful Bishop pair, but more importantly, a strong Queenside attack in the way that happened in this game! That is exactly the reason why I chose this game! }
17... h5 18. a4
{ Nice move that goes along well with Be3, because all of a sudden, two ideas become possible: a5 followed by Ba7 or Rfb1 followed by b4. }
18... h4 19. Ne2
{ Our Knight on e2 does not have any specific role, but it is certainly better than on g3, where it was limited without any future. }
19... Kb8 20. a5 c5
{ I believe that this move could only help White's main idea coped with Rfb1 and b4, making it smoother and easier. }
21. Rfb1
{ b4 is about to happen and looks like White's attack becomes unstoppable. I do not see the way for Black to stop the attack! }
21... Rd6 22. b4
{ After pretty extensive preparation, White has finally launched an attack! All of a sudden, Rooks on a1 and b1 get a better-attacking role and the Bishop on e3 looks way more active! From my point of view, lately, I am of opinion, with the good placement of pieces and logical development, the side who runs the attack has way better chances and richer attacking opportunities if all these conditions are fulfilled, rather than just forcing some crazy sacrifices! }
22... cxb4 23. Rxb4 Ka8 24. Rab1 Nd8 25. Bb3
{ Finally, even the light-squared Bishop gets into an attacking stance! } 25...
Ne8 26. Ba4 Qb8 27. Nc1
{ Even that 'famous' Knight on g3 has improved its position. Now, Nb3-Nc5 becomes quite realistic even Qf3 will change its destination and go to e2 which is going to create further pressure on the Queenside! }
27... Rf6
{ Black, in lack of good options, even helps White to keep on improving his pieces. That usually happens, when you conduct your initiative well and leave your opponent without proper defensive and counterattacking resources. }
28. Qe2 Nd6 29. Bb5 a6 30. Ba4 Qc7 31. Rxb7
{ A well-conducted attack by White! Everything started with the Bishop pair advantage and more than typical Knight 'journey' Nb1-Nd2-Ng3. An attempt by Black to avoid attack on the Kingside by castling Queenside did not work fine enough as this game is an example that should show you how to break your opponent's Queenside defense when they castle there! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Grischuk, Alexander vs. El Gindy, Essam"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d3 c6 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3 Bd6 6. Nc3 d4 7. Ne2 O-O 8. O-O
c5 9. Ng3 Nc6 10. Nh4 g6 11. Bg5 Be7 12. Nf3 Kg7 13. h3 Ng8 14. Bd2 h6 15. c3
Bd6 16. Rc1 Bd7 17. cxd4 cxd4 18. a3 Qe7 19. Nh2
{ Slightly better game for White. White can later choose to push f4 or try being more subtle with Rc2 and Qc1, followed by Ng4. While White has an active play on both sides, Black needs to search for a way to activate Knight from g8.   Of course, we have already analyzed all of this in the theoretical section of the course! }
19... Rac8 20. Bc4
{ From this point onwards great maneuvering by Grischuk begins! With the last move, White opens up the possibility for b4 with further expansion on the Queenside, afterward followed by Qb3 at some point, as well as covering c-file without the possibility for Black for further material simplifications. }
20... Rc7 21. Ne2
{ That Knight on g3 had nothing to do with g3 since Black limited its activity with g6. Also, 21. Ne2 manages to secure an easier break on the f-file with f4 and allows surprising retreats with Kh1!? and Ng1!? }
21... Be6 22. Bxe6 fxe6 23. Ng4
{ Pretty strong maneuvering move that provokes h5 with weak dark-squares afterward. }
23... h5 24. Nh2
{ Now when the weaknesses of the dark squares have just been provoked, that Knight can come back to its home on h2. It is remarkable how Grischuk found all these moves on such a small number of squares and how he even came up with the ideas that are about to be played. I guess that is one of the main power of Super GMs! }
24... Qh4 25. Be1
{ This move secures temporary defense of the f2 square and allows possible f4 break if the Queen wants to be there on h4. }
25... Rcf7 26. Kh1
{ Now when f2 square is successfully defended, it is time for White to do something with one of the worst pieces - the Knight on e2! With the last move, White has just opened up g1 square for the Knight as Grischuk was patiently looking for a chance to improve the position of his pieces and break on the Kingside at some point! }
26... Qd8 27. Ng1
{ I would like to emphasize this moment of the game. Grischuk plays on just a few squares but managed to find surprisingly good maneuvering resources such as Nh2, Kh1, Ng1, and Be1. }
27... Nf6 28. b4
{ An old good rule, when possible, play on both sides of the board! It is the strongest positional approach in middlegames! }
28... a6 29. Bd2
{ This move improves the dark-squared Bishop and White tries, after all, to take advantage of the weak g5 square. From this point onward, White begins to exploit weaknesses in Black's game. Also, pay attention, how Grischuk still patiently kept on improving the placement of all his pieces with great maneuvering skills! }
29... Nh7 30. Qe2
{ Once again White defends pawn on f2, although this time with the Queen, since he moved his Knight to g1 and Ngf3 is on the horizon... }
30... Be7 31. Ngf3
{ White has not just solidified the position of previously limited Knight on g3  @@StartBracket@@Ng3-Ne2-Ng1-Ngf3@@EndBracket@@ but also threatens Rc6 followed by Ne5 with positionally winning game. }
31... Bd6
{ Black defends the pawn on e5 and consequently the Knight on c6, although, it weakens the h4-d8 diagonal as well as control of the g5 outpost! }
32. h4
{ Points out the weakness of the g5 square and slowly preparing for a jump on the Kingside! Also, pay attention to how the Knights are ideally connected without the possibility for Black to ever sacrifice an exchange on f3! }
32... Rc7 33. Ng5
{ White clears the way for the Knight on h2 to finally bring it into the game with Nhf3, and could even prepare some Kingside breaks with Rg1 and g4 eventually. }
33... Nxg5 34. Bxg5 Be7 35. Nf3 Qd6 36. g3 Bxg5 37. Nxg5 Rfc8 38. Qd2 Nd8 39.
Rxc7+ Qxc7 40. b5
{ Much better was  40.Qa2!  pointing out a weakness on  e6  where Black would have to defend himself harder. }
40... Qc2
{ 40...Qc3!  would be way better and would pretty much prevent White's activity. }
41. Qb4
{ A great display of an experienced player and the willingness by White to win and succeed! Grischuk finds the only active way to push for a win! }
41... Qc5 42. bxa6 Qxb4 43. axb4 bxa6 44. Ra1
{ After all, Black has too many weaknesses to defend and this is practically a very hard position to hold. }
44... Nc6 45. Ra4 Kf6 46. Rxa6 Nxb4 47. Ra7
{ I enjoyed this game because it clearly shows how one should play this similar type of position. Also, the whole game was a brilliant example of positional play and high ability by one of the top World-class players - Alexander Grischuk, not just to maneuver, but to do that on one part of the board without much space!   Finally, I would like to point out one more thing, even though Grischuk won this game, we have to notice that he did that mainly thanks to his outstanding positional skills, so get ready for a hard game and lots of difficulties in a similar type of positions to gain the full point! }
