[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Yu, Yangyi vs. Wang, Yue"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d3 c6 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3 a5 6. a4 Bb4+ 7. c3 Bd6 8. exd5
cxd5 9. Bg5 Be6 10. Na3 Nbd7 11. Nb5 Bb8 12. O-O O-O 13. Re1 Re8 14. Bh4 Ra6
15. Nd2
{ White seems a bit better in the arising position, as we have already seen in the theoretical section.   White is ready to play d4 and meet Black's e4 with the immediate c4-blow and this center break would put pressure on Black's vulnerable center and White will be able to activate the pieces. }
15... h6
{ This is one of those 'waiting' moves where Black does not know what is White about to do and makes a useful waiting move to see White's idea. }
16. d4
{ This d4 break seems crucial in pawn structures like the one on the board, especially because e4 is forced. }
16... e4 17. c4
{ Altogether with 16.d4! this is another move that gives White quite a promising initiative and chances. Black's center is about to collapse, the e4 pawn will turn out to be weaker, while the weakness of the isolated d4-pawn in White's position will be fully compensated with great activity of minor pieces! }
17... dxc4 18. Bxc4 Bxc4 19. Nxc4
{ This is the activity I mentioned in the previous comment. Now apart from having nicely placed Knights, there are also few nice ideas such as Qb3 or Rc1. }
19... Nb6 20. Bxf6
{ Deep positional understanding and a great move by White which strength I have to point out! White gives up seemingly strong Bishop for the 'normal' Knight on f6 but gets better control of d5 square, also 21.Ne3 supports the d4 pawn and afterward with Rc1, White will slowly but surely create a middlegame initiative, as happened in the game! }
20... Qxf6 21. Ne3
{ The Knight has taken its nice blocking position and White hopes for either Rc1 or Qb3 afterward. Pay attention to pretty misplaced Ra6, Nb6, and quite 'good' but useless Bb8! }
21... Bf4 { Black would like to know what to do with this Bishop too! } 22. Qb3
{ Opens up back rank, takes better control of the d5 square, and after Rac1 White will create a huge initiative. }
22... Qd8 23. Rac1
{ Rooks should always take open files! An idea could be either Rc5!? or Rc1 followed by Rec1. }
23... Ra8
{ Black hopes to solve the problem of the inactive Ra6, by playing Ra6-Ra8-Rc8, but after the next move, White seems to get unstoppable initiative! }
24. Rc5
{ Aimes against  24...Rc8?  due to  25.Rf5!  , also points out how weak the a5-pawn could be afterward as well. }
24... Bxe3
{ Once again @@StartBracket@@like in some of the other model games@@EndBracket@@, Black who was in the trouble, helps White in an already difficult position to launch an attack easier. f7 pawn becomes weak, Rf1 is an option followed by Rcf5 or Rc7 too. }
25. fxe3 Rc8 26. Rf1 Qd7 { The more stubborn defense was  26...Re6 } 27. Rcf5
Nc4 28. Rxf7 Qe6 29. Nc7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus vs. Wang, Yue"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d3 c6 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3 Qc7 6. Nc3 dxe4 7. Nxe4 Nxe4 8.
dxe4 Be7 9. Ng5 Bxg5 10. Bxg5 Na6 11. Be3 O-O 12. Qd2 Qe7 13. Qc3 Re8 14. O-O-O
{ Everything up to this point has been analyzed in the theoretical part of the course. }
14... Nc7
{ Black is looking for a possible Queenside expansion with either a5, Nb5 or Qf6 followed by Be6 }
15. Rd3
{ A strong idea that keeps  d2  square open in the case of  15...Nb5  16.Qd2  . }
15... Qf6
{ Black defends pawn on e5 and hopes for  Be6  to deprive White of the Bishop pair. In the meantime, Carlsen just develops and does not care much about the Bishop's pair advantage, but fights for full activity and a better middlegame where he keeps d2 square open in the case of  15...Nb5  16.Qd2 }
16. f3
{ Typical Carlsen move. White continues to improve his position, while Black desperately takes certain measures about fighting against the Bishop pair, open d-file, and the weak diagonal g1-a7. }
16... Ne6
{ In my opinion, in an already difficult position, Black does not follow logical ideas in the position, like  16...Be6  and goes for this mistake which shows that he does not have any obvious plan but tries to defend move by move. Once someone said, 'it is even better to have a wrong plan, than not to have one!' }
17. Rd6
{ Carlsen penetrates and without much hesitation takes the strong d6 square, pins the Knight on e6 and Queen on f6, the Bishop on c8 seems passive too. }
17... g6 18. Rhd1 Qg7
{ If one has to centralize a Queen like this during the game, everyone can come up with a logical conclusion, White is nearly technically winning! }
19. Qd2
{ Tripling heavy pieces along the d-file and threatens Bh6 at some point. }
19... h5 20. g3 { Cuts off any Nf4 idea and could prepare for f4 by himself }
20... Nc7 21. Bh6 Qh7 22. Rd8 Bh3 23. Rxa8 Nxa8 24. Bg5
{ A funny position that shows how strong is Magnus Carlsen. Even though he was not up materially, he was completely winning. Open d-file fully under his control, the Bishop pair and on top of all that a 'locked' Queen on h7 and 'angled' Knight on a8, as well as the inability to do something active with Re8 - Sad position for Black! }
24... Nc7 25. Qa5 Ne6 26. Bxe6 Bxe6 27. Rd8
{ Complete domination by the World champion! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Caruana, Fabiano vs. Akobian, Varuzhan"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d3 c6 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Bd6 7. Nc3 dxe4 8.
Ng5 O-O 9. Ncxe4 Be7 10. h4 Nbd7 11. Qf3 Qe8 12. O-O-O a5 13. a3 Nd5 14. Rde1
h6 15. Ng3 Ra6 16. Nf5 f6 17. Ne6
{ We have already extensively analyzed this line in the theoretical section of the book! }
17... Nc5
{ Akobian attempts to release the pressure at least by removing the Bishop on b3 from the a2-g8 diagonal, but the downside is that the Kingside is about to be absolutely shattered! }
18. Nexg7 { King becomes vulnerable and left without proper defense. } 18...
Nxb3+ 19. cxb3 Qg6 20. Rh3
{ Even though the position looks completely winning for White, with this nice move White adds another piece into the attack and Black is about to get mated after Rg3 or be faced with serious material consequences. }
20... Bxf5 21. Nxf5 Kh7 22. Rg3 Qf7 23. Nxh6
{ Of all of the model games that I analyzed in this course, this one is my absolute favorite!   I was an official commentator of the ProLeague for the Chessbrah Twitch channel and Caruana was playing our top board. On top of all that, this was one of the crucial games, and Caruana made this game look pretty convincing and smooth! Ever since that moment, I realized, the Bishop's opening is going to become one of my main White weapons! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Polzin, Rainer vs. Fritzsche, Helmut"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Qxd4 Nd6
{ This is a bad choice for Black, although it is very common, especially in blitz and rapid games. The main idea of the move is to get rid of the light-squared Bishop.   However, Black loses track with development allowing us to take advantage of his exposed King. Despite good development, White's main advantage is an active Queen that controls g7 square, not allowing Black to continue with normal development with 6...Be7. }
6. O-O
{ Thanks to much better pieces, we can ignore Black's main idea of 6...Nxc4. After this simple development move, Black is faced with a very dangerous threat of 7.Re1 as Black cannot block the check with the Bishop. As previously described, the pawn on g7 would be hanging. }
6... Nxc4
{ Although the 7.Re1 is on the table now, many of my opponents dived directly into a losing position after this terrible mistake. What is adorable is that there is no player who uses the Urusov gambit as a weapon who did not win the game this way! As I started thinking to release the course on this theme, I discussed it with my students. They helped me a lot to check the stability of the lines within it, and most of them came back to me excited to show how they mated after 10 moves only! }
7. Re1+
{ Everything is forced now. Black's only chance to survive is to block the check with the Bishop. But it's too late... }
7... Be7 8. Qxg7
{ With a tempo attack on the Rook on h8, White has other things in mind. It is a position with a piece down, but as you will see soon, Black will not have any option that will allow him to save the position. }
8... Rf8 9. Bh6
{ Game over! There is no way to defend against the tremendous threat of Qxf8#! All of White's pieces are perfectly placed on the board, and Black can only resign here, as it happened in this game.   The trainable variation can be found here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Hausner, Ivan vs. Belunek, Vladimir"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Qxd4 Nf6
{ Even though the Knight comes back on the square from where it came, this is the best option for Black in this position.     5...Nd6  interrupts the connection between White's Queen and g7 spot and allows Black to proceed with normal development Be7, O-O . }
6. Nc3
{ White continues with development and centralizes the fourth piece. The forthcoming idea is to take advantage of the clumsy Knight, pinning it with Bg5, Qh4, and the tremendous attack coming after O-O-O. }
6... c6
{ Black wants to be ready for the central strike with d5. At the same time, this move will block White's light-squared Bishop. However, White has plenty of time to finish development and to fully compensate the lack of the pawn with huge activity. }
7. Bg5
{ Almost all the pieces are in the game! Black already faces issues with the Knight on f6 while White gets ready for O-O-O. }
7... Be7 8. O-O-O
{ White completes development with the most favorite idea - a long castle! This move showcases the direction of the game, opposite-side castles.   White will launch the attack on the Kingside while Black could try to do the same on the Queenside. Anyway, speaking about what happens with practice, I hardly remember a game where Black arranged the attack on the Queenside. As it will be obvious from this game, there is simply no time for Black to take advantage of the center to create action through the Queenside. }
8... d5 9. Rhe1
{ Maybe it looks at first sight that Black managed to complete the central break with tempo attack on the Bc4, White proves that there is no such a threat. Black cannot take the Bishop as Be7 is pinned and there is no defense of Qd8. Nevertheless, I would emphasize again that White concluded the development, having activated all of the pieces, while Black still struggles to find a proper plan. }
9... Be6
{ Although Black interrupts the pin with this development move, aiming to proceed with Nbd7 and O-O, it can not be said that he feels comfortable playing this position. White is ready to toggle the pieces through the Kingside, getting ready for the mating attack! }
10. Qh4
{ Keeping all pieces active, without retreating, White continues to put pressure on Black. After Black finally threatens the light-squared Bishop we will be ready to put it on the more active square - d3. One shall not forget that the Bd3 will control the h7 spot and it will be very hard for Black to keep the King in safety. }
10... Nbd7
{ Black finally threatens the Bishop on c4, but that fits with White's plan. As previously mentioned, the light-squared Bishop finds a more attractive square to go. }
11. Bd3
{ White keeps all the pieces active and Black has issues to castle Kingside. He would be very brave to castle at this point of play when all the White's pieces are eyeing the h7 spot. }
11... Nc5
{ While Black tries to find a solution for a problem with castling and the vulnerable h7 pawn, White will point new weaknesses in Black's position as it will be shown soon. }
12. Nd4
{ Of course that White is not afraid of a possible Nxd3 as that would bring another Rook in action after Rxd3. Black must feel uncomfortable facing the threat of Bf5 now! }
12... h6
{ I would say that this is a suspicious move that does not change White's plans. Black threatens nothing as the Rook on h8 hangs after the capture of the Bishop on g5. }
13. Bf5
{ As Black does not threaten the Bishop on g5, White uses some extra time to improve the position of pieces, revealing again the pin coming from the Rook on e1. }
13... Kd7
{ Black aims to keep the Bishop on e6 safe and to gain activity. Now Black indeed threatens to take the dark-squared Bishop but White will easily resolve this issue. }
14. Bd2
{ It is a fact that the Queen looks a little clumsy now as it is pinned by Black's Bishop from e7. For this reason, White aims to proceed with Qh3- putting more pressure on the Bishop on e6, but also escaping from the possibly uncomfortable pin. }
14... Nfe4 15. Nxe4
{ I can bet that no one expected this move coming! Although it is very attractive I must admit that it's not maybe the best.   Engines admire more the stable  15.Qg4  move, but there is no doubt that  15.Nxe4!  makes it more enticing. White uses the badly positioned Black King to grab two pieces and huge activity if Black decides to accept the Queen sacrifice. }
15... Nxe4
{ Black decided not to take risks and tried to keep the King safe. If  15...Bxh4  was played White would be much better after  16.Nxc5  Ke7  with nasty  16...--  17.Bb4  coming! Black's King would be miserable there. }
16. Bxe6+ fxe6 17. Qh3
{ White now provoked another weakness that is hard to defend. One should not forget that Black's King is still exposed in the center and that opens many options for White! }
17... Qg8 18. Rxe4
{ White uses the opportunity to open the Rook for the d-file, exposing Black's King to a deadly attack. Black needs to accept this sacrifice hoping for the best. }
18... dxe4 19. Nxe6
{ Another tactical engagement for White! Of course, all of these were possible due to the terribly placed Black King. Black did not make many mistakes in this game, but bad pieces allowed White to outplay the opponent without much effort. }
19... Ke8 { Of course  19...Qxe6  leads to  20.Bf4  and Black loses a Queen. }
20. Bc3
{ White has it all now! It seems that everything hangs in Black's position - Nc7, Nxg7, Bxg7 all those threats are impossible to be defended. }
20... Rh7 21. Qf5
{ It looks that White plays with his opponent now. Black is out of moves and White wants to show complete dominance after this move. Nc7 is now a mate threat! }
21... Qf7 22. Nc7+
{ First the intermediary check and then White will be ready to capture the hanging Rook! }
22... Kf8 23. Qxh7 Rc8 24. Bxg7+
{ Beautiful ending of the beautiful game! Another sacrifice that Black needs to accept and then it will be definitely game over after  24...Qxg7  25.Ne6! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Allerberger, Peter vs. Paleckis, Eugenijus"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Qxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Bg5 c6 8.
O-O-O d5 9. Rhe1 O-O
{ This move looks logical as Black puts the King in a safe zone and at the same time gives support to the Queen on d8, threatening dxc4. However, this is a suspicious move due to the placement of White's pieces eyeing the King right away! }
10. Bd3
{ White improves the position of the light-squared Bishop putting the pressure on vulnerable h7 spot after a simple Qh4.   It is extremely important to emphasize that  10.Qh4?!  leads to unclear position without much chances for attack due to  10...Bf5!  which guards Kingside. With this move, White also blocks this option for Black and keeps things under control.   All of this up to this move was already covered in the theoretical section of the book. }
10... a5
{ Black does not recognize the danger of the attack on the Kingside. He needs to go instead for alternatives as  10...Re8  or  10...h6  . It is clear that Black hopes to create a Queenside attack but there is no time for that as it will be shown in this game. }
11. Qh4
{ White quickly toggles the Queen to the Kingside eyeing the h7 pawn. Black needs to turn to defense mode now. }
11... h6 12. Bxh6
{ A well-known and desirable idea of the Urusov gambit finally comes true! Black falls into a position with a naked King! }
12... Ne4
{ If Black accepts the sacrifice instead  12...gxh6  13.Qxh6  leads to winning position as after  13...Qd6  14.Ng5  comes with threats of Re7 or Bh7.  There is no defense anymore! For this reason, Black needed to search for alternatives, but anyway, White has a clear advantage now. }
13. Qh5
{ It is obvious that everything hangs in Black's position and I would not like to be in their shoes at this point. }
13... g6
{ Black follows the only line that makes the game last longer, but not nicer to play. Dark squares are weakened now and White will take full control over them. The main square to fight for now is g7! }
14. Qe5 Bf6
{ Again Black needs to follow the only moves to keep the King safe. } 15. Qf4
{ White simply steps back and now threatens the Knight on e4. Both Ne4 and Be4 are deadly threats for Black that he needs to address. It is clear that Black needs to go for trades at this point, leaving the Rook on f8 attacked. }
15... Nxc3 16. Bxf8 Nxd1
{ It might look that Black keeps the material after this continuation but the truth is that White holds the control over the dark squares. }
17. Bh6 Bxb2+ 18. Kxd1
{ After all the trades Black kept the pawn up, but one shall notice that most of the Black's pieces are still positioned on the starting position. With poor development, Black will not be in a position to defend. }
18... Nd7 19. Ng5
{ White is ready for decisive action! The f7 pawn is attacked, and the h4-h5 comes soon! }
19... Bf6 20. h4
{ It is very hard to find a good response for Black. White threatens to open the King after h5, but also to include the Rook in the attack with a Rook lift of Re3-Rg3. Black's pieces are too inactive for any kind of counterplay or proper defense. }
20... Nf8 21. h5
{ White finally advances with h5 and Black cannot prevent the opening of the King now! }
21... Bd7 22. Re5
{ Beautiful move which leaves Black speechless! The idea is to defend the Knight on  g5  , threatening  23.Bxf8  Qxf8  24.Qxf6  with a clear piece-up advantage.   If Black continues with  22...Ne6  here the game will be finished in joy after  23.Nxe6  Bxe6  24.Re3  with  Rg3  coming afterward and the King will be in the mating net. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Bauer, Robert vs. Grabliauskas, Virginijus"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Qxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Bg5 c6 8.
O-O-O d5 9. Rhe1 Be6 10. Qh4 Nbd7 11. Bd3 Nc5 12. Nd4 h6 13. Bf5 Nfd7
{ This is maybe the only move for Black that provides a fairly active position. Black's main threat now is Bg5 and the Bishop on e6 looks well defended. White needs to accept the trades which comforts Black as he will gain some space for the pieces. }
14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Qg4
{ White steps back and avoids the Queen exchange. The main idea is now to advance with b4, where White will aim to take full control of the light squares.   Of course, the attack on the Kingside can be improved by Re3, followed by Re1 and Rg3, and White will have a nice compensation for the pawn. The engines are not delighted to evaluate this position in favor of White, but in practice, White has better chances as it is very hard for Black to follow the only defending moves that hold the balance.   All of this up to this point has been already analyzed in the main course. }
15... O-O
{ Black slides the King onto the kingside, but White keeps active play thanks to the previously mentioned 16.b4! }
16. b4 Nf6
{ This is the only way for Black to save the game and equalize the position. As it will be shown in the game, Black hopes for the perpetual check as the only defense of the forthcoming Kingside attack. }
17. Qh4 Nce4 18. Nxe4 dxe4 19. Nxe6
{ White needs to accept the trades as Black could gain counterplay if we are stubborn to continue attacking. 19.Bxe4?! instead gives very good play to Black after 19...Qxb4 . White cannot take risks here and we must be satisfied with a draw. In addition to this game and line, I would like to mention that in my long experience with the Bishop opening I have never faced this almost forced draw line. }
19... Qxb4 20. Nxf8 Qa3+
{ And Black ends the game with a perpetual check that White cannot avoid. } 21.
Kb1 Qb4+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Aldrete Lobo, Jorge vs. Herrera, Gabriel"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5 6. e5 d5 7. exf6 dxc4 8.
Re1+ Be6 9. Ng5 Qd5 10. Nc3 Qf5 11. Nce4 O-O-O 12. g4 Qe5 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14.
fxg7 Rhg8 15. Bh6 d3
{ The most aggressive and direct approach by Black, this has been played in more than 180 games!   Black is trying to take advantage of the potentially dangerous d-pawn and get the maximum benefit out of it!  With this move, Black has just opened the position up for the Bishop on c5, threatens a lethal d2 push, a hyper solid Bb6  @@StartBracket@@with the idea of keeping a strong Bishop and to avoid Nc5 by White@@EndBracket@@, and more so hopes for Knight jump onto d4 at some point! }
16. c3
{ Quite an important move that prevents some Nd4 and gives White a pretty simple threat of Nc5 or even the way more dangerous Qf3! that supports Nf6! with an attack on the Queen on e5 and the Rook on g8! }
16... d2
{ Very challenging! Black takes advantage of the d-pawn, and uses the fact that White can not take it, also threatening the Rook on e1, but more importantly all of a sudden gives Black the very tactical idea of Rd3-Rh3 threat! Believe it or not this position was seen in more than 100 games so far! }
17. Re2
{ This is practically forced. White has the quite typical simplifying idea of Nxc5 in which case the pawn on d2 would just end up as a serious weakness. }
17... Rd3
{ Even though the idea of the last move seems quite forcing and obvious, I am of opinion that White might easily forget about it, which would lead to complete catastrophe! If White simply allows the Rook invasion on h3, he could easily pack his stuff and leave the battlefield badly beaten! }
18. Qf1
{ Apart from preventing Rh3, this move also gives White hyper solid Rd1 which could fully consolidate White's game and turn the rest of the game into an easily winning middlegame where Black lacks effective counterplay eventually! }
18... Qd5
{ Black still has a glimmer of hope for one of last trick, the d1 pawn promotion into a Queen... }
19. Nxd2
{ With this move, it looks like Black's dreams have shattered into pieces, and from this point onwards White begins the conversion of his advantage! Now, the g7 pawn gets a full role! }
19... Be7
{ Black hopes for either Bg5 or Bf6, in which case pawn on g7 would not be any more dangerous in the position. }
20. Qg2
{ When your opponent has a broken pawn structure it is reasonable, to begin with, to piece trade and leave your opponent only with a weakened pawn structure. }
20... Bf6 21. Qe4
{ The strong central positioning of White's Queen poses plenty of questions for Black, such as Qxh7!, Qxe6, the pawn on c4 is weak as well and this practically leaves Black without proper defense. }
21... Bxg7 22. Qxh7
{ Black is hopeless since none of these two pieces can be defended simultaneously and the game is ended. }
22... Ne7 23. Bxg7
{ Black resigned due to the inability to do anything after  23...Rxd2  24.Rxd2  Qxd2  25.h3!  , which would defend and over-support the g4 pawn and keep threats such as Bd4, Bf6, or Bh4.  I also have to point out that after @@StartFEN@@2kr2r1/ppp3Pp/2n1p2B/2b1q3/2p1N1P1/3p4/PPP2P1P/R2QR1K1 w - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@ 15...d3! I found more than 180 games that had been played in absolutely the same fashion! In my opinion, even though it was played many years ago, this game was superb in terms of White's defense, in opposing Black's threats, and almost perfect realization and conversion of the advantage!  This is why I chose it to be the model game. Usually, remembering one important game should be enough for a proper understanding of certain variations. Hope this one will give you lots of pleasure and success in the future!  Enjoy the Max Lange attack! }
*

